<SLUG> BC-GUNS-MELT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVIST WANTS TO MELT GUNS FOR DAD'S DAY
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By M. BRADFORD GRABOWSKI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Dr. Roger Axford wants for Father's Day Sunday is the
world's largest gun collection.
</P>
<P>
   But the 78-year-old Arizona State University professor isn't
your typical collector. He is a gun control activist trying to
convince fathers that their families will be safer without guns in
the home.
</P>
<P>
   Axford is organizing a Father's Day Gun Meltdown for today at
Tempe City Hall. He hopes to collect 10,000 firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a perfect day this will be for fathers to set an
example,'' Axford said. ``If you're a good father, come down and
hand your gun in.''
</P>
<P>
   Two police officers will accept the weapons from 10 a.m. to 4
p.m. Those donating guns will not have to identify themselves and
will get a free meal at a local restaurant, Axford said.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe Police Chief Ron Burns said that most of the guns
collected will eventually be destroyed. A background check will
first be conducted to see if the gun has a criminal history.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get just one gun that could have been used to commit a
crime or cause an accidental fatality in someone's home,'' Burns
said, ``it will be a success.''
</P>
<P>
   Tempe Councilman Dennis Cahill, a gun owner, wants to promote
gun responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lack of responsible gun ownership,'' said Cahill,
who doesn't plan to hand in his guns but hopes others will as a
symbol of responsible ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear about things like Littleton, and it stimulates people
in different ways,'' Cahill said. ``It is my hope that people will
hand in their guns as a demonstration of their frustration with all
of the recent tragedies.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so supportive of Axford's idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nonsense,'' said Joe Foss, a member of the National Rifle
Association board of directors who lives in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``A gun is a piece of art,'' he added. ``That's what Hitler did,
take the guns away. Mao Tse Tung said, `He who has the guns has
control.' I don't want to be directed by any group of clowns about
what to do with my gun. They won't get mine, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Axford, an author of 13 books, has been involved in
anti-violence movements for several decades. He founded the
Coalition for Peace and Justice, which will mark its 25th
anniversary this August.
</P>
<P>
   Axford said his children are his primary motivation for the
meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day there is an article in the paper about kids getting
shot and killed,'' he said. ``There are too many 13- and
14-year-old kids getting access to guns and then going and using
them. We have to stop this. Somebody's got to take initiative.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
