<HEADLINE>
WHITERIVER RESIDENTS CONFRONT FIRE'S DEVASTATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITERIVER, Ariz. _ One Apache child said it looked like an
erupting volcano. A woman described a fireball that resembled a
``red-hot candy apple.''
</P>
<P>
   A week after a fast-moving fire raged through the Fort Apache
Indian Reservation here, devastating some and sparing others,
tribal members began to rebuild their lives as they sought a reason
for their loss.
</P>
<P>
   Verlinda James was struggling for explanations as she rocked her
3-month-old daughter in a car seat on the hotel bed.
</P>
<P>
   Her comfy four-bedroom house, with its white picket fence, was
gone _ incinerated in the inferno that charred more than 5 square
miles in its first five hours and destroyed more property than any
Arizona blaze since the 1990 Dude fire near Payson.
</P>
<P>
   It must have been the mysterious ways of God, James said. She
noted that the 100-foot wall of flame that roared down the ridge to
claim her house didn't even smudge the paint on the homes of her
three neighbors along Arizona 73.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe, James said, it was because she hadn't recently cleared
out the carpet of dead, dry pine needles around her house. Then
James' 17-year-old daughter, Yolanda Harvey, chimed in, blaming
firefighters for not spraying fire retardant on their house.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, James, a single mom of four, is among the
worst casualties. Her house wasn't insured, she has no job or car
and she said she receives no financial help from the former men in
her life.
</P>
<P>
   Her large supply of beads, with which she fashioned Apache
crafts, also was lost. The American Red Cross has put her up for a
week in the White Mountain Apache Tribe's motel. The tribe has
kicked in $500 and rent for one month in a house after the family
leaves the motel. But after that, what?
</P>
<P>
   It's the same bleak question facing the other 16 families who
lost homes, most also uninsured. A total of 30 structures were
destroyed during the 4,300-acre fire, which came dangerously close
to burning Whiteriver's hospital and the Alchesay National Fish
Hatchery north of town.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the tribe's business enterprises lost his home
to the flames. So did a 65-year-old woman who was caretaker for her
83-year-old mother. And so did a mother of five, a Whiteriver
minister and an elderly couple on public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the near misses.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Lavender and his family heard about the roaring blaze
while shopping 25 miles away in Pinetop-Lakeside. They raced home _
to be told at a roadblock that they had five minutes to get out.
</P>
<P>
   Nine-year-old A.J. Lavender, Albert's son, said it looked as if
a volcano had just exploded atop the 800-foot-high ridge behind the
home. The family members hurried together a couple of boxes of
pictures and heirlooms and tossed them into their pickup along with
their three dogs. They decided to leave their cats behind.
</P>
<P>
   But the truck wouldn't start.
</P>
<P>
   They saw the flames move into a neighbor's yard. Then the
firestorm moved into their back yard, burning a small pine tree,
cactus and their woodpile. Emergency workers sped past on the
highway but didn't stop.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the pickup's engine kicked in.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy and Velma Martel had no trouble getting their old school
bus started by their log cabin in the community known as Jurassic
Park. They loaded their children and possessions and picked up some
nearby kids as a fireball that Velma Martel described as a
``red-hot candy apple'' closed in from the south.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Martel said he never expected to see his cabin again.
After all, it was surrounded by large pines, firewood and scrap
wood he had used to fashion the eaves.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case, he left behind a long garden hose. Though still a
quarter-mile away, the fire shot out embers that ignited two small
fires in the trees behind his house. Firefighters put those out
with his hose.
</P>
<P>
   Velma Martel was counting her blessings days later as she drove
her children into Whiteriver for a tribal parade honoring the 800
firefighters who helped prevent the blaze from entering two
subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
   Bedsheets scrawled with praises for the firefighters lined four
miles of Arizona 73. Children waved streamers from a school bus in
the red and blue colors of local Alchesay High School. The Apaches'
all-woman firefighting team marched in formation with shovels and
picks. Slurry planes flew low.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been told all spring that a fire was going to come and
wipe out our school and homes,'' said White Mountain Apache
Chairman Dallas Massey. ``But given what could have happened here,
we feel very fortunate.'' &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at (602) 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
