<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-COURSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COURSE THAT'S A FORCE OF PURE EVIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. - He felt like he had been locked in a light
saber fight against an orange-eyed warrior from the Dark Side.
</P>
<P>
   For almost five hours he battled for survival. His relentless
opponent tested his skill. His will. His courage. His patience. His
nerve.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, after he had bogeyed three holes in a row and
then found salvation with a heroic shot to the 18th green, Phil
Mickelson closed his eyes and filled his cheeks with air.
</P>
<P>
   He exhaled, a sigh of exhaustion and relief.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Open is like no other major sports event. The NFL
doesn't narrow the goal posts for the Super Bowl. Pro basketball
doesn't raise the rim for the NBA Finals. But the United States
Golf Association selects a challenging course for its national
championship and then does what it can to make the test even more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Wicked pin placements _ ``borderline sadistic'' one player
called them _ and swirling winds transformed Pinehurst No. 2 into a
force of pure evil.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kite, the 1992 Open champion, shot 80 Saturday. John Daly
who has won two majors, shot 81. Former Masters champ Larry Mize
shot 84.
</P>
<P>
   Par at Pinehurst is 70. The average third-round score was 75.9.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, players trudged off the course, heads bowed,
disheveled and defeated. Each survivor had his own story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm often asked what's the hardest golf course I've ever
played,'' Lee Janzen, the defending Open champion, announced after
shooting 76. ``Now I have the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hank Kuehne, the 23-year-old amateur, played the first eight
holes in 10 over par. He ``rallied'' to shoot 81.
</P>
<P>
   Searching his memory, Kuehne said the last time he played nine
holes in 10-over par he was 11 years old. Tired? Kuehne smiled. ``A
double (bogey), a triple and a quad in nine holes pretty much zaps
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played on a lot of golf courses, but this is beyond
extremely difficult. If I had to play golf like this every day I
don't know if I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandel Chamblee, from Phoenix, called the course ``Augusta
(National) on steroids.'' Pinehurst No. 2 played tougher than the
Masters course. Harder than Pebble Beach, Old Double-Bogey by the
Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see carnage out there,'' Chamblee confidently predicted
after his round. He was pleased his ordeal was over. ``I'm going to
go have a couple of beers and enjoy (watching) it.''
</P>
<P>
   For disaster lovers this was entertainment at its best. The
game's finest shot-makers saw iron shots hit their target and then
roll off the crowned, linoleum-hard greens. The fifth hole was
almost impossible to par. Chamblee's approach shot bounced off the
putting surface ``and ended up back there where they sell
popcorn.''
</P>
<P>
   The wind was vexing, to those easily vexed. ``It was doing
this,'' Gary Hallberg said, making a quick circular motion as if
his finger were a spoon and he were stirring cake batter. Like
others, Hallberg felt if he could just make three pars in a row he
could gain some ground.
</P>
<P>
   Kite won the Open at Pebble Beach in a gale. He found Pinehurst
just as challenging. because many of the pins were placed atop
knolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf course is wonderful,'' Kite said, ``but (the USGA)
has got to give us a chance to hit 7-irons that will stick on the
green.''
</P>
<P>
   But the USGA isn't going to oblige. Golf's governing body would
like to see par win the Open and 280 for four rounds may be good
enough. Only Payne Stewart is under par. Knickers holds a one-shot
lead over the former ASU star, who today finally will win his first
major championship or once again go home disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the course is playing very fair,'' Mickelson said
voicing a minority opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price provided the best line when asked how he felt about
the U.S. Open possibly returning to Pinehurst No. 2 in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a great thing,'' Price said. ``I won't be
here.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
