<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-THIRD-OPEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIDLOCK ON CRASH COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Saturday is known as ``moving day'' on the PGA
Tour. Of course, the U.S. Open doesn't fall into that category.
</P>
<P>
   This Saturday at the 99th national championship was more like a
heavy backup situation. When the pileups finally subsided at
Pinehurst No. 2, only Payne Stewart had the distinction of being
under par, and even his 1-under total for 54 holes was not without
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Seven players had begun the third round in red numbers, but one
by one they suffered a variety of fender benders. More calamities
can be expected today, as this storied layout is proving to be
golf's version of a stock car race.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, one of those who suffered most in the wind and
occasional rain that spit through the tall Carolina pines, defined
today's strategy best.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy that backs up the smallest will be the winner,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, for one, will be trying to build on the momentum he got
on the final hole Saturday. He also hopes to reverse his fortune
from last year, when he led the Open at the Olympic Club near San
Francisco for three rounds before ending up 1 stroke behind Lee
Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to it,'' said Stewart, who is 1 stroke in
front of Phil Mickelson, and 2 better than Tiger Woods and Tim
Herron, who like Mickelson hails from Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wanted this opportunity, and now I've got to go out and
deal with it,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   There were times during Round 3 when Stewart looked like he
might not get a chance at redemption. Beginning at the eighth hole,
he was hit with three straight bogeys, and looked as if a fourth
was on the way at No. 11, where he faced a tricky, 10-foot putt to
save par.
</P>
<P>
   ``The saving grace of the whole round was the putt at No. 11,''
said Stewart, who ended up making a 10-foot birdie putt on the
final hole to grab the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the (bogey) train in a big way, and there's not many
stops around here where you can get off.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who captured the 1991 Open in a playoff over Scott
Simpson at Hazeltine National near Minneapolis, said he felt like
his 72 was ``even par.'' And considering the average score on this
torturous day was 75.97, and that only Steve Stricker broke par
with a 69, his point was well-taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no such thing as a routine par out there,'' Stewart
said of Pinehurst No. 2, which seems to be a killing field built on
crowned greens that have been enhanced by brutal weekend pin
positions.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, this Open remains wide open, with Mickelson,
Woods, Duval and Vijay Singh being the most likely challengers. But
Herron, and yet another Scottsdale pro, Billy Mayfair, also might
prevail in what basically comes down to a short game showdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I played poorly, but if that's my worst round, and I
can improve on it, I should be in good shape,'' said Mickelson, who
bounced back with a 6-foot birdie on the last hole to get to 73
after being stung by three straight bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who is coming off two consecutive victories, one in
Germany and one at the prestigious Memorial, also rebounded after
getting off to a double bogey-bogey start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tough day,'' sighed Woods, who managed to get back to 72 with
a birdie at the 15th.
</P>
<P>
   Even the birdie didn't come easy, as Woods flinched on a 5-iron
that somehow ended up 4 feet from the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hoped I would be at par by the end of the day, but after the
start I got off to, I'll take it,'' he said. ``I just love this. I
love playing in the most intense pressure of the final day.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Duval, who was 5 over after nine holes, then ground out
nine straight pars coming home to finish at 75 and give himself a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a lot of bad shots, but I thought if I was lucky, I
might still be there,'' said Duval, who like Mickelson is looking
for his first major championship. ``I did what you have to do after
I got so far down, I hung in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is the theme of the week, along with Stewart's
never-wavering presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm playing better this year at the U.S. Open than
I played last year, and that I've got some unfinished business to
take care of,'' Stewart said. ``I could have crawled away and hid
after what happened last year, or I could build on what happened
and use it to strengthen myself. That's the avenue I have chose to
take.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
