r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BULLET-KILL-AZR &LR;      06-20 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLET-KILL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIENDS OF SLAIN GIRL SEEK CLUES TO BULLET'S SOURCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Even as Keri Amrhein knocked on doors, handing out
fliers Saturday morning, she wondered if her effort would make a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   If telling people about her friend Shannon Smith would matter.
If anyone could really find out who fired the bullet into the air
last Monday, the bullet that fell from the sky, killing 14-year-old
Shannon as she stood in her central Phoenix back yard.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't think about those things, she reminded herself as
she walked the narrow, quiet streets along Central Avenue near
Camelback Road, where cute brick-box houses sit next to Spanish
villas and sprawling ranches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to stay hopeful,'' she said, shuffling her thick
Doc Martens sandals along the asphalt. ``All we can do is pray and
hope. And getting out and doing this is better than just staying at
home and crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Keri, 14, was joined by about 200 others Saturday morning. They
were friends of Shannon and her parents. They were students who had
attended Madison Meadows Elementary School with her. They were
strangers, those who simply heard about the girl's death and wanted
to help.
</P>
<P>
   They came together at St. Francis Xavier Catholic Church to pass
out more than 6,000 fliers, asking for help. They wanted anyone who
may have heard gunshots or seen anything suspicious the night
Shannon was killed to call police. And when they delivered each
flier, to every house, apartment and business in a half-mile radius
of Shannon's home, they came back for more.
</P>
<P>
   The fliers told residents what happened last Monday night when
Shannon was talking to a friend on a cell phone in her back yard.
Between 9:30 and 10:30 p.m., a stray bullet that likely was fired
from within a half-mile radius from her home hit her.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon's dad found her about 10:40 p.m. She died later at a
hospital, where X-rays showed a bullet had penetrated her brain.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone looked at the photograph of Shannon on the flier
and saw themselves or their children. They could see themselves
standing in their own back yards, in the safety of their own
neighborhood where people push baby buggies and walk dogs at night,
just like Shannon. And it scared them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been my daughter,'' said Judy Meyer, 54, a
speech pathologist, whose daughter was a classmate of Shannon's and
who lives just a few blocks from the shooting. ``It just upsets
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer and her husband, Richard, and their 14-year-old daughter,
Tova, walked their neighborhood Saturday morning, passing out
fliers. And they plan to pass out more later this week.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Phoenix police detectives say, tips haven't led them any
closer to solving the case. But the investigation is continuing.
Sgt. Mike Torres, a police spokesman, says the flier distribution
is helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that can keep it out there in the public eye can't
hurt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon's parents, Otis and Lory, were heartened by the efforts
for their only child.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to thank everybody,'' said Otis' sister, Edie
Smith, 58. ``We are really touched by the outpouring of the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Edie Smith flew to Phoenix from to New York City for the funeral
this week, then helped deliver fliers.
</P>
<P>
   `We're never going to know why Shannon,'' she said. ``But it
would be of some small comfort, both to our family and our
community, to know who did this. The more you know about something,
the more you can avoid it.''
</P>
<P>
   Edie Smith had bought her niece an airplane ticket to visit her
in New York for the girl's 14th birthday. She was supposed to visit
in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be her first big trip to New York alone,'' said Edie
Smith, who teaches English as a second language. ``Kids evolve in
such interesting ways. I was so looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   After Shannon's funeral Thursday, family friends Dan and Kendis
Drake organized the canvass, printing out maps of the neighborhood
and fliers.
</P>
<P>
   The Drakes, who have known the Smiths so long that they got one
of the first calls when Shannon was born, say they are hopeful the
fliers will move someone who may have information about the
shooting to call police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do anything to help out, so it won't happen to
anybody else,'' said Dan Drake, 51, an assistant U.S. attorney.
``With the Fourth of July coming, and people shooting guns then, we
want to get awareness out there about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the shade of a palm tree in front of St. Francis
Xavier Church on Central, Drake smiled as volunteers showed up to
help Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   By noon, more than 200 people had stopped by.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Tweedy pulled up in his cab, offering to hand out fliers
to all his passengers this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work in the area, I live around here, so whatever I can do
to help,'' said Tweedy, 45, of Phoenix. ``I'll get the message out.
It's just so sad.''
</P>
<P>
   The cheerleading squad from Madison Meadows canceled their
carwash Saturday, instead delivering fliers. Phoenix firefighters
canvassed streets. Kinko's wouldn't allow volunteers to pay for
fliers. And AJ's donated water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The really cool thing is people seemed so thankful,'' said
Megan Bednarz, 39, a marketing manager. She walked more than a mile
in her K-Swiss tennis shoes, handing out fliers throughout the
morning. ``People just wanted to pass on their wishes to the
family. And they were grateful we are doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with information about the shooting should call Phoenix
police general investigations at (602) 262-6141. &QL; 
Laura Trujillo can be reached at (602) 444-8891 or at
laura.trujillo(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
