<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPT-FATHERS-OWNERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNER/FATHERS ENJOY DYNASTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LES POLK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Give the dads a break today.
</P>
<P>
   Professional sports team bosses catch flack year-round for
everything from stadium issues to ticket prices to player and coach
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they're celebrating Father's Day amid the ascent of their
children to key positions in the Valley's pro sports scene _ and
the children could help leave a mark on sports for another
generation to come.
</P>
<P>
   From the Bidwills to the Burkes to the Colangelos, family
dynasties are in the making as the younger generation becomes more
prominent.
</P>
<P>
   At America West Arena, Jerry Colangelo is president and CEO of
the Suns and son Bryan is executive vice president and general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Across town at the Cellular One Ice Den, Coyotes owner and
governor Richard Burke's son Taylor is the assistant general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   And in Tempe, home of the Cardinals, team president and sole
owner Bill Bidwill has an even larger family presence _ son Michael
is a vice president and general counsel, Bill Jr. is a vice
president, and daughter Nicole is marketing manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real gift,'' the senior Burke said. ``Most parents lose
touch when their kids go away to college.''
</P>
<P>
   In these families, even when the kids did go away, they didn't
lose touch and eventually came home to the family business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a special joy in thinking that if you had a dream or a
goal it would turn out like this,'' Jerry Colangelo said. ``It's
somewhat of a dream come true.'' &QL; 
Back to the business &QL; 
When the Bidwills gather around the grill today for a cookout,
they'll be sharing that same feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up around the organization, I had always wanted
someday to be involved with the team and my father,'' Michael
Bidwill said. ``I looked forward to it as a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Cardinals would lose?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a challenge growing up and the team wouldn't win,
hearing things from other kids,'' Michael said.
</P>
<P>
   His father encouraged him to go away to law school, and he did.
And even while serving as a federal prosecutor in Phoenix for six
years, Bidwill stayed close to the team by charting opponents from
the press box.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's a key figure, leading the effort to get a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that visible and controversial position, Michael is
pleased to be working with dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' he said. ``It's great to work with him.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about his dad, a sometimes mysterious figure to Valley
residents?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have them here because I know they've grown up in
the business,'' Bill Sr. said. ``They have the background and
history and are really interested in the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Dad has a sense of humor many in the Valley might not know
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always fun to see what new jokes he has going on,''
Michael said. ``Most people don't see that side of him.''
</P>
<P>
   That photo you see accompanying this story that includes
Michael's brother, Tim, a lawyer who doesn't work for the team?
</P>
<P>
   Dad's practical joke was sending Tim home to get dressed up for
the photo, complete with tie, on a hot day. Much to the family's
delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of fun working with him, and I wish him a happy
Father's Day,'' said Michael, who's been with the team since 1996. &QL; 
Learning the trade &QL; 
Bryan Colangelo has been with the Suns for 11 seasons now, four in
his current job.
</P>
<P>
   He went away to school at Cornell University in New York and
then lived and worked in New York City, but somehow he and his dad
knew he'd be back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought someday it would be terrific,'' father Jerry said.
``He grew up with it, so it was ingrained in him. When I thought it
was an opportune time, I called.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bryan, who has three sisters, returned to his native
Phoenix, home to all the Colangelo children and eight
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bryan had some reservations at the time because of the
perception that he would be joining us just because of me,'' Jerry
Colangelo said. ``But that wasn't even a concern of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Bryan used to rip his father when he didn't like a
particular Suns trade pulled off by dad. It was just part of
learning by osmosis. Now Bryan's the one who gets ripped _ or
praised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The education of growing up around him prepared me for the
job,'' he said. ``All the relationships and positive situations in
the NBA have fortunately carried over for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colangelo relationship has been scrutinized and criticized
more than the others, but father and son are unequivocal about the
arrangement. The job is earned, not a handout.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan previously was a scout, assistant director of player
personnel, and vice president/assistant general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows he's being judged by his job performance and the
results and doesn't expect anything more,'' Jerry Colangelo said.
``He didn't get any special favors. In fact, I was probably harder
on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Bidwill can relate to that. The only girl in the family,
she grew up with four brothers and joined the Cardinals 10 years
ago when they moved to the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually did have to send my resume in,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, she was attending graduate school in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   And like Bryan with his dad, Nicole says her dad expects _ and
gets _ a lot of hard work.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Colangelo acknowledges he could be fired or leave the job
on his own someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives me enough leeway to prove myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Each Colangelo has a strong personality, and they respect that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a hard head, he's a harder head,'' Bryan said. &QL; 
Respecting boundaries &QL; 
Taylor Burke, 26, is the youngest of these three sons making a mark
on Valley sports. Bryan Colangelo is 33, Michael Bidwill 35.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Colangelo and Bidwill, Burke, one of five children, is
somewhat sheltered from the storm because of a layer of management
between him and his owner/dad. Burke reports to Coyotes General
Manager Bobby Smith, whom he met while both were attending graduate
school at the University of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``My situation is a little bit different with Bobby in
between,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father gives me the business perspective, Bobby gives me
the hockey perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   But he and his father are able to put family aside when business
calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect the boundaries,'' the younger Burke said. ``You
have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke, heading into his fourth year with the team, decided after
graduate school that he wanted to do something in business with his
father rather than head to the financial world in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many businesses where this might not be as
appealing,'' his father said, citing the medical companies he has
run as an example.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is a unique business. Sports has a glamorous and fun
aspect to it.'' &QL; 
Emotional bonds &QL; 
The moments of fun can be especially meaningful to a family such as
the Bidwills, who endured years of losing and public ridicule
before last season's playoff run that featured a win over the rival
Dallas Cowboys at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so much fun and so rewarding to be able to celebrate
that as a family,'' Nicole Bidwill said. ``It was so great to see
my father that happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have been in the Bidwill family longer than Jerry
Colangelo, 59, or Richard Burke, 54, have been alive.
</P>
<P>
   It all began when Bill Bidwill's father, Charles, bought the
then Chicago Cardinals in 1932.
</P>
<P>
   And Bill, 67, has kept alive the family tradition.
</P>
<P>
   As the team passed from his father, who died in 1947 when Bill
was 15, to mother Violet for 15 years, and then on to sons Bill and
Charles Jr. before Bill became sole owner in 1972, Bill did just
about everything you could imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a ballboy, I was in scouting, I signed players,'' Bill
Sr. said. ``I did a little bit of everything. I was sort of the
assistant everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's able to share that past with the present generation.
And it's not always as easy or glamorous as one might think.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in an emotional contact sport, and there are times when
some of that comes out privately,'' Bill Sr. said.
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill's private persona has somewhat puzzled the Valley over
the years, but his children defend his privacy and clearly enjoy
him in a way not many can in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a private person, and I respect him for that,'' Michael
Bidwill said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Bidwill wishes more people could hear about her dad as a
father.
</P>
<P>
   She fondly recalls him carpooling around St. Louis, driving her
back and forth to college, taking her to ballgames.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only girl in the family, and growing up with all boys
in a male-dominated sports was interesting,'' she said. ``He always
included all of us in the team. Dad used to take each child to one
away game each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Each family shares its memories, its victories and losses.
Privately and publicly, prominent sports business figures and their
kids endure through the potshots and barbs _ whether deserved or
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his turn to take some of the bullets,'' Jerry Colangelo
says with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   And Bryan smiles, knowing his dad is right. And knowing he's
almost as hard-headed as his dad. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
