<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LADY LUCK SMILING ON KERR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO - Steve Kerr knows all about The List, and he breaks
into a sheepish smile, smart enough to know there is no logical
reason for the company he keeps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like that game you play when you're a kid: One of these
things is not like the other,'' Kerr said. ``John Havlicek. Bill
Russell. Sam Jones. Steve Kerr.''
</P>
<P>
   The List is relevant and where you'll find Kerr's latest kiss of
good fortune. And as a dreadful series moves to New York for an
inevitable conclusion _ unless you think the Knicks can win four of
five games against a team that has won 44 of its past 50 _ Kerr is
about to become the 11th man in NBA history to win four consecutive
NBA championships.
</P>
<P>
   So The List is floating around these NBA Finals, littered with
ex-Boston Celtics, a team that won 11 championships in 13 seasons.
But it hasn't had a new addition in 33 years, and that's about to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of shocking, really,'' Kerr said. ``To think I'm in
my fourth Finals with four years left on my contract.''
</P>
<P>
   With a team in San Antonio that could rattle off a few more
titles in the very near future.
</P>
<P>
   The smile becomes serene. After all, there is already a
safe-deposit box in Chicago stuffed with three championship rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I ever wanted to impersonate Liberace,'' he said, ``I'll
just wear them all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, good things happen to good people, and this is about
as much an explanation as you'll find for Steve Kerr.
</P>
<P>
   When he graduated from Arizona in 1989, one year after current
teammate Sean Elliott, he was already reflecting on his luck, how a
player with obvious limitations had managed to compile a wonderful
career at a major college program. Now, if he could just taste a
piece of fruit from the NBA tree, to say he made it, if for only a
day, he would really be blessed.
</P>
<P>
   A new century is approaching, and if he plays to the end of his
contract, Kerr will have authored a 15-year career.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, a wonderful life, even for a man whose father was
assassinated overseas so many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell myself that every day,'' Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it is bittersweet, all this attention for doing very
little. Like every other ex-Bull, with the exception of Jud
Buechler, Kerr has struggled in a new locale. His three-point touch
is missing, his playing time is down, and there are times when he
appears frighteningly overmatched.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no jealousy among the Spurs, a room full of
wonderful human beings. And there is very little talk about Kerr's
paycheck (he signed a five-year, $11 million deal in the
off-season) outweighing his value (he shot 31 percent from beyond
the three-point line this season and has not been a postseason
factor).
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, Kerr is treated more like a good-luck charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans are very nice to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Through all of his success, Kerr's greatest feat is that he has
remained one of us. A millionaire athlete who knows that the value
of celebrity is shaky, shallow and better suited for others.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, just before the Spurs won their 12th consecutive
playoff game, a writer from ``Sports Illustrated'' sat down next to
Kerr. Tabbed as one of the NBA's smartest players, Kerr rattled off
answers to a quasi-intelligence quiz, listing the latest book he's
read, pondering who he'd most like to have dinner with, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Then came his most embarrassing moment, and the sheepish smile
returned.
</P>
<P>
   One day, Kerr pulled up to a gas station. He got out of his car,
leaving the door open. He bought a paper, reading it on his way
back to the vehicle. He got into the car and shut the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put the paper down, and I realized I was in someone else's
car,'' Kerr said. ``I looked up and in the store, and the person
was looking at me, like I was about to steal her car.''
</P>
<P>
   Laughter. And then the last question: What happened at the
Alamo?
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost,'' Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   True, but this is not the Alamo. This is not even a battle. This
is a series in desperate need of an ending, a coronation and not a
competition.
</P>
<P>
   And, as his smile will tell you, just the latest stop in the
charmed professional life of Steve Kerr. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
