r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-OFFENSE-TEX     06-20 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-OFFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA CONSIDERS TRANSFUSION OF RULE CHANGES TO SPARK OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like Austin Powers, the NBA needs to go back in time
and reclaim its potency. Something evil _ lax defensive rules,
better athletes or a worse work ethic _ has stolen the league's
offensive mojo.
</P>
<P>
   With this year's Spurs-Knicks Finals yet another example of how
defense wins championships but loses fans, the league will meet
here Tuesday to consider drastic rules changes aimed at returning
the game to the wide-open, high-scoring style of the '70s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring averages have plummeted 16 points per team since 1990,
15 of the past 16 Finals games have seen both teams held under 100,
and the Knicks are averaging just 29 field goals in this series,
the same amount of ``rebounds'' that Boston's Bill Russell averaged
in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've basically gotten away from basketball,'' said Denver
Nuggets general manager Dan Issel, who played for some of the
league's highest-scoring teams when Doug Moe coached Denver. ``It's
more one-on-one, two-on-two, and other guys stand around and watch.
We have to come up with some rules changes to get back to playing
team basketball again. And some of them have to be drastic.''
</P>
<P>
   A committee that will include, among others, commissioner David
Stern, Issel, Boston Celtics coach Rick Pitino, Houston Rockets
coach Rudy Tomjanovich, Miami Heat coach Pat Riley, Phoenix Suns
owner Jerry Colangelo and Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski, will come up
with proposals to present at the next the Board of Governors
meeting. If approved, the proposals might be implemented as early
as summer-league games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for something less physical, with more points
and less offensive repetition,'' deputy commissioner Russ Granik
said. ``We don't want to alter the fundamentals of the game, but
it's time for a fresh look at some real problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes being considered:
</P>
<P>
   International lane. Two feet wider at the baseline, the lane
makes centers post up farther from the basket. In theory, this
makes big men harder to double-team while also allowing more room
for cutters toward the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Isolation violation. Like college, closely guarded players could
only hold the ball for five seconds. This would eliminate Charles
Barkley pounding the dribble for 15 seconds, trying to coax a
double-team and find an open 3-point shooter.
</P>
<P>
   Zone defenses. There are proponents of allowing any type of
defense, including zones. The thinking is that it would persuade
offenses to push the pace before defenses could set up, and would
keep games from following the monotonous
dump-to-the-post-and-spot-up pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Clock tinkering. Some want a 30-second shot clock, others 20.
Either way, this Finals will probably be the last of the 24-second
era. A longer clock, say its backers, would give offenses more time
to probe for a better shot, while supporters of the quicker clock
reason that teams would be forced to play at a faster tempo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see a much different game next season,''
Colangelo said. ``We've got to open things up. If it works, teams
may actually score 100 points again.''
</P>
<P>
   What the league wants is basketball light on the 3-point set
shot and heavy on the slam dunk and transition jumpers perfected in
the late '80s and early '90s by Magic Johnson's Lakers and even
Larry Bird's Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics scored 148 points in Game 1 of the 1985 Finals.
Friday night in San Antonio, the Knicks and Spurs combined for 147.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ugly basketball, there's no way to hide it,'' Spurs
center Tim Duncan said. ``We're not the prettiest team to watch.
But even if they change the rules, it'll still be about putting the
ball in the basket. Defenses are physical and very aggressive, and
that's why you see so many missed shots. Right now, defense is the
name of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   There's more than enough evidence to suggest the league's
offensive meltdown requires a complete reboot.
</P>
<P>
   This season, scoring was at it lowest since the inception of the
shot clock in 1954-55. It has been four years since two teams (the
Rockets and Orlando Magic) topped 100 in the same game of the
Finals. Allen Iverson's 28.6 average was the lowest for a scoring
champ since 1956-57 and his 41.2 shooting percentage the lowest
since 1949-50.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, actually considered an up-tempo team, are on pace to
break Finals record lows for points per game (80.1 by Utah last
year), field-goal percentage (33.9 by Syracuse in '55), field goals
per game (29.5 by Syracuse) and assists per game (16.8 by Seattle
in '96).
</P>
<P>
   In the past seven quarters, New York has scored a whopping 117
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, it's boring a lot of the time,'' said Spurs
Hall of Famer George Gervin, whose team once scored 82 points in
the first half of an American Basketball Association playoff game.
``Where's the style? Where's the originality? It looks like
everybody's doing the same thing and none of them are doing it too
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for Sacramento's flashy up-tempo game and Utah's
trademark pick-and-roll sets, the rest of the league's offenses are
cookie-cutter schemes designed to draw double-teams in the post to
set up 3-pointers. In a Rockets-Mavericks game early this season,
Houston had 67 offensive possessions. On 53 occasions, they dumped
the ball into Barkley or Hakeem Olajuwon on the low left block.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days of Gervin's creative finger roll or Julius
Erving's swooping reverse layups. Instead, the two most dominant
moves in today's game are Shaquille O'Neal's monster dunk and Allen
Iverson's crossover dribble, which, ultimately, still requires him
to make a 15-foot jumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys today are athletes, but not skilled basketball
players,'' Gervin said. ``They spend too much time in the weight
room looking in the mirror or at the tattoo parlor and not enough
time in the gym working on dribbling with their left hand or
shooting bank shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as it's difficult to envision the Warriors of Don Nelson,
now the Mavericks coach, producing four 50-point quarters in 1991,
it's harder to stomach the Spurs easing into a 2-0 Finals lead
without making half their field goals, missing 35 percent of their
free-throw attempts and failing to score 90 points.
</P>
<P>
   But of all the glaring numbers, the one that hurried the league
to act now was that Game 1 was the least-watched Finals opener
since 1986. Low-scoring, defensive tug of wars may be exciting and
popular in the NHL, but in the NBA they are a problem that will
soon be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game has lost something, and there needs to be something
inserted to meet the demands of the TV viewers and the players,''
new Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. ``For the good of the game, we
can't continue to be regulated by individual play. I'm glad we're
admitting a problem and addressing it. That's the first big step.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
