r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-TEX     06-20 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART TAKES U.S. OPEN LEAD AS COURSE TAKES ITS TOLL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Payne Stewart separated himself from his U.S.
Open pursuers Saturday by a single stroke, provided by a 15-foot
birdie putt on the final hole of the third round at Pinehurst
Resort and Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not the shot the SMU graduate singled out as most
significant in allowing him to sit on the 54-hole lead at the Open
for the second consecutive year and third time since 1991. Instead,
Stewart pointed to a 10-foot putt at No. 11, which allowed him to
rescue par from a greenside bunker after three consecutive bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got on the bogey train and I had to get off,'' said Stewart,
who took seven pars and a closing birdie over the final eight
holes. ``Until you stop the bleeding, anything can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Few among the 68 cut survivors found ways to avoid Pinehurst's
magnetic attraction to bogeys and double bogeys during the third
round, setting up a logjam on the leader board that shows Stewart
(1 under par) as the only player remaining with a sub-par total.
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of his third-round 72, a score bettered by only two
players, Stewart carved out a one-stroke lead over Phil Mickelson
(even par) and a two-stroke margin over Tim Herron (1 over) and
Tiger Woods (1 over) heading into Sunday's final round. A dozen
players remain within six strokes, including David Duval (2 over),
Steve Stricker (2 over) and PGA champ Vijay Singh (2 over).
</P>
<P>
   That sets up a world of possibilities for Sunday's conclusion.
Stewart, 42, could complete what he called some ``unfinished
business'' by winning the title a year after frittering away a
final-round lead to 1998 champ Lee Janzen. Duval and Woods, the
world's two top-ranked players, could swap positions in the
rankings, depending on Sunday's outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, whose wife is due with the couple's first child,
could become a father and a major champion on Father's Day. Or he
could withdraw, regardless of his place on the leader board, if he
receives word that his wife has gone into labor during the round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what hole I'm on. If the beeper goes off,
I'm out of here,'' Mickelson reiterated Saturday, after a 73 moved
him into position to play in the final group on Sunday at a major
championship for the first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins might not need many birdies, Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I love about this tournament is that par is
rewarded, no matter how you make them,'' he said. ``If I can make
18 of them (Sunday), I'd like my chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on Saturday's scoring conditions, that would be a
high-percentage play. Among the 68 cut survivors, 19 failed to
record a third-round birdie. Included was Duval, who soared to a
75. Also shut out were past major champions Justin Leonard and
Steve Elkington.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Verplank, a Dallas native, described playing conditions as
``a perfect Open Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was blowing hard and the pin placements were
borderline sadistic,'' said Verplank, who shot a 74. ``You knew it
was going to be incredibly hard when you got to the first tee.''
</P>
<P>
   If not for afternoon showers that caused 25 mph wind gusts to
abate for the leaders, Tom Lehman said it would have been much
worse than the 75.97 scoring average _ a half-stroke per player
higher than during the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it would have stayed bright and sunny, like it was early in
the day, you would have seen the highest scores in the history of
the U.S. Open,'' said Lehman, who shot a 73 while playing in the
second group of the day. ``That's how tough the course was.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Pinehurst layout proved forgiving enough that Stricker,
who ranks next-to-last among Open participants in driving accuracy,
managed to scramble his way to a 69. It marked the day's lone
sub-par round, an achievement that fellow competitor John Cook
called ``the round of the year on the PGA Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Stricker downplayed his achievement, which was highlighted by a
136-yard bunker blast for eagle at No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like I shot the round of the year,'' Stricker
said. ``I just feel like I gave myself another opportunity, and
that's all you can ask going into the last day.''
</P>
<P>
   That's enough for Stewart, who has a career batting average of
.500 as the third-round Open leader. He won in 1991 and finished as
the runner-up last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm playing some pretty decent golf. And, at my age,
I'm coming to the back end of my chances to win another U.S.
Open,'' Stewart said. ``I plan to use that to motivate myself. I'm
back in the final group with another chance to win. So, I want to
go out and make the best of it.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
