<HEADLINE>
U.S. AMATEUR CHAMP EXPERIENCES ``FUNSTRATING'' DAY AT OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Hank Kuehne, the reigning U.S. Amateur
champion from Southern Methodist University, created a new word to
describe Saturday's round of 81 that included a double bogey,
triple bogey and quadruple bogey in his first eight holes:
``Funstrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne, the only amateur to make the cut, said it is fun knowing
he will be the low amateur in his Open debut regardless of what he
shoots in Sunday's final round. But it is frustrating trying to
keep the ball in play on a layout that Kuehne described as ``beyond
extremely difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played in a lot of golf tournaments. And I haven't been
10 over after eight holes since I was 10 or 11 years old,'' said
Kuehne, 23, who will turn professional tomorrow. ``The incredible
thing is, I'm not even in last place.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Kuehne will not be in Sunday's first group off the tee
because Ted Tryba, winner of last week's FedEx St. Jude Classic,
soared to a third-round 82 and Bob Burns ballooned to an 84.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne, however, reached his high number in a more dramatic
fashion. He pulled his first tee shot out of bounds at No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know there was out of bounds on this course. I
found out, though,'' Kuehne said. That set up a triple bogey, his
second consecutive seven at the par-4 hole.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne followed with a quadruple bogey at No. 8. He pushed his
tee shot into the right woods, hit a tree, chipped to the fairway,
then flew the green with his approach. His fifth shot checked up
short of the green and Kuehne chipped on and two-putted for an
eight. On his final 10 holes, Kuehne carded a birdie, two bogeys
and seven pars.
</P>
<P>
   But the first eight holes were brutal. Even with a birdie at No.
4, Kuehne shot a 45 on the front side _ highest nine-hole score in
the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to play golf like this every day, I don't know that
I'd play,'' Kuehne said. ``It's neat that I'll be the low amateur
in the Open in my last amateur event. But it's very frustrating to
shoot 81, regardless of where you are.'' SIZING UP PINEHURST
</P>
<P>
   Freed from the Pinehurst perseverance test, where players
averaged 75.97 strokes per man in Saturday's third round, golfers
took turns offering kudos to the course for its degree of
difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been asked many times, `What's the hardest golf course
you've ever played?' I now have the answer: Pinehurst No. 2,'' said
Lee Janzen, the defending Open champ, after a 76.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its sloping greens, former University of Texas golfer
Brandel Chamblee described Pinehurst as ``Augusta on steroids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was total carnage,'' said Chamblee, who shot a 74. ``But I
still enjoyed myself, because everyone was in the same boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Verplank, a Dallas native, said pin placements were
``borderline sadistic,'' especially with 25 mph wind gusts. After
the first hole, Janzen said he quit paying attention to the par
figures printed on the course scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, I played every hole as a par-5,'' Janzen said.
``That way, I knew I'd have a decent chance to make some birdies.''
STRICKER STRIKES QUICKLY
</P>
<P>
   Boosted by a 40-foot birdie putt and a bunker blast for eagle
during his first three holes, Steve Stricker turned in the only
sub-par effort (69) of the third round and climbed into contention,
at 2 over for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start like that at the Open, it leads to a good
day,'' said Stricker, who drained a 40-footer at No. 2, then holed
an 8-iron for eagle from a fairway bunker at No. 3. ``You know
you've made up some ground. But I tried to get a little too greedy
at the end. I tried to stuff in a couple of shots that I
shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Those shots resulted in bogeys at Nos. 16 and 17, leaving
Stricker three shots off the lead. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Tim Herron, on recording one of only two birdies at No. 6, a
222-yard par-3 with a well-tucked pin: ``I hit it to about three
feet and, luckily, the ball stayed. With that pin, that might have
been a skin.''
</P>
<P>
   _ No birdies were recorded at No. 12, a 447-yard par-4, during
the third round. But there were 34 scores of bogey or higher. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
