<HEADLINE>
STARS IN POSITION TO EVOLVE INTO A TEAM FOR THE AGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Postcards from the ledge:
</P>
<P>
   There's a perception among some members of the national media
that because the Stars have so many older players, this team has
been assembled ``for the moment,'' as one reporter phrased it to
coach Ken Hitchcock on Saturday, and not for the future.
</P>
<P>
   That couldn't be further from the truth.
</P>
<P>
   As Hitchcock has pointed out on numerous occasions, the Stars'
core features plenty of youth, including offensive stars Mike
Modano, 29, Joe Nieuwendyk, 32, Jere Lehtinen, 25, and Jamie
Langenbrunner, 23, and defensemen Derian Hatcher, 27, Richard
Matvichuk, 26, Darryl Sydor, 27, and Sergei Zubov, 29.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there will be a changing of the guard over the next
two or three seasons as veterans such as Brian Skrudland, Craig
Ludwig and Guy Carbonneau are phased out, and the team, of
necessity, gets younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a terrific opportunity to have a smooth transition,''
Hitchcock says. ``That's why when we made our moves (at the trade
deadline), they were minor ones and not major ones, because we felt
like we were already set up with what we wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team really revolves around the Modanos, the Hatchers, the
Matvichuks and the Nieuwendyks. Our older players are basically
role players.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons why the Stars will gradually get
younger, not the least of which is financial. The payroll can't
continue to grow. Younger players are cheaper players.
</P>
<P>
   But there's also a trend in the NHL to more speed and offensive
firepower, and that means younger legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's looking for ways to get more scorers on the ice,''
Hitchcock said. ``It's easier to take a young player who knows how
to score and teach him to check, than it is to teach someone how to
score. In today's game, you just can't afford to have people on the
ice who score just four or five goals a year, even if they're great
checkers.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no reason to think that the Stars, if they're willing
again to make the physical and emotional commitment it takes, can't
be back in the Stanley Cup Finals next year. But there will be some
fine tuning and changes between now and then. ADD-A-CUP TATTOO
</P>
<P>
   Craig Ludwig's left shoulder, above the biceps, features the
Grim Reaper and his red-eyed devil dog. Clutched in the dog's
teeth: A Stanley Cup. The tattoo is a souvenir of the '86 Cup that
Ludwig helped Montreal win (along with Skrudland, Carbonneau and
Stars' GM Bob Gainey).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to add another cup to it,'' Ludwig says. ``It was
actually worse. They toned it down a lot. There were lot of things
behind it at one time. I just keep those things inside now. I don't
let 'em out.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I got it, there wasn't a lot of thinking that went
into it. Actually I think (Dennis) Rodman was in the chair next to
me, so you know where that was coming from.'' JUST FLIRTING, OR ...
</P>
<P>
   Don't look now, but TCU and SMU both sent representatives to the
Conference USA meetings a couple of weeks ago. Why? Because both
schools would drop the Western Athletic Conference in an instant if
they thought they had a chance to switch to Conference USA.
</P>
<P>
   It's much more appealing geographically and both schools are
concerned that when the new super football conference shakes out,
they won't be included. The thinking is, they'd have a better
chance if they were aligned with Conference USA, plus it's a great
basketball conference with the likes of DePaul, Marquette,
Cincinnati, Memphis, Louisville, South Florida and UNC Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned. FRAN AT PEBBLE BEACH
</P>
<P>
   During the first week of June, Horned Frogs coach Dennis
Franchione vacationed at Pebble Beach. Here's the lowdown on his
golf game:
</P>
<P>
   First day: Spanish Bay _ He shoots a very respectable 85.
</P>
<P>
   Second day: Spyglass Hill _ A not-so-smooth-running 92 (I'd take
it).
</P>
<P>
   Third day: Pebble Beach _ Closing out with a bang, he rings up a
nifty 83.
</P>
<P>
   I propose a coach's shootout: Franchione, the Cowboys' Chan
Gailey and the Stars' Hitchcock. I'll drive the beer cart. A HUFF
AND A PUFF
</P>
<P>
   TCU punter and wide receiver Royce Huffman, drafted and signed
by the Astros, will play for their rookie team this summer and is
debating about whether to return to TCU for his senior football
season (he has used up his baseball eligibility). The Astros have
been hinting that if he does come back to the Frogs, they'd like to
see his role reduced to punting only. NICE TO SEE YOU, TOO
</P>
<P>
   Toronto manager and long-ago Ranger Jim Fregosi got into a
barroom brawl at a sports bar in south Philly last weekend and
showed up at the ballpark last Sunday with cuts around his left
eye. As the story goes, Fregosi, who once managed the Phillies, was
introduced to another man in the bar, reached out to shake hands
and got clocked.
</P>
<P>
   No official word on what the guy's beef was. Maybe he was still
upset that Fregosi had Mitch Williams in the game when Joe Carter
hit that game-winning home run for Toronto in the '93 series.
Baseball is investigating amid rumors that the attacker and a
friend who also jumped in might have had mob connections. NOT SO
PRO
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates, who prides himself on his
professionalism, lost his cool in the worst possible place last
week, blowing up at Yankee Stadium over a question being posed by
our Johnny Paul after another Rangers' loss there.
</P>
<P>
   Players easily overheard his postgame temper tantrum and weren't
impressed. ``Immature,'' is how one characterized it.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional outburst was definitely out of character for the
normally self-controlled Oates, who explained the next day that he
was reacting to the buildup of frustration at the Rangers' futility
against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he should let off steam more often. The Rangers snapped a
four-game losing streak the next night and won the final two games
there, the first time they've won consecutive games at Yankee
Stadium in six years. SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   New Orlando Magic coach Doc Rivers had former Mavs coach Jim
Cleamons in for an interview last week. ... The annual Jim
Reeves/UTA Celebrity Challenge golf tournament is scheduled for
Aug. 17 at Great Southwest Golf Club. Call UTA for more info. ...
Stars linemates Joe Nieuwendyk and Jamie Langenbrunner have been
roommates since Langenbrunner was called up from the minors. ... In
Chicago, rumors abound that Michael Jordan is moving his restaurant
to more high-toned Michigan Avenue and that Sammy Sosa will be
putting ``his'' restaurant into Jordan's old building on LaSalle.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
