<HEADLINE>
STOTTLEMYRE TO BEGIN THROWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 and TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Todd Stottlemyre's con job didn't work. The
right-hander wanted to throw for the first time on Saturday since
suffering a partial tear of his rotator cuff and labrum on May 17,
but Diamondbacks officials wouldn't allow it.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre will get his wish soon enough, however.
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled to throw lightly off flat ground on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm stronger than I've ever been at this time of year from the
(weight) lifting,'' Stottlemyre said.
</P>
<P>
   He admits he has been and is anxious, ``but on the first day,
I'm going to take it easy. How long will I throw? How far? there is
no right answer. We'll just have to see how it feels. The good
thing is that I'm a week ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have maintained a positive outlook. I've had the arm in the
throwing motion, an easy motion, and there has been no sharp pain,
no stiffness afterward. I think that's a good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some who might say that surgery would have been the
best route. Others think that even without surgery, Stottlemyre
likely won't pitch again this season after posting a 4-1 record
with a 3.59 ERA in nine starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are a lot of skeptics who say I probably won't
pitch this season,'' Stottlemyre said. ``But I've pitched with it
before and I'm in the best shape I can be.'' &QL; 
Finley has MRI &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Steve Finley, who has been bothered of late by
tenderness and stiffness in his lower back and hip area, had a
magnetic resonance imaging test on Saturday. It revealed a slightly
bulging disc in the lower back.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known when the injury originally occurred, but Manager
Buck Showalter said it should not keep Finley from playing. He is
expected to return to the lineup today. &QL; 
Look out, Babe! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OK, so he's not ready to be the next Babe Ruth and go from the
mound to the outfield and fame as one of baseball's great hitters
ever.
</P>
<P>
   But Randy Johnson is at least becoming respectable at the plate,
considering he entered this season with five lifetime hits and a
.091 average.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he's the Diamondbacks fourth leading pitcher at the
plate behind Todd Stottlemyre, Armando Reynoso and Brian Anderson.
Johnson, who is today's starting pitcher against Atlanta, has a
.170 average and eight hits and two doubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything you put your name on you want to put some pride in
and do the best you can,'' Johnson said. ``Obviously, hitting is
going to help me out in the game, too, and after not doing it for
such a long time I think I'm doing pretty well. I also realize I
have to get better at it and I'm working hard on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Short stops &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Erubiel Durazo and third baseman Jarrod Patterson
have been promoted from the Double-A El Paso affiliate to Triple-A
Tucson. Both were among the Texas League leaders in batting
average.
</P>
<P>
   In honor of Father's Day, the Diamondbacks will have their
annual family baseball game before today's game. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
