<HEADLINE>
DREAM MATCHUP: JOHNSON VS. GLAVINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - As matchups go, they don't get any better than the one
fans will see at Bank One Ballpark today: The Diamondbacks Randy
Johnson vs. Atlanta's Tom Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Glavine is off to a struggling start, backing up last
season's Cy Young winning 20-6 season with a 4-7 record and a 4.78
earned run average to date.
</P>
<P>
   But you're still talking about two Cy Young winners and two of
the most dominant lefthanders the game has seen in this decade.
Glavine served notice in his last start at Houston, giving up five
hits and striking out eight in an eight-inning winning effort, that
the slow start has aberration written all over it.
</P>
<P>
   Both Glavine and Johnson, who has won a club record five
consecutive starts and is 9-2 while leading the National League in
strikeouts (151), realize what they will be up against.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always going to be focused on the game no matter who's
pitching for them,'' Johnson said. ``But when I'm going up against
a pitcher of that caliber I know there is a super good liklihood of
him pitching a good game against our team, than there would be
against a younger or inexperienced person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to get the nine guys out that I'm facing and that's the
way I approach it. There's really nothing I can do against who I'm
facing. I just have to bear down myself. You can pitch against a
kid who gets called up from Class AA who nobody knows and he can
pitch a shutout against you just as easily as Tom Glavine can, so
you just have to bear down and pitch your own game.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, the only active NL pitcher with four 20-win seasons
under his belt, admits that squaring off against Johnson means a
bit more. Especially considering Johnson came away with an 8-3 win
in Atlanta in their only meeting this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You anticipate the match up a little bit more than you
probably do in a normal start,'' said Glavine, who owns a 3-1
liftime record against the Diamondbacks. ``You're always pumped to
go out and pitch because we only do it every four or five days. But
when you're facing another pitcher who is one of the elite pitchers
in the game, it definitely brings a different feel to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You anticipate going out there that your team isn't going to
get a lot of opportunities to score runs, so you better do the same
thing to their team because you want to give your guys a chance to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Glavine said, can be a double-edged sword, because a
pitcher easily could find himself trying to be too fine in such a
scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``You definitely have to fight that tendency,'' Glavine said.
``The No. 1 thing you have to keep in mind is I'm not going out
there facing Randy, or Randy facing me. That's only going to happen
three times a game maybe. You're going out there to get their guys
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tendency is to try to be a little bit better or sharper.
Most times you'll go out and think if I hold them to three runs or
less, I have a pretty good chance to win the game. Against a guy
like Randy you lower that to two runs or less. You still can go out
there and bear down without hurting yourself by trying to be too
fine and trying to do too much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' Greg Colbrunn has had the opportunity to play
behind both Johnson and Glavine during his career, claims the
matchup is a fan's delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last six, seven years they've been the most
dominating lefthanders in baseball,'' he said. ``Their pitching
styles are a big contrast, Randy being a power pitcher and Tom more
of a finesse guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a bottom line playing behind each of them, Colbrunn
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everytime you go out on the field you expect to win the
ballgame,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
