<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHO SHOWS THE WAY FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-RANGERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On a couple of occasions during Saturday's 7-4 victory
over the Texas Rangers, the Red Sox' starting pitcher could have
hit the Jin Ho Cho Trail.
</P>
<P>
   A three-run homer by third baseman Todd Zeile in the second
inning and a two-on, one-out jam in the fifth were moments for
pause, but Cho, dedicating his first major league victory to his
late father, helped stop Boston's two-game skid by pitching six
tough innings before Pudge Rodriguez's solo homer in the seventh
ended his day.
</P>
<P>
   Cho's effort with help from the bullpen, including two scoreless
innings by new closer Tim Wakefield (save No. 4) enabled the Sox to
eek out a much-needed win and keep them 1 1/2 games behind the
Yankees in the American League East.
</P>
<P>
   The win also featured a 15-hit Red Sox attack led by Nomar
Garciaparra's 3-for-4, two-RBI day. Garciaparra and first baseman
Mike Stanley padded the lead with seventh-inning solo homers.
</P>
<P>
   Cho, 7-1 with a 3.41 ERA at Pawtucket prior to his June 14
call-up, had pitched well but did not figure in the decision in his
first start against Minnesota Tuesday, going six innings and
allowing six hits, two earned runs, and no walks with three
strikeouts in a 4-3 Red Sox win.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts Saturday had Cho's fastball topping off at 92 miles per
hour, though Cho didn't think he spotted it well early in the game.
He also had good movement with his slider and changeup and scouts
were impressed with his poise and the way he rebounded from
adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy and excited,'' said Cho. ``I wished my father (who
died last year at age 63) could have seen this. I wanted to show
him my first major league win.''
</P>
<P>
   He said on the eve of Father's Day that he had kept a promise to
his father to make it to the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Cho is one of the Band-Aids being used by the Red Sox while
starters Bret Saberhagen and Juan Pena recover from injuries. The
win continued to illustrate the job done by Red Sox call-ups, who
are now a combined 13-0 (Brian Rose 4-0, Pena 2-0, John Wasdin 6-0,
and Cho 1-0).
</P>
<P>
   Cho credited being familiar with his teammates as the key reason
he's been successful this time around after going 0-3 with an 8.20
ERA in four starts with Boston last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I didn't understand things, but this year I'm able
to communicate with players and I'm able to fix the problem,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cho retired the first four batters before singles by Lee Stevens
and Rodriguez set the stage for Zeile's first-pitch homer, a
403-foot shot over the screen in left. But instead of the
23-year-old Korean righthander losing his poise, he set down the
next nine batters until Luis Alicea's fifth-inning single was
followed by a walk to No. 9 hitter Jon Shave. Again, instead of
buckling, Cho got Rusty Greer and Roberto Kelly on fly balls to
right.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the first four batters in the Rangers' order went 0 for
13 against Cho.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like he's much more comfortable out there,'' said
Garciaparra, who extended his hitting streak to seven games, during
which he's hitting .423 with five doubles and two home runs. ``It
seems that he's been through situations now that he's worked on in
the minors and knows how to get through them better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox looked at 31 pitches before scoring their first run
in a first inning when seven batters came to the plate. A Brian
Daubach double advanced Jose Offerman (3 for 5) to third, and after
starter Mark Clark, who lasted just 1 1/3 innings and was placed on
the 15-day disabled list after the game with soreness in his
pitching elbow, pitched around Garciaparra to load the bases,
Stanley's hard-hit grounder to Zeile at third handcuffed him,
allowing Offerman to score.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile more than made up for his error, giving the Rangers a 3-1
lead with his blast, but the Sox responded immediately with RBI
hits from Offerman, Daubach, and Garciaparra in the bottom half of
the second for a 4-3 Boston lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lead Cho cherished and held until the sixth, when it
expanded by one as Trot Nixon doubled in Damon Buford. It was
Nixon's second RBI and extra-base hit in his last 36 at-bats since
a June 1 seventh-inning homer.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was the first batter of the seventh and he scorched
the 0-1 offering, Cho's 91st pitch.
</P>
<P>
   After Kirk Bullinger and Mark Guthrie got the Red Sox through
the seventh, Wakefield and his personal catcher, Jason Varitek,
entered the game and shut down the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked I got to come in in the eighth,'' said
Wakefield, who hadn't pitched in four days. ``It's great they feel
I can do that and I'm grateful for the opportunity. I don't want
this to be my permanent job because I want Tom Gordon back, but I'm
just glad to be able to contribute to the team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
