<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2510 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROSCOST-ETHICS-AZR &LR;      06-20 2473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROSCOST-ETHICS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA HOUSE SPEAKER'S ETHICS AGAIN QUESTIONED  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE MCCLOY  
 and CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The most powerful man in Arizona's House of
Representatives is at it again, his critics complain, stretching
ethical standards as if they were rubber bands. And this time, even
some members of his own party say Jeff Groscost has gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   They say Groscost, a Valley jeweler with a history of financial
troubles, has made money as a consultant for groups that stand to
benefit from his power as speaker of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer and fall of 1998, Groscost was paid at least
$10,000 by a plumbing trade association to do what he calls
``membership development and relations,'' mainly involving the
recruitment of new members. During the closing hours of the 1999
legislative session, he made a procedural ruling that helped a bill
that would have benefited the trade group.
</P>
<P>
   The bill remained alive in the House, but died in the Senate a
few hours later.
</P>
<P>
   A financial-disclosure statement also shows Groscost was paid
more than $10,000 by Southwest Gas subsidiary LNG Energy Inc. to
lobby for liquefied natural gas franchises in Utah, New Mexico and
Wyoming in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Although Groscost has been a champion of bills supporting the
natural gas industry in Arizona, he said the work was outside the
state, so there was no conflict with his legislative role. But he
was introduced at a Utah legislative committee meeting as ``chair
of the Ways and Means Committee, Arizona Legislature'' when he made
a pitch for a subsidy to provide natural gas service to the town of
Panguitch on July 16, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost, R-Mesa, says the consulting jobs were legitimate. He
denies pulling any legislative tricks, or taking any improper
benefits. He boasts that he knows the legislative process better
than anyone, a point that just about any legislator readily
concedes. If he wanted to manipulate the process, he probably could
have done it without anyone realizing what was going on, he says.
</P>
<P>
   But to Dennis Burke, executive director of the government
watchdog group Arizona Common Cause, Groscost's actions involving
the plumbing contract were ``wildly inappropriate'' and deserving
of an ethics inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to be offering a precedent where special-interest
groups can hire legislative leaders during the summer and fall for
large sums of money and then do their bidding during the
legislative session. It's disheartening to see that precedent being
set by the speaker of the House,'' Burke says.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost says he's scrutinized his business dealings to avoid
even the appearance of a conflict of interest, consulting with
House attorneys and filing a letter listing bills he couldn't vote
on. If other House members have a problem with his actions,
Groscost says, then let them file an ethics complaint. But no one
has.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost argues that his outside work is no different from jobs
other lawmakers hold. He says virtually all lawmakers vote on bills
that affect their employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had anyone come tell me that to my face . . . I've
never had a member raise that issue,'' he says. ``I don't see any
more of a problem with that than the fact that we let teachers hold
a teaching job and still work here. . . . If it's a legal job, then
it is legal for the person to hold it and serve down here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Burke isn't the only one who disagrees with Groscost.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mike Gardner, R-Tempe, who would like to become speaker
when Groscost's term expires in 2001, says it's absolutely
inappropriate for any lawmaker to seek consulting contracts with
groups that lobby the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is what's legal and what's appropriate. I don't
think it is. Other people think it's fine,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many legislators may be skirting the intent of the
state's conflict-of-interest law.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner's wife, Patricia, for example, works for lobbyist Stan
Barnes. Yet Gardner declared no conflicts on any of the bills
Barnes was pushing. Last year, he offered floor amendments on an
insurance bill supported by Barnes. Gardner said he opposes most of
the bills Barnes lobbies.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Senate President Brenda Burns, R-Glendale, has
repeatedly backed legislation that passed this year to expand the
scope of practice for optometrists. Her husband, Bruce, is an
optometrist.
</P>
<P>
   And state Sen. John Huppenthal, R-Chandler, who works for Salt
River Project, voted on a deregulation bill last year that was
sought by SRP. Then-House Minority Leader Art Hamilton, an SRP
employee, and Sen. Chris Cummiskey, whose wife works for SRP, both
recused themselves from voting on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   All said they did nothing wrong _ that their actions remained
safely within Arizona's ethical guidelines. According to state law,
lawmakers have a conflict of interest when they support legislation
that benefits them financially. However, they are permitted to vote
on a bill that affects their professions or businesses, as long as
it equally benefits at least 10 other members of the same
profession or interest.
</P>
<P>
   The ethical cloud continues to hover over Groscost, partly
because of his blotchy background in business and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Former Attorney General Grant Woods reprimanded Groscost in 1992
and 1994 for failing to meet filing deadlines for campaign reports.
But Woods said in an interview last week that he had no problems
with Groscost after the rebuke.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's learned. He was hurting his credibility by attracting
attention to things that ultimately got in the way,'' Woods said.
``I believe he has matured. He's shown he's probably intellectually
superior to many of the other people down there. He enjoys the
process and he's learned it well. That gives him a leg up.''
</P>
<P>
   But fellow House Republicans remain critical.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve May, R-east Phoenix, says Groscost's actions in
accepting the consulting contracts were inappropriate even if they
were not illegal.
</P>
<P>
   May argues conflict-of-interest laws should be tightened so that
the threshold would be much lower. For instance, he says, it should
be illegal for lawmakers to declare a conflict and abstain from
voting, but still lobby for a bill.
</P>
<P>
   He believes lawmakers should be very careful about accepting
work from groups with business at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is their connection to these pieces of legislation
is through the people who gave them jobs,'' May says. ``When a
lobbyist or interest group gives you a job, you do feel an
obligation.''
</P>
<P>
   Groscost would not say how much he was paid by LNG Energy Inc.,
to lobby for the liquefied natural gas franchises. His financial
disclosure statement in the Secretary of State's Office lists the
compensation as more than $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Because Groscost has been a supporter of alternative fuels from
his first day in the Legislature, he disavows any conflict in
working for LNG. Dick Foreman, lobbyist for LNG's parent Southwest
Gas, offered him the job, Groscost says.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost adds that he checked with attorneys at the Arizona
House before accepting the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Foreman says LNG's contracts with Groscost were between
legislative sessions, so Groscost was not being paid while bills
affecting Southwest Gas were considered. Foreman says he did not
recall whether Groscost asked for the job, or LNG offered it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure he has approached people saying, `If you know of any
options, I'm trying to make a living,' '' Foreman says. ``I made
introductions for Jeff.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if there was even the inkling of a quid pro quo, that is
just not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The allegation that Groscost helped out the plumbers' trade
association surfaced in May when lawmakers were considering a bill
to speed up payments to plumbers and dozens of other construction
subcontracting groups.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was strongly supported by the Arizona
Subcontractors Coalition, a group of about 400 individual members
and more than a dozen trade associations. One of those groups is
the Piping Industry Progress and Education Trust Fund, a
Tempe-based lobbying and education group for plumbers. PIPE
officials said the bill was not part of their legislative agenda.
But they supported it through the Subcontractors Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost had a consulting contract with PIPE during the summer
and fall of 1998. He says he got the job after meeting PIPE
executive director Carl Triphahn either at the Capitol or through
activities with the Boy Scouts. Triphahn did not return calls
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   According to his 1999 financial-disclosure form, Groscost was
paid at least $10,000 for the work, which was at least 25 percent
of his income in 1998. Groscost declines to specify how much PIPE
paid him.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before the Legislature adjourned, the subcontractors'
prompt-pay bill appeared to be headed for defeat, falling one vote
short of the 31 required for final passage in the House.
</P>
<P>
   But shortly after the vote, the proposal became snared in
parliamentary warfare. Rep. Mike Gleason, R-Sun City West, made a
motion to reconsider the bill the following week, long after
adjournment, a routine maneuver that kills legislation. Another
motion was made to table the bill instead, and a third motion was
made to adjourn to a House caucus.
</P>
<P>
   A 45-minute delay ensued while Speaker Pro-Tem Joe Hart,
R-Kingman, conferred with House clerks. Groscost remained in his
office, working on other matters, he says, until he emerged to
invoke an obscure procedural rule to wipe out the three motions.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a move to table the issue was adopted. Hours later, the
bill was voted out of the House only to die in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Several House Republicans were outraged. House Majority Leader
Lori Daniels, R-Chandler, and Gardner made repeated trips to the
dais to argue Groscost had kept the bill alive improperly.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner assumed Groscost had declared a conflict on the bill
because he had not voted on the measure previously and he was not
on the floor when it was considered. Groscost never declared a
conflict. But he kept the bill alive and voted to move it on to the
Senate while lobbying fellow House members for support, Daniels
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any connection between the people that are pushing
the bill and the person implementing the rule to keep it alive,
that is a problem,'' Gardner says.
</P>
<P>
   Others think Groscost acted properly.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marilyn Jarrett, R-Mesa, a close Groscost ally, points out
that Daniels' husband is a subcontractor, and thus she should have
recused herself from the vote. Daniels scoffs, noting she opposed
the bill, while most subcontractors supported it.
</P>
<P>
   A leading House Democrat, Rep. Ken Cheuvront, also says Groscost
did nothing wrong. ``I don't know why he would have had to recuse
himself,'' says Cheuvront, who is a construction contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost says some members are angry simply because he beat them
at their own procedural game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point was we had done exactly what they had tried to do,
and we had done it about as tightly within the confines of the
rules so there couldn't be any question,'' he says. And Groscost
says he made sure he had no conflict of interest on the bill,
pointing to a ruling from House attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the session, he filed a conflict-of-interest letter
with the House clerk's office declaring he would not vote on any of
four bills on PIPE's agenda. Groscost was the only House member to
file such a letter during the session. ``I was the only one who
complied with the law,'' he says, contending that others surely had
conflicts of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost explains that technically, he didn't have a conflict
even on the four PIPE bills because his contract with the group had
expired, and so he had no financial interest in the bills.
</P>
<P>
   According to a ruling by House attorneys, the prompt-pay bill
posed no conflict for Groscost because plumbers were only one of
dozens of groups that could have been affected.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost also denies any conflict in working for LNG Inc. But he
acknowledges his job as a lawmaker helped get him the contract,
which he received before he was elected speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (LNG) would have had a clue who I was if I
wasn't a lawmaker. However, I'll point out there are 89 other
lawmakers who didn't get that opportunity . . .'' Groscost says.
``I don't think there's any question that I've got fairly good
political skills and that I'm a halfway decent salesman, and that's
what they needed. . . . Every now and then, the stars come into
alignment for a good reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Groscost, who is married and has four children, notes most
lawmakers cannot live on their legislative salaries alone.
</P>
<P>
   He sold a restaurant before he took office because he didn't
have the time to run it. His gem business suffers, he says, because
he misses many of the most lucrative holidays like Valentine's Day
and Mother's Day because of the legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   And Groscost puts in as many hours as anyone at the Capitol,
routinely staying well into the night during the session.
</P>
<P>
   He points to the fact that the so-called ``citizens''
Legislature isn't a very diverse body: It includes many members who
are supported by spouses who work, or are retirees or the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have one complaint, it's that we don't have enough
citizens down here, people who have tried to meet a payroll or put
themselves at risk financially,'' Groscost says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a legislator shouldn't mean you sacrifice your kids'
ability to go to college. . . . The first few years I was down here
we went through the savings accounts, the CDs, and the IRAs. I
don't think anybody has ever said that somebody who works here
should not be able to have any other job. Certainly . . . $24,000
is not sufficient. This is supposed to be public service, not an
unmanageable sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   Groscost says at least two of his future clients will have no
business pending at the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, it was announced one of those clients is Sen. John
McCain, who hired Groscost to help run his Arizona presidential
primary campaign. The announcement follows Groscost's unsuccessful
efforts in the closing days of the legislative session to delay the
primary balloting in Arizona by a month.
</P>
<P>
   McCain supporters backed the date change to avoid the
possibility of losing Arizona before competing in states like
California.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost's contract with the campaign runs through Dec. 31,
about two weeks before the next session begins. He declines to say
how much will be paid. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCloy can be reached at (602) 444-8111 or at
mike.mccloy(at)pni.com via e-mail. Chris Moeser can be reached at
(602) 444-8069 or at chris.moeser(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
