u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-USOPEN-BOS &LR;      06-20 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART IN DRIVER'S SEAT AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Not that the 68 golfers remaining in the hunt
for the 99th United States Open championship can say they haven't
been warned. The large sign is stuck into the grass directly across
from the practice putting green on Pinehurst No. 2, for all eyes to
see.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obviously the function of the championship course to
present competitors with a variety of problems that will test
competitors with a variety of problems that will test every type of
shot which a golfer of championship ability should be qualified to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   The sign is signed by Donald Ross. It is the credo of Pinehurst
No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Which, for the third day, whittled and whittled and whittled
down the Open field more and more, Saturday's shavings leaving only
one golfer able to better par for three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   That golfer is Payne Stewart, whose birdie on the 18th hole left
him with a 2-over par 72 for the day, but with a three-round score
of 209, 1 under par, and a shot better than a struggling Phil
Mickelson (73), and two shots ahead of Tiger Woods (72) and Tim
Herron, winner of the 1996 Honda Classic, the 1997 LaCantera Texas
Open, and the 1999 Bay Hill Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's deja vu is all too real, and a bit too painful. Last
year at Olympic Club in San Francisco, Stewart also was the only
golfer entering the final round with an under-par score. Indeed,
his four-stroke lead entering Sunday play was the second-largest
lead by an Open non-winner, second only to the five-shot lead Mike
Brady had at Brae Burn in 1919 before he lost in a playoff to
Walter Hagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wanted another serious opportunity to win the Open,''
said Stewart after Saturday's round, ``and now that I have it, I've
got to make the most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart became stymied at the 12th hole last year when his tee
shot landed in a divot and he delayed while seeking a ruling on
whether he was entitled to relief. Instead of relief, he was given
extra pressure as United States Golf Association rules guru Tom
Meeks placed Stewart ``on the clock'' for slow play.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart bogeyed two of the next four holes and ended up losing
the Open to Lee Janzen by a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do like the way I played,'' Stewart said of Saturday's
round, despite his touring Pinehurst 2 over par. ``To me, a 72 was
a par round. You knew very few birdies were going to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson kept the media waiting for two hours after his round
for more pressing matters _ work on his swing at the practice
range. ``I hit the ball awfully sloppy,'' said the southpaw. At the
start of his round, he was nervous ``and I felt I was steering the
ball a lot. The swing was getting a little longer and sloppier.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was one of many who struggled Saturday, though,
Mickelson would not take a shot at the course. ``It's a testament
to how great this golf course is that only one player is under
par,'' said Mickelson. What is so demanding about Pinehurst, he
went on, ``is that even on a very good ball-striking day, the best
golfers are still going to miss five or six greens.'' Thus, the
secret is get up and down as quickly and as well as possible, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. In an amazing display of the effect of Ross's Pinehurst
No. 2 and the refining of the course by the USGA, an amazing 20 of
the 68 golfers played 18 holes without notching even one birdie.
Even more, a miniscule number of 80 birdies were made by the 68
golfers, compared to 406 bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the snide comments by some golfers were these of
Australia's Chris Perry, who shot a 79 Saturday: ``Boys, they say
an object of this game is to land the ball on the green,'' said the
Aussie. ``You hit the ball on the green and the ball will stay on
it. But not here. Here is the only place in the world where you hit
a 7-iron into the green and it rolls another 25 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Rees Jones, the ``course doctor'' for the Open and the USGA,
merely smiled when he was told of the comments of Perry and others
that Pinehurst was unfair by saying, ``That's the rub of the
green.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite scoring over par, Stewart was not alone among those
golfers who felt pleased leaving the 18th green despite scores that
groaned. Along with Stewart, Mickelson was able to birdie the 18th
(``I was able to hit my only cut shot of the day there''), while
Woods was superbly pleased with his recovery from a disastrous
first two holes, on which he frittered away three strokes to par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that players, especially those near the lead, were
going to make some bogeys out there,'' said Woods, who was 1 under
for his 16 final holes. ``I knew I just had to make some birdies,
but I also knew I couldn't get aggressive on this golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   There are eight golfers within five strokes of Stewart and
Sunday's final round should be a pulse-quickening show for many,
many reasons. Mickelson, of course, is trying to win his first
major; Stewart wants redemption from last year; Woods needs to show
he can be a major competitor in the majors; and Vijay Singh, three
shots behind at 2 over and whose golf has been superb, can make a
breakthrough move with a victory. Then, of course there also is the
world's top-ranked player, David Duval, who has yet to win a major.
Starting the day tied for the lead, he struggled to a 5-over 40 on
the front nine before regrouping for nine straight pars for a 75.
He is also just three behind Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, though, it will be fascinating to see how pressure
of winning the Open dovetails with the incredibly fine standard of
golf needed to conquer this Ross masterpeice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
