<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBS EATING CROW  
 NOMO, NOW A BREWER, TURNS HEADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whenever the subject of  &UR; Hideo Nomo comes up on Chicago's north
side, the local baseball officials become slightly touchy and
combative. After all, the Cubs had Nomo in their grasp but refused
to take the final step of calling him up to the majors back in
April.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo walked away from the Cubs and the possibility to be paid
$2.8 million, which was his right under the terms of his contract,
and instead accepted a $200,000 deal to pitch for the Milwaukee
Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   Most embarrassing for the Cubs was losing to Nomo on Tuesday
night in Milwaukee. Cubs Manager  &UR; Jim Riggleman was asked by a
Japanese reporter if the Cubs would like to have Nomo back now.
</P>
<P>
   ``How would you like to eat that microphone?'' he said with a
strained laugh. ``How can I answer that? He pitches for them now.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to this weekend, and Nomo is 4-1 (which should be
at least 6-1) with a 4.01 ERA. He has 46 strikeouts in 51 innings
and took no time in establishing himself as the Brewers' best
starter. In eight starts, Nomo has given up more than two runs just
twice.
</P>
<P>
   All of this leads to Nomo's future. Since being released by the
Mets during spring training and the Cubs in early April, the 1995
NL Rookie of the Year who took the country by storm that summer has
found his niche in the small-market haven of Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Brewers seemingly having no shot at competing for
the National League West title and their ability to keep Nomo next
year very much in doubt, talk has begun circulating about how much
longer Milwaukee will hang onto Nomo, who pitches in front of
several scouts whenever he starts. An attractive deal from a
contender for Nomo's services is a scenario that very well could
develop soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very needed here, and I really appreciate that
feeling,'' Nomo said. ``The surroundings are very good for me. I am
very happy to be here, and I hope to come back. But management has
to consider different things, so I can't be sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee Manager  &UR; Phil Garner, who has little to work with when
it comes to a rotation, is aware of the possibilities. He remains
focused, however, on trying to right the Brewers' ship and keep his
own job.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be true at some point, but now now,'' Garner said of
the speculation surrounding Nomo. ``I don't think we need to be
throwing in the towel.'' &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
The recent interleague games saw Cleveland's  &UR; Dwight Gooden hit the
eighth home run of his career, the highest total among active
pitchers. Who holds the records for home runs by a pitcher in each
league? &QL; 
Hey Abbott! &QL; 
Milwaukee pitcher  &UR; Jim Abbott reached a significant milestone last
week, one that should have caught the attention of baseball and
life fans everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott collected his first major league hit last Tuesday. So
what, you may ask? Well, let's remember Abbott was born without a
right hand. The mere fact that he made it all the way to the major
leagues is worthy of praise alone.
</P>
<P>
   But to finally get a hit, while basically holding the bat with
one hand, deserves high praise, indeed. Since he played his entire
career in the American League before this year, Abbott never had an
official at-bat in a game before April.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday night, in his 14th at-bat and 17th plate appearance
(he also has three sacrifice bunts), Abbott drove a single over the
head of Cubs shortstop  &UR; Jose Hernandez. On top of everything, it
was an RBI single. The Brewers managed to lose the game, which took
away any luster Abbott could feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you play the game for _ moments like that . . .''
said Abbott, who is 1-5 with a 6.87 ERA this season. ``I was
wondering if I ever was going to get a hit. I just want to hold my
own up there and not be a complete liability.'' &QL; 
Voodoo in Queens &QL; 
The National League office may have a scandal on its hands if it
deems New York Mets catcher  &UR; Mike Piazza is using an illegal
substance on his bats.
</P>
<P>
   It seems reliever  &UR; Turk Wendell performs a mystical ceremony on
Piazza's bat from time to time. After putting his magic spell on it
Tuesday night in Cincinnati, Piazza belted a monster 443-foot home
run.
</P>
<P>
   The next night in St. Louis, Piazza delivered a pair of doubles
to extend his hitting streak to 19 games. He raised it to 22 in
Saturday's game at St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza knows to use the power sparingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go to the well too often,'' said Piazza, who is
batting .325. ``You don't want to dilute the mystical powers.'' &QL; 
Tampa Bay Buccaneers? &QL; 
These days, little appears to be standing in the way of the Tampa
Bay Devil Rays' out-of-control spiral toward the worst record in
the majors.
</P>
<P>
   But if their farm system is any indication of what's on the
horizon, then it appears a football mentality will be setting in
with this ballclub in the coming years. The Devil Rays sport five
players, all quarterbacks, who were either headed to major college
football programs or currently there.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cal Crawford, slotted to become Nebraska's next great option
quarterback, instead accepted a $1.55 million signing bonus last
week to give up football for baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Already in Tampa Bay's system are  &UR; Doug Johnson, the starting
quarterback at Florida who spends his summers hitting baseballs;
 &UR; Kenny
 &UR; Kelly, listed at the top of the University of Miami's depth chart
at quarterback, who is batting .392 at Class A St. Petersburg;
 &UR; Jason
 &UR; Standridge, a right-hander, who turned down a scholarship at
Auburn; and  &UR; Marquis Roberts, another pitcher, who had a full ride
at Fresno State before taking the Devil Rays' baseball offer. &QL; 
I left my heart . . . &QL; 
 &UR; Chris Speier, the Diamondbacks Triple A manager at Tucson,
indicated recently how much of a pull he still feels for the San
Francisco Giants' organization, where he broke in as a solid rookie
in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy where I am, but I'd love that opportunity to be back
at the big-league level with the Giants,'' Speier said before
ceremonies to honor the all-1970s Giants team. ``There's a special
place in your heart for your first organization.'' &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
 &UR; Wes Ferrell, who bounced from Cleveland to Boston to Washington and
the Yankees during a 13-year run in the American League from 1927
to '39, hit a major league-record 36 home runs as a pitcher. Hall
of Famer  &UR; Warren Spahn holds the National League record with 35.
Ferrell also holds the single-season record with nine, hit as a
member of the 1931 Indians. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; Forget the guy who popped him, we want to meet his wife: Toronto
Manager  &UR; Jim Fregosi was involved in a bar brawl last week when the
Blue Jays visited Philadelphia, a club he managed for years. ``I'm
very fortunate that when I came home with this black eye, my wife
didn't blacken the other one,'' Fregosi said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Eerie, very eerie: Houston Manager  &UR; Larry Dierker's seizure
last weekend occurred just hours after former Astros All-Star
pitcher  &UR; J.R. Richard, who suffered a career-ending stroke before a
game in 1980, tossed out the ceremonial first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Tito Fuentes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Maybe a dismissive
 &UR; wave of the hand was all he needed: Since Baltimore Manager  &UR; Ray
Miller cast aside his right fielder in the dugout more than a week
ago,
 &UR; Albert Belle has been on a tear, going 13 for 29 (.448) since then
entering the weekend series.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; And they wonder why fans think they're out of touch
 &UR; with reality: The Chicago White Sox decided to give their players a
half-share of road meal money for games played across town at
Wrigley Field last weekend, amounting to $103.50 for each player.
One reason? ``We just felt that it shouldn't be out of the players'
pockets to go over and pay the clubhouse man for his services,''
Sox General Manager
 &UR; Ron Schueler said. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
With the addition of second baseman  &UR; Craig Counsell, Los Angeles
has the same number of 1997 World Champions on its roster as the
Florida Marlins, who won that series. The Dodgers have  &UR; Kevin
Brown, &UR; Gary Sheffield,  &UR; Devon White and Counsell. The Marlins have
 &UR; Antonio
 &UR; Alfonseca,  &UR; Alex Fernandez,  &UR; Cliff Floyd and  &UR; Livan Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Since Mets GM  &UR; Steve Phillips fired pitching coach
 &UR; Bob Apodaca, New York starters were 7-0 with a 3.20 ERA entering
the club's weekend series against St. Louis.  &UR; Al Leiter, who was
2-5, is 3-0 with a 1.71 ERA since  &UR; Dave Wallace took over as
pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   Inconsistent in his 15 starts, Seattle Manager  &UR; Lou
 &UR; Piniella has decided to move  &UR; Jeff Fassero, the Mariners' opening
day starter, to the bullpen. Fassero is 3-7 with a 7.23 ERA and has
given up a major league-high 25 home runs.  &UR; Melvin Bunch will
replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Since Belle's consecutive games streak stopped at 392 after a
benching last week and Colorado's  &UR; Vinny Castilla saw his streak
stopped at 307 because of a prolonged slump, the new active leader
for games played is Orioles outfielder  &UR; B.J. Surhoff, who had
appeared in 226 straight games entering Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City relievers had saved nine games entering the weekend
series at Toronto and blown 15. No club has ever blown more games
than saved in a full season. The 1994 Dodgers blew 21 and saved 20,
but that was a strike-shortened season.
</P>
<P>
   Since CF  &UR; Lance Johnson landed on the disabled list because of
injuries, Cubs leadoff hitters have not fared well. Entering the
weekend, Cubs leadoff hitters are batting a combined .105 (4 for
38). &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
In what would amount to a blockbuster deal, Detroit is mulling over
the possibility of making an offer to Toronto for first
baseman &UR; Carlos Delgado, one of the premier power hitters in the
game who may be falling out of favor in Toronto. One trade
possibility would be Tigers first baseman  &UR; Tony Clark.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis is showing a strong interest in acquiring Chicago
White Sox starter  &UR; Jaime Navarro, who is finally starting to pitch
well. One obstacle is Navarro's guaranteed $5 million salary in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Former Cy Young Award winner  &UR; Jack McDowell, who has undergone
several surgeries on his arm, threw 46 pitches in a simulated game
last week. McDowell is scheduled to start an exhibition game for
the Angels on Monday against their Class A affiliate in Erie (Pa.)
and, if all goes well, could return to action for Anaheim within a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati and Toronto, which continue to fall out of
contention, are talking about a deal that would send  &UR; David Wells
back to the Reds (he was there for half a season). If a deal for
Wells cannot be worked out, look for the Reds to still make a trade
for a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, which is in the market for a first baseman, is
trying to make a run at Cincinnati, where former Royals outfielder
 &UR; Michael Tucker remains mostly a bench player. Tucker began his
career as an infielder. But if the Reds continue to hold out for a
young pitcher, no deal will be made.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's  &UR; Paul Sorrento is a player seeking a change of
scenery. The experiment to move him to left field has failed and
Sorrento is barely playing since the club called up  &UR; Bubba Trammell
last week. Sorrento, who is being paid $3 million this season and
has another $3 million club option for next season, may not be
marketable. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. ClevelandAll this offense and the Indians lead the AL in stolen
bases, too.  &QL; 
2. NY YankeesSS  &UR; Derek Jeter is the best all-around player in the
game.  &QL; 
3. Atlanta &UR; Tom Glavine and  &UR; Greg Maddux finally put together solid
consecutive outings.  &QL; 
4. Arizona &UR; Vladimir Nunez, you're the next contestant on ``Can
You'' ``Close the Game''?  &QL; 
5. HoustonAstros vowed to keep the club in first place while &UR; Larry
Dierker recovers.  &QL; 
6. TexasFuture superstar CF  &UR; Ruben Mateo was called up. Will it be
for good?  &QL; 
7. BostonScary but true: Knuckleballer  &UR; Tim Wakefield is the new
temporary closer.  &QL; 
8. NY MetsThe Mets seem capable of winning games only when chaos
rules.  &QL; 
9. San FranciscoAll the Giants want to do is stay within striking
distance of Arizona. &UR; BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. FloridaBig news!  &UR; Kevin Orie takes over as first baseman.  &QL; 
29. Tampa BayThe state of big-league ball in Florida is completely
rank.  &QL; 
28. MinnesotaThe starters' 6.43 ERA ranks 14th among 14 AL clubs.  &QL; 
27. San DiegoAt least there's  &UR; Tony Gwynn's march toward 3,000
hits.  &QL; 
26. MontrealSeven players have had their shot at leading off.  &QL; 
25. MilwaukeePitcher &UR; Cal Eldred is yanked from the rotation and put
in bullpen.  &QL; 
24. Kansas CityRoyals fever has given way to a royal case of
sickness.  &QL; 
23. DetroitThey're finally admitting they may be a year behind
schedule in Motown.  &QL; 
22. Anaheim &UR; Terry Collins goes from extension to the hot seat
within two weeks. ON THE RISE &QL; 
 &UR; Colorado Rockies: A victory Wednesday would have pushed the Rockies
to the elusive .500 mark. But a 15-2 loss knocked those plans by
the wayside. Still, Colorado had lost just four times in its
previous 13 games entering the Rockies weekend series against
Florida. Colorado has seen the evolution of  &UR; Pedro Astacio, who has
decided to take on the role of staff ace. After starting the season
0-3, Astacio is 6-2 in his past nine starts. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL; 
 &UR; Chicago Cubs: Nine games over .500 less than two weeks ago, the
Cubs have seen their record drop and their deficit increase in the
NL Central standings. During a stretch that included six losses in
seven games, Cubs pitchers combined for a 9.00 ERA. Starter  &UR; Steve
Trachsel, expected to be one of the better starters, fell to 2-9
after losing Wednesday. Rookie starter  &UR; Kyle Farnsworth, has
started to struggle also. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
Cincinnati Manager  &UR; Jack McKeon decided to have a little fun with
Cleveland Manager  &UR; Mike Hargrove last weekend. When the two met
with umpires at home plate to discuss Cinergy Field's ground rules,
McKeon pointed to a new bright yellow line of paint that had been
applied to the second deck, high above the playing field, and
quipped, ``That yellow line way up there? Cleveland's home runs
have to hit above that line. Ours just have to clear that yellow
line on top of the wall.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL; 
In this case, it's out of the rotation. Left-handed pitcher &UR; Ryan
Mills, a former All-American at Arizona State, has been taken out
of the rotation at Class A Fort Myers (Fla.) while Minnesota's No.
1 pick in last year's draft works on his mechanics. Mills was 2-5
with an 8.17 ERA before he was lifted from the Miracle's rotation.
He has 22 strikeouts, but had issued 36 walks and hit eight
batters. Twins officials hope to straighten out Mills' delivery and
thought process. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at (602) 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
