r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CUP-USA-DENMARK-A     06-20 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-USA-DENMARK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DOMI NATES DEN MARK  
 HAMM'S GOAL ERASES SLUGGISH START BY AMERICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM THOMAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ When U.S. star Mia Hamm drilled the ball
into the net, it sent an emphatic message to the Danish team and
the 14 others gathered in this country for the international
women's soccer championships:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our World Cup and you're not welcome to it''.``''
</P>
<P>
   Hamm's goal in the 17th minute turned the momentum in the U.S.
national team's favor and sparked the Americans to a 3-0 victory
over Denmark in the opening match Saturday of the Women's World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The win, in front of 78,972 fans at Giants Stadium _ the largest
crowd to watch a women's sporting event of any kind, anywhere _
gave the United States three points in Group A and clearly
emphasized that the Americans deserve the role of tournament
favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a tournament like this, you really want to start off on the
right foot,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm got the U.S. team started with both feet. The forward
gathered a long pass from Brandi Chastain, touched it deftly past a
defender with her right foot and blasted a left-footed shot into
the upper part of the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little nervous in the first half and didn't play our
game,'' U.S. forward Cindy Parlow said. ``But fortunately we got
the 1-0 lead and that really helped us. Mia was outstanding. She
was out there telling us to settle down, settle down, play our
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Denmark was surprisingly in control at the start with an
aggressive counter attack and physical play at both ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm satisfied,'' Denmark Coach Jorgen Hvidemose said. ``We
should have scored a goal or two, especially in the first half. If
you score the first goal, often you win the match.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamm's goal seemed to deflate the Danes, who became flat-footed
at midfield and disorganized on defense. The United States created
three more good scoring chances in the first half, the best being a
shot by Parlow that hit off the right post in the 24th minute. The
forward also had a shot that tipped just over the crossbar early in
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like I've been hitting the bar all week (in
practice),'' Parlow said. ``It's become a joke with the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Parlow wasn't the only U.S. player to be frustrated by missed
opportunities. Kristine Lilly had one shot hit the crossbar and
missed wide left on another while going one-on-one against Denmark
goalkeeper Dorthe Larsen.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly was finally able to convert in the 89th minute, dribbling
across the top of the box before hitting a left-footed shot into
the left corner of the net to finish the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   That goal came after Julie Foudy gave the Americans a 2-0 lead
and what at the time was some much-needed breathing room. Again, it
was Hamm who was the catalyst, sending a pass through the box that
Foudy hit high and hard past Larsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mia was awesome,'' U.S. Coach Tony DiCicco said. ``She wanted
the responsibility, wanted the ball, wanted to make the shot or get
it to someone else for the score.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We created some good chances up front, and when we needed to
finish, we did so,'' said Hamm, the world leader in career goals
with 110 and counting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense played really solid throughout.''
</P>
<P>
   Denmark managed only three shots, two that tested U.S.
goalkeeper Briana Scurry. The first came on a corner kick moments
after Scurry had the wind knocked out of her in a collision with
Denmark's Mikka Hansen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hurting, but I had to get up,'' said Scurry, who
struggled to her feet. ``I didn't want to, but the ball was still
loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Scurry's final save came with only seconds left in the match.
Janni Johansen Lund broke through the defense and fired at Scurry
from close range, but the goalkeeper hugged the ball and earned a
standing ovation from her teammates on the bench as time ran out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting the three points was very important for us,'' Hamm
said. ``Everyone was really excited in the locker room. It was a
very, very proud moment for us. It's only the first day, but this
was a great start.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team will play Nigeria in Chicago on Thursday in the
second of its three Group A matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we did a good job against a quality team,'' DiCicco
said. ``We're delighted with the win and the three points, but this
is only the beginning. We'll enjoy it now, then start to focus on
Nigeria.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
