<HEADLINE>
SEARCH FOR ASSISTANTS TO INTENSIFY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Coyotes are expected to interview candidates for
two assistant coaching positions this week in Boston at the NHL
Entry Draft and should have both hires in place by July 1.
</P>
<P>
   One coach will be responsible for working with the defensemen
and the other for working with the forwards. The Coyotes retained
goalie instructor  &UR; Benoit Allaire.
</P>
<P>
   Two candidates identified before the club hired  &UR; Bobby Francis
as head coach are New York Islanders assistant  &UR; Wayne Fleming and
former NHL player-turned-broadcaster  &UR; Ryan Walter.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager  &UR; Bobby Smith has met with both men, but at the
time, it was about possible assistant coaching positions for
then-Coach  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld. Smith did not rule out either, however,
from joining the staff under Francis, who was hired on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other potential candidates include  &UR; Dave Farrish, the head coach
of the Springfield Falcons, the Coyotes' top minor-league affiliate
in the American Hockey League and possibly  &UR; Peter Laviolette, who
guided the Providence Bruins to the AHL's Calder Cup championship
in his first year on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Francis coached Providence for two seasons and then spent the
past two years as an assistant with the parent Boston Bruins. The
Coyotes would need permission from Boston management before
interviewing Laviolette, 34, who is close to Francis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby (Francis) called after we won the Cup just to say
congratulations and I said the same thing to him after word got out
that he was going to coach the Coyotes,'' Laviolette said. ``We
didn't talk about anything else and nobody's talked to me about a
job in Phoenix. Right now, I'm under contract with the Boston
Bruins as the coach in Providence and I love my job. I'm here and
that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another coach Smith and Francis may decide to target is former
Roadrunners player &UR; Bruce Boudreau, a longtime minor-league scoring
champion who has since made a successful switch to coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Boudreau guided the Mississippi Sea Wolves of the East Coast
Hockey League to the Kelly Cup championship this past season and
previously, coached the Fort Wayne Komets to the International
Hockey League's Turner Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea Wolves have a bit of connection with the Coyotes.
Springfield has a working agreement with Mississippi and constantly
shuttles players back and forth when needed.
</P>
<P>
   But Boudreau has already received interest from elsewhere. He
may have an opportunity to coach the Los Angeles Kings' new AHL
affiliate, the Lowell Lock Monsters, and has been contacted by the
Atlanta Thrashers about a similar job in the NHL expansion team's
system. &QL; 
Contract talks &QL; 
The Coyotes have had preliminary discussions with unrestricted free
agent  &UR; Mike Sullivan, one of their better defensive forwards last
season, and it's possible the center/left wing could agree to terms
on a new contract by this week.
</P>
<P>
   Smith indicated it appears doubtful the team will re-sign center
 &UR; Bob Corkum, also an unrestricted free agent. The New York Rangers
and Los Angeles Kings are expected to make him an offer after July
1. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
