<HEADLINE>
TIGER HAS EARNED BATTLE STRIPES 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Double bogey, bogey. Nice start, Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this had happened last year,'' he shrugged, ``I probably
wouldn't have handled it as well.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is the slowly-maturing Tiger Woods. He knew there was a
difference between blowing three shots to par in the third round of
the US Open at Pinehurst No. 2 and blowing three shots to par at,
say, the Phoenix Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I started out double bogey, bogey on a regular tour
event,'' he pointed out, ``I'd probably lose about five shots.''
</P>
<P>
   But in this tournament, on this course, under these conditions,
there was no need to panic. Tiger Woods knew that before too long
his competition would also make a mistake or two. Or three. Or, in
the case of the imploding John Daly, 11. The slowly-maturing Tiger
Woods didn't throw or slam down a club. He just reminded himself
that the object of the game is to shoot par here and that there
were 16 holes to go. He settled down, picked up a stroke to par
with birdies on Nos. 4 and 15, bogeyed just one more hole (14) and
put a 37-35_72 on the board.
</P>
<P>
   And guess what? Eldrick ``Tiger'' Woods has just as good a
chance to win the 1999 United States Open as anybody. He is only
two strokes behind Payne Stewart. And doesn't NBC like that.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger hasn't compiled a very good dossier in this tournament
during his young life. He played it twice as an amateur,
withdrawing in 1995 after an opening round 74 at Shinnecock Hills
and finishing in a tie for 82d with a 14-over 294 at Bloomfield
Hills in '96. As a professional, he placed 19th (Congressional) and
16th (Olympic CC). He has never been a factor.
</P>
<P>
   But he came here as one of the favorites, as much for his
performance in winning The Memorial two weeks ago as anything else.
For en route to his 15-under score of 273 Tiger was forced to
demonstrate a Houdini-aspect to his game that most people feel
would be necessary for success here at hallowed No. 2. Tiger won
that tournament with a variety of great salvaged pars and superb
birdies resulting from creativity around the greens. In picking
Tiger to win, many people cited the apparent convergence of man,
course, and time.
</P>
<P>
   It may all turn out to be true.
</P>
<P>
   He is definitely in a winning frame of mind. ``I'll take it,''
he said of his 2-over score on a day when only one man, Steve
Stricker, could break par. ``After the start I had, I'll certainly
take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger continues to marvel at Pinehurst No. 2, particularly the
amazing greens. ``My game plan here is very simple,'' he says. ``I
want to hit the fairways and the greens. I hit a lot of greens
today. The ball didn't stay on them, but I hit 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   He then laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, that's the way it is here,'' he explained. ``You've
got to spin the ball to make sure it stays on the greens.''
</P>
<P>
   That astonishing Masters victory now seems like it happened a
very long time ago. Tiger is now such a towering presence on the
American (and, indeed, international) sporting scene it always
seems he's been around as long as Arnold Palmer. So much was
expected of Tiger after that explosive Augusta domination in 1997
that it is possible to frame him as an underachiever if you are so
inclined.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is Tiger's then unpolished game meshed perfectly with
Augusta. That particular confrontation was unfair, a total
mismatch. The US Open is different. This tournament presents
different challenges for all golfers, and particularly difficult
challenges to young ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what you guys are thinking,'' said the man who
won't turn 24 until the end of this year, ``but I am still young.
I'm learning how to handle myself and how to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people thought the Memorial was a better preparation for
this tournament than Tiger does. ``It really didn't matter,'' he
declared. ``This is something I've been preparing for my entire
life. Anyone watching me play since I was a kid would attest to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even people who didn't have that pleasure understand that Tiger
was a Mozart-like golfing prodigy who has no recollection of a life
spent without a golf club in his hand. Earl Woods raised his boy to
be the greatest golfer of all-time, and one of the ways that
designation might some day be his is if he has a string of US Opens
to brag about.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he some day manages to challenge Jack Nicklaus and
Willie Anderson for Open titles (4), he is likely to remember any
championship won at Pinehurst No. 2 with more fondness than
anything else. Consider this: Asked just how much of a legitimate
target there is on virtually every green if you'd like to have a
reasonable birdie putt, he replied, ``2 yards by 2 yards.'' And
then, he added, ``you've got to have the correct spin.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he's complaining. Pinehurst inspires awe, not anger.
``It's fair.'' he said. ``The gold course is set up fairly. If the
USGA had set the rough up to the greens, I don't think you'd hear
guys saying such nice things, but they haven't. Most US Open
courses require you to grab a lob wedge and hack your way out. Here
you need a plethora of shots.''
</P>
<P>
   He has all anyone can rightfully ask for here in Sunday's final
round, and that is a fair chance. ``You're gonna make mistakes
here,'' he said. ``Everyone's gonna do it. Hopefully, you don't
make them down the stretch on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Tiger said he was off for a brief stint at the
practice tee. Then he was going to watch the Sabres and Stars. He
was feeling good. He can win the US Open before his 24th birthday,
which is pretty much what Earl Woods had in mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
