<HEADLINE>
TWINS TOWER OVER NHL DRAFT  
 SWEDISH PAIR EXPRESS DESIRE TO STAY TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are the Twin Peaks of the 1999 NHL entry draft, the two
highest-rated brothers ever to enter the same draft class. But
Swedish twins Daniel and Henrik Sedin might be more Double Trouble
than Dynamic Duo.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the mirror-image 18-year-olds aren't awesome
talents. They are the top two-rated players among Europeans,
according to the final release by the Central Scouting Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel, a 6-foot-1 left wing, is a dynamite, can't-miss
prospect. Henrik, a 6-foot-2 center, is a hungry, tougher version
of his twin who also is a sure thing. All scouts agree they will be
future stars in the NHL for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the catch. The twins don't want to be separated. They
want to play in the same organization when they come to North
America in another year. If it doesn't happen, both of them figure
to be impossible to sign and, for the first time, it's being
whispered they may opt to remain in Sweden indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're starting to hear,'' one scout for a
Canadian-based club said. ``It makes you wonder how much their
stock is really worth now.''
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, doesn't bode well for any of the first five
teams picking in Saturday's draft at the FleetCenter in Boston. If
one team picks Daniel, it will be under intense pressure to swing a
draft-day deal or a later trade to pick up Henrik as well. A costly
gamble? You bet. But whichever team does it will be the most-talked
about club in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not saying they won't play on separate teams in the
NHL,'' said Michael Barnett, the twins' agent, ``but time is on
their side because neither of them is playing in the NHL next
season anyway. We think there's an obvious advantage for a team
with one of the twins to try and get the other one, and some teams
have expressed an interest in doing that. We'll do everything we
can to try and make that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most likely candidates to make a pitch for both Sedin
brothers are the Atlanta Thrashers, who pick second overall, and
the Vancouver Canucks, who select third. But don't count out the
next two teams in the order, the Chicago Blackhawks and the New
York Islanders, both of whom have scouted Europe thoroughly and are
in desperate need of signing young, explosive talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to have them both,'' Thrashers General Manager Don
Waddell told ``The Hockey News.'' ``One would be terrific. Two
would be fantastic. Although I'm confident they'll be excellent
players whether they're together or apart in the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel scored 21 goals and 42 points in 50 games last season for
MoDo of the Swedish elite league. Henrik had 12 goals and 34 points
in 49 games. But which twin do you pick first?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you like a scorer, Daniel is is the better player,'' said
Per Beckman, the twin's coach with MoDo. ``But if you like a worker
on the whole ice, Henrik is better. Henrik is good in both ends and
always plays for the team. Daniel plays for the team, too, but he
wants to score.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect the Coyotes to get involved in the Sedin
sweepstakes. They pick 19th overall and have targeted a handful of
other prospects that should be available when NHL Commissioner Gary
Bettman calls them up to the podium.
</P>
<P>
   The first team to stand up from the draft table will be the
Tampa Bay Lightning, which will be picking first for the second
straight year after nabbing consensus No. 1 overall pick Vincent
Lecavalier last June.
</P>
<P>
   While the Sedin twins interest Coach/General Manager Jacques
Demers, he no longer is calling the shots in Tampa, and it is
believed the Lightning will take Pavel Brendl, the high-scoring
wing for the Calgary Hitmen of the Western Hockey League, who
scored 73 goals and 134 points in 68 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech Republic native added 21 goals and 46 points in 20
playoff games to help the Hitmen advance to the Memorial Cup. He
tends to skate some invisible shifts from time to time, and he
isn't always much of a factor away from the puck, but his numbers
are simply too good to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised, I'm shocked,'' Paul Henry, the director of
player personnel of the Florida Panthers, said of Brendl. ``The
biggest thing is, he has emerged as a pure goal-scorer. He has
game-breaking ability that all great NHL players have.''
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1-rated player in North America, however, is Patrik
Stefan, a 6-foot-1{, 205-pound center who missed half of last
season with the Long Beach Ice Dogs of the International Hockey
League because of two major concussions. Another Czech-born player,
Stefan appears the most ready to step into to the NHL element right
away, but his health concerns are an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Other top prospects expected to go high in the first round next
Saturday include Moose Jaw center Jamie Lundmark (40 goals, 50
assists, 90 points), Calgary center Kris Beech (26-41-67), Seattle
forward Oleg Saprykin (47-46-97), Erie center Tim Connolly
(34-34-68), Sudbury left wing Taylor Pyatt (37-38-75) and Barrie
right wing Denis Shvidki (35-59-94).
</P>
<P>
   ``His ice vision and his passing ability are second to none,''
Barrie Coach Bert Templeton said of the Ukranian-born Shvidki.
``He's already at the NHL level with those.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
