<HEADLINE>
ROOKIES' CON CENTRATION AT CAMP PLEASES TOBIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Cardinals Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin pronounced his
fourth rookie and free-agent camp his best ever on Friday. Then, he
and his coaching staff closed up shop for brief vacations until
preseason camp opens July 30 in Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an excellent camp,'' Tobin said. ``They really
concentrated on the tasks at hand, which was to learn the offense,
defense and special teams. In terms of concentration, it's probably
the best camp we've had in the four years we've been here. It's a
group of rookies that want to make this football team, and they did
everything in their power to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The only damper on the two-week camp was the limited physical
roles of first-round picks  &UR; David Boston (shoulder) and  &UR; L.J.
Shelton (orthoscopic knee surgery), but even that didn't affect
Tobin's impressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really weren't assessing athletic talent in this camp,'' he
said. ``The main thing we were trying to do was teach our system
and plays. Shelton was in every meeting, so mentally he hasn't lost
anything. And, what he has lost physically, is very minimal because
the way the camp was structured.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that hurt Boston the most was NCAA rules. He missed
a week of the insertion. But as long as they were in the meetings
they'll pick it up. It was mostly mental and the physical part was
secondary.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston, from Ohio State, missed the first week of camp because
of an NFL rule prohibiting participation until a player's
graduating class holds commencement exercises.'' &QL; 
Eye catching &QL; 
While Tobin wasn't stressing the physical aspect of play, one
player who did catch his eye was middle linebacker  &UR; Mel Bradley
from Arkansas, one of two sixth-round picks who is making the
transition from the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy who was the most unanswered question coming in was
Bradley,'' Tobin said. ``He showed us he has the athletic ability
to play middle linebacker. He has good speed, an ability to change
directions and to get outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's a matter of his learning to play the position. He
played it for two years, but he became a football player by playing
the defensive line. It' s new to him, but I was impressed with his
athletic ability. &QL; 
Doctor snap &QL; 
It was reported earlier that backup center  &UR; Mike Devlin and his
wife welcomed daughter Carlie Elisabeth, their third child, into
the world on Tuesday. What wasn't reported was that the
``ham-handed'' Devlin delivered the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor was right there telling me to do this or to do
that, and right before she was totally delivered he told, ``OK,
now, don't drop the ball,' '' Devlin said, laughing. ``I've been in
the Super Bowl and thought there could be no greater experience,
but it doesn't compare to this.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
