<HEADLINE>
MOTHER-TO-BE GRIFFITHS PLANS VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - On Father's Day, the Mercury is thinking ahead to a
four-game homestand in late July when it expects the chance to
salute its impending mother.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Michelle Griffiths, who started 25 games at power forward last
season but is on maternity leave awaiting the fall birth of her
first child, is planning a visit July 23-29. Phoenix is hosting
Orlando, Washington, Utah and Minnesota during that week in its
longest homestand of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Griffiths, 6 feet 1, will be the first Mercury player to give
birth since the WNBA launched in 1997.  &UR; Edna Campbell and
 &UR; Merlelynn
 &UR; Lange-Harris came to the team already with children.
</P>
<P>
   Griffiths plans to return next season when she and Australian
teammates  &UR; Michele Timms and  &UR; Kristi Harrower will use the WNBA as
preparation for the 2000 Sydney Olympics. Other Australian
national-teamers in the league are:  &UR; Sandy Brondello, Carla Porter
and
 &UR; Rachel Sporn with Detroit;  &UR; Trish Fallon and  &UR; Annie LaFleur with
Minnesota; and  &UR; Jenny Whittle with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Australian national-team head Coach  &UR; Tom Maher was here for the
Mercury home opener vs. Sacramento. His assistant coach,  &UR; Carrie
Graf, is a Mercury assistant.
</P>
<P>
   The entire Australian national team, called the Opals, will be
in San Diego on Sept. 9-12 to play in the U.S. Olympic Cup vs. a
WNBA team, Brazil and Poland. Brazil and Australia were silver and
bronze medalists behind the United States at the 1996 Olympics
while Poland won the European Championships earlier this month. &QL; 
Olympic bid loses &QL; 
Poprad-Tatry, the Slovak Republic home of Mercury
guard/forward &UR; Andrea Kuklova, was one of the losing cities in
Saturday's decision to award the 2006 Winter Olympics to Turin,
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Poprad was one of four cities first eliminated when the field
was reduced to Turin and Sion, Switzerland. Turin then won in a
53-36 upset vote.
</P>
<P>
   Kuklova, 27 and a 1992 Olympian, stayed at home playing for
Kosice during the off-season. &QL; 
No reunion &QL; 
Cleveland center  &UR; Chasity Melvin expected her first trip here to be
reunion with  &UR; Umeki Webb. The two were teammates at North Carolina
State, then Webb was a graduate assistant in 1997-98 when Melvin
and the Wolfpack reached the NCAA Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   But Melvin was the only 1998 Kodak All-American to sign with the
American Basketball League, thus missing the second WNBA season.
And now that she's in the league, Webb is out, having been one of
the Mercury's final cuts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
