<HEADLINE>
CARDS RECEIVER STARS IN EU ROPE  
 MCCULLOUGH BE COMES A FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget joining the Army or Navy, Andy McCullough became a pro
football player and found a better way to se the world.
</P>
<P>
   Since signing a contract out of the University of Tennessee a
year ago, McCullough has already made NFL stops with New Orleans,
Miami, Detroit and the Arizona Cardinals. He now finds himself
lighting up the NFL Europe as a wide receiver for the World
Bowl-bound Frankfurt Galaxy with hopes of finding a permanent home
with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Entering today's season-ending game against the Barcelona
Dragons, McCullough leads all NFL Europe receivers in yards per
catch (18.4) touchdowns (nine), and ranks second in receiving yards
(793) and is fourth in receptions (43).
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, he has proved something to himself and the
Cardinals coaching staff, which sent him to Frankfurt for further
schooling after signing him late last season and carrying him on
the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been very productive over there,'' Cardinals Coach
Vince Tobin said. ``He has shown he can catch the pass over the
middle and make big plays in that league. He has run well after
making the catch, too. He has done what we wanted to find out if he
could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked him up late and had him on the scout team, and this
has really helped him and given him an excellent chance to compete
for a spot on our football team, whereas if he hadn't gone over
there he probably would have been just a camp member. He has a
chance. As a coach you like to see what a guy does in the heat of
battle, and he has shown he can come through.''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough, whose Galaxy has already clinched a World Bowl spot,
believes his European experience has opened doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the coaches told me they were sending me here I was
really excited about it,'' said McCullough by telephone on Friday.
``I hadn't played in a game in so long I just wanted a chance to
prove what I'm capable of doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had confidence, but now my confidence is
astronomical. Before I was always afraid of making a mistake, but
now I know I'm not perfect and am ready to play receiver and play
through mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6-foot-3, 210-pounds, McCullough could become a welcome
addition to the Cardinals as a physical receiver or on special
teams. When he returns from Europe, he plans to work out with
Vikings receivers Cris Carter, Randy Moss and Jake Reed in Florida.
Still, he credits much of his improvement to a pair of Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a problem getting off bump coverage after
getting knocked around every day by Aeneas Williams and Corey
Chavous,'' he said. ``What I've been working on is getting out of
my cuts faster and doing something with the ball after I catch it.
I've always been good at running the deep routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Cardinals receiver) Frank Sanders really helped me last year,
too. He was like a big brother to me and helped me out running
better routes and by making me a better man off the field. There
are a lot of great people on the Cardinals. I was with three teams
last year because I kept getting caught in the numbers game, and
they made me feel at home.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough said when he went to Europe, he had concerns about
playing an 11-game schedule and then going straight to a much
longer NFL schedule with little rest. He has put those fears to
rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about it at first, taking a lot of hits and the toll
it would take,'' he said. ``But I've been taking care of myself and
do a lot of little things like taking vitamins and getting a lot of
rest at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game here is a step under the NFL, but the coaching staff
is good, and the practices are just like the NFL. I've been doing
the same things I did in Arizona to prepare myself for games. The
crowd here is unbelievable. They get 40,000 to every game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
