<HEADLINE>
MICKELSON EXPECTS SILENCE FROM BEEPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _  &UR; Phil Mickelson is not quite a father yet, but
he knows the perfect gift for Father's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking about it, yeah,'' he said, referring to the
possibility of his first major championship after winning 13 times
on the PGA Tour. ``But there's a long way to go. I hit the ball
poorly (Saturday), but my swing is off just a smidgen. That's why
I've got to go hit balls.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, the Scottsdale pro was off to the range, trailing
 &UR; Payne Stewart by 1 stroke going into today's final round at
Pinehurst No. 2. Only three things seem to be standing in the way
of him clearing his biggest career hurdle:
</P>
<P>
   The possibility that Stewart or another of the leaders might
post a great score.
</P>
<P>
   The chance Mickelson won't play well.
</P>
<P>
   A beeper that could go off, telling him his baby girl,  &UR; Amanda,
is on the way. He has said on several occasions this week that if
he gets the call from his wife,  &UR; Amy, he's ``outta here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked with her already (on Saturday), and things are going
well,'' said Mickelson, who at one point held a 3-stroke lead at 3
under before he needed to birdie the final hole just to finish with
a 73 and at level par. ``I'm really not all that concerned about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experts tell us (the baby) still is a week or two off, and
I believe them.'' &QL; 
Arizona connection &QL; 
Mickelson is not the only Arizona pro who could walk away with his
first major championship. Fellow Scottsdale residents  &UR; Billy
Mayfair and  &UR; Tim Herron also are knocking on the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, the U.S. Open probably isn't my style of golf,
because I don't drive it real straight,'' said Herron, who is 2
shots behind Stewart after a 70 _ the day's second-best round.
``But this week I'm driving it good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only missed one fairway (Saturday), although I missed it by
a huge margin. I just hope I can continue to keep lagging the ball
well around the greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfair, who shot 74, was stung by three straight bogeys on the
back side, the result of approach shots that would not settle down.
The statistic that killed him was only eight greens in regulation,
but he still is right there, 4 shots off the pace.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's other three survivors fell farther back, as  &UR; Tom
Lehman (73, 10 over),  &UR; Jim Carter (74, 11 over) and  &UR; Brandel
Chamblee (74, 11 over) can only hope for a top-15 finish that would
get them into next year's Open at Pebble Beach. &QL; 
In the red &QL; 
Hard to believe a round of 1-under in a U.S. Open could command
such attention. Even the guy who did it,  &UR; Steve Stricker, was a
little mystified to be the only player to break par in Round 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like I shot the round of the year,'' Stricker
said of the 69. ``But getting off to that start, you really don't
expect something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Stricker holed a 40-foot birdie putt at the second hole, which
he called ``the longest putt I've made in I don't know how long.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I holed an 8-iron out of the bunker at No. 3,'' he said
of the 136-yard eagle. ``All of a sudden I'm 3 under through three
holes, and the crowd is going crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   From there he rode it out with four bogeys and two more birdies,
jumping from 20th place to a tie for fifth, 3 strokes away from
Stewart. &QL; 
How hard was it? &QL; 
Everyone felt Pinehurst No. 2 was way too difficult on Saturday,
but several players took their potshots to new levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played this as a par 88. I made 12 birdies and a bogey,''
said  &UR; John Cook, whose 77 pushed him to 14 over. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
