<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-LEHMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEHMAN WILL TEE OFF EARLY  
 STREAK OF PLAYING IN LAST GROUP ENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ For the first time in four years, Tom Lehman
won't be paired in the final group of the U.S. Open today. His
record-tying streak came to an end Saturday at Pinehurst No. 2,
where a 3-over 73 shoved him to 10 over and the middle of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how it felt to be out of contention for the first time
since the 1995 Open at Shinnecock, when Lehman began the string
that equaled Bobby Jones' feat, the Scottsdale pro shot back:
``What do you mean I'm out of contention? I'm going to shoot 59
(today).''
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter responded, ``Which nine?'' Lehman just laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty brutal, but fairly accurate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman said that a stiff breeze and some pin placements that
``seemed to be suspended in air'' are making the old course more
treacherous by the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``My prediction is that someone might be under par at the end of
(Saturday), but there won't be anybody under par (tonight),''
Lehman said. ``For starters, the course is a par 72, not 70. And
when you put those pins on those little ledges, it seems like
they're sticking out of nowhere. It's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, who has not finished out of the top-five in the past
four Opens, said his goal now is a top-20 finish. But that wouldn't
be bad on the ``toughest Open course I've ever played.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said once that Augusta National was a chamber of horrors,
but I found a new one,'' he added. ``(Pinehurst No. 2) almost makes
Augusta look easy.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean Lehman feels the course should not be used
in the Open rotation. In fact, he likes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great old golf course,'' he said. ``But I prefer the
courses where the rough is up. You know, six-inch hay. This is more
like Augusta, no rough, but much tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, Lehman's 73 during the third round looked pretty
good. He only got beat up once, at No. 2, where he left a 5-iron
short, then failed to get his chip up the hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Easy 6,'' he said. ``There will be a lot of those there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past four years, Lehman posted third-round scores of 67,
65, 68 and 68, but he never came close to lapping the field on this
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I shot 73, and I definitely think that was under par,''
he said. ``My problem has been that I've made just three birdies in
three days, and one of those was a chip-in. It's a great course to
have a lead on, but it's just too darn tough to play catch-up.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
