<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BULLETINS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE AT PEACE WITH DOVE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In the early 1970s, Arizona still was in its heyday
for dove hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities such as John Wayne, who had a couple of ranches in
Arizona but didn't live here often, came to Arizona with buddies to
shoot doves during opening weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It was more like a slaughter. The ``hunters'' would take a limit
or so in the morning and return in the evening for another.
</P>
<P>
   Great deal: Cook doves, drink whiskey and have a heck of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Game and Fish Department didn't have nearly enough
officers to enforce the law. They could catch only a few offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Then Arizona began to grow quickly in population. Agricultural
areas began to dwindle in favor of development. Dove habitat took a
dive.
</P>
<P>
   With dwindling habitat and still a large number of hunters, the
dove population began to suffer. Then hunter numbers dropped.
Arizona became less than a party place to shoot doves, although
Californians, who have rotten game management, kept coming because
of the agricultural areas around Yuma, a dove mecca.
</P>
<P>
   In the years before 1989, the Arizona Game and Fish Department
decided it had to do something about the dwindling dove and dove
hunter populations.
</P>
<P>
   Since the dove is a migratory bird, it is under the auspices of
the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, which sets up hunt guidelines
for the states.
</P>
<P>
   Long ago, it had decided on split seasons, opening Sept. 1 with
a two-week season and then resuming the season in November. Almost
all the doves in some areas were killed in the first few days of
the first season.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the department instituted a two-week opening season
that lasted only half a day each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year, mourning doves did better,'' said Tice
Supplee, game chief for Game and Fish. ``In 1990, white-wings began
improving in numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past decade, doves posted a modest increase _ despite
the fact habitat still was shrinking except in the Yuma area.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's also a growing quality of hunt in the late season,''
she said at an Arizona Game and Fish Commission meeting Saturday in
Phoenix. ``The number of hunter-days (number of days utilized by
hunters) is increasing in the southern part of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, dove numbers have stabilized in Arizona, and so have
the number of hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Some groups were asking commissioners Saturday to liberalize the
seasons. Game and Fish biologists presented several different
season scenarios. They preferred the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners made only one change.
</P>
<P>
   During the early season, juniors, those 15 and under, can hunt
all day in the southern zone. That means hunting after school,
giving them more opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Since juniors account for only about 2.3 percent of the dove
kill, the change will have little impact.
</P>
<P>
   The commission did a pretty good job on this one. Once stability
is reached on a declining population, why liberalize it?
</P>
<P>
   Also, the band-tail pigeon limit was raised to 4 from 3. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 0044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
