<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RIVER-KEEPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVER GUARDIANS DISCUSS SETBACKS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ga., S.C., N.C., Maine, Fla., Alaska, Calif., Canada)   (nk) 
 BY JOHN T. MCQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAG HARBOR, N.Y. _ Billy Joel took the helm of his new
65-foot-long boat, the Redhead, and with Robert F. Kennedy Jr. at
his side in the pilot's seat, led 50 environmentalists who keep
watch on the nation's waterways on a tour of Peconic Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when you're heading in from Block Island, you can
almost imagine how pristine it was here when the first explorers
arrived hundreds of years ago,'' Joel said as he maneuvered the
Redhead away from the dock at the Sag Harbor Yacht Club early
Friday, gave a warning blast on the boat's horn and headed out into
the bay.
</P>
<P>
   It was Joel, long an advocate for the dwindling number of
commercial fishermen and baymen on Long Island's East End, who
helped win congressional approval of the bay as a national estuary
in 1993, providing it with protection from pollution under the
Clean Water Act.
</P>
<P>
   Adopted by Congress a quarter-century ago, the Clean Water Act
gave citizens broad powers to enforce environmental laws through
private lawsuits. It led to hundreds of suits filed by citizens
that produced millions of dollars in penalties paid to the
government and scores of court orders to stop pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, more of the suits are being turned back by
rulings by the Supreme Court and lower federal courts, greatly
diminishing the power of environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past decade, right-wing jurists have eroded or
dismantled many of the environmental protections and citizens'
rights that Congress wrote into the environmental statutes passed
after Earth Day in 1970,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These decisions are being written just as many of the nation's
rivers and beaches are recovering from decades of abuse and are
being reopened for fishing and swimming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Water Keeper Alliance, all grass-roots river and
bay advocates from across North America, gathered Thursday at the
Southampton College of Long Island University for a four-day
conference to discuss their legal rights and form a strategy to
respond to the legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was organized by Kennedy, a founder of the alliance,
an umbrella group of 35 keeper programs in the United States and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The keepers cast themselves among the most aggressive and
litigious members of the environmental movement. While there is no
current legal action involving Peconic Bay, groups like the San
Francisco Baykeeper and the Hudson Riverkeeper maintain more than
40 lawsuits against environmental polluters at one time, according
to Kennedy, who also is the supervising attorney for the Pace
Environmental Litigation Clinic at the Pace University School of
Law in White Plains.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the Upper Chattahoochee Riverkeeper in Georgia
recently won a $1 billion judgment against the city of Atlanta for
violating clean water laws at its sewer treatment plants. But the
recent losses in court, he said, were the primary concern at this
week's conference on Long Island, which is scheduled to end Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The first keeper program was started on the Hudson River by a
coalition of commercial and recreational fishermen who came
together in 1996 to reclaim the river, Kennedy said. Since its
incorporation in 1984, Hudson Riverkeeper has brought over 150
successful lawsuits against river polluters.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery of the Hudson inspired similar keeper groups from
Cook Inlet in Alaska to the St. John's River in Florida, and from
San Diego Bay in California to Casco Bay in Maine. Kennedy said he
christened the 35th riverkeeper and the first Canadian keeper
program a week ago on the Petitcodiac River in New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon, the keepers, buoyed by encouragement from a
rock-and-roll legend, were back at work at the Southampton campus
absorbing the finer points of legal standing in a court of law from
a lecture by Karl S. Coplan, a lawyer with the Pace Environmental
Litigation Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the Congress has said in the Clean Water Act that
any person can sue, the courts are now saying there are
limitations,'' Coplan said. ``The courts are now saying you have to
show an actual injury that you can point to and perceive. It may be
true that a plant may be putting pollution in water and breaking
the law, but when you get to court you have to point to something
tangible that proves the water has been affected.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted a ruling June 2 by the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Columbia, S.C., in a lawsuit brought by the Friends of
the Earth, a citizens environmental group, on behalf of the
operators of a canoe trip company. The lawsuit was filed against
the Gaston Copper Recycling Corporation, which sits aside Lake
Watson in Gaston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled that the plaintiffs had no standing because they
failed to prove that the canoe business suffered because the
recycling plant had once discharged lead and copper into the lake.
The canoe company argued it could sell more trips if the water did
not have a history of pollution. The court said this was not good
enough, Coplan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get standing, the courts are insisting that we get very
personal and specific about how we are affected by pollution, and
this can be tough to litigate,'' he told the keepers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
