A2526 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FATHER'SDAY-BOS &LR;      06-20 1862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FATHER'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS DADS, PRO OFTEN SECOND-STRING 
</HEADLINE>
 DAY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Before he or she arrives, you ponder the sacrifices you
will make, whether you're ready for the changes in lifestyle some
say are inevitable. Yet at birth, something amazing happens: Your
heart and soul become linked, and the little one determines the
state of both. So much so that her smile makes you feel as if you
will live forever, his sadness spurns dark depression, her
curiosity sheds new light on the dullness around you.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, you realize that of all the things you ask of The
Creator, children are the greatest answer. And, of all the things a
child asks of you, the greatest gift you render is your presence.
Time to use your ams as a security blanket. Time to be a hero. A
cheerleader. A chauffeur. A coach. A compass. A friend.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of pondering how much time spent with your child (or
children) causes sacrifices in the rest of your world, you consider
the inverse. For there is only one first step, one first day of
school, and only so many piano recitals and Little League games.
The only memory more firmly etched than that of being there is that
of wishing you had been.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sunday is Father's Day, and Red Sox pitcher Bret Saberhagen, a
father of three, has to work. There is something unjust about that.
Perhaps some fathers don't think so. In fact, some dads might be
present at Fenway for Sunday's Sox-Rangers game because of a gift
from their offspring, an outdoor alternative to soap-on-a-rope.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine, except that plenty of those dads work 9-to-5
shifts. They see their children every day. Saberhagen is a
professional baseball player, one whose occupation makes him as
stationary as a deer in hunting season.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday is Father's Day. It is bad enough Saberhagen and other
Red Sox dads cannot always be there to enjoy their childrens'
proudest moments. They have to make amends for missing their own
designated day in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost seems like you're a part-time dad at times,'' said
Saberhagen, whose three children, Drew (13), Brittany (12), and
Dalton (7), live in California with his ex-wife, Janeane. ``The mom
has to have two roles, being mom and dad, the disciplinarian and
the one who gives them the pat on the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew was born the day before the seventh game of the 1985 World
Series, as Saberhagen and the Kansas City Royals met the St. Louis
Cardinals. Both he and Dalton play baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get a chance to see too many (of his children's)
baseball games,'' said Saberhagen. ``I don't get a chance to see
piano recitals. So you see a lot of videotape. The good thing is
that you get four months during the offseason where you don't have
days where you have to be anyplace so it makes up for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once baseball is all over and done with, too, you're going to
have a lot of time. But unfortunately you miss a lot of their
childhood growing up. And as anybody knows, with kids it seems like
they grow up awfully quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen empathizes with fellow Red Sox pitcher Mark Portugal,
who announced his retirement in early June after 18 1/2 years of
pro ball to spend more time with his kids, who also live with his
ex-wife. He changed his mind a few days later and returned to the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Both say that for a professional athlete, being away from family
is something you put up with but never fully adjust to.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I spent Father's Day with them was two years ago
in Philadelphia,'' said Portugal. ``I had surgery on my knee and I
came back to Rhode Island right after surgery, so I was home for
Father's Day. Prior to that, I don't remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's move is far from unusual. Many pro athletes/fathers
become so bothered by the time away from their kids that they do
something about it.
</P>
<P>
   Often their solutions are temporary: The Celtics' Kevin McHale
once skipped a Christmas Eve flight to New York for a Christmas
afternoon game with the New York Knicks so he could spend Christmas
Eve with his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed to watch my kids open presents (Christmas Eve) and
then I caught a flight out the next morning,'' said McHale, who has
five children. ``The coaching staff was upset, but later on Red
Auerbach came up to me and said, `Aww, you did the right thing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Often the solutions are permanent. Former Bruins player Dave
Poulin walked away from the game in 1995, when he could have played
at least another season, and subsequently became hockey coach at
Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   He has three daughters, including 12-year-old twins who were
born so prematurely they had to spend three months in intensive
care. He was in training camp at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, because you don't realize it early on in your
career (how much you sacrifice),'' said Poulin. ``It's like any
other job; you realize that in order to be successful, you have to
make sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play golf with doctors, and they'll tell you they've
sometimes missed 8-12 years of their children's lives, from medical
school to residences to practices. They don't know about music or
movies or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why Red Sox outfielder Darren Lewis said Portugal's
decision is one most every athlete/father faces before his playing
days are over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if it hasn't come to the point where you are asked to
leave,'' he said, ``there might be a time where you're like Kirk
Gibson, who said, `I'm retiring to my family.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lewis relishes things some fathers who work 9 to 5 take for
granted. Making breakfast for his son, 5-year-old Austin. Driving
him to school. Often when they're en route, Austin points to
certain objects along the road and asks, ``Daddy, what's that?'' or
asks the meaning of certain words in songs heard over the radio.
</P>
<P>
   Those moments are treats for Lewis. He tries to drive his son to
school at least twice a week, but often it's difficult because he
arrives home so late from the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he makes the effort, knowing full well that once those
moments are gone, they're gone for good.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was not there when Austin took his first steps. The
youngster was crawling when dad, then playing for the San Francisco
Giants, embarked on an extensive road trip. When Lewis returned,
Austin had already gotten the hang of one foot before the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came home, and the flight got in kind of late,'' said Lewis.
``My mom and dad were over, and I was talking, probably about
baseball. And my mom said, `Darren look.' And I looked over, and
there he was, running across the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough because sometimes you feel like you're not
contributing as much as you would like to, and it's not by choice.
It's tough not having the daily contact with (Austin) like the
average father who works 9 to 5 has.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin was born in 1994, the year of the baseball strike, so
Darren got to spend a portion of the summer with him. He said his
son is at the age now where he understands the nature of pro
baseball. And despite the downside, there are advantages to having
a father who plays ball.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal said his children enjoy the celebrity of having a
father in the major leagues. McHale said he played a final year
with the Celtics because his sons pleaded for one more year of
being the team's ball boys and getting into games free.
</P>
<P>
   The financial aspect doesn't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, children learn to make the adjustment. ``I
think they realize (dad won't be home often) as soon as they're
able to walk and start hanging out with dad out in the yard or
whatever,'' said Portugal. ``They say, `Mommy where's dad?' and she
says, `Daddy had to go to work. He'll be back.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job requires us to travel and there's no getting around
it. After a while they accept it as part of their lives; they know
it's going to happen and there's nothing they're going to do to
change it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes having children during a key point of a season can be
a blessing in disguise. Saberhagen said his son's being born during
the World Series took the pressure off the games (he left the
Series to witness the birth of his son). ``Plenty of people still
ask about him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the more time you spend with your kids during the
offseason, the more you miss them during the season. ``I went
through a divorce, and that makes it even tougher,'' said
Saberhagen. ``They live in California. They come out four different
times during the season, and we're usually in California two
different times. We try to make up a lot of times during the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there was a time during the divorce that was kind of ugly,
where I pretty much gave her everything and I came to a point where
I was coming back from surgery and I said, `It's kind of nice being
home, and I get a chance to see the kids a little bit more. If we
can't come to a reasonable agreement between her and I, I won't be
playing anymore.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids weren't really happy about that. They really wanted
to see dad play some more if it was possible. It's tough. You miss
a lot. You miss an awful lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen smiles when he considers what it will be like when
his playing days are over, when he can do all the things he's
wanted to do the last 17 years while playing professionally. Until
then, he doesn't spend time mired in regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have three great kids who are well-behaved,'' said
Saberhagen. ``They get great grades in school. My oldest is going
to finish with honors this year. It would have been nice to be
around 9 to 5.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Poulin is among many who have taken an added interest in this
weekend's US Open golf tournament because of Phil Mickelson, whose
wife Amy is due June 30 with their first child (a girl). There was
speculation that he would not play in the Open.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson is one shot out of the lead at Pinehurst, N.C., but
ready to leave if he gets a call. ``It's not worth a tournament,''
he said. ``This is the most important thing as far as our family is
concerned. I would be very disappointed if she were to go in labor
and not call me.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might say that Mickelson's conviction is a far cry from
that of years past, when fathers assumed the role of breadwinner
and were not expected to play a huge role in the day-to-day events
of their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the role of the father has increased tremendously over
the last 15-20 years,'' said Poulin. ``You've seen an increase of
fathers in the birthing room to fathers being there for the primary
responsibilities of fatherhood.''
</P>
<P>
   McHale, now vice president of basketball operations for the
Minnesota Timberwolves, said he now hears current players voicing
the same parental concerns he did when he was a Celtic. ``Oh yeah,
especially as guys get older,'' he said. ``With younger players,
you don't get it as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as you get older you realize you really are missing out on
some things. It gets harder and they're a little more demanding.
They keep growing and it's like, man, they're 12, 15 now, soon
they'll be going off to college, and you start becoming aware of
what you've missed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
