</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'TIS THE DRAFT SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With only 10 shopping days left before the NBA Draft lands on
us, an over-aged kid holding the first pick remains perched on
Santa's knee.
</P>
<P>
   (Skit warning.)
</P>
<P>
   SANTA: Hurry up and tell me whatcha want already. The over-sized
kid from Vancouver's flipping me the bird.
</P>
<P>
   KID: Aw, the kid from Vancouver doesn't know what he wants
either. By the way, that cheesy beard can't fool me ... I know
you're commissioner David Stern.
</P>
<P>
   SANTA: Well, since Jordan abandoned us, I thought it might be
wise to have another income.
</P>
<P>
   KID: Amen, Santa.
</P>
<P>
   (Skit over.)
</P>
<P>
   So who's the over-aged kid?
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Krause is the name, attempting to bamboozle other NBA
personnel executives for the betterment of the Chicago Bulls is the
game. Jerry, you may have heard, is the rascal blamed for huffing,
puffing and blowing Phil Jackson out of the Windy City.
</P>
<P>
   His general popularity is somewhat minimized, because he appears
to be a candidate for the kind of face-lift that could attract a
hernia. Among his NBA peers, he's the guy wearing eight watches on
his arm.
</P>
<P>
   He also is the guy who thought Phil
</P>
<P>
   Jackson would be a dandy coach for the Chicago Bulls. Hurts,
doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Krause also realizes the first overall draft pick he
earned by casting a staggeringly awful 1999 Bulls team has been
sabotaged by timing. Believe it. He wouldn't mind trading it to
Toronto for a lower lottery pick and Raptors swingman Tracy
McGrady, but Raptors GM Glen Grunwald realizes McGrady still may be
a better prospect than anyone in this months's draft.
</P>
<P>
   History will have its say, but the 1999 draft-lottery candidates
offer more question marks than a ``Jeopardy'' transcript.
</P>
<P>
   There is not one factory-installed, Nike-sponsored messiah in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   No, the two alleged candidates for No.1 are Maryland's Steve
Francis a 6-foot-2 acrobat with point-guard skills that may be
repressed by the insensitivity of a shooting guard and reluctant
Rhode Island deserter Lamar Odom.
</P>
<P>
   Odom is a 6-9 southpaw who's been defined as the millennial
edition of Earvin Johnson and, for once, the comparison holds
water. Nah, really? Well, like the retirement-model Magic, the kid
doesn't seem to know if he wants to step into the NBA spotlight or
stay put. Since the end of his college season, we've been tripped
by frequent resets on this versatile small forward's Odom-eter. He
could be the league's first come-and-go-to guy.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, the school declared it would not file an appeal to
restore Odom's NCAA eligibility, leaving him with little
alternative beyond making $3 million or so in the NBA next season.
</P>
<P>
   Although his actions certainly smell like Bull, will they cause
the otherwise well-intentioned Odom to slide a spot or two down the
selection board? One GM suggested that overlooking him could be as
catastrophic as the NFL's fear of drafting Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
   However, unlike Moss, the only laws Odom has broken involve
those of unwritten NBA protocol. He skipped the pre-draft camp
measuring stick in Chicago, and missed private workouts for the
Bulls and Hornets. He had been scheduled to dance for the Clippers
on Monday, but they haven't exactly started the music.
</P>
<P>
   All of this means the 1999 NBA Draft offers more trepidation and
uncertainty than the front porch at the end of a first date.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's always more.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend in Chicago, Elton Brand the taped crusader from
Duke was measured at 6-8. Without shoes. His agent is David Falk,
so Brand won't be shoeless much longer. Is checking in at 6-8
important? Boy howdy yes. See, before this intriguing measurement,
Brand was believed to be, oh, 6-7 assuming the requisite callouses
on his feet. That would have rendered him altitude-challenged as a
candidate for the job of NBA power forward.
</P>
<P>
   NBA personnel types had labeled him more suspect than prospect.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Chicago measurement'' could push Brand back into the top
three, which might be good news for the Clippers, who had been
worried that point-guard favorite Baron Davis of UCLA will be a
goner by then.
</P>
<P>
   The Charlotte Hornets, another franchise with rumored
point-guard fever and previous reservations vis-a-vis Brand, is
picking third. Vancouver, with no power in its forwards, is second.
</P>
<P>
   Is that all? Hell, no.
</P>
<P>
   According to more than two and less than 20 NBA personnel
hounds, Davis' famous left knee continues to make everyone except
Davis and power agent Arn Tellem nervous. The knee was checked out
in Chicago, where normal rehab progress was noted, but absolute
blessings for a trouble-free career were not given.
</P>
<P>
   This could be little more than self-preservation by doctors, or
it may be pre-draft scare tactics.
</P>
<P>
   We hired a fortune teller to get a better handle on June 30, but
she said the entire evening will be up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   MAGGETTE UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   After last week's cameo workout in Chicago, the Corey Maggette
Road Show came west.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-Duke grasshopper worked out in Vancouver on Thursday
morning, did Seattle the same afternoon, and dined with the
Clippers in L.A. that night.
</P>
<P>
   He worked out for the Clips on Friday morning at USC's Lyon
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you haven't been through it,'' Maggette said of the
audition process, ``there's no way you can mentally prepare. But I
think these workouts have been going well.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite dragging a slight groin pull into the Clipper test, the
6-6 small forward (tip to future coach: don't be silly and put him
at guard, like Philly did with Jerry Stackhouse) demonstrated
quicker defensive reactions than a husband who forgot to tell his
wife he'd be home a bit late.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the release on his jumper looks as smooth as your
first beer tasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do need to improve the technique on my jump shot and work on
my ballhandling,'' said Maggette, who was a baseline wonder at
Chicago's Fenwick High just 15 months ago. ``But I think I've
already come a long way since leaving Duke.''
</P>
<P>
   After a season with the powerhouse Blue Devils, would playing
for the Clippers bother him?
</P>
<P>
   Maggette demonstrated that one year at Duke provided enough
schooling for the lottery X-factor to issue the right answer. ``Not
at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Would picking an inexperienced (but splendidly athletic) small
forward at No.4 bother the Clippers? Probably.
</P>
<P>
   THE BULL MARKET
</P>
<P>
   Toni Kukoc, the last Bull, has one year remaining on his
contract and has been shopped by Krause to teams with high lottery
picks. Acquiring Kukoc means living with the threat that he'll go
back to Europe when his contract expires. Krause also has miles of
cap room, but may save most of it for the free-agent class of 2000.
One target for the class o' '99 may be 20-year-old, college-dodger
Jermaine O'Neal, a lively 6-11 forward who's on the last fumes of
his three-year deal in Portland. The Blazers realize O'Neal is on
the verge of goodness, but if Rasheed Wallace isn't moved, O'Neal
realizes he still may be on the verge of more time on the pine.
</P>
<P>
   SHOT-CLOCK VIOLATIONSThe Minnesota Timberwolves have put center
Dean Garrett and Laker alum Anthony Peeler on the market to woo
backboard help for Kevin Garnett . ... Chicago pre-draft camp
busters include New Mexico power forward Kenny Thomas and Kentucky
center Jamal Magloire, who has until Wednesday to hustle back to
Lexington where he probably belongs. Pre-draft camp surprises
include George Mason point guard Jason Miskiri and 6-10 Taymon
Domzalski, a strong and athletic power-forward prospect who died on
the vine at Duke while Coach Mike Krzyzewski was proving Chris
Burgess has little inside game (so far). ... Speaking of
Krzyzewski, will losing Brand, Maggette and sophomore point guard
William Avery lead to the nickname ``Coach Y2K?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 0127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
