<DOCNO> NYT19990620.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2528 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      06-20 1701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS GIVING SAINTS, FANS NEW INCENTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Ricky Williams has yet to gain a yard in the NFL, but
according to Saints president Bill Kuharich, he's already become a
cult hero in the Big Easy because he did what few professional
athletes do. He gambled on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans here already love the guy because of what he did,''
Kuharich said recently. ``Ricky signed a contract where the better
he plays the more he gets paid. The fans love that because that's
how it should be. That's how it is in their lives. They don't get
paid if they don't produce, and Ricky Williams is saying that's how
he wants it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes he's a great player and if he is, he's going to
become one of the highest-paid running backs in football. That was
good enough for him. Before he signed the deal I asked him if he
was happy. He said he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Rival agents say the incentive-laden eight-year deal Williams
signed was a huge mistake that could cost him millions. However,
because many of those incentives are so high, he will, in fact,
have to be one of the game's greatest runners to earn the money,
and even if he is, he could still miss out on much of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky doesn't care what anyone else has to say,'' Kuharich
said. ``He's happy and he's confident in himself and in us.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously so, but many rival agents point out many things can
happen from signed contract to fully-funded stock portfolio, and
the sad fate of Patriot running back Robert Edwards is ample proof
of that. Yet Williams believes he will collect all or nearly all of
his potential $68.5 million contract rather than the minimum $11.1
million if things work out as he and the Saints plan.
</P>
<P>
   What Williams ended up with was an $8.84 million signing bonus,
of which he collected $3.6 million May 14. He'll collect another
$3.6 million May 14, 2000, and the remaining $1.6 million Nov. 14,
2000. There are various scenarios by which Williams might have to
refund some of that bonus if he is not still playing for the Saints
voluntarily or because of violations of NFL rules.
</P>
<P>
   But the real kickers are escalator clauses based on the first
four years of his production and 26 incentive clauses worth $50,000
each. Williams is able to earn only 10 of those a year (there is a
$500,000 cap on possible incentives per season) but the escalator
clauses based on his beating three of four numbers put up by
Denver's Terrell Davis in his first four seasons could skyrocket
Williams's salary if he runs the way he did while winning the
Heisman Trophy at Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the particulars.
</P>
<P>
   Between 2000 and 2002, if Williams rushes for 1,600 yards, he
earns $1 million in salary the next season. If he rushes for 1,800
yards, it's $1.5 million. If he hits the magic 2,000-yard mark, he
earns $2 million the next season. If he gets to 2,100 it means an
additional $2.5 million in salary, and if he reaches 2,105 yards,
he earns a $3 million salary the following season.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, his salary in years 2003-05 will depend on his
acheiving three of four goals: rushing for a total of 6,413 yards,
producing 7,594 total yards, averaging 4.8 yards a carry, or
scoring 366 points. These numbers would match Davis's production in
his first four seasons with the Broncos, who won two Super Bowl
titles during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   What this means is that Williams will earn only $175,000 in
salary this year (on top of his $3.6 million share of his signing
bonus), but next year he could earn as much as $3.5 million against
a minimum salary of $250,000. In 2001, his potential earnings range
from $325,000 to $3.5 million, in 2002 $350,000 to $3.5 million,
2003 $375,000 to $8.6 million (now there's a raise for you), 2004
$400,000 to $11.03 million, 2005 $400,000 to $13.46 million and
2006 $400,000 to a potential $15.89 million.
</P>
<P>
   The agents say that the way his contract is structured, Williams
could be one of the league's best backs and still miss the
incentives that would swell his salary, pointing out that if he
rushed for 1,599 yards, averaged 4.4 yards a carry and scored 11
touchdowns in three of his first four seasons he would not trigger
the escalator clauses.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Williams is on the Saints' books to make his minimum
salary every year if he doesn't hit his escalator clauses or his
incentives. Williams understands this, but he also understands he
can run, and if he's right, he'll run all the way to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the greatest runner in college football history,''
Kuharich said. ``He believes he can do the same thing in the NFL.
We do, too. That's why we gave up so much to get him. He's betting
on himself and we're betting on him, and the fans in New Orleans
love him for it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ditka was on WEEI recently talking about life, the Saints,
Williams's dreadlocks, and his banning of any jewelry worn by his
players while in uniform. That included the silver stud Williams
wears through his lower lip (ouch!). He wore it in the team's first
minicamp but was told to remove it at the second camp, and the
opening closed within two hours. Now Williams will have to get his
lip pierced again. Or maybe he could take the hint from his lip and
leave well enough alone . . . Speaking of Williams, you can e-mail
him at Dreaded34(at)aol.com . . . Bill Parcells reports 58 of the
59 Jets on his roster completed the full offseason workout program
and the other player did 75 percent of it. That included
quarterback Vinny Testaverde, who flew up to Long Island from
Florida on a private plane each week to get his workouts in without
disrupting his family. When linebacker Bryan Cox was in danger of
coming up short of the required 40 workout days, he stayed an extra
two weeks after the program was to have ended to get them all in.
Even late-signee Scott Zolak, the ex-Patriot backup QB, completed
24 workouts after he signed on . . . Speaking of focusing on your
job, Packer quarterback Brett Favre has decided to cut back on
personal appearances, autograph sessions, and even his Milwaukee TV
and radio show to devote more time to football and family this
season . . . Is this un-American? The NFL has outsourced its
instant replay system to a Toronto-based company, Leitch
Technology. The league will use Leitch's high-speed digital
recording system to instantly record every play this season as well
as all network replays for use in the league's instant replay
challenge system. The NFL sorted through at least a dozen proposals
from various companies before buying 31 Leitch systems, one for
each NFL stadium. Leitch will have its logo prominently displayed
on the monitors in the replay booth and on the sideline monitors
the officials will consult, so every time there is a challenged
call, they'll get a minute of free advertising on national TV _
even though most viewers will have no idea who they are or what
they sell . . . San Antonio Spurs big man David Robinson is
inspiring more than basketball fans these days. Recently, 49ers
All-World receiver Jerry Rice said he finally sees the end of his
career approaching and intends to take a page from Robinson's book
on how to handle it. Rice has promised the 49ers he will not
continue griping about getting the ball more as he did a year ago,
when he got into a public spat with coach Steve Mariucci. Rice
often complained he was not being used properly as the ball more
and more went to younger receivers Terrell Owens and J.J. Stokes.
Upon reflection, Rice says he sees times have changed and so has
his place in the Niners' offense. ``It's hard to step away, but
I've just got to let go,'' Rice said. ``I want to go out feeling
good about my career. Basically, it's coming to an end and I don't
want to go out on a sour note. I'm not going to be able to carry
this team like I used to.'' Rice doesn't have to. Owens led the
club with 14 touchdown catches last year and two weeks ago signed a
$3.5 million tender offer for this year with hopes of negotiating a
long-term deal before the season begins. Stokes also signed a new,
long-term deal for big bucks, so the two of them are clearly the
pass-catching future in the Bay Area. Rice, who may well be the
greatest receiver of all time, seems to have finally accepted this
after fighting it much of last year, and he said that acceptance
came from watching the way Robinson embraced his diminished role in
the Spurs' offense after the arrival of Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shed no tears for former Redskins owner John Kent Cooke, son of
the late owner Jack Kent Cooke. The younger Cooke couldn't muster
up the cash to outbid Daniel Snyder for the team after his father
died, but he stands to collect about $60 million as his share of
the sale and is using some of it to move to Bermuda. Cooke won't be
allowed to work there because he's not a British citizen, but he
also doesn't have to pay taxes. Not a bad trade off. Although Cooke
will still have to pay federal income tax, he beats the District of
Columbia's 9.5 percent income tax, which will save him millions . .
. The Denver Broncos received their new Super Bowl rings at a
recent ceremony at the toney Breckenridge Resort in Colorado
Springs, and they may have needed a Bronco just to carry their new
hunk of jewelry home. The 120-diamond ring was 46 pennyweight and
included Australian orange diamonds that filled the two horses
manes and eyes on the ring. It also included two Lombardi Trophies
on one side and six diamonds on the other to represent the six
Super Bowl appearances by the Broncos. Last year's rings cost
$15,000 each. This year's were closer to $20,000 each. What do you
do with a ring bigger than your finger if your name isn't Dennis
Rodman? . . . The Falcons did something historic last year by
reaching the Super Bowl for the first time. Now they want to do
something else to make history. They want to move their practice
facility into Stone Mountain Park, the most visited state park in
Georgia. The new facility would cost an estimated $10 million and
would be built for the Falcons by a Missouri company that
specializes in theme parks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
