<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLENDOR ON THE GRASS AT WIMBLEDON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Monday is not just another day, despite what the
backhanding Scarlett O'Hara used to say. Not around here anyway.
This Monday hasn't happened for 100 years: the first day of the
last Wimbledon of the century.
</P>
<P>
   All right, so, for once, let's lay out the Big W's formal
designation: The Lawn Tennis Championships at the All England Lawn
Tennis &AMP; Croquet Club. A mouthful even for a babbler like Eddie
Andelman. But just-plain Wimbledon suffices anywhere across the
globe, though curiously mispronounced as ``Wimple-ton'' by most
Americans, including several who have won it.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Sampras has got it right after a few misses, while becoming
the resident maestro in weeding the grass of rivals. He and ruling
associate Jana Novotna, granted first and fifth seeds,
respectively, would dearly love to kiss the century goodbye by
winning as two locals, Reggie Doherty and Blanche Bingley Hillyard,
did in 1899.
</P>
<P>
   As the first and foremost fiesta of the fuzzy ball, launched in
1877 in the lawn-proud southwestern London suburb called Wimbledon,
Wimbledon is alone among the four majors in preserving God's own
sod as the mysterious, tricky terrain. The US and Australia,
preferring green only in the color of their pavement, abandoned
grass in 1975 and 1988, respectively. Trusting little that is
embraced by speakers of English, the French have stuck with red, as
in clay and wine, throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Californian Stan Smith, the victor in 1972, muses, ``Grass is
pretty strange to the players now. When I was coming up all the
important tournaments _ except the French and Italian _ were on
grass. But now, for a tournament of this importance to keep this
surface, it's sort of like the Indy 500 being run on a rutted dirt
road. But . . . tradition is pretty strong at Wimbledon.''
</P>
<P>
   So, ladies and gentlemen, start your internal engines, and get
those sneakered wheels moving. It's going to be a bumpy 13-day ride
even though groundskeeper Eddie Seaward's emerald rectangles,
foremost the revered throne room, Centre Court, look innocently
placid and untroubled today.
</P>
<P>
   The house is silent, sunswept. You can hear the birds kibbitzing
amid the decor of plentiful ivy, roses, petunias, and hydrangeas,
and the scent of freshly mowed lawns. Yet dawn will bring thousands
besieging the gates, though patiently lining up in that peculiarly
civilized British way, the vanguard of almost 300,000 patrons for
the fortnight.
</P>
<P>
   As the tempests in rectangles begin, a triangle with Graf,
Agassi, and Sampras at the corners takes shape to hold tremendous
attention. Even though there may not be another championship within
Staffi Graf (she has seven), Pete Sampras, or Andre Agassi, champ
in 1992, they are the story line _ with offshoots in several other
directions, of course.
</P>
<P>
   For the homefolks: Can 1998 semifinalist Tim Henman, a 7-1 shot
with London bookmakers, make the prominent statue of Fred Perry
blink by becoming the first Englishman to triumph since Fred
himself 63 years ago?
</P>
<P>
   For casual observers who judge tennis players by their pictures:
Might the Glitter Girl, 18-year-old Anna Kournikova, semifinalist
in 1997, keep photographers in ecstacy for two weeks as the
big-hitter girl in the winner's circle? At 33-1 she's a terrific
wager.
</P>
<P>
   For the sociology-minded who love a ghetto-to-gravy story: Is
this the moment for Venus Williams, just turned 19, and 5-1 with
the bookies, to make her major breakthrough? (Unfortunately kid
sister Serena, ranked No. 10, has pulled out with the flu.)
</P>
<P>
   For the Down Under-looking and those mindful of the Aussie-US
Davis Cup clash headed for Boston: Will Patrick Rafter, twice US
Open champ, pull himself together at 12-1 to renew his country's
bygone stranglehold on the Big W?
</P>
<P>
   For supporters of the aging and infirm: Has the champ, Novotna,
edging toward 31, recovered enough from an ankle injury in Paris,
to display her splendor on the grass one more time and pay off at
14-1?
</P>
<P>
   For Dutch treat fans: Couldn't 1996 champ Richard Krajicek, the
only man to beat Sampras here over the last six years, crank up his
right elbow again to delight every Heineken sipper and bettor (8-1)
in his homeland?
</P>
<P>
   For ``children should be seen _ and heard'' _ believers: Has the
champ of 1997 and 3-2 favorite Martina Hingis, whose behavorial age
at the French matched her world ranking (1), gotten over her
Parisian petulance?
</P>
<P>
   Still, the compelling trio are the reconstituted Graf and Agassi
(both 4-1) plus the unraveling Sampras. Are Steffi and Andre
writing new acts in their dramas? Can Pete dig himself out of an
avalanche of ``a terrible, disastrous year for me if I don't win
here or the US Open''?
</P>
<P>
   Pete remains No. 1 into a seventh successive year only because
the guys with the opportunity to seize his lottery-winning digit _
Rafter, Carlos Moya, Marcelo Rios, Henman, Greg Rusedski, Petr
Korda, Yevgeny Kafelnikov, Krajicek, Mark Philippoussis _ swooned
at the opportunity. Kafelnikov, Moya, and Rios did get there for a
few minutes but found the throne as comfortable as an electric
chair.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, still the prohibitive favorite (11-8) is well aware of
his rendezvous with history, despite the buffeting he's taking in
this his worst season. ``I feel like I'm home again,'' he says. ``I
know the grass, and how to win. Look, I never dreamed I'd win five
times. One more would be great, but it wouldn't be like I didn't
win my share if I lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning would make him the man of the century, edging Laurie
Doherty, a long-vanished Limey (1902-06) and Swede Bjorn Borg
(1976-80) with whom he's lodged at five. He'd also pull abreast of
Aussie Roy Emerson (1961-67) at the male record of 12 major singles
titles.
</P>
<P>
   Two behind the female record of 24, belonging to Margaret Court
(1960-75), Graf is suddenly a contender again after winning the
French, her first major in three years. Also she's two behind
Martina Navratilova's Wimbledon record of nine (1978-90).
</P>
<P>
   But Steffi says, ``I never give it a thought. I'm just happy to
be playing again, out on this wonderful grass. After my knee and
back injuries two years ago, Wimbledon again didn't look
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   After losing to distantly ranked Doug Flach here two years ago
and callow Tommy Haas in 1998, possibilities for Agassi could be
seen maybe only in a cracked crystal ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have written that Paris scenario of mine _ too
crazy,'' grins the improbable champion, who kept rebounding from
near defeat to the only major that had eluded him. ``And if I had
nobody would have bought it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now I'd believe in anything. How about a Sampras-Agassi
all-American final on July 4?''
</P>
<P>
   That's a long tomorrow away, as even Scarlett O'Hara would
agree. But at least Andre's no longer gone with the wind, and Pete
just might hang on in the current gale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
