<SLUG> BC-BOX-GRANT-SAVARESE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANT OUTPOINTS SAVARESE UNANIMOUSLY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His handlers have anointed Michael Grant the future
heavyweight champion of the world. And he just may be, if he could
somehow manage to start each of his fights in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   It was another slow start for Grant against Lou Savarese before
3,583 at the Theater at Madison Square Garden on Saturday night.
Grant (30-0) tossed away the first couple of rounds like
yesterday's garbage before his interest was piqued. Unfortunately
for Savarese (39-3), Grant began punishing him with well-placed
uppercuts once he got going, and that paved the way for Grant to
score a 10-round unanimous decision. Judges Melvina Lathan and
Steve Weisfeld both scored the fight 98-90, and Judge Joe Dwyer
scored it 97-91.
</P>
<P>
   Lennox Lewis, the World Boxing Council heavyweight champion, was
sitting at ringside, scouting Grant as a future opponent. Lewis
might take heart that Grant gets hit often and is an inviting
target. But Lewis might not like the fact that Grant's jab, when he
decides to use it, lands with the authority of a jackhammer.
</P>
<P>
   Grant tried to finish off Savarese in the final round, throwing
his entire arsenal at him. He managed to score two knockdowns in
the round, but he could not knock out Savarese. On the first
knockdown, Grant landed a barrage of punches that sent Savarese
through the second rope and onto the ring apron. Savarese managed
to climb back into the ring and get to his feet by the count of
seven.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese, who received a cut along the outside of his left eye
from an unintentional head butt in the third round, was no
pushover. He tried to bully Grant and rough him up as best he
could. But Grant proved too powerful, completely controlling the
fight from the third round on.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Savarese was bleeding from the cut over his
eye, one on the bridge of his nose and another at his mouth. It was
testimony to how heavy the 256-pound Lewis's hands are.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the co-featured bout, heavyweight Maurice Harris (15-9-2), of
Newark, pounded out a 10-round unanimous decision against Jeremy
Williams (34-3) of Long Beach, Calif. Harris said he thought he
broke his hand in the third round, but it did not stop him from
battering Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The pounding began in the fourth round when Williams walked into
a big right hand that left him stumbling about the ring. Williams
never recovered and was operating on wobbly legs for the rest of
the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Harris was a last-minute replacement for Hasim Rahman, who
pulled out of the fight on Tuesday with what he said was a
backache. Lathan scored the fight 99-89, Weisfeld scored it 98-90
and Judge Fred Ucci scored it 98-91.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough to close him out, because I wasn't in the best of
shape,'' Harris said. ``I took this fight on four days' notice.''
</P>
<P>
   In his last fight, on the undercard of the Oscar De La Hoya-Oba
Carr welterweight bout in Las Vegas, Nev., last month, Harris
stopped Louis Monaco in a first-round technical knockout.
</P>
<P>
   On the undercard, the welterweight contender Vernon Forrest
(29-0) knocked out Ed Goins (16-13-2) at 2 minutes 57 seconds of
the fourth round. The lightweight contender Vivian Harris (14-0) of
Brooklyn won an eight-round unanimous decision over Damian Brazoban
(12-5) of the Dominican Republic. The welterweight John Molnar
(11-0) of Middletown, N.J., knocked out Claude Staten (4-8) at 1:59
of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Vaden (28-2), a former junior middleweight world champion,
scored a sixth-round technical knockout of Jorge Luis Vado (16-7-1)
when Vado did not come out of his corner for the seventh round.
Elvir Muriqi (8-0) scored a technical knockout when Thomas Barker
(1-2-1) quit after he was hit with a body shot at 2:03 of the
second round. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
