<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SNACKS-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD INDUSTRY SEES MOVIE SNACK BAR AS NEXT FRONTIER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Tired of Junior Mints and popcorn? Don't
worry. Coming soon to a theater near you: buffalo wings,
cappuccino, jalapeno-cheddar pretzels, Creamsicle Candy Twists and
Bavarian cream-filled churros.
</P>
<P>
   With bigger and flashier theater complexes seemingly opening
daily, operators have turned their attention to concession stands
in an effort to distinguish one megaplex from another down the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time of major experimentation with new items in
movie theaters,'' said Susan Cross, spokeswoman for the National
Association of Concessionaires, during the recent two-day Snack Bar
University trade show at the Disneyland Hotel. ``We're trying to
enhance the experience for customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Michael Kulka, sales director for pretzel maker J&AMP;J Snack
Foods, put it: ``We think people are looking for new kinds of
finger foods.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is a natural caution among theater operators who
fear killing the goose that's lays the golden eggs. Concessions
already make an awe-inspiring contribution to the bottom line from
$3 billion in annual sales at U.S. theaters. Wall Street analysts
believe AMC, for example, profits on snack bar sales in the
astronomical range of 82 to 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of return, it's little surprise the chains are
hesitant to make major lineup changes. ``We're constantly testing
new items, but we can't say what they are for competitive
reasons,'' AMC spokeswoman Brenda Nolte said. The chain offers a
standard menu with a few regional variations, such as pretzels in
California and pickles in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an industry where people are pretty tradition-bound
since snack bars work pretty well,'' said Lee Kopulos, chief of
Kansas-based Regal Distributing. ``On the other hand, you really
are starting to see a move toward restaurant-style foods. We've
noticed that operators are having to look at the problem of
customers leaving chicken wings on the theater floor, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   American moviegoers will spend around $7billion on movie tickets
this year and, for many of them, the experience won't be complete
without some kind of snack. Newer megaplex theaters feature the
combination of staggered starting times and massive concession
stands, both aimed at luring customers to the snack bar before they
go into the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``The staples will always be there but customers are starting to
expect more sophisticated menus,'' Cross admitted. ``On the other
hand, you don't want the experience of going to the snack bar to
get unwieldy.''
</P>
<P>
   Popcorn remains the undisputed No. 1 seller, followed by soda
and candy. Milk Duds, Red Vines, Junior Mints, Raisinets and
Goobers are among the top items. Nachos, pretzels, coffee, bottled
water, hot dogs, pizza and self-serve bulk candy occupy a second
tier _ somewhat popular but not pervasive.
</P>
<P>
   But those pitching offbeat items, such as Sheriff Blaylock's
chili, face resistance from theater operators wondering why they
should fix something if it's not broken. The answer, according to
Rick Kellum, vice president at the Texas-based chili company, is
that customers want something better and will pay for the
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're emphasizing that this is real chili, not wannabe chili
like you get at most places,'' Kellum said as he showed off a
temperature controlled dispenser that squirts out a cheese-chili
mix over three ounces of nacho chips. The suggested retail price is
$3.75 to $4.25. ``This tastes so much better than what you buy in
most places.''
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Sheriff Blaylock executives, whose first success came
in Southwestern convenience stores, traveled from Fort Worth to the
Anaheim convention to woo theater owners and persuade other
suppliers to switch over. ``What you're seeing here is the new wave
of how nachos are sold,'' the company president, Terry Awalt,
proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   Even more ambitious at the trade show was Vernon-based J&AMP;J Snack
Foods Corp. Nearly a dozen staffers offered new versions of Super
Pretzel, Funnel Cake, Mrs. GoodCookies, Tio PepeChurros, Luigis
Italian ices, Icees and Shape Ups frozen deserts. Sales director
Kulka admits that the challenge of weaning moviegoers away from
popcorn is daunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get so much more for your money from our pretzels than you
do from popcorn, which they have to serve in a bucket to give it
value,'' Kulka said.
</P>
<P>
   J&AMP;J counts the four big Los Angeles chains _ Mann, Edwards, AMC
and Pacific _ as customers and is pitching the idea of selling
fresh-baked goods at snack bars. For example, J&AMP;J's frozen pretzels
are dipped in browning soda, then heated up in small ovens.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition industry's biggest innovators are opening cafes,
usually specializing in desserts and coffees, in theater lobbies to
snag customers before and after shows.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-screen Loews Cineplex in Universal City offers a cafe
with a spectacular view of L.A.'s San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thought is that people don't necessarily want to rush out
of the theater once the movie's over, but you can't really sell
people cake and coffee from the snack bar,'' said Lee Josselyn,
vice president of the Galaxy Theaters chain. ``So we're putting the
cafes in every new project.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rosenberg, president of New Jersey-based Promotion in
Motion and Ferrara Pan, source of the Creamsicle twists, agrees
that in-theater cafes makes sense because Americans increasingly
place more of a premium on spending their time efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theaters have come to realize that they have to have
alternatives for customers, just like supermarkets sell
home-replacement meals,'' he said. ``You want more food items
because you want people there longer.''
</P>
<P>
   But AMC's Nolte said her chain has not adopted the in-theater
restaurant concept. ``We are in the exhibition business,'' she
said. ``Our prototype is to be part of an entertainment-themed
center with places that are in the restaurant business.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, though, is that customers want more options,
according to entertainment analyst Kevin Skislock of Laguna
Research Partners. So it's crucial that theaters diversify, even on
such a basic level as what's available at a snack bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have something different to choose, it makes the
experience of being at the theater much less mundane, even if you
still pick popcorn when you get to the front of the line,'' he
said. ``The fact that people have a choice to buy nachos or
pretzels makes it better, even if they exercise it only 10 percent
of the time. Exercising choice is appealing because if it's not
there, you feel like the snack bar's operated for the theater's
convenience instead of yours.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
