</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS WORK (TRIPLE) OVERTIME TO WIN CUP
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ The day before the Dallas Stars won the Stanley
Cup with a goal in triple overtime by Brent Hull, Pat Verbeek was
talking about the dreams of childhood. At 35, Verbeek has played
almost half his life in the National Hockey League without ever
before skating with the big, silver trophy. Like many of his Dallas
teammates, Verbeek is a scarred old pro. And, like many veteran
athletes, his outlook is part man and part boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the things that you always enjoyed when you are
out on your pond or out on your backyard rink,'' Verbeek said.
``You always enjoyed doing this, just being on the ice and playing
the game and loving to play the game. And now we are just really
grown-up kids right now and we are just trying to achieve the same
thing we did as kids in our dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night was not a dream, but at times it seemed surreal.
It was a 2-1 victory over the Buffalo Sabres, the fourth for the
Stars in six playoff games that were passionate and closely
contested. It was the first cup for the Stars, who began their
history as an expansion team in Minnesota in 1967 and moved to
Texas six seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   The winning goal was scored by Hull on a rebound at 14 minutes
51 seconds of the third overtime period. He knocked the puck past a
sprawled Dominik Hasek, the Sabres' star goalie, at 1:30 a.m.
Sunday to end a game that took more than five hours to play. Jere
Lehtinen and Mike Modano got the assists.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second-longest game in the history of the Stanley Cup
finals, falling just 22 second short of the longest finals games
ever; that one ended at 15:13 of triple overtime in 1990 when
Edmonton defeated Boston, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Conn Smythe trophy for most valuable player in the
post-season was won by the Stars' Joe Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres had 54 shots on goal and the Stars had 50.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, son of the Hall of Famer Bobby Hull, missed almost two
games of this series with what was called a groin injury. Playing
under obvious limitations, he passed up several shooting
opportunities earlier in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Jere Lehtinen scored in the first period for Dallas, and Stu
Barnes scored in the second for Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were the first team since the 1994 Rangers to win both
the regular-season championship and the Stanley Cup. Victory came
with a price. Many of the Stars played with injuries, including top
scorers like Mike Modano and Hull. Modano discussed why so many
athletes break into tears in such moments of triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you have been pushed to the limit,'' he said. ``Pushed
to the edge. It does not get any more emotionally or physically
draining than this run. And I think this is where you see a lot of
guys just break down when it is all done.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning goal ended a match of excruciating tension and tight
checking. Of the six games between these teams, three have ended
with scores of 2-1. In six games, the two teams have combined for
22 goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres had an 11-5 edge in first-period shots and had the
best scoring chances in the first 20 minutes. But the Stars held a
1-0 lead at the first intermission on a goal of the sort that
goalie Dominik Hasek does not usually allow. It was scored at 8:09
by Lehtinen, whose short shot got past Hasek between the post and
his stick. It was set up by Modano, who carried the puck over the
blue line and took a hit to make a play. Lehtinen scored despite
being checked by two Sabres. Modano entered the game with 5 points
this series, the most of any player, all of them assists. He also
had 21 points in the playoffs, tied with Nieuwendyk for the team
lead.
</P>
<P>
   After dominating the second period, Buffalo tied it, 1-1, on a
goal by Barnes shortly before the second intermission. Barnes, who
finished a rush by shooting from the right-wing circle over a
sliding Craig Ludwig, beat Belfour on the far side at 18:21.
</P>
<P>
   The contrasting technical styles were interesting. Choosing to
protect their early lead, the Stars fell back into the neutral-zone
trap and iced the puck frequently. The Sabres countered with speed
through the neutral zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars rarely threatened in the second session, although
Dallas defenseman Sergei Zubov had two great chances on a power
play, one a low wrist shot after a rink-length rush, the other a
high slap shot. At the other end, Buffalo's Aleksei Zhitnik clanged
a post.
</P>
<P>
   The third period was tense and edgy. Belfour was knocked down
twice, first when he was tripped by Miroslav Satan, later when
Vaclav Varada crashed into him. Belfour punched Varada and later
complained to the officials while the crowd roared. Zubov, a Ranger
on the 1994 cup team, played well and extensively, setting up
scoring chances at one end and breaking them up at the other.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 0151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
