<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990620.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2538 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAY-WOMEN-AZR &LR;      06-20 1754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAY-WOMEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE POLITICAL GAINS BY WOMEN, MEN GET BIGGEST PAYCHECKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID PARRISH  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women may run the state Capitol, but men still pull in the
biggest paychecks in Arizona government.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 34 highest-paid state employees there are no women,
and just five make the top 100.
</P>
<P>
   While women form more than half of the workforce within the
state agencies and universities, they have but 15 percent of the
nearly 800 jobs that pay $100,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics and other minorities fare about the same. Although 30
percent of the state's population are minorities, they compose only
14 percent of those paid $100,000 or more, according to a state
workforce review by &UR; ``The Arizona Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   At stake is not just money, but equity issues and bringing
diversity of backgrounds to the uppermost decision-making
positions.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kathryn L. Reed, a professor at the University of Arizona's
College of Medicine, is the highest-paid woman in state government,
drawing an annual salary of $201,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assumption has been that women would be there by now, but
they are not,'' Reed said. ``There are reasons, but there are
barriers.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the state's 800 six-figure jobs are held by key
non-elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   They include influential university deans and professors who
shape future leaders, as well as agency department heads and
deputies who establish policies affecting people statewide. Also
among them are senior staff members in both the Governor's Office
and the Legislature who craft Arizona's laws and determine where
tax dollars will be spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diversity is important because we serve a diverse
population,'' said John Clayton, newly appointed director of the
Department of Economic Security and the only African-American to
head a state agency. ``We have to know the people that we serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout state government, from clerks to Gov. Jane Hull,
there is general agreement that women and minorities are
underrepresented in the highest echelon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see both of those higher,'' Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns seemed out of place last Jan. 4 as she and four
other women made national news when they were sworn into the top
five positions in state government.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Fab Five,'' as they were called, projected an image that
Arizona was on the cutting edge when it came to gender equality.
</P>
<P>
   So why, overwhelmingly, are White males in state government
getting the big paychecks?
</P>
<P>
   Hull and other state officials said the state is making progress
but acknowledged that there is still a significant way to go. Women
and minorities are being hired in increasing numbers, they said.
Those women will have to work their way up the ladder to the upper
echelon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take time,'' Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office in September 1997, she has appointed four
women to key state positions, including Mary Peters, the first
female director of the Arizona Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made 16 judicial appointments _ three Hispanics and three
women,'' Hull said. ``You have to continue to reach out and
continue to give people a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hispanics make &UR; up more than 20 percent of Arizona's
population, they hold 5 percent of the jobs paying a six-figure
salary at the University of Arizona and 6 percent among workers in
state agencies and at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State University and Northern Arizona University refused
to release ethnic background information on their highest-paid
employees, even without names attached, citing privacy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the demographics of the state government's nearly
63,000 employees reflect Arizona's population, both in gender and
ethnic background. But the higher up the job, the less likely a
woman or a minority holds the position.
</P>
<P>
   Women professors at the medical school who are paid $100,000 or
more annually still earn, on average, $34,500 less than their male
counterparts. More than 90 percent of UA full professors are White.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised that we don't have more than 10 percent minority
professors,'' said UA President Peter W. Likins, who, at $195,000
annually, is tied for 44th on the pay list.
</P>
<P>
   Many reasons were cited for the pay disparities in interviews
with more than two dozen employees throughout the ranks of state
government. Rarely was intentional discrimination mentioned as the
cause for the disparity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a conspiracy or malice in male behavior,'' Likins
said. ``Why do we still find ourselves not advancing women to
leadership positions? My own guess is human beings are very slow to
accept change.''
</P>
<P>
   State employees cited two major reasons for the disparity: the
``mommy track'' that women sometimes are on, and White male
executives not looking beyond their friends when they hire or
promote.
</P>
<P>
   ``You appoint people you feel comfortable with, who hold your
own views,'' said Deborah Brouhard, chairwoman of the Commission on
the Status of Women at ASU.
</P>
<P>
   Because White males dominate the top positions and often promote
or hire other White males, the status quo is maintained, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not be a conscious decision; it's a comfortable
decision,'' Brouhard said.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton said he was hired 16 months ago as deputy director at
the Department of Economic Security because then-Director Linda
Blessing did a nationwide search, seeking the most qualified
person.
</P>
<P>
   A similar search for the best candidate would over time increase
the number of minorities and women in elite positions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must look at quality first, then diversity,'' Clayton
said. ``I'd be offended with a policy that allowed people to just
come in strictly on race.''
</P>
<P>
   At $115,000, Clayton is ranked 454th on the state's payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Women throughout the ranks of state government said that
building a career often takes second place to raising children.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman sometimes makes choices that make it less likely they
will get one of those top jobs,'' said Heather E. Campbell, an ASU
assistant professor in the School of Public Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   When women gravitate to a job that allows them to spend more
time with their children, that may limit the extra time needed to
push a career forward, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Meeks, an accountant at the Department of Administration,
said that over the past 14 years she had to sacrifice career plans
while she raised her child and tried to squeeze in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got my bachelor's degree. I took one course per
semester. It took almost 14 years to do it,'' Meeks said. ``I see
men as old as I am in much higher positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeks plans to become a certified public accountant shortly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to move up to the managerial level,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even those women who have reached significant positions in
government said it was not easy to have both a career and a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have made a lot of conscious decisions that have hurt my
career, but I wanted to choose my family,'' said Margie A.
Emmermann, a Hispanic who was appointed by Hull as the state's
policy advisor for Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think women feel more of a responsibility to hold the
family together,'' Emmermann said.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, an obstetrician and gynecologist at the University of
Arizona's medical school, said the long hours necessary in the
highest positions at the university often conflict with the needs
of family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are looking for more of a balance; they do care how
their family lives are going,'' Reed said. ``I know women who have
said, `I can't turn away from my family to give what it takes to
succeed in academic medicine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   State institutions may have to rethink the demands they place on
their executives at the expense of families, Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   At the UA College of Medicine, Reed is one of only a handful of
women who hold the rank of full professor; men account for 92
percent of those faculty.
</P>
<P>
   This is in contrast to the students in the medical college,
where half are women.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of women doctors increases, so will the number of
women full medical school professors, said Dr. James Dalen, dean of
the College of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Among the associate professors in the medical college, 18
percent are women. Women make up 36 percent of assistant
professors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in 10 years we will see a significant increase,''
Dalen said of female full professors at the College of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, about 7 percent of doctors nationwide were
women. Today, women make up about 21 percent of physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in medical school there was one woman in my
class,'' added Dalen, who is 17th on the pay list at $264,450
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the pay disparity between men and women
at the medical school can be traced back to the types of medicine
that women choose to practice, Dalen said.
</P>
<P>
   Fees from patients generate much of a professor's pay at the
medical school. Surgeons generate the most income, and the
overwhelming number of surgeons are men, Dalen said.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons also put in the longest hours at the medical school,
which Reed said makes that specialty less attractive to some women.
</P>
<P>
   To address the disparity of women in the top ranks, UA is
developing a study to determine if women are being discriminated
against, and, if so, then how, President Likins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus right now is on gender bias, but the lessons are
transferable (to minorities),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said that sometimes women can contribute to the disparity
in pay or promotions by not speaking up for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four to five years ago, I did bring up (that) there was a
discrepancy with my salary and the men who did the same work,''
Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   She gave university officials a choice: Raise her salary or
lower the men's.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they raised my salary,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That style of aggressive career card play was alien to her, Reed
said, as it is to many other women. Often women assume that good
work will be rewarded, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to be taught by my business friend, you have to ask for
a raise,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Reed is now working with College of Medicine administrators to
establish a program where women professors at the medical school
will receive leadership training to help them progress up the
academic ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love for us to be gender- or ethnic-blind,'' Reed
said. ``I wish it would happen overnight, but I know there are
still barriers.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
