<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PHILLIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WIN WITH PLAN B
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Turns out the Los Angeles Dodgers really do have
this nifty little team, it was just on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   With a lineup that would look familiar during a spring training
road game, the Dodgers pushed the Philadelphia Phillies around on a
hazy Saturday afternoon for an 8-1 victory before a Dodger Stadium
crowd of 32,315.
</P>
<P>
   For one day, all things went right. Runners were advanced, plays
were made, mistakes by the opponent were taken advantage of, hits
fell and fell, and Darren Dreifort made like the dominating
right-hander everyone keeps waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   A Dodgers squad that had lost six of its past seven and been
feeble at the plate punched out 13 hits on the way to a three-run
third and a five-run fifth. As though there were nothing to it.
Only most of the big hits came from the likes of Todd
Hollandsworth, just seconds off the disabled list; Craig Counsell,
making his first start as a Dodger; Tripp Cromer, Dave Hansen,
Angel Pena and Trenidad Hubbard. Not the guys the $84-million
Dodgers normally push in their marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Young dubbed them the ``rescue team.'' Inspired part by
nagging injuries and part by desperation, Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson shook things up, waited to see how they fell, and then
basked in the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``They scored more runs than I think I've seen in a month,''
Johnson said. ``That should take some heat off the regulars, or put
some pressure on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson probably wouldn't be too upset if the regulars did feel
some pressure. Four of the regulars who sat _ Eric Karros, Devon
White, Jose Vizcaino and Young _ were a combined 9 for 51 (.176)
during the opening four games of the homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Vizcaino has a sore hamstring, White a sore groin, Young a sore
ankle and Gary Sheffield a sore knee. Fortunately, they were not
sorely missed. Hubbard continued his recent hot play (10 hits in
his past 23 at-bats) with three hits; Hollandsworth struck the
day's biggest blow with a two-run, two-out double in the third;
Cromer singled in two and Counsell added two hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously this won't be the team to take us forth, but who
knows, it might be the team to spark us,'' Hubbard said.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort was out of the rotation for one day last week, or at
least until the Carlos Perez-inspired demise of the bench water
cooler. Dreifort's whole season has been a struggle. He was tied
for second in the NL in wild pitches (eight) and fourth in walks
(46), and had seen his ERA swell to 6.42. But Saturday, he made
like someone who had undergone an amazing transformation.
</P>
<P>
   For three innings, he did not allow a hit. Through five, he had
allowed only two. He finally gave up a run in the sixth on a Ron
Gant single and Scott Rolen double, but when he left after 62/3
innings, he had surrendered only six hits, struck out five and
walked only two.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a pretty good statement for why he deserves to
start,'' Johnson said. ``He actually pitched. He didn't overthrow.
He actually threw quite a few changeups and stayed in a nice
rhythm. That was a good pitching performance.''
</P>
<P>
   For a team hungry for positive news, it made for a good day. The
Phillies didn't help their cause, giving right-hander Robert Person
_ who began the year as Toronto's closer _ just his third start of
the year. After he surrendered three runs (one earned) in four
innings, right-hander Mike Grace took over and the game got out of
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort singled off the wall, Counsell dropped a hit and
Hubbard's RBI single to center was overrun by Doug Glanville for an
error. Raul Mondesi doubled off Rolen's glove at third to score two
and Grace hit Adrian Beltre and Hansen with pitches before getting
pulled. Cromer singled in two off right-hander Amaury Telemaco, and
the Rescue Rangers had the Dodgers cruising.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Mills got the only batter he faced, and Jamie Arnold held
the Phillies to two hits in the final two innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a team,'' Mondesi said. ``You can't just play one group
all the time. That's why they call it a team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
