<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREIFORT PITCHES LIKE HE BELONGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was Darren Dreifort, pitcher under control.
Darren Dreifort, pitcher with control.
</P>
<P>
   After Dreifort gave up seven earned runs in his last start, Los
Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he was moving the
talented but frustrating right-hander to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Then left-hander Carlos Perez, who actually leads Dreifort in
the frustration department, blew up and Dreifort was back in the
rotation before he even had a chance to be skipped.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday he pitched like someone who was trying to make it
known he wanted to stay in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really, I just felt like I had to make pitches and let the
defense work behind me, and they did,'' Dreifort said.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort (6-5) went 62/3 innings, allowing one run on six hits
in the Dodgers 8-1 victory. He walked two and struck out five. Of
his 98 pitches, 65 were for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pitching today, instead of throwing,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I felt, too,'' Dreifort said.
</P>
<P>
   With an off-day Monday, Johnson can continue to use Dreifort as
his No.4 starter and not need a fifth starter until Friday in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   B-team power: After using only two starters _ Raul Mondesi and
Adrian Beltre _ from the opening-day lineup and watching the
Dodgers score their most runs since a 9-3 victory at Cincinnati on
May 26, Johnson didn't sound like a man ready to scrap success.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few of 'em would be in the lineup again today,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' he said. ``I've been scratching around, trying to
get something more exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, the only Dodger to start every game this season, said
he expects to be rested today. Sheffield (inflamed knee) will also
likely held out again.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was able to start three left-handers (Craig Counsell,
Todd Hollandsworth, Dave Hansen) to put some flexibility in his
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter honored: The Dodgers retired the No. 1 media credential
of Bob Hunter, former sports writer for the Daily News and the Los
Angeles Examiner, in a ceremony prior to the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also honored Hunter with an exhibit at their Dodger
Experience, an interactive museum on the club level.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter was inducted into the Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y.,
as the recipient of the J.G. Taylor Spink Award in 1988. When he
retired from the Daily News in 1992 after seven decades as an area
reporter, the Dodgers named their press room at Dodgertown after
him. He died the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Hall of Fame scribe Jim Murray's No.2 media credential is
the only other press pass retired by the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   FYI: Right-hander Doug Bochtler (5.54 ERA in 12 relief
appearances without a decision) was designated for assignment to
make roster room for Hollandsworth. If he clears waivers, he will
be reassigned to Triple-A Albuquerque.... Hollandsworth went from
the DL to the cleanup spot. ``I was just pumped to play, it didn't
matter where I was hitting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
