<DOCNO> NYT19990620.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2541 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CUP-PREVIEW-LADN     06-20 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSE BOWL SHOWCASES SECOND DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ There won't be 78,000 screaming fans inside
the Rose Bowl today, but that shouldn't detract from what figures
to be two attractive matchups on the second day of the 1999 Women's
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Less than half that fan total likely will show up to watch
Germany face Italy at 4 p.m., followed by Nigeria and North Korea
at 6:30 p.m. in the only matches the Rose Bowl will host until the
championship and third-place games on July 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Group B matchup between Germany and Italy figures to be one
of the most intriguing of the tournament's first two days.
</P>
<P>
   Both are traditional European powers and both will be trying to
keep pace with Brazil in what is known as the ``Group of Death.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil got off to a rousing start with a 7-1 win over Mexico in
East Rutherford, N.J., Saturday where 78,000-plus fans also watched
the U.S. knock off Denmark 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take a very tight midfield,'' Italy forward Patrizia
Panico said of the key to today's match. ``We've going to have to
push a lot in the midfield and counter-attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy usually plays a deliberate style and is content taking its
time in building an attack.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders up front are Panico and Rita Guarino, both of whom
roam freely and constantly change sides.
</P>
<P>
   Midfielders Antonella Carta and Federica D'Astolfo are the
primary ball handlers, but the Italians also are boosted by a
strong back line, featuring Damiana Deiana and Roberta Stefanelli,
along with veteran goalkeeper Giorgia Brenzan.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, the runner-up at the 1995 World Cup in Sweden, needed
to win a playoff against the Ukraine just to make it to the U.S.
But now that the Germans are here, they loom as a possible dark
horse.
</P>
<P>
   They are bolstered by one of the world's best defenses,
featuring Doris Fitschen and Steffi Jones, which should make
Italy's penetration difficult. Up front, Germany has its own
quality tandem, led by Sandra Smisek and Birgit Prinz.
</P>
<P>
   As with Italy, Germany also has two veteran midfielders, Martina
Voss and Bettina Wiegmann, to help distribute.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1991 World Cup in China, Germany beat Italy 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria will be eager to show the world its time has finally
arrived. A victory also would give the Super Falcons huge
confidence heading into Thursday's match against the U.S. in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In two previous World Cup appearances, Nigeria has one tie and
five losses. Coach Ismaila Mabo said that record should change.
</P>
<P>
   ``By our predictions, even though we are in a very tough group,
I believe we shall be able to go beyond the first round,'' Mabo
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marvelous'' Mercy Akide and Patience Avre lead the charge up
front for the speedy Nigerians, who at times can be suspect on the
back line.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea, appearing in its first World Cup, is one of the
tournament's mystery teams, doing its best to not be distracted
while in the U.S., shunning interview requests and tourist
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   What is known is that the North Koreans are physical and known
to ``win ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Kum Sil, who scored six goals during the Asian Cup, is the
weapon up front. Teammate Kim Sun Hui is the team's best defender,
representing her country at the FIFA World Stars match in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 0209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990620.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2542 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-US-DENMARK-LADN     06-20 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-DENMARK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WINS WORLD CUP OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ They came by the thousands, in pony
tails and soccer cleats, to see the best in the world. Mia Hamm was
all of that and more.
</P>
<P>
   In front of the largest crowd to ever witness a women's sporting
event at Giants Stadium, Hamm led the United States soccer team to
a 3-0 Women's World Cup victory over Denmark on Saturday afternoon
with a goal and an electricity that stirred 78,972 fans every time
she touched the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm's goal, the world-record 110th of her career, came just 17
minutes into the first game of the three-week tournament that
concludes July 10 at the Rose Bowl. It also set a tone for the U.S.
team favored to regain the title it lost four years ago to Norway.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team, which won the gold at the 1996 Olympics in
Atlanta, plays Nigeria on Thursday in a Group A game at Soldier
Field in Chicago. Later in the tournament, it could face an
improving Brazil, which routed Mexico 7-1 in the second game at
Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful way to start the tournament,'' Hamm said.
``This is what we always dreamed the World Cup should be. To see
the crowd and the atmosphere was phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   The response by the crowd, many of them girls and young women,
was overwhelming to the team, which started slowly before Hamm's
goal. Many players admitted after the game that the sight of the
waving American flags brought the team to tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great atmosphere to play soccer,'' said Julie Foudy,
who scored the second U.S. goal. ``But this is our event. In the
locker room, we were saying, `This is our party. Welcome to our
party.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And the party always goes through Hamm, whose brilliant
playmaking always has been the hallmark of this team.
</P>
<P>
   She is a reluctant star who has appeared in ads with Michael
Jordan, but who often deflects the attention to teammates. And like
Jordan, Hamm seems to play one gear above the competition.
</P>
<P>
   On her goal, Hamm settled a ball that deflected off a defender
as she tried to push it through with her right foot. She beat the
defender to the ball and, with her left foot, drilled a 30-foot
dipping volley over the outstretched hand of Denmark goalie Dorthe
Larsen and into the top of the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``That changed everything,'' said Denmark's Mikka Hansen. ``They
started slowly, but you could see their confidence building. After
that they took off.''
</P>
<P>
   The proof might have been on defense, which pretty much went
untested after the first eight minutes. U.S. goalkeeper Briana
Scurry recorded her 50th career shutout and had to make just two
saves.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the U.S. team wasn't so precise at the outset.
Cindy Parlow and Kristine Lilly each hit the crossbar. Lilly also
missed a wide open shot in the second half, but capped the scoring
with a goal with three minutes left in the match.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm's nifty pass across the middle set up Foudy's goal in the
73rd minute. After scoring, Foudy raced to the U.S. bench, then
struck a pose that was equal parts show business and Heisman
Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, she must have been doing an Austin Powers
thing,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly, who grew up in Wilton, Conn., also displayed a little
American brashness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was caught up in the emotion of the thing,'' she said. ``I
was fouled just before I scored and when I scored I told the Danish
player, `this one is for you.' This was awesome and unbelievable.
You can't compare this to the Olympics. This was so much better.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was better, too. In fact, it was the largest crowd
ever to see a sporting event in Giants Stadium history, beating the
78,817 that watched an NFL playoff game between the New York Jets
and Jacksonville Jaguars in January. The stadium record was set in
1995, when the Mass held by Pope John Paul II drew 82,948.
</P>
<P>
   Women's World Cup CEO Marla Messing estimated a $4 million gate
for Saturday's doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   ``People outside soccer know this stadium, the name Giants
Stadium, and that what happens here is great events,'' midfielder
Brandi Chastain said. ``And women's soccer now can be put right up
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
