<HEADLINE>
DUNCAN NBA'S NEW POSTER BOY 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The NBA's next goodwill ambassador lives here. He
is everything the league should want in a player. He's talented.
He's self-disciplined, the anti-Antoine on the court. He should be
the guy around which the league builds its marketing campaign in
the next century.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA ought to revisit its scheduling situation so that each
city gets to see Tim Duncan a little more. It's a treat to watch
him. It's a treat to listen to him. He simply shows up for work,
does his job without fanfare or hoopla, and represents all that's
good about the game.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan isn't the sole reason the Spurs lead the NBA Finals, 2-0,
but he's a very, very, very big reason. But what's so refreshing
about him is that he stands out for all the right reasons: he's
fundamentally sound and schooled on the floor _ watch his footwork
some time _ and he's not a crotch-grabber, chest-thumper,
high-fiver, finger-wagger, or body wiggler.
</P>
<P>
   His coach, Gregg Popovich, likes to say there's ``no MTV'' in
Duncan. There isn't. There isn't even any VH-1 in his game, not to
mention any shindig or even Lawrence Welk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real strange bird in the sense that he's uncommon for
someone his age,'' Popovich said. ``He's got this natural
disposition. I always say he's on island time because nothing fazes
this guy. It doesn't matter if he does something real well or he
makes a bad turnover. He will compete on the very next play. He
doesn't get excited about anything and I don't think there are too
many guys like that.''
</P>
<P>
   It goes without saying that Duncan got the best arrangement
possible when the lottery delivered him here. There was a good team
in place. There was a superstar in place. He could blend in, be
allowed to grow, and not have to worry about being a savior. That
would not have been the case in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   He fits in well with the relaxed pace here. The frenetic,
frantic East would have been horrifying to him. He's content with
playing in a small market in a city with one major pro team and
with an amenable climate that probably reminds him of his native
St. Croix.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, he will start feeling the tugs and pressures of
stardom now that he's front and center in the NBA firmament. ``If
it comes, it comes,'' he shrugged, referring to the marketing
opportunities sure to come his way. ``I have a lot of fun with what
I do. But I'm still pretty boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to us. We'd like to see many more of him. That's the problem
_ there aren't any. So enjoy him when and where you can.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Would someone please explain what the New Jersey Nets are doing?
OK, they took a shot at Phil Jackson, who, it might be argued, used
them to get the Lakers off the proverbial schneid. (Jackson
reportedly told the Nets owners that he didn't plan to coach this
season.) Now what? Don Casey, who knows what it's like to twist in
the wind, is, well, twisting in the wind. (He also had surgery this
past week.) The Nets' coaching staff will be at work Monday for a
mock draft meeting, even though the team has no first-round pick.
But they have no official head coach as Casey waits for ownership
to make up its mind. (Did Donald Sterling take over here when we
weren't looking?) There could be a rebound effect at work; once
Jackson has gone off the screen, it's an understandable
psychological hit to have to go to the next name, whoever it is.
(The Knicks will face that same dilemma should they let Jeff Van
Gundy go.) Is there another name? Well, Chuck Daly has been calling
people _ to boost Casey. People representing the interests of Mike
Fratello inquired and were told to forget about it. The only other
name that has surfaced is Van Gundy, which makes little sense. The
new owners of the Nets missed out on Jackson, which would have been
a home run. That doesn't mean they have to revert to Knucklehead
Mode in going to Plan B. Jackson left them high and dry. Why should
they then turn around and do the same thing to Casey? Either hire
him or tell him he's not the guy . . . As The Penny Turns, Episode
XXVXLMXCCLXM: The latest Penny Hardaway rumor has the Orlando
guard, thought to prefer a warm, Western Conference clime such as
Phoenix, instead moving north to Toronto as part of a
sign-and-trade deal. The Raptors would part with Doug Christie,
maybe one of their lotto picks, and, perhaps, another body. But
they could absorb some of the extra money because they have cap
room. Why Toronto? Well, Hardaway is pals with both Tracy McGrady
and Vince Carter, although he wouldn't solve the Raptors' need for
a real point guard. But should he do it, the move would put Toronto
on the NBA map for years to come. What seems more and more
inevitable is that he's played his last game in Orlando. But
knowing Penny . . . There's still a lot of speculation and talk,
but with 10 days left before the draft, the only player anyone is
mentioning in terms of actually wanting is Steve Francis. Oh, and
by the way, Elton Brand did measure 6 feet 8 inches at the Chicago
pre-draft camp . . . Johnny Davis and Sidney Lowe are in the
running for the No. 2 assistant's job in Orlando. Dave Wohl, as we
mentioned last week, has the No. 1 spot. Don't be surprised if
Butch Beard resurfaces in Washington as an assistant to new coach
Gar Heard. And while we're on the topic, how did the Wizards manage
to time their announcement the same day as Jackson's coronation in
Los Angeles? Heard has had one coaching assignment and went 9-44
with the hopeless, pre-Quinn Buckner Mavericks. Isiah Thomas's
chances in Washington apparently were torpedoed when he went
directly to ownership and then didn't exactly get ringing
endorsements from either Pistons owner Bill Davidson or former
Toronto owner Allan Slaight . . . Dominique Wilkins not only has
been waived by the Magic (which owed him a small guarantee), he's
also switched agents _ again _ and is selling his spectacular home
in Dover, which backs up to the Charles River. Wilkins has latched
on with Chicago's Mark Bartlestein, who will need his considerable
skills to find employment for Wilkins, who turns 40 in January. If
you're interested in the home, it's on the market for a paltry $2.5
million, about double what Wilkins paid for it in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jackson may eventually be terrific for the Lakers, but he
inherits the same problems Kurt Rambis had: no point guard, no
power forward, no chemistry. The Scottie Pippen-Glen Rice rumor
makes sense from the Lakers' standpoint because Pippen knows how to
bring up the ball and get the triangle offense in gear. He's also
miserable in Houston. Rice is not all that keen about being the
third option in LA and would be a risk keeping around if not
extended. Whether it happens, of course, is another matter.
Jackson's real strength in Chicago was managing the team, rather
than coaching it. He knew whose button to push and when to push it.
He had a real feel for the dynamics of a team and what it needs to
make it through those interminable NBA seasons. The challenge in LA
will be to institute such an atmosphere and also get the players to
play defense. They don't have a serious defender on their roster,
although they have several players capable of doing so when the
spirit moves them. There also will be greater pressure on the
Lakers to get it done with Jackson aboard. But the team also is in
a very similar state as Chicago was when Jackson succeeded Doug
Collins. That Bulls team had talent, but was frustrated by its
inability to get over the hump. Jackson soon got them there . . .
Here's one rumor to keep in mind: Ron Mercer for Jerry Stackhouse.
The Celtics would have to add one of their many undesirables for
salary cap purposes, but those two would be the principles.
Stackhouse has never blossomed as projected and those are the kind
of projects Rick Pitino likes. But Stackhouse also is prone to
making unwise decisions at critical times, which is why Detroit
often had him on the pine at crunch time. From a financial
standpoint, he's under contract for several more seasons, so that
would be a benefit . . . Tough Luck Dept: Sixers president Pat
Croce, a real motorcycle kind of guy, started off this past week
for what he called an ``ocean to ocean'' bike trip with some
buddies. But while pulling off the road to change into rain gear,
Croce's left leg got in the way of a skidding bike. You know who
wins those collisions. Croce suffered multiple fractures in the leg
and underwent surgery at the University of Pennsylvania. He'll need
a second operation as well and, in the best of cases, will be back
to normal in three or four months. Allen Iverson said Croce has to
exercise more responsibility in the offseason . . . Tougher Luck
Dept: Former Celtic Derek Strong almost died last week after
routine surgery to fix his oft-broken nose. Strong had a bad
reaction to the anesthesia. His heart started racing moments before
he was to awake and his temperature shot up to an astonishing 107
degrees. He was wrapped in ice, injected with fluids, and given
dantrolene, which probably saved his life. While still unconscious,
he was airlifted to a second Orlando-area hospital. Strong had
thought about having the nose operation done at an outpatient
clinic. The fact that he chose a hospital may have saved his life .
. . Utah owner Larry Miller has a lot of work to do this summer.
His immediate concerns: re-signing Karl Malone, John Stockton, Jeff
Hornacek, Shandon Anderson, and lighting a fire under the comatose
Greg Ostertag. He said he expects Stockton and Hornacek to sign
one-year deals, although he added, ``If we had won, I think John
would have retired.'' Malone? ``There's no doubt Karl will return
to the Jazz for four more years,'' Miller said. He noted that
Malone is a neighbor and friend and that the Mailman's wife has
opened a bed and breakfast in the area. ``He's doing the things
that entrench you in a community,'' Miller said. ``I know four
years for a guy Karl's age is scary. But if I'm going to bet on a
guy that old playing well for four years, it's going to be Karl.''
Now, Larry, what about Ostertag? He showed up for one of the Jazz's
11 playoff games. That's not a good percentage. ``When does he
learn? It's really disconcerting,'' Miller said. ``At some point,
you gotta question what's inside of him.'' He said the Jazz have
one clip of Ostertag blocking Hakeem Olajuwon three times in one
stretch. ``That's the Ostertag we're trying to find,'' Miller said.
``But the defense and rebounding weren't there and he was getting
into foul trouble. Right now, for me, it's hard to see where we are
with him.'' Miller is committed to re-signing Anderson, although he
said, ``There were times when he was terrific for us and there were
times when you didn't even know he was on the floor. But that was
the story of our season. Our problem wasn't Karl, Jeff, and John.
Our problem was that our other guys didn't show up on a consistent
basis.'' One final Jazz moment: Jerry Sloan. ``I don't know anybody
else I'd rather have coach this team,'' Miller said. ``I think he's
looking forward to coaching beyond John and Karl.''
</P>
</TEXT>
