<HEADLINE>
LORDS OF RINGS THINK BIG 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ By choosing Turin over favored Sion as its 2006 winter
site Saturday, the International Olympic Committee was merely
following its recent preference for big cities (Salt Lake City and
Nagano) over cozy hamlets (Lillehammer and Albertville). Even
though the Lords were forbidden to visit the Italian city (they'd
seen the Swiss resort during the 2002 bidding), they knew enough
about it from the IOC's detailed evaluation report to conclude that
Turin could easily handle the massive carnival the Winter Games
have become.
</P>
<P>
   Though Sion would have had excellent venues in a charming,
compact setting, the Games are now as much about spectator access
and comfort (and corporate entertaining) as they are about the
athletes. Turin simply has many more hotel rooms and restaurants
and better overall transportation links than Sion. It also has the
usual big-city downside _ the venues are scattered. Only the ice
events will be in Turin. The Nordic events will be in Pragelato (a
two-hour drive), the Alpine in Sestriere (75 minutes away), the
freestyle in Sauze d'Oulx (60 minutes), and the bobsled/luge in
Beaulard (55 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not there was an anti-Swiss backlash against Sion
from the IOC voters (Swiss member Marc Hodler blew the whistle on
his colleagues during the Salt Lake payoff scandal), there may be a
Swiss backlash against the IOC. Swiss sources say their Parliament
may take a harsh view of the perks (including tax-free status) that
the Lausanne-based committee has always taken for granted . . .The
chief Lord of the Rings in a federal clink? It could happen if the
US government decides that Juan Antonio Samaranch broke the law by
taking gift firearms from the Salt Lake bidders out of the country
without a permit. The feds are looking at everything from customs
violations to money laundering as part of their investigation into
the scandal . . . Double-secret probation for beleaguered IOC
member Phil Coles of Australia. After already getting the ``most
severe warning'' for taking a Super Bowl trip from the Salt Lake
organizers, he received an additional reprimand from his colleagues
last week for compiling dossiers on them for the Utahns. He also
had to step down from the Sydney organizing committee and can't be
part of any IOC commission or working group for two years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fact that it took someone (i.e. Maurice Greene) more than a
decade to match the drug-tainted 100-meter mark set by Ben Johnson
shows one thing: steroids work. Johnson, meanwhile, is running into
roadblocks in his quest to run again at 37. While he's appealing
his lifetime ban (a Canadian arbitrator ordered him to be allowed
to compete domestically), he can't find a race to run in to post
the sub-10.6 he needs to qualify for the national championships.
Under the international track-and-field federation's contamination
rule, anyone who runs against Johnson is ineligible. So he's hoping
he can run a solo timed race before or after a meet and beg
Canadian officials to accept it. ``All I'm looking for is someone
to fire the gun and let him take off from the blocks,'' says Morris
Chrobotek, Johnson's agent. ``Ben can't contaminate a clock, can
he?'' . . . The inaugural Track and Field Association pro meet on
Long Island, which drew barely 3,000 a fortnight ago, was a
financial bust, costing its backers an estimated $1.5 million.
Their plan is still to have between five and eight meets next year
_ and make a profit in four or five years . . . What drug did Irish
swimmer Michelle Smith take to get her banned? Andro, the same
``diet supplement'' that will send Mark McGwire to the Hall of
Fame. Besides the four-year international suspension (for pouring
whiskey in her urine sample), which has pushed her into retirement
at 29, Swim Ireland is considering taking away Smith's national
records . . . Though the International Skating Union has suspended
the Russian and Ukrainian pairs judges who colluded during the
world championships in Helsinki, it won't change the results.
Sviatoslav Babenko and Alfred Korytek were caught winking and
blinking by Canadian TV before the marks for China's Shen Xue and
Zhao Hongbo were posted. Babenko and Korytek put Russian
competitors first and third, while most of their colleagues had
them second and fourth. So Babenko is banned for three years,
Korytek for two. Korytek, by the way, was the swing judge (and
father of Oksana Baiul's first coach) who gave Baiul the 1994
Olympic gold medal over Nancy Kerrigan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 0219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
