<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-2006 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRATE SWISS CLAIM IOC WAS AMISS 
</HEADLINE>
 OLYMICS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ Dousing each other with champagne, leaping in the air
and cheering in the lobby of a luxury hotel, Italians celebrated
their surprise victory Saturday in the bid to host the 2006 Winter
Olympics, the first Games awarded in a controversial new selection
process since an influence-peddling scandal broke late last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiat car-producing capital of Turin, Italy's third largest
city, trounced the odds-on favorite for the Games _ the tiny Swiss
mountain hamlet of Sion _ in a 53-36 secret ballot cast by members
of the International Olympic Committee at the IOC's 109th meeting
here in South Korea Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But while Turin loyalists rejoiced and praised the new selection
process as a fair one that allowed an underdog bidder to prevail,
the second-place finishers lost sorely. Sion boosters accused the
IOC of bias and vindictiveness and the Turin committee of shameless
lobbying or worse. The fact that Turin won _ even though Sion had
the best rating from a technical evaluation committee _ was proof
that the IOC is still a corrupt and high-handed group that must
clean up its act, Sion committee members charged.
</P>
<P>
   The site selection was more significant and closely scrutinized
than perhaps any in history, coming as it did on the heels of
revelations that Salt Lake City, host of the 2002 Winter Games,
spent more than $1 million in gifts, trips, ``scholarships,'' and
other bribes to win its bid. The dirty dealing was apparently part
of a larger culture of greed and graft in which some IOC members
expected to be wined, dined, and bought off by prospective Olympic
hosts. Ten IOC members have resigned or been expelled in the
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's selection was a test of a temporary new system, which
barred IOC members from visiting bid cities to avoid impropriety
and created a selection committee of 16 that narrowed the field
from six candidates to two before the full IOC voted on the winner.
For the first time athletes were included in the selection process.
</P>
<P>
   But far from clearing up any suggestions of crookedness and
inequity, Turin's upset victory provoked fury and accusations from
the runner-up bidder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were robbed,'' spat out a bitter Jean-Loup Chappelet,
technical director of Sion's committee. He credited Turin's win on
``factors that had nothing to do with winter Olympics . . .
obviously lobbying was very important. You should investigate. This
(vote) margin is suspicious _ like the one Salt Lake won with.''
</P>
<P>
   Chappelet accused IOC members of voting out of vindictiveness
against a Swiss IOC member, Marc Hodler, the main whistleblower in
the scandal that sullied the Olympics' name. Chappelet said the
Sion committee had begged Hodler ``to keep quiet.'' Asked if Hodler
had not been right to expose the graft, Chappelet said, ``Certainly
other people could have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   IOC members cast a payback vote to prove ``they are masters of
the world,'' he complained, adding that votes should be public so
IOC members can be held accountable for their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss sour grapes aside, there was no evidence Saturday that
Turin had bought the vote or that Sion's loss _ given the huge
margin _ was entirely the result of an anti-Hodler backlash.
</P>
<P>
   Some IOC members may also have avoided picking the ``shoe-in''
bidder for fear of creating an image of a rigged deal. Turin's
video presentation was arguably more innovative and less corny than
Sion's. And voters may have passed over the traditional model of
hosting a Winter Games in a charming mountain village of 26,000
people, in favor of a new trend of hosting them in cities that can
accommodate the behemoth that the Games have become. The last two
Winter Games selections _ Nagano (1998) and Salt Lake (2002) _ are
urban centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IOC had to decide between two very different bids. Sion
was an old-fashioned one . . . (Ours was) a big city. I think we'd
win all the same, even without the said ``Hodler effect,''' said
Marco San Pietro, a Turin member.
</P>
<P>
   The decision shatters the myth that cities must bid a few times
before getting the gold. Sion played heavily on the sympathy
factor, reminding judges it lost two bids, one to a corrupt Salt
Lake committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Winter Games will go to Italy for the first time since 1956,
when they were in Cortina D'Ampezzo. Those were the last
untelevised Games, before a new era of sponsorship and big money
began to transform the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Turin, though not known for winter sports, has hosted numerous
world sporting events, including the Soccer World Cup in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
