<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-WOLF-PHILLIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOLF COMES HOME TO DODGER STADIUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One spot in the Philadelphia Phillies' rotation
prevented Randy Wolf from getting the start today at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   On Father's Day, no less.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have almost been too ironic,'' Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wolf passed away in 1994 when Randy was a high school
senior. Dodger Stadium was a favorite retreat for father and son,
and Randy played there twice in helping El Camino Real High to
back-to-back City Section championships in 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The second of those titles was won three months after Jim Wolf
suffered a fatal heart attack in March, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bottled most of it up after it happened,'' said Wolf, who
won his first two major-league starts after the Phillies called him
up 10 days ago. ``Two days after he died I was out there pitching
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing with a heavy heart, he finished his senior year
at ECR with a 12-3 pitching record, a .443 batting average, six
homers and 28 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the Conquistadores defeated Chatsworth 7-6 in
the City finals that Randy let his emotions out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did change as a person (when Jim passed away). When that
happens it's going to change you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Wolf said such a tragedy can have either a positive or
negative impact on a teen-ager's life. Jim's death made him more
focused on following his baseball dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something that's really important to me is how I carry
myself,'' he said. ``It's easy for somebody to be a nice guy when
things are going well for you. But I try to be the same person when
things are going bad. I try to have a good positive attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   He had a standout collegiate career at Pepperdine, was a
second-round pick of the Phillies in 1997 and reached the majors
just three years into his professional career at the age of 22.
</P>
<P>
   His colleagues and bosses rave at Wolf's polished demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch him and you get the impression he's been groomed to
do this his whole life,'' Philadelphia first baseman Rico Brogna
said. ``It looks like he's been here for two or three years
already.''
</P>
<P>
   Added manager Terry Francona, ``We kind of expected this out of
him. We've known about him for a while. He's got a good head on his
shoulders and I think that's why he's here already.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf (2-0, 1.32 ERA) was called up from Triple-A
Scranton/Wilkes-Barre and made his debut June 11 at Veterans
Stadium against the Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's rabid and sometimes unforgiving fans, 26,541
strong, served as Wolf's critics. One batter into his major-league
career he was given an emphatic thumb's down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't take me long to get booed. I walked the leadoff
guy,'' Wolf said with a grin. ``I just think they're really good
baseball fans. When you're good they'll let you know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   When he rebounded to toss a solid 52/3 innings (one run, six
hits, six strikeouts) Wolf left the field to a standing ovation, a
tribute he'd never before experienced.
</P>
<P>
   When he watched highlights of the 8-4 victory, Wolf noticed a
sign in the left-field bleachers bearing the slogan ``Wolfpack''.
</P>
<P>
   One game into his major-league career and the kid had his own
Veterans Stadium fan club?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say that just yet,'' he cracked. ``There's already
a (teammate Paul) Byrd Cage.''
</P>
<P>
   And it didn't take long for the rookie to make believers out of
his teammates. Wolf showed his mettle when he struck out two Blue
Jays in his first big-league inning after that leadoff walk,
including fanning Shawn Green on a fastball clocked at 91 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a batter making your major-league debut at least
you have seven other hitters behind you,'' Brogna said. ``But when
you take that mound for the first time everyone is watching you.
You are the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a cautious optimism with guys like Randy. We'd heard
of him. We know he's a prospect. Once he started throwing strikes I
knew he was going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf made sure there was even less anxiety in his second outing
last Wednesday in San Diego. He lasted eight innings, giving up one
earned run on five hits with seven strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf arranged for 20 guests on the Qualcomm Stadium pass list.
Twice that number made the trip from the Valley, including his mom
Judy, who planned on watching his debut in Philadelphia before her
flight was delayed by inclement weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see that many people come down was great. I tried not to
think about it but once the game started I could hear them,'' said
Randy, who is sure Jim Wolf was watching too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's here to share all of this with me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
