<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'LL GET JIGGY WITH ZIGGY? 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ Whither Ziggy?
</P>
<P>
   Word broke early last week that the Islanders and Rangers cut a
deal that had Ziggy Palffy headed to Broadway for a package that
included former first-round picks Patrik Sundstrom and Todd Harvey
heading to Uniondale.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a week later, the music is still playing, and Islander
general manager Mike Milbury is still fiddling with offers from
around the league. Other than the Rangers, word is that the Kings
and Panthers have shown the most interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about our best player,'' said Milbury, here for
the GM meetings Tuesday. ``And he's a good, good guy, to boot. It's
not easy on anyone. But, hey, it's part of the reality of today's
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation on Long Island borders on the surreal. The club's
owners want a new stadium and Nassau County has responded with a
show of long faces and empty pockets. To avoid bleeding more from
the bottom line, owners Steve Gluckstern and Howard Milstein
instructed Milbury weeks ago to trim payroll way back, while at the
same time he was searching for a new coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Butch was fully apprised of the status of the franchise before
he signed on,'' said Milbury, referring to former Boston coach
Butch Goring, named some six weeks ago as the new Islander bench
boss.
</P>
<P>
   So what uniform will Palffy wear next season?
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, it could be the league that has the final say. Not
long after the Isles shipped Trevor Linden to the Canadiens for the
No. 10 pick in Saturday's amateur draft, the NHL made it clear that
VP Colin Campbell would assess any move(s) the Isles made and
ultimately would be the one to OK all trades. The league wants to
avoid the appearance of the Isles essentially cashing out at the
poker table, stripping assets, and running what amounts to a minor
league franchise while charging major league ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that names have been mentioned,'' said
Campbell, ``but so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Milbury and Kings GM Dave Taylor huddled briefly at the meetings
here and by mid-week LA appeared the primary suitor, believed to be
offering up relatively unknown prospects Scott Barney and Josh
Green _ both forwards _ and defenseman Mathieu Biron (the
6-foot-6-inch brother of Sabres netminding prospect Martin Biron).
Only Green has NHL experience, appearing in 27 LA games this past
season.
</P>
<P>
   Like the proposed Islander-Ranger deal, there would be some cash
involved, likely much more than the $2.5 million the Rangers
offered. The Blueshirts also were going to send prospects Patrick
Leahy and P.J. Stock and a first-round pick (No. 11 overall) to the
Island. Chances are, the Kings offered substantially more cash. But
the league, with its main interest keeping the Isles competitive,
would have to look more favorably upon the Ranger offer _ first and
foremost because Sundstrom and Harvey are legitimate NHLers who
could produce now for the Islanders, as opposed to prospects who
might never make it to the show.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers, who cut the biggest deal of 1998-99 when they
swapped for Pavel Bure, have a number of interesting young players,
especially forwards, to spice a trade. Milbury's top priority there
could be 24-year-old center/wing Rob Niedermayer, with the rest of
the parts to be arranged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of GMs dealing strictly with GMs on trades, other
than when it's a third- or fourth-liner, are just about gone,''
said Milbury. ``When you're getting into seven-figure contracts and
multiple-player exchanges _ well, it's not for me to make decisions
about (the owners') money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our owners have said they're not prepared to keep losing tens
of millions of dollars. They're not in the position of having
players retire comfortably while they lose their shirts. Have we
made mistakes? Yes. But my fondest wish now is that we stay the
course, stay on a path with the new players we'll have, get a new
building and in three or four years those assets will make for a
much stronger, healthier franchise on Long Island.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis GM Larry Pleau on the Blues' decision to make Group 2
free agent Pierre Turgeon a qualifying offer for next season:
``Pierre was a leader for us in the playoffs _ it seemed like he
was trying to make a difference out there every shift. We'd like to
see more of that, in the regular season.'' . . . The Blues and the
Kiel Center remain up for sale. Goldman Sachs has been shopping
around for a suitor since the start of the year . . . When the
league finally gets around to modifying the man-in-the-crease rule
(revision No. 1,345,867), look for something that resembles life
before replay. The bet here is that replay will exist, but referees
will be encouraged only to go to the tape when blatant interference
has taken place (i.e., games won't be decided on the tip of Tim
Taylor's toe). A little bit of common sense and a healthy dose of
modern technology could be just the right mix _ finally. Among the
many faults of the existing system: goals go under review far too
often, leaving a crowded arena and a television audience in a state
of suspended animation; the game's flow gets lost in the whir of
technology . . . LA GM Dave Taylor boiled his head coach candidates
down to Andy Murray and John Van Boxmeer and ultimately chose
Murray, who most recently was coaching prep school hockey in
Minnesota. ``I like his intelligence, his discipline, the fact that
he's a hard worker,'' said Taylor. ``I hope people around the
league aren't surprised by the pick. They shouldn't be. In LA, it's
not a traditional hockey market, and some people might say, `Andy
Murray? Who's that?' But that would be almost anyone we chose. I
think people in LA will like the choice.'' . . . The best player in
today's game? Look no further, says Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock,
than Colorado center Peter Forsberg. ``We won the series (against
the Avalanche) and it was a great feeling. But as a hockey person,
to see a player like that is amazing. Once he ran out of gas, it
was to our advantage. There were times he'd keep it in our end for
40 seconds and we couldn't get it away from him _ that's 40 seconds
with three guys, 200 pounds or more, who couldn't get it away from
him. You can play him anywhere, any situation. And he gets this
really strange look in his eyes, like there's something really
scary going on in there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the topics when GMs met last week in Buffalo was the
troublesome seamless glass above the boards that has led to head
and shoulder injuries in some NHL rinks. The Molson Centre in
Montreal already has switched to a new design, glass with some
give, and the GMs could mandate other buildings be retrofitted.
``The new stuff is more like the glass at the old Garden,'' said
Islander GM Mike Milbury, the former Bruins defenseman. ``It's more
like the WWF stuff.'' The old Buffalo Auditorium had the most
spring in its glass, providing almost a slingshot for battles
between the likes of Jim Schoenfeld and Terry O'Reilly. ``Yeah,
those were definitely Taz's battles _ I stayed away from Schoeny,''
said Milbury . . . The AHL's four-on-four format for deciding games
in OT has received decent reviews by the NHL. The big league hasn't
approved it, but the Lords of the Boards are giving it some
consideration . . . Until otherwise informed, Jacques Demers
remains the GM/coach of Tampa Bay, although he now reports directly
to Rick Dudley, the ex-Ottawa GM who is now running the show for
the Bolts. ``I don't think it's very complicated,'' said Demers,
the last coach to lead the Canadiens to the Stanley Cup (1993).
``The new owner has never said that I wouldn't be part of the team.
And I've said before that I don't want to do both jobs _ GM and
coach _ for very long. We've made a lot of changes in Tampa. We've
got the youngest team in the league now, and we've cut payroll. I
think everyone likes the direction of the club.'' Demers has three
more years on his contract. He'll remain in Tampa, but look for
Dudley to channel him more toward scouting duties . . . Ron Salcer,
agent for Bruins netminder Byron Dafoe, said late last week that
he's had a few ``exploratory'' conversations with management about
a new deal for his client, who becomes a Group 2 (high
compensation) free agent July 1. ``We're hopeful to come to an
amicable conclusion,'' he added. Dafoe has until July 15 to file
for salary arbitration. The Bruins haven't come up with a figure,
but assistant GM Mike O'Connell has made it sound as if the Bruins
are pegging Dafoe for around $2 million a year. He's far more
likely to seek nearly double that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ailment that sent Houston Astros manager Larry Dierker into
seizure and later last week led to brain surgery _ an arteriovenous
malformation _ was similar to the condition that brought permanent
paralysis to Normand Leveille at the start of the '82 season.
Leveille required life-saving brain surgery that night in Vancouver
when his AVM ruptured. Last seen in Boston for the Bruins' final
game at the Garden, when teammates helped him around the ice,
Leveille now lives in Montreal, his speech limited, and he gets
around with the aid of a cane . . . Oiler boss Glen Sather remains
hopeful that the NHL will increase its number of playoff teams from
16 to as many as 20. ``We equate success in this league with making
the playoffs,'' said Sather, the former Boston forward. ``And
making the playoffs equates to selling season tickets.'' Look for
the idea to gain momentum with the approach of fall 2000, when
Minnesota and Columbus open for business . . . Atlanta now has
interviewed three prospective coaches: Don Hay, Ron Low, and Curt
Fraser. GM Don Waddell late last week had plans to interview Bill
Barber, the former Flyer who now coaches the AHL's Philly Phantoms
. . . O'Connell on Providence goalie John Grahame's readiness for
the NHL: ``He's close. He's an athletic goalie, and that
athleticism gets him in trouble at times. He skates well. He uses
those skills to take some unnecessary risks at times. We've got to
get him to play within himself a little more.'' . . . NHL GMs don't
like to see Dominik Hasek repeatedly drop his stick in the crease _
yet another way he has changed the game. But Campbell admitted last
week, following the GM meetings here, that coming up with a rule
change to legislate against it would be tricky . . . The Bruins
signed free agent Jeff Zehr, who finished the season with the
Sarnia Sting in the OHL, Thursday. Drafted 31st overall by the
Islanders in '97, Zehr never came to terms with New York and now,
at age 20, was able to cut his own deal. He finished with 24 goals
in 57 games last year, traded at midseason from Erie to Sarnia.
He's 6-3, 203 pounds, and has a strong shot, making him a potential
power forward. In April, he needed an arthroscopy to clean up a
bone chip in his right knee. ``I'm not going to Boston thinking
that I'll play a year in the minors,'' said Zehr. ``I'm thinking
I'll make the club. I play a feisty game. I like to be involved out
there, in all key situations. And this is great, the Bruins are
keying on me, telling me I'll get a chance _ and now it's up to me
to make the most of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
