<SLUG> BC-SOC-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMM LIVES UP TO HYPE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Mia Hamm stood in front of a huge wall
with ``GIANTS'' scripted on it in red and blue letters. Hamm, who
stands 5 feet 5 inches, actually looked like a shrimp standing
there. But as I listened to her speak Saturday _ after watching her
play _ I immediately wanted to compare her to the greatest champion
of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   I will try to get through this report without mentioning that
man's name. Really, it would be very superficial of me to compare
Hamm to a certain bald basketball player who is now retired. What
does his success have to do with hers? So what if they were both
born in North Carolina. Who cares if both attended the University
of North Carolina and won at least one national championship while
at Chapel Hill. Both have done commercials. They even did one
together, but that was probably coincidental. He was born in
February; she was born in March. He made shots that suggested that
he carried a gravity exemption card in his wallet. She recently
made a leftfooted shot that made her say to herself, ``Are you
kidding me? Are you kidding me? (Teammate) Michelle Akers only
makes shots like this.''
</P>
<P>
   That, I think, is as far as I will take it. I will be contained.
There will be no more references to that retired player.
</P>
<P>
   Against that towering wall Saturday, Hamm looked straight ahead
and said, ``The majority of the time, frontrunners fail.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right. That's why Hamm is the best soccer player the
women's game has ever seen. She is a frontrunner who doesn't fail.
She entered Saturday's World Cup opener as the game's all-time
leading scorer with 109 goals. She wasn't the only reason more than
78,000 people packed Giants Stadium for the United States' match
with Denmark, but there were a lot of people wearing jerseys with
her name on them. Many of those people have also seen the
commercials and read the stories about how great this forward named
Hamm was supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   You know what happens in situations like that, right? A movie is
hyped and it's never as good as you expected. A player is hyped
and, on the day you plan to watch them, they have an average game.
Saturday, Giants Stadium held the largest crowd to ever witness a
women's sporting event in the world. In front of that crowd, Hamm
waited 17 minutes before scoring the first goal of the tournament.
It was that leftfooted goal, the one that made her talk to herself.
You can watch a lot of soccer and you won't see many goals like
that. Those goals are not normal. Unless you are Mia Hamm.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm's goal was much more than a creative play. It was a
nerve-loosener for the US. The American women came into this game
as Cup favorites. But in the first 15 minutes, they looked tight
and rusty (they hadn't scrimmaged against anyone in two weeks).
Although the final was 3-0, the Danes probably should have beaten
Hamm to first-goal honors in the first few minutes. Denmark's Gitte
Krogh found herself standing in front of the net while goalkeeper
Briana Scurry was in a defenseless position. Krogh kicked and
missed. It was the best opportunity the Danes would have. They
could have increased the American tension. Instead, they helped
fulfill a script: the best player on the best team in the world
helped bring a victory in the opening match.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was bouncing the ball off her body and I didn't think she
would get it,'' midfielder Julie Foudy said of Hamm's goal. ``When
she made the goal, I think we were all like, `Yeah, yeah. We're
going to be OK.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Now Hamm has 110 goals in her career. For some reason, we don't
hear a lot about her assists. But the US wouldn't have had its
second goal if it hadn't been for Hamm's passing. She drew a couple
defenders toward her as she dribbled in the 73d minute, as they
went for the ball, she made a cross pass to Foudy, who in turn
found the net.
</P>
<P>
   After all of that, I still haven't talked about Hamm's speed. In
soccer, the rule, ``No cheering in the pressbox'' is kind of
liberal. You hear people shouting and screaming when a goal
situation unfolds. So I found myself saying aloud, ``Why aren't
they marking Mia? They're leaving her wide open. What's wrong with
them?'' And then it became obvious that the Danes were marking Mia;
they were just not fast enough to keep pace with her. Someone asked
Hamm's teammate, Kristine Lilly, if Saturday's match was one of the
best she had seen Hamm play. She said no. ``She'll probably play
her best one in her next one,'' Lilly said. ``That's how she is.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamm shrugged off all the compliments. ``I am only as good as my
teammates,'' she said. She was then asked, inevitably, about the
other guy. You know, the retired basketball star who will not be
mentioned by name here. Nope. We are much more responsible than
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have so much respect for him,'' she said. ``You watch him
play and you're speechless.''
</P>
<P>
   She talked of their filming commercials together for five and
six hours at a time. In one segment, she picked him up and threw
him to a mat in a judo scene. ``He helped with that,'' she said.
She knows that kids talk about her the way she talks about him.
Both are innovators of their sports. He wore his shorts long and
his socks short. Saturday, she had her left toenails painted red
and the right ones painted blue. Some kids noticed that. They will
do what she did.
</P>
<P>
   There were young boys wearing her No. 9 jersey here, but there
were more girls with them on. ``I feel good about that,'' Hamm
said. ``When they leave the stadium, they want to play in the World
Cup. That's what it was about.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she moved away from that wall and walked away from
the people asking her questions. All you could see was the No. 9 on
her back. Yes, it was the same number the retired guy wore in the
1984 Olympics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 0246EDT &QL; 
