<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-MUTINY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIRED REVOLUTION HANG TOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ The Revolution had many reasons to celebrate their 3-2
victory over the Tampa Bay Mutiny Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. But they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just exhausted,'' defender Dan Calichman said. ``We're
excited, yes, but I think we're just too tired to appreciate it.
We'll see things better later.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution locker room was subdued, the players feeling the
effects of having three games in seven days. This one was against a
physical opponent in 85-degree heat, extreme humidity, and a brief
tropical storm.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution deserved the victory, showing enough
resiliency to pressure the Mutiny and capitalizing on mistakes.
They also showed some of their most fluent midfield play of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Joe-Max Moore scored twice, including the deciding goal in the
81st minute, combining with Ivan McKinley after a throw-in.
McKinley, who was cautioned in the first half and will be suspended
for the team's game at Dallas Saturday, returned the ball to Moore
on the edge of the penalty area, and Moore sent a leftfooted shot
off the inside of the far post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought hard for 90 minutes and we were disappointed to go
in at halftime at 1-1,'' Moore said. ``I don't think anyone would
have been happy if we didn't get 3 points out of this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of the game, though, I was tired. This is a big
field and if you don't stay compact and organized, you can get
spread out, and there was a lot of room out there. My boots were
heavy, my jersey must have weighed an extra three pounds. All the
games we've been playing and the weather took their toll.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinley, John Harkes, and Jair keyed an effective midfield
which made the Revolution dangerous offensively throughout the
contest. Jair scored a highlight-film goal in the 62d minute,
taking a pass from Moore, holding the ball on his left foot, and
causing two defenders to collide just before he converted past
Scott Garlick.
</P>
<P>
   Moore gave the Revolution the lead in the fourth minute, as
defender Chad McCarty sent a clearance directly to him inside the
penalty area. Moore took a touch and buried a shot into the far
corner of the net.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution controlled the pace, but failed to increase their
lead as the Carlos Valderrama-led Mutiny retaliated. In the 34th
minute, Musa Shannon shielded Brian Dunseth from a Steve Trittschuh
through ball, then ran 50 yards into the Revolution goal area
before tying the score, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   After Jair's goal, Mutiny substitute Pete Marino finished an
excellent move started by Valderrama, then continued through a
Marino backheel and Paul Dougherty return pass to tie the game,
2-2, in the 75th minute.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Harkes (left hamstring) and Jair had been substituted
for and the Mutiny had momentum. But the Revolution remained
resourceful, surprising the Mutiny with the deciding goal as Moore
continued to press.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just toe-poked the ball and didn't even know Ivan was
there,'' Moore said. ``And he sent a nice ball into my run. I
didn't even hit the ball that well, but it went in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution now have 15 points in 14 matches, good for third
place in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
