u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-BOS &LR;      06-20 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' CUP IS FULL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ The Stanley Cup is now a 10-gallon trophy.
</P>
<P>
   It also has an embarrassing asterisk.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Stars, who had the National Hockey League's best
record during the regular season, captured their first Stanley Cup
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night when Brett Hull lifted home a doorstep forehander
with 5:09 remaining in the third overtime to capture the Cup in six
games.
</P>
<P>
   Unnoticed by referees Terry Gregson and Bill McCreary was the
fact that Hull's left foot clearly was in the crease, by nearly
half a skate length, and the goal should not have been allowed. But
the goal was never reviewed, either, by on-ice officials or by
Scott Brinkman, the video goal judge, or Bryan Lewis, the
supervisor of officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted Bettman to answer my question,'' said Buffalo coach
Lindy Ruff, who stormed out of the Buffalo locker room soon after
the game ended and asked Commissioner Gary Bettman why the goal was
not disallowed. ``I asked, `Why was it not reviewed?' He turned his
back on me. No review. No answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory (), which came 54:51 into overtime, was the second
longest game played in Stanley Cup finals history. The Bruins went
55:13 into OT in Game 1 of the 1990 finals, losing to the Edmonton
Oilers on a Petr Klima shot.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nieuwendyk, who scored a record-tying six winning goals
during the playoffs, won the Conn Smythe Trophy as the series' most
valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it,'' said an overwhelmed Nieuwendyk. ``I
can't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres were even more overwhelmed. Because of Hull's foot
foul, they felt the game shouldn't have ended, the Cup shouldn't
have been hoisted. According to Ruff, Lewis explained the goal was
allowed because Hull never lost possession of the puck after making
a first attempt to score on netminder Dominik Hasek. But replays
clearly showed Hull lost possession, and his left skate blade
clearly was in the blue crease area when he regained possession and
fired home the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some will say he had full possession,'' said Dallas coach Ken
Hitchcock. ``Some will say it wasn't full possession. Whatever. He
scored the goal. And when it all comes out, Brett Hull is just an
incredible story, what it took for him to play.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Hitchcock, Hull played with a left knee torn apart
and both major groin muscles pulled. With proper rehabilitation,
said Hitchcock, Hull might be able to start the season in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played on one leg and no groins,'' said Hitchcock. ``On the
winning goal, he limped to the corner and he limped to the front of
the net. With the left knee blow and both groins finished. Tough
shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull was brought to Dallas in the offseason as a free agent,
signing a three-year deal for some $17 million, based on years of
scoring prowess with the St. Louis Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have all the other ones,'' said Hull, asked to put the
trophy in context with all his other awards. ``This is the biggest
for me. It's unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars took a 1-0 lead with 8:09 gone in the first on a Jere
Lehtinen strike that did not have the Sabres looking sharp. Most
surprising of all, it was Buffalo's pillar of strength, Hasek, who
looked the worst. Lehtinen turned by defenseman Darryl Shannon low
in the circle and shoveled off a seemingly harmless shot as Randy
Cunneyworth came racing in to cut the angle. Hasek slid to the near
post for what should have been an easy block, but he didn't cover
enough of the post. The shot squeezed by Hasek's hip and dropped in
for the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 32 minutes, through the end of the second period,
the Sabres went on to outshoot the Stars, 22-12. Finally, with only
1:39 to go before the second intermission, Stu Barnes hammered home
the equalizer with a slapper off the rush from the right circle.
Set up by linemate Wayne Primeau, Barnes ripped a one-timer for his
seventh goal of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   As the overtimes progressed, good scoring opportunities
decreased.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, limping and exhausted, Hull moved in front for the
kill. Brian Holzinger, skating ferociously through the crease, just
missed stripping Hull of the puck. Perhaps the greatest scoring
sniper in the game's history, Hull held his ground, tiptoed in and
out of the crease area and finally shoveled home the biggest goal
of his career.
</P>
<P>
   The league now will have to explain to the hockey world how it
let stand a goal that should not have counted. The league is
expected in the next few days to modify the man-in-the-crease rule,
in order to let stand the type of goal Hull scored _ a goal where
his encroachment in the crease was insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, in a postgame news conference, maintained the goal stood
because Hull maintained possession of the puck the entire time he
was in the crease area.
</P>
</TEXT>
