   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO PACKAGE:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Podujevo) _ The last of some 40,000 Serb forces left
Kosovo on Sunday a few hours ahead of NATO's deadline for
withdrawal, leaving in their wake new scenes of jubilation among
the province's Albanians, as well as new acts of retribution. With
the withdrawal completed, NATO's secretary-general, Javier Solana,
announced that he had lifted the alliance's threat to resume
bombing, formally ending an air war that lasted 78 days and
culminated with the occupation of Kosovo by NATO-led peacekeepers
over the last eight days. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SUMMIT (Cologne) _ Leaders of the G7 nations and Russia
outlined on Sunday a plan for ending eight years of war in the
Balkans through a massive program of aid and political support for
the region, but said Yugoslavia must undertake ``democratic and
economic reforms'' to be part of the process. At the end of a
three-day summit meeting, the leaders of Britain, France and
Germany said democratic reform in Yugoslavia involved the departure
of Milosevic; but in deference to Russia no explicit reference to
the Serbian leader was included in the final statement. By Roger
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-RUSSIA (Cologne) _ Clinton and Yeltsin meet and
smooth over ties. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ The authorities in Belgrade are
telling the Kosovo Serbs to return. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   The following three Kosovo stories are tentative:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SCENE (Dateline TK) _ As Serbs troops and civilians
leave, Albanians burn down their homes. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje) _ Macedonia grows tired of being
portrayed as the `bad guy'.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON-RATINGS (Washington) _ Something important
happened, or rather didn't happen, after Clinton went on TV last
week to proclaim that the United States and NATO had won the 78-day
war in the Balkans _ he got no ``victory bounce'' whatsoever in
public opinion polls. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER INTERRNATIONAL NEWS:
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-UNREST (Bogota) _ The National Liberation Army,
Colombia's second largest guerrilla group, has managed to thrust
itself back into the center of national attention through a wave of
bold and dramatic kidnappings. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-MIX (Alon Shvut) _ Israel has a new breed of politicians
who represent a new generation of Israelis. Younger and from a
greater mix of ethnic backgrounds, they are less likely to be
veterans of the great Israeli wars, lifelong Zionists or even
Jewish. Instead, their stories form the new narrative strands of a
country that is redefining itself. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   TOGO-POLITICS (Lome) _ A year after winning re-election in
voting widely considered tainted, President Gnassingbe Eyadema of
Togo has continued to tighten his three-decade hold on his nation's
politics, ensuring his status as sub-Saharan Africa's
longest-ruling head of state.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DRIVE-IN (Moscow) _ Russia gets its first drive-in movie
theater. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   EASTEUROPE-EU-DOUBTS (Plonsk, Poland) _ The post-communist world
in Central Europe is entering a new phase. After tireless and
largely successful efforts to align their economies with those of
western Europe, countries like Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic are pushing hard for the ultimate badge of acceptance:
membership in the European Union. But at least here in Poland,
Central Europe's biggest country and thus its brightest economic
star, leaders now find that a sizable part of the population is
balking. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-POLITICS (Baton Rouge) _ After a few years of relative
political quiet, Louisiana is reverting to traditional chaotic
form.
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-POLITICS (Denver) _ Rep. Tom Tancredo, a Republican
conservative who lives just six blocks from Columbine High, got
tepid but polite applause at a youth violence seminar on Saturday.
He voted for the Dingell amendment and was the only member of the
House from Colorado to vote for the entire gun package. By James
Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-FISH-KILL (Portola, Calif.) _ In the fall of 1997, the
Fish and Wildlife Service dumped 76,000 pounds of toxins into Lake
Davis to get rid of the pike that had threatened salmon and trout
populations. The toxins killed the pike as well as a source of
water for Portola and its tourism-dependent economy. Now the lake
is restocked with trout and salmon; but three pike were found last
month and the town again is fearing for its lake and its future.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   SECRET-SERVICE-SHOOTINGS (Washington) _ The people who protect
the president have turned their attention to school violence.
Spurred by the killings in April of 12 students and a teacher in
Littleton, Colo., a Secret Service team has begun a detailed review
of earlier cases, interviewing as many of the killers as it can.
Instead of focusing on ``troubled kids,'' the Secret Service is
looking for patterns of motive and behavior. The goal is to help
schools and the police recognize which students are moving from
interest in murder to the idea of murder to weapons acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-PRIVACY (Washington) _ Legislation to protect the
privacy of medical records is hitting some heavy weather. By Robert
Pear.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-ABORTION (Washington) _ The Republican Party
establishment has undergone a fundamental repositioning, and
softening, of its stand on abortion, recognizing that a more
tolerant position on perhaps the most divisive issue in American
politics is imperative to their hopes of reclaiming the White
House. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   DELAY-PROFILE (Washington) _ A timely look at Tom DeLay. By
Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Dateline TK) _ Commentary by William Safire;
details later.
</P>
