<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2668 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-RUSSIA-HNS &LR;      06-20 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-RUSSIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON-YELTSIN SUMMIT SETS STAGE FOR THEIR SUCCESSORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ President Clinton and Russian President Boris
Yeltsin set the cornerstone Sunday for future U.S.-Russian
cooperation and to rebuild Russia's ties with the West to allay an
anti-western backlash in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The presidents raced through their first meeting, the first
since a near break-up over Kosovo, and made tradeoffs on nuclear
arms control, economic ties, debt relief and steps to spotlight
their understudies and possible successors.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Russian television, Clinton underscored
U.S. efforts to address Russia's concerns and declared that the
United States remains committed to ``a strong, successful,
democratic Russia, fully participating in world affairs and a
leadership role.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Yeltsin, at their 17th meeting since April 1993,
deliberately skipped mention of Russian troops' defiant seizure of
the airfield in the Kosovo capital of Pristina that led to a
week-long impasse over Russian participation in the 50,000-strong
international security force.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to the U.S. embassy staff in Bonn, Clinton said:
``The summit gave us a chance to work on what we have in common.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's waxen appearance, his clumsy body movements and
slurred speech during a photo session fanned continuing questions
over his health. Yeltsin coughed deeply and loudly. He slipped his
arm through the arm of German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder for
support after being greeted with a bear hug by Schroeder, the host
of the Group of Eight nations' summit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a post summit interview with CNN, insisted that
Yeltsin ``was neither erratic nor shaky today,'' adding: ``He was
strong, clear, forceful and looking to the future.''
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger said Clinton
and Yeltsin acknowledged their partnership suffered ``some scars''
during the NATO-led 78-day bombing campaign against Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic, a Russian ally.
</P>
<P>
   But the leaders agreed ``it was now time to turn to the future
and spend the remaining period'' in their terms to ``getting things
done for the United States and Russia,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Berger added: ``The two countries are back in business,''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Yeltsin summit coincided with the completion of
Serbian troop withdrawal from Kosovo. That enabled NATO to formally
declare an end to the air campaign that had been a thorn in the
U.S.-Russian relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian leader appeared to respond to Clinton's focus on the
future and extended a surprise invitation to Clinton to visit
Moscow this fall. White House officials said Clinton hoped to
accept even though, by tradition, it is Yeltsin's turn to visit the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Both Vice President Al Gore and Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin won boosts to their future political fortunes with
Yeltsin's decision to immediately resume twice-yearly U.S.-Russian
meetings of the Cabinet-level commission led by the vice president
and the Russian prime minister. Officials said Gore and Stepashin
will convene their first meeting since the Kosovo crisis in July.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, a Yeltsin protege named to power in May, could seek
the presidency in Russia's June 2000 presidential elections.
Stepashin also could be thrust into leadership if Yeltsin becomes
disabled, governing the country for three months until a new
president is elected.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders agreed on a broad range of issues.
</P>
<P>
   _ ARMS CONTROL _ Clinton responded to Yeltsin's eagerness for
quick action on a cost-cutting START III treaty by agreeing to
intensify expert-level discussions on a warhead-cutting accord even
before the Russian parliament ratifies the START II.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has been unable to win ratification of the
seven-year-old START II treaty from the communist-controlled
Russian parliament despite approval by the U.S. Senate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin is so eager for action that he insisted that
U.S.-Russian experts report back to respective Cabinet ministers by
July 30.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Yeltsin agreed to begin discussions with Clinton at
their next summit on U.S. proposals to overhaul the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty (ABM) to permit U.S. deployment of a
limited anti-missile defense system to counter missile launches by
rogue nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration plans to decide next June on whether
to begin deployment of a limited anti-missile defense by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The Cold War-era ABM accord limits the United States and the
Soviet Union to single anti-missile sites with no more than 100
anti-missile launchers.
</P>
<P>
   _ KOSOVO: Clinton agreed to Yeltsin's request that a greater
share of day-to-day European security-related affairs _ including
civilian reconstruction of Kosovo _ be handled through the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) and the
U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has rejected western allies' insistence that Russia deal
with the U.S.-dominated 19-nation North Atlantic Treaty
Organization where Russia has only consultative, non-voting status.
</P>
<P>
   _ ECONOMICS: On economic issues, Clinton offered to examine with
allied leaders Russia's request for an eventual write-off of
Russia's $69 billion in Soviet-era debt _ 48 percent of the $145
billion owed by Russia to western creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told Yeltsin that even if he was unable to win allied
agreement ``we at least would be able to reschedule the debt,''
Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also promised Yeltsin that he would go back to Congress
to seek repeal of the Cold War-era Jackson-Vanik amendment that
restricts U.S. economic assistance to Russia. Clinton told Yeltsin
that Congress will resist repeal until the Kremlin discourages
anti-Semitic actions and rhetoric by Yeltsin's political rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin replied: ``Provide me with all of the material you have
(on anti-Semiticism) and I will really sit on them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ KENNEDY ASSASSINATION: Yeltsin turned over to Clinton a packet
of declassified Soviet-era documents unearthed in an extensive
search of Kremlin military and civilian archives that relate to the
assassination of President John F. Kennedy in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Harvey Oswald, identified by the Warren Commission as the
lone gunman who murdered Kennedy, had once lived in the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell can be reached via E-mail at
stewart(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
