<DOCNO> NYT19990620.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2697 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTH-INTEGRATION-COX     06-20 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-INTEGRATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern attitudes are changing, poll shows
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While the South has long been viewed as a crucible of
racial intolerance, a recent poll shows a majority of whites in the
region saying they favor integration. But white Southerners'
support still lags that of whites in other regions and of black
Southerners who continue to overwhelmingly endorse a racially mixed
society.
</P>
<P>
   In The Atlanta Journal-Constitution Southern Focus Poll taken
this spring, 56 percent of Southern whites voiced their approval of
integration. In a similar poll eight years ago, 47 percent of
whites said they approved of integration.
</P>
<P>
   Also significant: Southern whites seem less ambivalent about
their feelings toward integration. In 1991, 42 percent of whites
said they favored ``something in between'' integration and strict
segregation.The number of whites who now say they feel that way has
dropped to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, however, Southern whites were less likely to favor
integration than whites living in other parts of the country, where
71 percent said they supported the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Among Southern blacks, support for integration _ which for many
was seen as a way of securing racial equity _ has remained
steadfast. Sixty-seven percent of blacks who participated in the
earlier poll said they favored integration, compared to 69 percent
in the poll this spring.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of integration, the poll also found a wide
disparity between natives and newcomers to the South. About 55
percent of lifelong Southerners, black and white, support
integration compared with 70 percent of respondents who have lived
in the South 10 years or less. Like sex and money, race is still an
issue some people find hard to talk about openly and honestly.
Taking that into account, many of the questions in the race
relations poll were framed to provide respondents with ``wiggle
room'' _ an opportunity to express themselves candidly without
feeling pressured.
</P>
<P>
   While pollsters say taking the racial pulse of the South is a
difficult task because people find it hard to talk about the topic
openly and honestly, there are numerous signs of change, what some
might even call progress:
</P>
<P>
   A vast majority of blacks and whites in the South said they felt
either ``very, or pretty comfortable'' interacting with people of
other races.
</P>
<P>
   While 35 percent of Southerners say the racial makeup of their
neighborhoods remained stable, about a quarter of respondents said
their communities were becoming more racially and ethnically mixed.
</P>
<P>
   About 84 percent of Southerners now say they favor teaching
children about diversity to eliminate racism.
</P>
<P>
   More results from the Atlanta Journal-Constitution Southern
Focus Poll and an online forum can be found at www.ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 1557EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990620.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2698 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTH-POLL-COX     06-20 2655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-POLL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A comfort zone at arm's length
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We believe in integration, but the reality still
eludes us.
</P>
<P>
   We claim to be comfortable with other races, but for many that
comfort is usually at arm's length.
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to interracial dating and marriage _ the most
ancient of America's racial taboos _ our aversions have diminished,
not disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   As part of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution's ongoing Southern
Focus Poll, we asked more than 1,300 people in the South and other
parts of the country about their racial attitudes, hoping to
discover how race affects their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was an Alabama man who considers blacks and whites a
different species, and says they should simply avoid each other.
</P>
<P>
   In Memphis, a black college student views whites differently now
after a roommate turned her on to the head-banging lyrics of a
white rock band.
</P>
<P>
   Churchgoers and clerics in Mississippi and Atlanta follow a God
who sees no color, but trying to integrate his flock has tested
their faith.
</P>
<P>
   There was an interracial couple in suburban Atlanta who says
they are raising colorblind kids, while also teaching them to be
proud of their diverse heritage.
</P>
<P>
   In the South, where American slavery took root, the history of
race is marked by centuries of oppression and brutal conflict as
well as periods of progress, tolerance and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that we are still evolving, due in part to an influx
of transplanted Southerners who are slowly reshaping the region's
distinctive racial topography.
</P>
<P>
   But how far has the South really come?
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on four main areas of Southern life _ community,
workplace, church and marriage _ the stories behind the AJC poll
statistics illustrate a tantalizing racial paradox where racial
attitudes and actions have come closer, but still only rarely
intersect.
</P>
<P>
   Community
</P>
<P>
   She grew up in all-black neighborhoods and attended all-black
schools, so Rocena Taylor's crash course in race relations came as
a freshman at the University of Memphis last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was living in a dormitory that was predominantly white,''
says Taylor, 19, a Southern Poll respondent. ``I remember one day
my white suitemate walked in and saw this big jar of Vaseline on my
desk and she said, `Omigod, what do you do with that?' She didn't
know that black people put Vaseline on their skin when they get
ashy.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't much but the incident got them talking, and they still
are. During the semester break, they have written to each other,
and Taylor says the experience has opened her eyes _ and her ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I couldn't stand alternative (music) or rock and
roll, but my roommate was always listening to Aerosmith and I would
listen to it too, especially that one about Armageddon. That's one
of my favorite songs now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor admits her racial attitudes have changed only
slightly. She has few other white friends on campus, still
preferring the company of her black schoolmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think change is slow. We've got a long way to go but at
least we've come this far.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Robb of Jonesboro considers herself a child of ``the
movement'' and says she's come far enough. A former civil rights
activist, she once believed integration would solve America's
racial dilemma, but her idealism has faded. Robb was among 19
percent of Southern blacks polled who favored ``something in
between'' segregation and integration, saying she's no longer sure
a racially blended society is such a great idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think integration as a whole has done more to hurt blacks
than to help us,'' said Robb, 55, who works for a computer
technology company. ``My friends in the movement didn't die so you
could drive a Mercedes, and turn up your nose at other black folks.
We were supposed to be helping each other.''
</P>
<P>
   For Fred Schofield of Dothan, Ala., integration was an outright
mistake, and he doesn't mince words when expressing his feelings
about blacks.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of a small construction company, Schofield, 48, says
his neighborhood is more integrated than he'd like. He's in the
small minority of Southern whites (3 percent) who in responding to
the poll favored segregation.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the poll found that lifelong Southerners tended to
be less enthusiastic about integration than newcomers. About 55
percent of respondents who lived in the South all their lives
favored integration, compared with 70 percent of respondents who
had lived here 10 years or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I'm from the old school,'' Schofield says. ``I don't
personally like blacks and they probably don't like me. I have
three black neighbors within hollering distance of me, but we don't
talk and we're fine just as long as they stay on their side of the
fence and I stay on mine.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sarah Johnson's hometown of Seagoville, Texas, outside
Dallas, race relations don't necessarily translate in black and
white.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson says about 70 percent of her neighbors are white, 20
percent Hispanic and 10 percent are black. Her racially
mixedcommunity represents the roughly 70 percent of poll
respondents _ in the North and South _ who say they reside in
integrated neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it may sound like a cliche, but my very best friend is
Hispanic,'' says the 36-year-old public school teacher who
participated in the poll. ``I have friends of all races who have
spent the night with us and I've been to their house for parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said her white neighbors typically express racial views
similar to hers in public. Privately, she suspects they feel much
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people sometimes pretend that they are
open-minded about race, but they are not really genuine and they
are passing that along to their children,'' Johnson said. ``I know
because my kids have talked to me and told me their friends can't
have a black or Hispanic person in their home, and it just breaks
my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The semi-rural community of Covington, Ga., is less integrated,
but newcomer Bill Hyatt says he likes everything else about the
town where he has recently re-located with his family.
</P>
<P>
   The 47-year-old driver for Federal Express estimates only about
10 percent of his neighbors are black, but he says their race is
unimportant. His opinion was also expressed by 71 percent of fellow
poll respondents living in the South, and 78 percent of those in
other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   A native of an integrated town in New Hampshire who moved to the
South recently, Hyatt also represents 55 percent of newcomers who
said they felt ``very comfortable'' around people of other races,
compared with 45 percent of lifelong Southerners.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how I know I'm not a racist?'' Hyatt asked. ``I could
have a black neighbor and he could be a jerk or a sweetheart, and
I'd tell him how I felt, no matter what race he was. And if he did
that to me, I wouldn't think he was racist because I can be a jerk
sometimes too.''
</P>
<P>
   Race in the workplace
</P>
<P>
   Robert Harding of Dale City, Va., is a 42-year-old information
resources manager for the federal government. He is among the 79
percent of poll respondents who was pleased with their employer's
diversity training program, even though he says such programs are
only ``window dressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Harding said he is one of two black people in his 12-member
department who hold a master's degree, but despite his advanced
education he's paid $7,000 less than white co-workers who have only
high school diplomas. He has filed a complaint with the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission that is pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love for life to be totally fair, and maybe
affirmative action hurts some white people. But huge masses of
black people have already been hurt so I don't have any sympathy
for those arguments.''
</P>
<P>
   Harding says he thinks his office is typical of others around
the country where blacks and whites, at best, maintain a water
cooler cordiality that rarely extends beyond the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't listen to the same music and we don't watch the same
TV shows,'' says Harding. ``We go out to lunch and stuff, but that
doesn't lead to us going out socially, or really being friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Callahan of Dublin, Ga., is a 28-year-old bartender at
Peg Leg Patty's, a local hangout he describes as a melting pot of
different races that get along well with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Although he supports diversity training and other workplace
programs aimed at improving race relations, he has doubts about
affirmative action. He was among the 56 percent of white Southern
males in the poll who say it leads to reverse discrimination
against white men.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan, who was born in Savannah, also echoed the sentiments
of 48 percent of lifelong Southerners who said affirmative action
hurts whites compared with 39 percent of newcomers who agreed.
</P>
<P>
   race isnt a factor in HOPE scholarships; it's strictly grades;
either this guy's ignorant or he just meant a regular scholarship
``White men don't scream that it's unfair; we're willing to work
hard and pay our own way,'' says Callahan. ``I think affirmative
action deals more with the problem than the cure.''
</P>
<P>
   Church
</P>
<P>
   Episcopal bishop James A. Pike once dubbed Sunday at 11 a.m.,
when many people are in worship services, ``the most segregated
hour in American life.'' Thirty years after his death, that seems
to be changing.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 721 Southern respondents who attended religious services,
about 70 percent of whites and 60 percent of blacks said they
worshipped with people of other races.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Kathi Martin of Stone Mountain says these poll results
sound promising, but she has a problem: ``I don't believe it,'' she
says bluntly. ``I just don't believe it's that high.''
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons for her doubts. Two months ago, Martin founded
the God, Self, Neighbor Ministries at an established church in
Virginia-Highland, where she is hoping to attract a racially mixed,
multicultural congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who is black, hired a white music director and began
reaching out to whites and blacks through newspaper ads and
pamphlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some whites who came the first week, but they haven't
come back on a consistent basis. It's disheartening because that's
not our vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin pins those difficulties on history and culture: Black and
white churches tend to have different styles of worship, and those
traditions are passed on through generations.
</P>
<P>
   That's no excuse for Christians, Martin says, because of a
larger mandate that should put them on the front lines of racial
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can be a good Christian if you go to an all-white
or all-black church,'' she says. ``But I'm not sure if you can be
fully human unless you connect beyond those boundaries. We are the
people of God and we have to break down those barriers.''
</P>
<P>
   At poll respondent's Rose Washington's all-black United
Methodist church in Lexington, Miss., the congregation is trying to
do just that. They regularly visit churches in white communities,
and invite them to visit their church. It's busing in the name of
the Lord.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess because we're in a black neighborhood, white people
might not want to come here,'' said Washington, a 37-year-old
mental health consultant. ``I understand that because when we first
started visiting other churches, I felt uncomfortable. Now it
doesn't bother me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Dating and marriage
</P>
<P>
   In some parts of the South, marrying someone of another race _
or miscegenation _ was once forbidden by culture and by law.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the Alabama state legislature repealed its
100-year-old ban on interracial marriage, becoming the last state
do so. The constitutional amendment must be approved by voters.
</P>
<P>
   Although the laws have all but vanished, the Southern Poll found
whites still six times more likely to say they would disapprove of
a relative dating or marrying someone of another race.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, Southerners were far more likely to disapprove of
interracial marriage: only 8 percent of newcomers said they would
disapprove of an interracial marriage in their family compared with
25 percent of respondents who lived their entire lives in the
South.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Roy Lancaster had felt the sting of disapproval before.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 25, I was engaged to a full-blooded Arapaho and my
family told me to go out and find a white woman, so I did,'' says
Lancaster, a 37-year-old pipe maker from Sands Springs, Okla. ``My
father is a preacher and he says you're supposed to stay with your
own race. I don't argue with him when it comes to the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Unrepentant segregationist Fred Schofield of Alabama puts it
this way: ``A cow doesn't marry a hog, does it? Animals have sense
enough to stay with their own species.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schofield is in the minority of those polled. About 62
percent of whites and 92 percent of blacks in the South said they
would not disapprove of an interracial marriage in their own
families, or that it would make no difference.
</P>
<P>
   Although the practice remains fairly rare among whites, the same
is not true for blacks. In the South, 52 percent of blacks said a
family member married someone of another race, compared with 24
percent of whites in the South and North.
</P>
<P>
   Luke Szerbinsky, 22, knows how it feels to be a white minority.
Born in a racially mixed Chicago neighborhood, it was no big deal
dating his black or Latino classmates. But when he moved to DeKalb
County as a teenager, other whites and blacks branded him ``a
wigger'' _ a slang term for a white person who tries to ``act
black.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 71 percent of of newcomers to the South have had a
relative who dated someone of another race compared with 44 percent
of Southerners. Lifelong Southerners were also three times more
likely than newcomers to disapprove of someone in their family
dating interracially.
</P>
<P>
   ``People down here are not exposed to that kind of thing,'' said
Szerbinsky of Stone Mountain, whose black girlfriend is the mother
of his 22-month-old daughter. ``You can tell you're really not
accepted, and I still get the looks every now and then if we go to
a real nice restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   They met and got married in New York 13 years ago, Suruba
Ibumando and Howell Wechsler, a black writer from the Republic of
Congo and a Jewish research scientist. They didn't agonize over
about what others might think. But before moving to the Atlanta
area, they worried that their family would be confronted by blacks
who thought she had betrayed her race, and whites who still
considered blacks inferior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was apprehensive because of the history of slavery and I
heard stories about people harassing interracial couples,'' said
Suruba Wechsler, 43. ``I prepared myself, and said if anybody says
or does anything to us, that's their problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple says they haven't encountered any difficulties, but
they are concerned about their two children in elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if children born to interracial couples would have unique
problems, 81 percent of Southern whites and 56 percent of blacks
agreed. A similar percentage of Northern blacks and whites answered
the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes young kids will see me and my son Alex, who is
dark-skinned and they'll do a double take and say, ``That's your
dad?'' Wechsler said. ``I don't think they mean any harm. Of all
the things that could happen to them, a double take doesn't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids are just kids,'' says his wife. ``They know they are
African. They know they are American and they are Jews. They are
proud to be all three. When people ask us questions, I tell them
the truth: My kids are beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris is a staff writer for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. More results from this poll can be seen at
www.ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
