<HEADER>
A2735 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-FISH-KILL-600&AMP;A     06-20 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-FISH-KILL-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOURIST TOWN FEARS ATTEMPT TO RID ITS LAKE OF PIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTOLA, Calif. _ The latest bad news from Lake Davis has an all
too familiar ring to it.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1997, the California Fish and Game Department,
fresh out of ideas for ridding Lake Davis of the northern pike that
for years threatened the state's crucial salmon and trout
populations miles downstream, dumped 76,000 pounds of toxins into
the lake.
</P>
<P>
   The lake treatment, called ``the poisoning'' by residents of
this Sierra Nevada town, was good for the state's fishing industry
but disastrous for Portola, killing the pike but also eliminating
one of Portola's sources of drinking water and jeopardizing its
tourism-dependent economy. Plumas County Supervisor Fran Roudebush
said the poisoning cost the city and county more than $15 million
in lost revenue from tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the toxins dissipated, the lake restocked with trout
and the region once more packed with anglers, pike have again been
spotted in Lake Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration and dread are back, too, settling like a fog on
Portola. The fear is that the state will again shut down Lake Davis
and strangle the city's economy, just when Portola was showing
signs of renewal and people were starting to trust the lake as a
water supply.
</P>
<P>
   Although officials are not yet suggesting that the lake will
have to be treated again, residents are not waiting to see whether
that happens. Town meetings that include briefings on developments
at Lake Davis have been packed. And at the request of the Fish and
Game Department, residents are forming an advisory group that will
include department and city officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about a fish,'' Jim Murphy, Portola's city
administrator, said at a recent town meeting. ``This is about a
water supply. This is about the ability of a community to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone still remembers the rancor that marked the poisoning,
when protesters, including the man who would become mayor two years
later, were arrested after chaining themselves to a buoy in the
middle of the lake.
</P>
<P>
   With the railroad and logging industries that made Portola run
nearly dead now, the town now gains most of its revenue from
tourists who come for the prime fishing in Lake Davis. So while
many residents are exasperated by the recent pike discovery, the
town is officially accepting the Fish and Game Department's offer
to work together.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the city has no choice: The state has final
jurisdiction over its lakes and the tributaries and rivers that
flow out of them. These waterways are home to salmon and Steelhead
trout that Roudebush said bring California $1 billion in revenue
each year and could be decimated should pike _ razor-toothed
predators known to eat snakes, rats and ducklings _ begin to live
and breed in them.
</P>
<P>
   Fish and game biologists are using DNA tests to determine
whether the three fish caught at the end of May, one of which was
carrying eggs that would spawn next spring, survived the chemical
dump or were put in the lake by anglers who enjoy the difficult
catch and meaty taste. But they are sure that pike, which are
native to cold waters in the Midwest, were at one time illegally
introduced to Lake Davis.
</P>
<P>
   They are also determined to find out who did it and when. (Pike
were first found in Lake Davis in 1994). For the last month,
wardens have been conducting an extensive search for leads into
what Fish and Game officials call a crime of ecoterrorism. The
state and city have put up a $30,000 reward for information leading
to the arrest and conviction of people responsible for planting
pike in Lake Davis.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since the latest pike were caught, more than 30 game wardens
have been dispatched to knock on doors, search catches and survey
anglers.
</P>
<P>
   Others in Sacramento are contacting fisheries across the nation
that sell pike and combing Internet chat rooms that specialize in
fishing, looking for people bragging about catching pike in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people out there who want to see pike in Lake
Davis,'' said Steve Martarano, an information officer with the
Department of Fish and Game.
</P>
<P>
   Leads have turned up nothing; the closest officials came was
searching a man's house after he took responsibility on a Reno
radio station for planting the pike. Patrick Foy, a Fish and Game
spokesman, said the caller had lied on the air to get attention.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest concern to residents is whether there are more pike
in Lake Davis and, if so, whether the painful memories of the
poisoning will have to be relived.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials have gone on ``electrofishing'' tours of the
lake, in which Fish and Game officers temporarily stun fish in a
small area with electric shocks and then check the surface for
pike.
</P>
<P>
   Options short of poisoning the lake, should more pike be found,
including draining it, which would also affect tourism but would be
easier to recover from, or putting strong screens or sharp gates
over the lake's dam, which they hope would prevent any pike from
going downstream.
</P>
<P>
   Although the focus here is on the future of Lake Davis and
Portola, residents recognize the need to eliminate pike from the
state.
</P>
<P>
   People here also say they are dealing with an entirely new Fish
and Game Department this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time, Fish and Game stepped on our throats and told us
what to do,'' said Terri Nacar, an editor of The Portola Reporter,
who sharply criticized the department in print when pike were last
found in Lake Davis. ``This time they have a totally different
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, residents take heart in the fact that the lake is full
of fish and that even at midmorning on a weekday, a parking lot by
one of its ramps was packed with pickup trucks towing boat
trailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing excellent, excellent up here at Lake Davis,'' said
Lloyd Lambeth, who works at the Gold Rush Sporting Goods Store.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
