NYT-06-20-99 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990620.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2737 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOUCH-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     06-20 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUCH-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE METAPHYSICAL TOUCH': THE MIND-BODY PROBLEM IN VIRTUAL REALITY
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  (DW) 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Metaphysical Touch'' is a brainy and ingenious story of a
virtual love affair conducted by e-mail. There is no sex of the
fantasy sort that e-mail is sometimes used for, part romance and
part pornography. Physical sex is restricted to what the two
virtual lovers have with others' bodies off-screen.
</P>
<P>
   In Sylvia Brownrigg's novel, on-screen and off-screen correspond
to the two sides of philosophy's mind-body problem. It is
appropriate, since Pi, the woman, is a budding philosopher and
J.D., the man, is knotty-headed enough to be one. Mind wins out in
this speculative fiction, which owes something to Milan Kundera's
novels of thought and eros, and something to Diderot's
philosophical romances.
</P>
<P>
   In a large sense _ recall the saying that the brain is the true
erogenous zone _ J.D.'s and Pi's long dialogue is sexier than
anything either has done in bed. It is love in Dante's ``Paradiso''
mode, disembodied and earth-displacing: Beatrice's ``Love moves me
and makes me speak.'' Except that in this case it is speaking (via
Internet) that makes Pi and J.D. love; more important, it makes
each of them move after each, separately, has bogged down.
</P>
<P>
   The bogging, set out in the first part of the book, begins with
two traumas. For Pi, it is the destruction of all she has in the
great Pasadena fire of 1992: a few possessions, her cat, a nearly
finished dissertation on Kant that was the sensation of the
Berkeley philosophy department, her lovingly collected books and
the notes tucked into or scrawled on each. These were her brain,
her life, her talent, her future.
</P>
<P>
   J.D.'s trauma has been oozing up all his life. He is achingly
perceptive and witty, but this is underwater lighting in a turbid
wash of depression and self-absorption. He inherited them from his
wandering father, along with a dilettantish notion of himself as a
writer.
</P>
<P>
   Undermined by his writing failures, J.D. crumbles when he is
downsized from a modestly satisfying job as a computer instructor.
Ms. Brownrigg, whose thought pings and ricochets off words as if
they were the electric posts on a pinball machine, has no need to
light up the resonance of ``fire'' and ``fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Pi went through the reverse of death. Instead of leaving her
things behind, they left her behind. She can't forgive her
absconding world. Suddenly she is unable to stand books,
philosophy, her old friends, Berkeley. She takes refuge in
Mendocino, an artists' community up the north coast. She stays with
Abbie, a woman going through a divorce, and her 7-year-old
daughter, Martha. There she finds warmth, a nurturing bond with a
bright and frail child, home cooking and a bit of lovemaking with
her hostess. The orgasms are rather like the home cooking, though:
they comfort but don't quite heal.
</P>
<P>
   J.D.'s retreat, like J.D. himself, lacks Pi's sprightly if
disconsolate energy. He resorts to a computer chat room that
discusses literary suicides.
</P>
<P>
   His entries, which he titles ``Diery,'' meticulously narrate his
lowering state of mind, hint at his impending suicide and with
witty condescension relate the efforts of friends and relatives to
pry him out of his funk. Not an especially attractive spirit, but
he acquires Internet chic with an audience made curious by his
literate style and their own sophisticated ghoulishness.
</P>
<P>
   At this point Pi stumbles upon the Internet and the airy
deliverance it can provide. With reality destroyed, virtual reality
beckons, its nowhere quality a balm for her incinerated somewhere.
Ms. Brownrigg is brilliant about the weightlessness of a
communication that resembles eavesdropping on yourself:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quiet; it didn't require immediate response, as a voice
on the telephone did; it was in her familiar medium, print, so it
emerged through the loved language of her fingertips. But it didn't
require a physical body of print on paper. Ontologically, e-mail
was not in any recognizable category: neither voice nor paper,
neither pure mind nor pure matter. Uncategorizable items often make
it past regulations that don't know how to understand them.''
</P>
<P>
   Having forbidden writing, Pi tries out a few tentative e-mails
to friends. Having banished reading, she surfs the Web and comes
upon J.D.'s Diery. She is touched by a kindred dead soul 3,000
miles away; it seems she can touch back in safety.
</P>
<P>
   In fact the e-mail exchanges at the core of ``The Metaphysical
Touch'' are safe up to a point. They are also stimulating; and
stimulation means change, and change, risk. What begins as an arch
play of wit develops into a rousing but still neutral exchange of
ideas, and advances gingerly to life stories and a tentative probe
of feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Pi probes harder; she asks for a meeting. J.D. is evasive; more
damaged than his buoyant if battered interlocutor, he can only hint
at a stir of feeling. The upshot is tentative and holds an element
of ironic surprise that should not be revealed. What can be said is
that their erotic metaphysical touching has brought both Pi and
J.D. at least partway back to life; their mind-body problem a
little less of a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brownrigg's novel is vital, provocative and written with a
wit and venturesomeness that go quite a way toward doing what
fiction should do: keep time for a ticking world. The e-mail
sections _ thought, and emotions disguised as thought _ are very
well done. So is the portrait of Pi's Job-like state and the
philosophical wrestling it engages her in.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, and it is a weakness, the characters are less
real when they are not thinking. To put it differently, their
thoughts about themselves are more vital than they are. An
exception is Martha, since a child's thinking and being are
inseparable. J.D., activated on e-mail, neither overcomes nor quite
inhabits his inertness.
</P>
<P>
   With him, with Abbie, Pi's hostess, and even with Pi (her
nonvirtual bisexuality barely gets beyond its description), we come
to the point of knowing we know people like them, yet we still fall
short of quite knowing them. It is appropriate and on the whole
captivating that ``The Metaphysical Touch'' has a mind-body problem
of its own.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL; 
`THE METAPHYSICAL TOUCH'
</P>
<P>
   By Sylvia Brownrigg
</P>
<P>
   390 pages. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $24.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
