u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     06-20 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
 (HLW)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are considering
for Page 1, Monday, June 21. The N.Y. Times News Service late-night
supervisor will be Sam Weiss; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Podujevo) _ The last of some 40,000 Serb forces left
Kosovo on Sunday a few hours ahead of NATO's deadline for
withdrawal, leaving in their wake new scenes of jubilation among
the province's Albanians, as well as new acts of retribution. With
the withdrawal completed, NATO's secretary-general, Javier Solana,
announced that he had lifted the alliance's threat to resume
bombing, formally ending an air war that lasted 78 days and
culminated with the occupation of Kosovo by NATO-led peacekeepers
over the last eight days. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SUMMIT (Cologne) _ Leaders of the G7 nations and Russia
outlined on Sunday a plan for ending eight years of war in the
Balkans through a massive program of aid and political support for
the region, but said Yugoslavia must undertake ``democratic and
economic reforms'' to be part of the process. At the end of a
three-day summit meeting, the leaders of Britain, France and
Germany said democratic reform in Yugoslavia involved the departure
of Milosevic; but in deference to Russia no explicit reference to
the Serbian leader was included in the final statement. By Roger
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-RUSSIA (Cologne) _ Clinton and Yeltsin meet and
smooth over ties. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   EASTEUROPE-EU-DOUBTS (Plonsk, Poland) _ The post-communist world
in Central Europe is entering a new phase. After tireless and
largely successful efforts to align their economies with those of
western Europe, countries like Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic are pushing hard for the ultimate badge of acceptance:
membership in the European Union. But at least here in Poland,
Central Europe's biggest country and thus its brightest economic
star, leaders now find that a sizable part of the population is
balking. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-FADIMAN (Undated) _ Clifton Fadiman, the essayist, critic,
editor and indefatigable anthologist whose encyclopedic knowledge
made him a mainstay of ``Information Please'' and other popular
radio programs in the late 1930s, '40s, and '50s, died on Sunday on
Sanibel Island, Fla. He was 95 and had lived on the nearby island
of Captiva. By Richard Severo.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-GAME (New York) _ For most of New York it was a normal
weekend, but mingling among the natives was a group of very unusual
tourists, mostly current and former Microsoft employees, more than
a handful of them millionaires, who for 24 hours turned the city
into a game board. The scavenger hunt, which players call ``The
Game,'' is normally played in Seattle. But this year the game
organizers decided to ``raise the rims'' and bring it to New York
City to add a new level of complexity. At its root the game is a
frivolous adventure, but one fueled by the players' and designers'
creativity, not to mention their stock options and ego.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
