<P>
   Here are the Kosovo-related stories that The New York Times is
planning for Monday, June 21, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service day
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Podujevo) _ The last of some 40,000 Serb forces left
Kosovo on Sunday a few hours ahead of NATO's deadline for
withdrawal, leaving in their wake new scenes of jubilation among
the province's Albanians, as well as new acts of retribution. With
the withdrawal completed, NATO's secretary-general, Javier Solana,
announced that he had lifted the alliance's threat to resume
bombing, formally ending an air war that lasted 78 days and
culminated with the occupation of Kosovo by NATO-led peacekeepers
over the last eight days. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SUMMIT (Cologne) _ Leaders of the G7 nations and Russia
outlined on Sunday a plan for ending eight years of war in the
Balkans through a massive program of aid and political support for
the region, but said Yugoslavia must undertake ``democratic and
economic reforms'' to be part of the process. At the end of a
three-day summit meeting, the leaders of Britain, France and
Germany said democratic reform in Yugoslavia involved the departure
of Milosevic; but in deference to Russia no explicit reference to
the Serbian leader was included in the final statement. By Roger
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-RUSSIA (Cologne) _ The reasonable face of Russia,
President Boris Yeltsin, walked stiffly, but the fact that he came
here on Sunday to meet with Clinton and other leaders was taken as
reassurance that dialogue between Moscow and the West was possible
in the aftermath of the Kosovo war. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ The authorities in Belgrade are
telling the Kosovo Serbs to return. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIAN (Pristina) _ Veton Surroi reckons he owes his
life to a bunch of looters in a utility truck. The prominent
publisher was one of the few leaders of the Albanian community to
remain in Pristina throughout the last three months of turmoil and
survive. On a rare occasion when he ventured outside to change safe
houses, Surroi saw three armed people climb out of a special police
car and come towards him. ``I was scared as hell,'' he recalled in
an interview today in the looted offices of his newspaper Koha
Ditore. ``I was saved by a utility car that came by,'' he said. The
men in the truck were looters and drew the interest of the police.
``I went quickly down a side street. It gave me time to get away,''
he said. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these, we have a related media story:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WAR-MEDIA (Undated) _ The conflict in Kosovo has produced
war coverage that has been in some basic ways different from any
battlefield coverage that has come before, according to editors,
correspondents and media critics. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   The following three Kosovo stories are tentative:
</P>
