<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, June 21, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Mostly cloudy skies Monday will occur east of the Appalachians
from southern New England to the Carolinas as a wavering front
lingers off the Atlantic seaboard. Intermittent rain will fall near
the coast, but the heaviest and most persistent rain showers are
expected to remain offshore. Patchy drizzle will occur near the
slopes of the central Appalachians. Farther north, a weak
disturbance will produce a few afternoon showers from the Catskills
to the mountains of northern New England.
</P>
<P>
   Plentiful sunshine will be mixed with a few clouds from the
eastern Great Lakes to the interior Southeast. During the warmth of
the afternoon, isolated showers will form in the interior Southeast
while dry conditions prevail farther north. Meanwhile, there will
be frequent showers over central and southern Florida as a moist
air flow from the east continues.
</P>
<P>
   Heat will build over the northern Plains as winds from the west
are warmed as they descend from the Rockies. At the leading edge of
the hot air mass, clouds and some thundershowers will develop in
the northern Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and thundershowers will be common from central across
Oklahoma to the central Mississippi Valley. Weak high-level winds
will lead to slow-moving thunderstorms over parts of Texas and
Oklahoma raising the risk of local flash flooding.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, interior sections will be very warm with afternoon
thunderstorms developing over many of the peaks of the Rockies.
Onshore breezes will keep the Northwest coast mostly cloudy and
cool with a few sprinkles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: The Longest Season
</P>
<P>
   The official start of summer is at 3:49 p.m. EDT Monday, and
astronomy, not meteorology, is the deciding factor. It is then that
the northward trek of the sun's direct rays across the planet
cease. At that moment when the sun stands still, the summer
solstice arrives.
</P>
<P>
   For the next six months, the direct rays of the sun will move
inexorably south, culminating in the winter solstice. But alas, the
summer season is the slowest to fade. As a result of the elliptical
shape of the earth's orbit around the sun, the Northern Hemisphere
summer lasts 93 days while winter is 89 days long.
</P>
</TEXT>
