<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2763 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SECRET-SERVICE-SHOOTI     06-20 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-SERVICE-SHOOTINGS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SECRET SERVICE IS STUDYING SCHOOL SHOOTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Colo., Mass., Ill., Calif., N.H.)  (lb) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On a Monday afternoon in 1993, in a small town in
Kentucky, an honor student shot and killed his senior English
teacher in one of the nation's first school shootings. The student,
Scott Pennington, is serving a life sentence in a Kentucky prison,
where this month he had two unusual visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Pennington's guests were a forensic psychologist and an agent
from the U.S. Secret Service. They asked the somber young man the
same questions they had asked dozens of assassins: What was he
trying to achieve? How did he choose his targets? When did he get
the gun? Did he hope to be killed?
</P>
<P>
   The people who protect the president have turned their attention
to school violence. Prompted by the slaying of 12 students and a
teacher at Columbine High School near Littleton, Colo., in April, a
Secret Service team has begun a detailed review of the Columbine
shooting and those at more than a dozen other schools, interviewing
as many of the killers as it can.
</P>
<P>
   The team is looking for patterns of motive and behavior. The
goal is to help schools and the police recognize which students are
moving from interest in killing to weapons acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be so much easier if all the people who did this
dressed weirdly or were outcasts,'' said Robert Fein, the forensic
psychologist, who visited the prison along with the team leader,
Bryan Vossekuil.
</P>
<P>
   What the Secret Service has already learned from a detailed
study of American assassins poses several conundrums for school
principals, the police and public officials struggling to respond
to the school shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the most common responses to school violence: armed
guards, surveillance cameras, metal detectors, dress codes and
special telephone numbers for reporting threats.
</P>
<P>
   While more schools are hiring police officers to patrol the
hallways, the Secret Service warns that a motive of many killers is
to be killed. Heightened security may be a deterrent, and it may be
a magnet for suicide.
</P>
<P>
   While schools are installing video cameras, many killers said
their motive was to become famous. A camera may be a deterrent, and
it may offer a video yearbook of a killer.
</P>
<P>
   While schools are prohibiting trench coats, many killers told
the Secret Service that they tried to blend into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   While schools are encouraging the reporting of any threat, the
Secret Service takes all threats seriously, but it found that not
one assassin in the past 50 years had made a threat.
</P>
<P>
   And while Congress is financing a national phone number for
anonymous reporting of concerns about students, nearly all schools
and the police have been given no training in assessing which
people are planning an attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that some of the same ideas used to help protect the
president may also help keep our nation's schoolchildren safe,''
said Brian Stafford, the new director of the Secret Service. ``We
want to offer any assistance we can to prevent this from happening
again.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Secret Service has shed some of its secrecy, and begun
forming the National Threat Assessment Center, the formal name of
the team. Working from a warren of desks two blocks from the White
House, the group of fewer than a dozen members has widened its
research to celebrity stalking, then to workplace violence and now
to school slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly far removed from presidential assassination, these
rare events with powerful social consequences have several elements
in common. Killers study security. They acquire weapons. They often
study the history of assassination. They plan their escape or their
death.
</P>
<P>
   The national response to school killings has focused on root
causes: What makes children kill?
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service is encouraging public officials to pay more
attention to the investigator's challenge: How does a police
officer or principal respond to vague information that classmates
or teachers are concerned about a student?
</P>
<P>
   The goal, agency officials say, is to develop training materials
for police and school officials. Later this month the agency will
convene a group of principals, counselors and other school
officials in the Midwest to discuss its research.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service once watched for people who fit the popular
profile of dangerousness: the lunatic, the loner, the threatener,
the hater.
</P>
<P>
   That profile has been shattered by the assassins themselves.
Many agreed to be interviewed on videotape by the Secret Service,
which studied all 83 people who tried to kill a public official or
celebrity in the United States in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The assassins were visited at home, in prisons and in hospitals
by Fein, a soft-spoken psychologist from New York, and Vossekuil, a
thoughtful agent who toured the world with Ronald Reagan. Their
work was supported by the National Institute of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   The first lesson taught by assassins is to discard stereotypes.
Killers are not necessarily mentally ill, or socially isolated, or
even male.
</P>
<P>
   Their second lesson is not to expect a threat. As assassins told
the Secret Service, why would they threaten? A threat would keep
them from succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   Few assassins express hatred for their victims, easily shifting
from one target to another. As a woman who approached President
George Bush with a gun explained: ``I liked the man. I would have
voted for him if I hadn't been locked up in county jail'' for
threatening to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   In the old view, a person is capable of violence or is not; a
person has to be crazy to commit mass murder; people just snap.
</P>
<P>
   In the new view, people are more or less violent depending on
the circumstances; people make a decision to kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they on a path toward attacking someone?'' said John
Berglund, a team member. ``If so, how fast are they moving? How
close are they to attacking someone? How might they be stopped?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Before committing the Colorado school massacre, the two
students, Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, copied school
keys, made bombs, acquired guns, kept a diary describing their
plans, and warned a student to leave the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some write about their ideas and activities, in a journal or
diary,'' Vossekuil said. ``Others tell friends, family or
colleagues _ but usually not the target _ about their thoughts and
intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   Killers often do not carry out a plan until a painful event _
job loss or the end of a relationship _ sends them into despair.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, the son of a career military man, kept a diary of his
plans for a year. The week before his suicidal attack, he was
rejected by the Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   Most assassins behave in ways that concern the people who know
them. As Robert John Bardo left for Los Angeles, where he would
kill the actress Rebecca Shaeffer in 1989, his father asked,
``You're not going to do a John Hinckley thing, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   The police in Colorado were criticized for not doing more to
prevent the attack at Columbine. Despite another student's
complaint that Harris was making threats on his Web site and
testing pipe bombs with Klebold, sheriff's deputies did not
interview either student, or talk with their parents, or examine
the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all learned a lesson on April 20th,'' said Lt. John
Kiekbusch of the Sheriff's Department of Jefferson County, which
includes Columbine. ``We need to take these in a more serious
fashion.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In assessing whether a person is dangerous, the Secret Service
recommends that schools and the police start with a detailed series
of questions about a person's behavior and motivation.
</P>
<P>
   What has the person said about his intentions? Has the person
shown an interest in assassins, weapons or militant groups? If
there is a history of mental illness, has the person acted on
hallucinations or delusions? Has the person been suicidal?
</P>
<P>
   On the campus of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, the
police have changed the way they react to vague reports of fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have cases where somebody is afraid of someone,'' said Anne
Glavin, chief of police at MIT for 18 years. ``It's not even real
tangible, but people have strong feelings about the situation, not
always in a way that they can articulate. Police have tended to be
dismissive of that sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with the Secret Service, MIT set up what it calls a
threat team to handle such cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone's scared, we spend a lot of time trying to find out
why they're scared,'' Glavin said. ``One can certainly rip a page
from the Secret Service's way of looking at violence.''
</P>
<P>
   This approach is being tested in stalking cases by prosecutors
in Chicago and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In Dover, N.H., the police and the Secret Service are
interviewing killers to learn more about the behavior of boyfriends
and husbands who kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to be cautious in drawing conclusions,'' said
Fein, the Secret Service psychologist. ``We have a set of ideas
that are a useful tool. But we would be skeptical of anybody who
claims certainty.''
</P>
<P>
   In Grayson, Ky., in 1993, English teacher Deanna McDavid was
certain that one of her students was dangerous. Thoughts of death
ran through Scott Pennington's journals.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, she had told a fellow teacher, that boy is going to
bring a gun to school and shoot himself _ or someone else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
