<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2766 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-2TAKES     06-20 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST YUGOSLAVS LEAVE KOSOVO; ALBANIANS CARRY OUT RETRIBUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and locator map are being sent to NYT photo/graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODUJEVO, Yugoslavia _ The last of some 40,000 Yugoslav forces
left Kosovo Sunday a few hours ahead of NATO's deadline for
withdrawal, effectively ending Yugoslavia's control over a province
at the center of Serbia's cultural and historical lore.
</P>
<P>
   With the withdrawal completed, NATO's secretary-general, Javier
Solana, announced that he had lifted the alliance's threat to
resume bombing, formally ending a 78-day air war that culminated
with the occupation of Kosovo by NATO-led peacekeepers over the
last eight days.
</P>
<P>
   By early Sunday, the last Yugoslav troops had left the province
along the main route north of here. Only a small convoy of Yugoslav
army trucks remained at the border to Serbia proper, seeking
permission from NATO to be escorted back to retrieve broken-down
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   At the Serbian border town of Rudnica, Yugoslav soldiers manned
a checkpoint, but otherwise there was no sign of Yugoslav forces
along the winding road into Serbia from Mitrovica, except for a
lone carload of soldiers heading north.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's spokesman, Lt. Col. Robin Clifford, said the withdrawal
had been completed roughly 11 hours ahead of a midnight-Sunday
deadline that was set 11 days ago when Yugoslav generals accepted
NATO's terms for suspending its airstrikes. Clifford said some
stragglers might remain, but that any found after the deadline
would be detained.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav withdrawal left in its wake new scenes of
jubilation among Kosovo's Albanians, as well as fresh acts of
retribution even as the 18,000 NATO troops now in the battered
province moved, with mixed success, to exert a semblance of
control.
</P>
<P>
   While the withdrawal of Yugoslav forces has gone relatively
smoothly, NATO's troops continue to have difficulties keeping
fighters from the Kosovo Liberation Army in check.
</P>
<P>
   After talks with the rebels dragged on for another day,
complicated by rivalries within their opaque and fractious
leadership, a NATO official said Sunday night that the rebel
command had signed a draft agreement to disband and turn over their
weapons within 30 days. The accord still awaited approval by NATO
ambassadors in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, NATO troops had new confrontations with the
group, confiscating weapons and arresting several of its fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night, Italian troops stopped a truck near Pec and
discovered an arsenal of weapons belonging to the rebels, including
more than 1,800 mortar rounds, 560 mines and 118 anti-tank rockets
and shoulder-fired missiles. British troops also intercepted and
disarmed two rebel patrols, while U.S. Marines arrested an Albanian
accused of killing three Serbs with a sniper rifle.
</P>
<P>
   With the final withdrawal of Yugoslav troops came vengeance
against Serb civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Albanians who only recently returned from hiding in the hills
looted and burned houses belonging to Serbs. In the lush valley
between Pristina and Mitrovica, smoke rose from dozens of homes,
leaving a thick pall in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Grace, north of Pristina, Albanians took
whatever they could from houses after driving out the Serbs who
lived there. ``Everything they did to us, we're getting back now,''
said Gazmehd Kosumi, 25, who returned with his family two days ago
to find their two homes nearby destroyed. ``They burned everything.
They took everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Albanians filled their aging tractors with loot, even after
British and French troops arrived. A British soldier simply
shrugged when asked if there was not something NATO could do to
stop the destruction. Half a dozen homes crackled in flames.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford described the violence in Grace as ``an unfortunate
incident,'' saying the commander on the ground had decided that the
way ``to avoid any danger to life and limb was to accept some
damage to property.'' He said NATO troops had rescued a 19-year-old
man who had been attacked by the looters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we don't want to do is inflame any situation,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the violence prompted a new exodus of Serbs, more
than 50,000 of whom have already fled since NATO troops arrived
eight days ago. On the road to Serbia proper from Pristina to
Leposavic, dozens of Serb families headed north in bedraggled
convoys Sunday, their trucks and tractors crammed with whatever
they could carry.
</P>
<P>
   Just outside of Lesak, near the Serbian border, one man from
Grace erupted in anger when asked why he was leaving Kosovo. He
said the Kosovo Liberation Army had arrived on Saturday and began
shooting. French troops came, he said, but took their weapons, not
the rebels'. Another man gestured angrily at his clothes, saying it
was all he had left.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took everything,'' he shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Dragomir Ristic left his home in Stanovic grudgingly. He said
Serb leaders had encouraged them to stay. ``But the French came,
and the Albanians started to burn things,'' he said, sitting atop a
pile of suitcases and furniture in a wooden trailer being pulled by
a tractor. ``If I stayed, they would have killed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Serbs have said the presence of Russian peacekeepers would
give them a greater sense of security, but Ristic had no idea the
United States and Russia had reached an agreement to deploy 3,600
Russian soldiers to the province, beginning in a few days. It did
not matter now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't wait for the Russians to come,'' he said. ``I don't
have a house. I don't have anything.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Mitrovica, a group of several hundred Serb civilians on
Sunday tried in effect to partition the city, erecting a makeshift
barricade at one of end of a bridge and declaring the northern
third of Mitrovica a Serb-controlled zone.
</P>
<P>
   From there, they jeered and heckled Albanians, including an
elderly woman and a mother with a baby carriage, who tried to
cross. Citing fears that they were being infiltrated by Kosovo
Liberation Army, the Serbs said that only Albanians who could prove
they had previously lived in the neighborhood were welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a border,'' said one young Serb who would
not give his name. ``There are going to be two parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Serbs said that the predominantly Serb towns between
Mitrovica and the border with Serbia, including Zvecan and
Leposvic, would also be part of the self-declared Serb zone. NATO
officials said Sunday night that the stand off was continuing.
</P>
<P>
   For the Albanians, however, the withdrawal of the much-feared
soldiers and police officers brought a palpable sense of relief.
Things are nowhere close to normal in Kosovo, but in city after
city, village after village, there are renewed signs of life and
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Podujevo, one of the last cities vacated by the Serbs,
there has not been electricity for three days, and no water for 10.
But vendors have begun to sell fruit and vegetables on the
sidewalks, which were crowded with Albanians who had returned after
hiding in the hills for more than two months. It is also possible,
at last, to buy cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   At an old concrete hotel on the edge of town, which until
Saturday morning had been a headquarters for the Serb special
police, Kimete Avdiu and her sister, Feride, found two chickens
that had made a roost in a pile of trash beside the building.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Avdiu, 26, said the chickens were among nine they had left
behind when Serbs drove them from the home across the street on
March 29. In the roost, her sister found four eggs, a bonanza after
weeks with little food.
</P>
<P>
   British troops from the Kings Royal Hussars Battle Group, who
are turning the building into their headquarters, gave away
whatever they did not need, including mattresses, chairs, tables
and other furnishings. ``These people have nothing,'' the group's
commander, Capt. Chris McGregor, said.
</P>
<P>
   On Podujevo's main street, Bekim Kamerolli, a 22-year-old
waiter, used a razor to scrape away the Cyrillic symbol of Serb
unity, which Serbs painted on storefronts and homes across Kosovo
to distinguish their properties from those being ravaged. Until
Sunday, it would have been an unthinkable chore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see it, because it is the Serbs' sign,''
Kamerolli said, standing on a milk crate as he worked the blade.
``It doesn't belong there anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
