<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BELGIUM21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke chairman gets briefing in Belgium
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brussels _ Coca-Cola Chairman M. Douglas Ivester met privately
here with top company executives Saturday in what amounted to a
post-mortem of what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting inside Coca-Cola Belgium's midrise steel and concrete
complex in a suburban office park, Ivester spent hours listening to
explanations of how Coke products became tainted, leading to scores
of reports that people were falling ill after consuming them.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester has not made a public appearance here and the
Atlanta-based soft drink company isn't expected to make any
statements until Monday, said Paul Pendergrass, the director of
communications for Coca-Cola Greater Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The Belgian government banned all Coke products a week ago today
after dozens of youngsters were hospitalized with complaints of
stomach pains and nausea after drinking the company's beverages.
The health scare rapidly spread to other nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Belgian government said Saturday its ban on canned Coke,
Coke Light (the European version of Diet Coke), Sprite and Fanta
will remain in effect until it is convinced of the company's
explanations about what happened, and until the problem is
corrected. Local TV news in Brussels showed tape of huge piles of
canned Cokes being disposed of in what appeared to be a dump.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Health Ministry officials said Friday they expected
to hear from Coca-Cola on Monday, Pendergrass said no meeting was
scheduled. He added, however, that such a meeting was entirely
possible.
</P>
<P>
   The government still expresses some impatience with Coca-Cola
executives. Mieke Van den Berghe, a government spokeswoman, said
the partial ban will continue until the company provides adequate
information about the cause of the illnesses and evidence that the
cause has been remedied. ``They still have not done this basic
thing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The government took the unusual step of banning all Coke
products in part because of its frustration at what it considered
the company's slow and insensitive response to the reports of
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Pendergrass said the company was in close contact with the
government and was trying to allay concerns by responding to
specific questions. ``Our communications have been very open and
direct with the government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coke was working over the weekend to develop more documentation
_ including gathering interviews from people who had fallen ill and
medical officials involved in their treatment, Pendergrass said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Coke products _ Nestea, Aquarius, Bonaqua, Kinley, Lift and
Minute Maid _ were reappearing in stores here Saturday after being
removed from shelves last week.
</P>
<P>
   While the furor over the Coke story seems to be subsiding,
Ivester's visit was reported in the major daily Le Soir under the
headline ``The boss of Coca-Cola has come to manage the crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, however, was identified as ``Jack'' instead of Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
