<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   G8-KOSOVO _ COLOGNE, Germany _ Final day of summit of the Group
of Eight industrialized nations, followed by news conference by
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder. Developing. (Deans, Cox News
Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISONERS _ PRIZREN, Yugoslavia _ As NATO warplanes
dropped bombs on Yugoslavia for 78 days, hundreds of ethnic
Albanian men were carted off north to prisons in Serbia. The story
of what happened to them is an untold one. Developing. (Kaplow, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WITHDRAW _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Yugoslav forces will or
will not meet the deadline for withdrawing troops from Kosovo
province on Sunday. But there is not question that the challenges
for NATO in this war-torn province are just beginning. Developing.
(Kunstel, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MONASTERY _ DECANI, Kosovo _ Offering a tranquil campus
behind a massive stone gatehouse, the Serbian Orthodox Visoki
Decani monastery is a refuge in Kosovo. But Kosovo Liveration Army
leaders are not pleased that the monastery is housing Serbs.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-BELGIUM _ BRUSSELS _ Coca-Cola Chairman M. Douglas Ivester
met privately here with top company executives Saturday in what
amounted to a post-mortem of what went wrong. Meeting inside
Coca-Cola Belgium's midrise steel and concrete complex in a
suburban office park, Ivester spent hours listening to explanations
of how Coke products became tainted, leading to scores of reports
that people were falling ill after consuming them. (Roughton, Cox
News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-INTEGRATION _ ATLANTA _ The change in attitudes toward
integration in the South in the 1990s has been marked. In a 1991
Atlanta Journal-Constitution poll, 47 percent of white Southerners
said they favored integration, compared with 56 percent of whites
now. (Harris, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-POLL _ ATLANTA _ We believe in integration, but the
reality still eludes us. We claim to be comfortable with other
races, but for many that comfort is usually at arm's length. And
when it comes to interracial dating and marriage _ the most ancient
of America's racial taboos _ our aversions have diminished, not
disappeared. It's clear that we are still evolving, due in part to
an influx of transplanted Southerners who are slowly re-shaping the
region's distinctive racial topography. But how far has the South
really come? Focusing on four main areas of Southern life _
community, workplace, church and marriage _ the stories behind the
AJC poll statistics illustrate a tantalizing racial paradox where
racial attitudes and actions have come closer, but still only
rarely intersect. (Harris, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION-SCIENCE _ RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C. _ The science
driving many of the nation's air quality laws was done at a
little-known cluster of EPA labs at Research Triangle Park. Here,
researchers conduct tests on both human volunteers and animals to
determine the health effects of ozone and other air pollution. And
specialists trek the nation, examining sickness and mortality
records in an effort to determine statistical connections between
bad air and death rates. We examine what they have learned, and how
the work on the links between pollution and health are driving
changes in Alanta and elsewhere. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ROCKMAN _ BALL GROUND, Ga. _ Drive through downtown Ball Ground
most any day and you'll probably see the old man in his parked red
pickup truck. He sits on the side of the road by one of the nine
buildings downtown that he has filled with a massive collection of
stones, rocks, gems and minerals. The man in the truck is Oscar
Robertson, a 75-year-old eccentric who watches people stroll past
the hardware store and post office before they try to open a locked
door to one of his shops. They often leave perplexed and
frustrated, however, because Robertson rarely unlocks his stores to
sell anything to anyone. City leaders cringe at the Rock Man's
reluctance to cater to the stream of tourists and rock collectors.
That stream, after all, could pump big bucks into the local
economy. Mayor Roberts and other civic leaders want Ball Ground to
get a piece of the action. They dream of a Ball Ground where people
from the big city and its suburbs visit antique stores, see the
rock shops and eat in sidewalk cafes. But the ``Rock Man'' just
wants to be left alone with his rocks. (Bixler, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ My 13-year-old granddaughter Betsy has a special
knack for winning new friends. ``I'm Betsy Vance,'' she says, ``I
have a three-legged dog.'' ``That will get you friends!'' I gasped.
She has many friends and she seemed to think Winnie, the big, black
three-legged, is the inducement. So I was prone to drop the subject
until she added: ``I believe it would be better if I could say,
`I'm Betsy Vance. I have a three-legged dog and a swimming pool.'''
(Sibley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
