<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2772 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEDDINGS-COX     06-20 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEDDINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lifetime series shows real-life weddings
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TV PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Weddings of a Lifetime XV''
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight on Lifetime
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There were few dry eyes in the house when Daryl Tate
and Melissa Summers shared their first married kiss one Friday
night last month.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing embrace seemed to last several minutes. When the
happy couple finally began moving down the aisle of Atlanta's
Hillside Chapel and Truth Center, toward happily ever after, they
passed rows of beaming relatives and
</P>
<P>
   friends . . .
</P>
<P>
   . . . And a guy with a headset giving them directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to re-create the magic of the kissing of the bride,''
floor director Dale Stern apologetically told the crowd. ``Welcome
to Hollywood, ladies and gentlemen!''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome, in fact, to ``Weddings of a Lifetime,'' which four
times each year takes the largely romantic fantasy of getting
married and matches it with the cold, hard realities of television
production.
</P>
<P>
   It's essentially an arranged date where everybody wins: The
hourlong ``Weddings'' are Lifetime Television's highest-rated
nonmovie specials, with one recent installment being watched by
nearly 1.2 million homes. Couples get fantasies fulfilled (Grammy
winner BeBe Winans sang at Summers' nuptials) and most of the
expenses paid (Lifetime alone estimated it would spend as much as
$500,000 on this 15th ``Weddings'' installment, for everything from
crew costs to music rights) _ all in exchange for letting anyone
with basic cable watch them take the plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a spiritual thing,'' Summers, the megapopular KISS 104.7
DJ, explained hours before her wedding to Atlanta police officer
Tate, to be shown tonight on Lifetime. ``Not only can we touch
Atlanta this way, but also people nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   The urge to share one's nuptial bliss isn't uncommon, says one
expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people just feel they have such a great love story,
they want to broadcast it _ out of general good will,'' said Lois
Smith Brady, whose new book, ``Love Lessons: 12 Real-Life Love
Stories,'' includes couples who'd previously let her describe their
weddings for millions of Sunday New York Times readers. ``And then
there's just plain old ego. Brides and grooms have big egos!''
</P>
<P>
   But forget why anyone would want to televise their wedding. How
it happens is the really interesting part.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a double production,'' executive producer Lou Gorfain
explained outside the Grand Hyatt Buckhead, where Summers' fully
decked-out and made-up bridesmaids were filming a segment nine
hours before the ceremony. ``And the wedding is just as much of a
production as the TV show.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a man equipped with a detailed, 12-page production
schedule and enough experience to know that when something
inevitably goes awry _ in this case, Mayor Bill Campbell had to
miss rehearsing his entrance with Summers' mother and
great-grandmother _ they'll just work around it.
</P>
<P>
   Over Gorfain's shoulder, ``Weddings'' co-host Eva LaRue Callahan
mispronounced a designer's name on-camera. Gorfain threw a mock
look of despair at maid of honor Carolyn Anderson, who'd already
had to introduce herself on-air several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``See? And she's the talent!'' Gorfain pointed at Callahan, late
of the ABC soap ``All My Children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right, now I feel better,'' Anderson chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   With husband John Callahan (Edmund Grey on ``All My Children''),
LaRue Callahan has hosted seven ``Weddings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting thing I find every time is how shocked not
only the bride and groom, but also their family and friends, are by
the end,'' LaRue Callahan said during a shooting break in a 16-hour
day. ``Yes, it's their wedding. But they sometimes forget it's also
about getting a show on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting this show on the air meant solving some common wedding
problems. Summers changed her mind ``so many times'' about the
wedding's color scheme, joked her mother, Mary Brand of Red
Springs, N.C., ``I didn't know whether to cry, fly or sigh.'' But
it also meant dealing with the unusual, even for ``Weddings of a
Lifetime.'' For starters, this couple had a much higher public
profile than their predecessors; one Lifetime staffer says Summers,
nicknamed ``Atlanta's Girlfriend,'' was the first ``Weddings''
bride with her own PR people.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually everything about Summers' relationship with Tate was
well-known to listeners _ from how they met in his capacity as a
member of Mayor Campbell's executive protection team to how he and
Lifetime surprised her on-air with the news they'd been selected
for ``Weddings.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, the couple had invited the entire city to attend their
Saturday wedding on the steps of the State Capitol. When city
officials raised concerns about nearby Braves game traffic, Tate
and Summers moved the ceremony back a day, to Hillside, and limited
fan attendance through a hotline number _ all to Lifetime's quiet
relief. ``We'd had a lot of conversations about `Can we control
this situation with so many fans?''' confided Julie Falk, an
original programming director.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Lifetime had kind of asked for all this. Having
produced ``Weddings'' everywhere from a cruise ship to the U.S.
Naval Academy chapel in Annapolis, the network was itching to show
a real ``hometown'' wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both outstanding `hometown' people,'' said Falk, whose
network culls thousands of letters looking for captivating story
lines. ``What a couple has to have to be chosen is not only a very
interesting relationship, but they have to be interesting as
individuals as well.''
</P>
<P>
   From Tate's law enforcement work to Summer's rags-to-riches rise
from Army enlistee to nationally syndicated radio star _ ``She is
the Lifetime woman,'' Gorfain enthused _ it all was interesting to
the network. Some 17 days of filming everywhere from the
Lillington, N.C., home of Summers' great-grandmother, Ella
McLaughlin, to inside Campbell's car added up to 40 hours of film.
Falk said it was well worth the effort to get tonight's 40-plus
minutes. ``This couple just pops off the screen,'' she said
emphatically the morning of the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, ``this couple'' looked a tad weary rehearsing
at Hillside. While crews positioned cameras and checked sound
levels, a handful of formally dressed guests provided background
for an interview segment with Brand and McLaughlin. Lifetime
doesn't stop the actual ceremony once it begins, so almost nothing
was being left to chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us, there are certain moments we can't re-create or
reshoot,'' Falk had explained. ``We can reshoot the bridesmaids
here a bunch of times, but Daryl will only see her in her dress for
the first time once. There'll only be one first kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean there can't be a second first kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Hollywood, ladies and gentlemen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
