<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2774 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SUMMIT-770&AMP;ADD     06-20 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SUMMIT-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN LEADERS DETAIL PLAN FOR AIDING BALKANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ Leaders of the seven wealthiest nations and
Russia outlined a plan Sunday for ending eight years of war in the
Balkans through a vast program of aid and political support, but
said Yugoslavia must undertake ``democratic and economic reforms''
to take part.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a three-day summit meeting, the leaders of
Britain, France and Germany said that in their view, democratic
reform in Yugoslavia would have to involve the departure of
President Slobodan Milosevic, but in deference to Russia no
explicit reference to him was included in the final statement.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton advocated a meeting of Western and regional
leaders in the Balkans in the next few months and said he would
attend. Such a meeting, unprecedented since Yugoslavia began to
unravel in violence in 1991, would symbolize a commitment to draw
the Balkans into the West and highlight Milosevic's isolation,
Western officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president got agreement from the leaders that there should
be a Balkan conference, in the Balkans, sometime in the
not-too-distant future,'' National Security Adviser Sandy Berger
said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Boris Yeltsin, looking puffy and uncertain on
his feet, joined the other leaders Sunday for the concluding hours
of the summit meeting and then talked for an hour with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In a determined effort to cast the encounter with Yeltsin in the
most positive terms Western leaders, including Clinton, avoided any
reference to contentious issues such as what sort of aid _ if any _
should be given to Serbia and what sort of orders should be sent to
the Russian troops who raced to the airport in Pristina, capital of
Kosovo, earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, there were no visible disagreements and the meeting
of the leaders of the United States, Britain, Germany, France,
Canada, Italy, Japan and Russia ended about an hour earlier than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   A final communique stated their support for a number of
important causes, including debt relief, lifelong education, more
employment, a balance between social security and greater personal
initiative, democracy in Nigeria and peace in the Middle East. But
the main thrust of the discussions was on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The positive, sometimes patently relieved tone of the meeting
seemed to reflect a growing conviction that the ethnic wars in the
region that have left more than 200,000 people dead and forced
millions of people from their homes may at last have exhausted
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The final statement called for ``the creation of a democratic,
multiethnic Kosovo.'' It added: ``The return of refugees and
displaced persons to their homes and the assurance of security for
all persons including Serb and all other minorities in Kosovo will
be high priorities of the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Serbs, afraid of reprisals from returning Kosovo Albanians,
have fled since the 11-week &UR;  &LR; war ended. The Serbian government is
now urging them to go back, and several hundred reportedly did so
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The statement said the eight countries would ``fully cooperate
with the work of the International Criminal Tribunal for the former
Yugoslavia,'' which indicted Milosevic last month. But it made no
reference to the acts of Serbian forces in Kosovo during the war.
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said of Serbia that,
``Reconstruction aid, re-establishment of economic structures and
re-incorporation into Europe need democratization and that is not
possible with Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   But because of disagreements with Russia, which wants Serbia to
receive broad assistance, the leaders' statement contained no
details of how the billions of dollars of planned aid should be
distributed through the war-ravaged region.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, the leaders of the richer nations, the Group of
Seven, but not Russia, agreed that only basic emergency assistance
_ food, shelter and medicine _ should be given to Serbia while
Milosevic remains in power. Britain expressed the view that even
this kind of aid was excessive and unjustifiable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe people would understand if we put money into
an undemocratic Serbia under Milosevic,'' British Prime Minister
Tony Blair said. ``Nobody can shut their eyes to the fact that
thousands were butchered with unforgivable barbarism in Kosovo, and
we cannot start giving money to those that perpetrated these
barbarities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plea to the people of Serbia is that you can be part of a
prosperous Balkan future, but first embrace values of democracy and
civilization that are incompatible with having an indicted war
criminal at the head of your country,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Germany, which earlier this month drew up a so-called
``Stability Pact'' involving the establishment of ``democratic
principles and values'' and ``vibrant market economies'' throughout
the region to aid the Balkans countries harmed by the war, said it
had agreed to Clinton's request that it organize the Balkan summit
conference.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that tens of billions of dollars will be needed
for the West's new plans for Balkan reconstruction and economic
reform, and the leaders said Sunday that the World Bank and the
European Commission would coordinate efforts to raise money. An
initial conference on emergency aid will be held in July.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Steiner, the chief diplomatic adviser to Schroeder, said
that money would be used as a political weapon to isolate
Milosevic. Aid would be pointedly channeled to Kosovo, Montenegro
and even perhaps areas of Serbia run or controlled by opposition
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there is a danger that some of this may seep to
Belgrade, but that should not stop us targeting the areas we want
to help, and so illustrating that democracy pays,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Kosovo and the republic of Montenegro are part of what is
left of Yugoslavia, but Western leaders are clearly determined to
draw a distinction between these parts of the federation and
Belgrade, however difficult this may be.
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac said all the countries of the
Balkans could now aspire to membership in the European Union, but
added that the 15-nation bloc ``is not prepared to import conflict
into its midst.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The countries in the area should take an example from Romania,
which wants to join the European Union and has therefore resolved
its problems with its ethnic Hungarian minority,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Milosevic's future, Chirac added: ``Serb forces in
Kosovo probably obeyed orders and certainly responded to instincts
that were inadmissible and intolerable. The Serbian people should
now draw the appropriate political conclusions, and my own view is
the sooner they do this, the better for everyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
