<DOCNO> NYT19990620.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-KOSOVO-WITHDRAW-0     06-20 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-KOSOVO-WITHDRAW-0621 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As Last Serbian Troops Withdraw Kosovo Town of Shame Appears
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAJKOVAC, Yugoslavia As the last Serbian Army troops pulled out
</P>
<P>
   of Kosovo on Sunday, they left behind a town of shame where more
than 8,254
</P>
<P>
   Kosovar Albanian refugees were herded at gunpoint and packed
into private
</P>
<P>
   houses with little more than bread and water for two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have enough to eat, but at least we survived,'' said
Fehmi
</P>
<P>
   Tahiri, 33, who leaving Sajkovac on Sunday, pushing all of his
possessions
</P>
<P>
   on a wheel barrow. The tall, gaunt farmer said he had dropped
from 165
</P>
<P>
   pounds to 143 pounds on a diet of bread and some occasional
soup. And he
</P>
<P>
   had his tractor stolen.
</P>
<P>
   On his way home, he passed the town's cemetery that bulged with
51
</P>
<P>
   freshly dug graves. Ten of the mounds were so stubby that they
appeared to
</P>
<P>
   be a burial ground for small children.
</P>
<P>
   Sobbing softly beside one three-day-old mound of earth was a
young mother.
</P>
<P>
   Abide Mulolli, 22, said her father was shot by Yugoslav soldiers
just
</P>
<P>
   hours before they abandoned the town and allowed the remaining
5,816
</P>
<P>
   refugees to go home. That was about three days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tried to sneak out to go and buy some food and medicine for
the
</P>
<P>
   children,'' she said. ``The British peacekeepers brought us his
body when
</P>
<P>
   they arrived on the same day the Yugoslavs left.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Serb campaign of ethnic cleansing struck northern
Kosovo in
</P>
<P>
   late April, dozens of members of the extended Mulolli clan were
driven from
</P>
<P>
   Sajkovac to join a refugee stream that spent two weeks being
herded from
</P>
<P>
   town to town, somehow never being allowed to flee into exile in
Albania or
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Then in early May, the Serbian police directed the Mulollis and
perhaps
</P>
<P>
   50,000 other refugees back north toward the Serbian border.
Abide Mulolli
</P>
<P>
   and her parents were allowed to return home -- so they could
turn their
</P>
<P>
   little courtyard into an involuntary refugee camp for 86 people.
</P>
<P>
   Every Sajkovac refugee even two-year-olds was assigned a number
and
</P>
<P>
   registration certificate that delineated how far each one could
travel. In
</P>
<P>
   many cases, refugees were only authorized to move around inside
their own
</P>
<P>
   house or walled compound. A few others were allowed to move
about the town.
</P>
<P>
   One refugee, a 38-year-old builder named Isup Kurtolli, took it
on
</P>
<P>
   himself to organize a house-to-house census of refugee families.
From the
</P>
<P>
   handwritten names in his green notebooks the size of the refugee
population
</P>
<P>
   in Sajkovac -- which is about 15 miles northest of Pristinea,
the Kosovo capital -- can be counted.
</P>
<P>
   On the scale of all the atrocities inflicted on the Kosovars
this year,
</P>
<P>
   the indignities suffered here are scarcely the worst. There was
no
</P>
<P>
   systematic torture in Sajkovac, no known gang rapes. Fifty-one
people died,
</P>
<P>
   some of hunger and others from scattered episodes of police or
Army
</P>
<P>
   shootings. But there were no known mass executions.
</P>
<P>
   All that happened to those concentrated by the Serbs in Sajkovac
is
</P>
<P>
   that they were forced to live 30 or 40 people to a room for two
months.
</P>
<P>
   And to be so short of nutrition that they lost 20 to 40 pounds
each. To
</P>
<P>
   stay alive, many were forced to buy bread flour from Serbian
troops at five
</P>
<P>
   times the standard price.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 86 people in our home,'' said Abide Mulolli.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took in 163 people -- 11 in my family and 152 refugees we'd
never
</P>
<P>
   seen before,'' said her uncle Nazmi Mulolli, 60.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 79 people sleeping in two rooms,'' said another
relative,
</P>
<P>
   Ramadan Mulolli. ``We spent almost all the time indoors because
there was a
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav Army post on the hill that would shoot at us if we came
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   He said nobody in the village ever knew for sure why they were
being
</P>
<P>
   held. ``Maybe they wanted to use us as human shields,'' he
speculated.
</P>
<P>
   With new revelations of mass graves and atrocities coming almost
daily,
</P>
<P>
   and with people like the hostages of Sajkovac consumed with
efforts to
</P>
<P>
   reassemble their lives, there was little inclination to
celebrate the final
</P>
<P>
   departure Sunday of Serbian military and police forces.
</P>
<P>
   They left quietly, most of them well ahead of the Sunday night
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Near the Serbian border only two dusky green military trucks
filled
</P>
<P>
   with soldiers were seen zipping up the road in mid afternoon. A
lone jeep
</P>
<P>
   had been abandoned in the middle of main north-south road,
facing the wrong
</P>
<P>
   way to exit Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the withdrawal ended a decade of Belgrade's dominance and
</P>
<P>
   repression in Serbia's Connecticut-sized province, a decade that
</P>
<P>
   culminated in the horrors still being uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovar Albanians in the southern and middle sectors of the
province
</P>
<P>
   happily marked the withdrawal of troops from their areas earlier
in the
</P>
<P>
   week. The final withdrawal of Serb forces came from the north of
Kosovo,
</P>
<P>
   where most of the inhabitants are Serbian rather than ethnic
Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   The northern population, being predominantly Serbian and sitting
so
</P>
<P>
   close to safety at the border with Serbia, seemed to care little
about the
</P>
<P>
   troop withdrawal. Nor did they have disparaging remarks about
the
</P>
<P>
   international peacekeeping units spearheaded by NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   Most are farmers who spent this sunny, hot Sunday as other days,
in
</P>
<P>
   backbreaking field labor. Now is hay harvesting time, and
families were out
</P>
<P>
   in force swinging arced scythes and making haystacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The troops left yesterday. For now there are no problems,''
said Srecko
</P>
<P>
   Radosavlevic, 26, who was standing by the side of the road
awaiting a ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do worry about the Kosovo Liberation Army.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he said he could not understand why so many Serbs living in
Kosovo
</P>
<P>
   gave in to ``momentary panic'' and fled. They were
</P>
<P>
   still leaving Sunday, not in a steady stream but in occasional
cars or
</P>
<P>
   horse-drawn carts piled high with family furniture and clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
