<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2789 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLLUTION-SCIENCE-COX     06-20 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLUTION-SCIENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. labs take the first step in pollution prevention _ research
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C. _ Inside an 8-by-4-foot chamber
with stainless steel walls and glass windows, volunteers work out
on an exercise bike while researchers carefully pipe ozone gas into
the room from air tanks outside.
</P>
<P>
   After the volunteers emerge from the chamber, researchers ask
them a battery of medical-related questions or conduct medical
exams, looking for signs or symptoms of health changes.
</P>
<P>
   To the casual observer, the experiments in this obscure lab near
Raleigh may seem little more than an academic pursuit. But, in
fact, this is ground zero in the nation's war on air pollution.
Here, researchers are working to find out how exposure to the
noxious gas _ at levels typically found in metro Atlanta and other
urban areas during the summer _ affects people in the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   And what researchers learn here in the blips and bits of data
that emerge from the tests reaches far and wide, driving
environmental regulations in Atlanta and other major metropolitan
areas.
</P>
<P>
   The laboratory and several others like it are part of the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency's Human Studies Facility on the
University of North Carolina campus in Chapel Hill. It is one of
several EPA laboratories and centers near Raleigh where scientists
conduct experiments and pore over scientific studies to determine
the standards to protect Americans against dangerous air
pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working here to make people healthy and reduce their
risks of dying before their time,'' says Dr. John Vandenberg,
assistant director of the EPA's National Health and Environmental
Effects Research Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Under the mandates of the landmark 1970 Clean Air Act, the EPA
must establish maximum acceptable pollution levels for the nation
for six key pollutants _ ozone, nitrogen oxides, carbon monoxide,
particulate matter, lead and sulfur dioxide.
</P>
<P>
   The law also requires that new scientific research on each of
those pollutants be regularly reviewed and a scientific analysis
issued at least every five years. If the new analyses indicate that
an air pollution standard is not sufficiently protecting human
health, the EPA administrator may be advised to tighten up the
standard.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Center for Environmental Assessment in Research
Triangle Park, air quality experts continually examine new
scientific information from laboratories and institutions all over
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Many studies are conducted by the EPA itself at its Human
Studies Facility. The research includes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Animal studies, which most often involve rats and mice and
sometimes dogs that act as substitutes for humans. The animals can
be exposed to doses of air pollutants many times higher than the
ranges commonly found in American cities to determine adverse
health effects.
</P>
<P>
   _ In vitro studies, which involve cells or small samples of
tissue that have been removed from humans or animals and then
exposed to pollutants to determine what damage may occur.
</P>
<P>
   _ Epidemiological studies, in which groups of people or entire
communities may be followed over a period of time to determine if
there are higher-than-usual sickness and death rates and if there
is a common source of a problem. Air in the community may be
monitored to see if health problems emerge on days when pollutant
levels are high. Hospital admissions and emergency room visits also
may be tracked over time to see if patterns emerge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Controlled human studies, in which volunteers with a variety
of backgrounds and characteristics _ such as age, sex, height,
weight, physical condition, the presence of illnesses such as
asthma and emphysema _ are placed in the testing chambers or other
controlled environments and exposed to pollutants for precisely
timed periods.
</P>
<P>
   In the Human Testing Facility, volunteers exposed to ozone in
the testing chambers may be surveyed about symptoms _ shortness of
breath, coughing, tiredness. In some cases, researchers may insert
scopes equipped with tiny cameras into their bronchial tubes to see
possible effects from the ozone, such as inflammation. Sometimes
the scopes are used to scrape cells from the lining of the
bronchial tubes to examine under the microscope.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason EPA does its own research is because we can respond
more quickly to regulatory concerns'' than outside institutions
can, says Dr. Bill McDonnell, medical officer for the clinical
research branch of the Human Studies Division.
</P>
<P>
   Under the provisions of the Clean Air Act, EPA must analyze all
of the scientific information for a particular pollutant _ from
EPA's own laboratories and from institutions around the world _ and
summarize it in a ``criteria document,'' which is often thicker
than a phone book. The document is scrutinized by outside experts,
and from that information EPA develops a ``staff paper'' that
becomes the scientific foundation for air quality laws.
</P>
<P>
   In the staff paper, EPA indicates levels of a pollutant
acceptably safe for human health, taking into account especially
sensitive groups _ such as those with asthma _ and also
incorporating a margin of safety which considers the possible but
unproven effects of the pollutant. That paper also is reviewed by
outside experts. From there, the staff recommendations move to the
White House for review and finally to the EPA administrator, who
publishes it in the Federal Register. After that, the proposed new
standard undergoes public hearings and other scrutiny before
becoming law.
</P>
<P>
   State and local governments, in turn, are responsible for
devising so-called state implementation plans spelling out how they
plan to meet the new standards by certain dates that may vary
according to the extent and nature of the problem. Georgia's new
SIP unveiled this month, for instance, will require vehicle
inspections every year, instead of every other year, controls on
existing and proposed new industries, cleaner-burning gas in 69
North Georgia counties and much cleaner power plants.
</P>
<P>
   The process can take years. Last year, it culminated in a
tighter nationwide ozone standard _ a limit of 80 parts per billion
of ozone per cubic meter of air averaged over eight hours. EPA's
scientists had determined that the new standard, which improves on
the previous 120 ppb exposure limit averaged over a one-hour
period, is necessary to protect people _ especially children _ who
are exposed to ozone several hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Implementation of the new standard, however, was blocked last
month by three federal judges ruling in a lawsuit brought by
trucking organizations and other industry groups. The judges did
not question the science in developing the ozone standard, but
ruled that Congress did not have the authority to delegate the
rule-making to the EPA. The agency plans to appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, EPA is enforcing its old standard in effect since
1979. State environmental officials must submit its detailed plan
by October on how the region will meet the standard by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
