<DOCNO> NYT19990620.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2790 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCKMAN-COX     06-20 2294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rock man won't budge
 &HT;    (Photos available.)
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALL GROUND, Ga. _ Drive through this North Georgia town most
any day and you'll probably see him. A man sitting in a parked red
pickup truck outside one of the nine buildings that he has filled
with a massive collection of stones, rocks, gems and minerals.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Robertson, 75, watches people stroll past the hardware
store and post office before they try to open a locked door to one
of his shops. The visitors often squint and cup their hands to
their eyes, peering through big glass windows at jade necklaces,
bracelets and earrings, smooth green rocks shaped like eggs and
bookends of shiny gray stone.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson owns so many rocks that word of his collection
attracts tourists and collectors from all over Georgia, Alabama and
Tennessee. They come each weekend to downtown Ball Ground, about 50
miles north of Atlanta, to see the famous rock shops. They often
leave perplexed and frustrated, however, because Robertson rarely
unlocks his stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones I talk to are the ones who come in City Hall and say,
`How do we get in those rock shops?' '' said Mayor Rick Roberts.
``We have to tell them, `Look for the red pickup.' ''
</P>
<P>
   City leaders cringe at the Rock Man's reluctance to cater to the
stream of tourists and rock collectors. That stream, after all,
could pump big bucks into the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Roberts and other civic leaders have watched as growth has
enriched and revitalized many communities around metro Atlanta, and
they want Ball Ground to have a piece of the action. They dream of
a picturesque Ball Ground where people from the big city and its
suburbs visit antique stores, see the rock shops and eat in
sidewalk cafes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rock Man stands between them and their vision.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Rock Man owns about half of the buildings
downtown. Roberts' dream of a downtown revival is being held up by
a man who says he just wants to be left alone with his rocks.
</P>
<P>
   People of the town like Nelle Hefner, a 70-year-old antiques
dealer, said the Rock Man has too much power.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has always been good to me. I have no personal bone to
pick,'' Hefner said. ``It's just that I'm sorry that any one person
can have so much control over a town.''
</P>
<P>
   Land, rocks his obsession
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't know it to look at him, but the Rock Man is very
rich.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't drive fancy cars or sail great big yachts, doesn't
jet off to the Caribbean or winter in the south of France. He lives
in a modest ranch-style house on a hill at the edge of downtown,
wears a baseball cap that says ``ROCKMAN'' and eats burgers from
the Checkers fast-food restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   He says he is worth $62 million, but he also says he was friends
with Presidents John F. Kennedy and Herbert Hoover. Over the years,
he has sold and repaired cars, cut hair and timber and driven taxis
and school buses.
</P>
<P>
   He made his fortune, though, buying and selling land.
</P>
<P>
   The Rock Man has bought and sold so much property in Cherokee
County that courthouse records of the transactions fill 367 pages
in 108 deed books. His real estate career began in 1948, when, at
age 24, he paid $800 for two tracts of land that didn't even total
an acre. He has gobbled up land, sold timber rights and unloaded
property at a healthy profit nearly every year since.
</P>
<P>
   Tax records in Cherokee, Gordon and Pickens counties show that
he now has 2,200 acres worth $5.9 million, although he has
transferred ownership of some of that land to his two grown
daughters. His holdings in Cherokee County, where he has lived
since he was a boy, include 990 acres worth $4 million. Dealing in
land has been an obsession, but it hardly compares to Robertson's
fixation with rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Step inside his shops and you see it at once.
</P>
<P>
   On a wall just inside the front door of one building, Robertson
has hung a framed box of arrowheads near strands of green beads
dangling from a wooden post. Slabs of pink and white marble lean
against a wall. Pale yellow rocks fill aluminum washtubs. In
another room, 98 boxes of fuel pumps for 1948 Plymouths and 1951
Studebakers gather dust. Baseball gloves, headlights and scissors
hang from hundreds of nails in the ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   But rocks are everywhere you turn.
</P>
<P>
   As Robertson walked through his stores he reeled off the names
of those rocks like a teacher recalling students who graduated
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Agate. Melilite. Staurolite crystals.
</P>
<P>
   The roll call ended when Robertson spied an egg-shaped rock on
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a break-in,'' he announced.
</P>
<P>
   Did someone climb in through the roof? Smash a window in the
side of the building?
</P>
<P>
   The Rock Man investigated for 15 minutes before concluding that
a squirrel had burrowed through the roof and mistaken the egg for a
nut. Then he paused to refine his deduction.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, he said, it was a wharf rat.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson knows people say he's strange, but he said that
doesn't bother him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're strange because you don't know the names of
gems and minerals,'' he said. ``That's strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Hefner, the antiques dealer, said Robertson's ability to amass
millions of dollars buying and selling land proves that he is more
than a one-dimensional and lonely man who whiles away his days in a
red pickup truck. Even so, Robertson struck her as odd when they
met decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was peculiar even then,'' she said as wind chimes tinkled
and a train whistled in the distance. ``He didn't have a great deal
to do with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Anger at city officials
</P>
<P>
   Robertson acknowledged that he has few friends but said he does
not get lonely. Much of his energy is focused on his anger at city
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The City Hall down there is really a bunch of Mafia,'' he
said. ``If they thought they could get away with it, they'd shoot
me dead in the street.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials characterize their relationship with Robertson in
less vitriolic terms. Roberts said he and members of the City
Council have tried to maintain friendly relations with the Rock
Man. Last year, they negotiated a deal to assemble a group of
investors who would buy Robertson's downtown properties for $2
million.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was for the city to keep ownership of one or two of the
buildings and run a small museum. Businessmen would decide what to
do with the others. Perhaps an entrepreneur would have maintained
the rock shops and marketed them to the legions of rock collectors
and tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those rock shops are drawing cards,'' the mayor said. ``They
could be such a plus for the city.''
</P>
<P>
   When Robertson backed out at the last minute, he dealt another
blow to their hopes for downtown Ball Ground.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1980, the population of Cherokee County has grown by 145
percent, from 52,000 to 127,000. Newcomers have flooded into
sprawling subdivisions with names like Towne Lake and BridgeMill.
Dry-cleaning businesses, convenience stores and bagel shops have
sprung up where once were miles of unbroken forest. The growth has
transformed the southern part of the county from sleepy countryside
to bustling suburb, but Ball Ground and other communities in north
Cherokee remain largely rural and undeveloped.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,300 people who live in Ball Ground still drive 25 minutes
to the nearest grocery store. Downtown consists of a post office,
pharmacy, hardware store and two restaurants on a strip that is
two-tenths of a mile long. In the last few years, a cafe, travel
agency and a doctor's office have opened, but a pizza restaurant
and a sandwich shop have folded.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said he expects a wave of construction to crash on Ball
Ground after 2001, when he expects the city to complete installing
a sewer system. Developers already have built a few subdivisions
near the city, and Roberts said he expects some commercial
development along an exit from nearby Interstate 575.
</P>
<P>
   `It don't need to grow'
</P>
<P>
   Roberts welcomes development but has a vision for the future
very much colored by Ball Ground's past. His great-grandfather,
Alfred Webb Roberts, opened a general store shortly after the city
incorporated in 1883. Alfred W. Roberts also founded a
marble-finishing company that made tombstones and dominated the
city's economy from 1898 to 1973.
</P>
<P>
   When Roberts was growing up, the city had five grocery stores, a
furniture store and a dress shop. There was even a Ford dealership
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a trading center for the surrounding area,'' he said.
``It was hustling and bustling.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's a small town even by small-town standards.
</P>
<P>
   A community bulletin board offers residents news of local
goings-on. Homemade signs advertise used campers, refrigerators and
motorcycles for sale. One leaflet promises ``Salvation Plain and
Simple.'' Another asks: ``Do You Need A Pet Sitter?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a place where locals joke that you can dial the wrong phone
number and still know the person who answers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rock Man wants it to stay that way. He challenges the
assumption that growth will benefit the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It don't need to grow. You can't get across the street here.
You can't get in here to park,'' he said. ``I'd rather have it the
way it used to be. It's going to look just like Fulton and Cobb
counties.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson fears that development will bring to Ball Ground a
crush of such things as pay-at-the-pump gasoline stations and
brightly lit discount stores selling everything from auto parts to
yogurt. He prefers the landscape of lush pastures where hawks soar
above grazing cows _ a landscape that survives in much of northern
Cherokee County.
</P>
<P>
   On a driving tour of land he owns west of Ball Ground, Robertson
pointed toward a row of red chicken houses and gentle green hills
undulating for half a mile to a line of trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to save what I like in life,'' he said. ``See, I get a
thrill looking at that. See across yonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Lots of older residents agree that Ball Ground does not need to
grow, but others whose livelihood is tied to the city's economy see
The Rock Man as an obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of businesspeople that would like to see him
do something with downtown,'' said Dale Coker, who opened the Ball
Ground Pharmacy on Main Street six years ago. ``They'd like him to
sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories about the Rock Man have made him a local legend.
</P>
<P>
   People still talk about the time in 1994 when Robertson paid
$2.9 million in unpaid income taxes from 1987-'91. Federal agents
with rifles and bulletproof vests came to his rock shops in an
armored car to collect the money.
</P>
<P>
   He paid most of his tab in hundred-dollar bills.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, whose wife worked at a bank then, said the Rock Man
gave the agents $80,000 in dimes and quarters and nickels and
pennies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stayed there until 8 o'clock rolling coins,'' the mayor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other people remember the nights when he dressed in white to go
dancing at a country music nightclub in Cobb County.
</P>
<P>
   ``The announcer would get on the microphone and say `Ladies and
gentlemen, Oscar Robertson has arrived!' '' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson doesn't dwell on those days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't dance anymore. That was years ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   City Hall's landlord?
</P>
<P>
   Old-timers also whisper about the time in 1967 that
investigators charged Robertson with fondling a young girl. He
pleaded no contest and was ordered in May 1969 to spend seven years
on probation and receive medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Three doctors said then that he had a history of mental illness.
One found him to be ``suffering from insanity, which manifested
itself by strong emotional disturbances and peculiar behavior.''
Another doctor said Robertson had a ``definite tendency to project
and to blame others for his difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   In case anyone doubts the existence of such charges, the mayor
keeps folded in his wallet a piece of paper torn from a yellow
legal pad. On it is written the barest details of the criminal
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Case Number 1633,'' it says. ``Date of disposition '69.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson again generated lots of discussion in March, when he
filed a handwritten claim at the county courthouse contending that
he owns the land on which City Hall stands. He demanded $4 million
in ``back rent ... and damages'' and accused the mayor of setting
fire to one of his stores in 1988. Robertson taped photocopies of
the affidavit on the windows of his rock shops.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit has no legal value except as a record of
Robertson's version of the truth, and City Attorney Thomas A. Roach
Jr. said Robertson's claims are false. The city has owned City Hall
since 1903, he said, and the mayor is the one who dialed 911 when
he saw flames at the rear of one of Robertson's stores in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel sorry for him. He thinks these things are true,''
Roach said. ``Everyone appreciates the fact that he is one to be
dealt with carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Several shopkeepers in downtown Ball Ground declined to talk
about the Rock Man for fear of his reaction. They may know that
Robertson has tangled in lawsuits with the former mayor of Canton,
the former chairman of the Cherokee Board of Commissioners and the
mayor's father, Roy Roberts Sr., a prominent banker and real-estate
developer who died on June 7.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Rock Man, the mayor remains upbeat about the
possibilities for downtown Ball Ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is permanent,'' he said. ``Things will change over
time.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, Robertson controls the future of this tiny
downtown from the front seat of his red pickup truck. You can see
him most weekdays near one of the rock shops that dominate Main
Street. Just sitting there. In the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
