<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2791 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FINALS21-COX     06-20 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FINALS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Video replay a nonfactor in Stars' win
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ There was no shortage of touchy-feely subplots,
the stuff of sports marketing nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Modano, the franchise fixture, who played with a crack in
his wrist, thanks to Novocaine, Vicodin and the determination some
doubted he had. Joe Nieuwendyk, who leaned on crutches with blown
out knees last year while his team fizzled in the playoffs, coming
back to tie an NHL record for game-winning goals. Ed Belfour, the
maligned goalie, who outplayed Dominik Hasek in a big game. Brett
Hull, the prima donna goal-scorer who changed teams, played through
the pain of tears in his knee and groin and scored the winning the
goals in two Stanley Cup games _ the title clincher in triple
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Dallas Stars embraced their first Stanley Cup at
1:31 a.m. Sunday after Hull's game-winner against Buffalo, the
NHL's potential golden moment mutated into commissioner Gary
Bettman's worst nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that we have been playing for two months (in the
playoffs) and somebody is sleeping,'' said Hasek, the Sabres'
goalie. ``When I saw the replay I was going to go back onto the
ice. But it was not going to do any good.''
</P>
<P>
   Video replay, which was expected to be voted out anyway for
goal-crease violations at today's Board of Governors meetings in
New York, surely received a death blow in Game 6 of the Stanley Cup
finals at Marine Midland Arena. Bettman's biggest concern about the
rule is that replay defuses spontaneous fan and player celebrations
after goals while the play is being reviewed in the press box.
There was no bigger goal or celebration than in the Stars' Cup
winner. When Hull converted a rebound past Hasek 14:51 into the
third overtime, ending the second-longest game in finals history,
his skate was clearly in the goal-crease, a violation of league
rules. But when Hull slid the puck past Hasek, the Stars poured
onto the ice in celebration, referees and linesmen hugged each
other in exhaustion . . . and NHL officials went into spin control.
</P>
<P>
   As Sabres coach Lindy Ruff fumed and yelled from the bench for a
video review, the oldest trophy in North America was brought onto
the ice and presented to the Stars by Bettman. Later, Bettman
declined to comment on the goal, sending director of officials
Bryan Lewis to speak, and even refused to speak to Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted was a review, but once you've got 200 people on
the ice, they're not going to review it,'' Ruff said. ``I mean,
we've gone through this procedure all year and in the playoffs. I
wanted Bettman to answer the question: Why is that not reviewed?
And he just turned his back on me. He almost looked to me like he
knew this was a tainted goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The post-game scene was a circus. Instead of the focus being on
Hull and Belfour and the Stars' first Cup in 32 years, there was
Lewis, sweating out a media drilling. The official ruling, he said,
was that Hull had possession of the puck, took it into the crease
area (which is legal) and never fully lost possession before
shooting it past Hasek. Replays showed otherwise. The puck bounced
away from Hull and came outside the crease, at which point Hull
became required to do the same. But with a skate still in the
crease, he slapped the puck in.
</P>
<P>
   In the post-game, even Modano said, ``Yeah, Brett was in the
crease.'' Then he smiled and resumed talking about the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis maintained a review took place in the booth, even though
their seemed no indication of that on the ice. But when asked how
long the review took _ one minute? five minutes? _ he said, ``I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   He denied feeling pressure to allow the goal because of the
ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   Sabres center Michael Peca said, ``They didn't have the nerve to
call the goal back. What can you do? It's over. But it'll be a
story for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no guarantee the Sabres would have won and evened the
series if the goal was disallowed. Even then, they faced the task
of winning Game 7 back in Dallas. But the Stars' didn't care about
any of this. The Cup was theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to not having to practice for a while,''
said Hull, who disclosed his torn knee ligament after the game.
``It's been a long year. I realize now what the sacrifice is to win
a Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the warmer, fuzzier moments.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
