<HEADER>
A2792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN21-COX     06-20 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Dreams of a pool slowly take a dive
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ My 13-year-old granddaughter Betsy has a special knack
for winning new friends. ``I'm Betsy Vance,'' she says, ``I have a
three-legged dog.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That will get you friends!'' I gasped.
</P>
<P>
   She has many friends and she seemed to think Winnie, the big,
black three-legged, is the inducement.
</P>
<P>
   So I was prone to drop the subject until she added: ``I believe
it would be better if I could say, `I'm Betsy Vance. I have a
three-legged dog and a swimming pool.'''
</P>
<P>
   She can't say that she has a swimming pool, but none of us
doubts its efficacy as a friend-getter. There are days when we all
look out across the weedy overgrown yard and dream of a pure placid
sheet of water.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy has friends who have swimming pools. They seem to go with
expensive houses in the subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
   Before our nearest subdivision was completed, our dog Kazan
discovered the pool and used to take a morning dip there daily.
</P>
<P>
   He also brought home the neighbor's Wall Street Journal. My
husband, Jack, was glad to get it, but when Kazan started bringing
USA Today, he threatened to cancel his paper dog.
</P>
<P>
   But neighbors build fences around their pools and their
mailboxes are difficult to access for even a tall dog, so we no
longer freeload in their front yards. We simply dream.
</P>
<P>
   A swimming pool would be wonderful. Looking back, our family has
had the advantage of water to swim in for generations.
</P>
<P>
   I grew up with a wonderful big millpond where the water was
clear and cold, and I had a diving board and a little pirogue,
where I could float and drowse when I grew tired from swimming.
</P>
<P>
   When the children were babies, we lived near Pensacola Beach,
Fla., and a bridge pass was all it took to get us to the blue water
and white sand.
</P>
<P>
   When we moved to Atlanta, the Woman's Club pool was less than a
block away and Piedmont swimming pool was in easy walking distance.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I walked my brood up there daily for two weeks to take
the Red Cross swimming lessons. (I can smell the sweat and the
suntan oil even today.)
</P>
<P>
   When we moved to Sweet Apple, we had Jack's lake, a small but
perfect little body of water to which we raced at the end of every
summer day. We even hauled in white sand to make a smidgen beach
there.
</P>
<P>
   Now the road to the lake has been obliterated. I believe that is
also true of the lake. At least, the children and I couldn't find
it the last time we looked.
</P>
<P>
   Friends' pools are a saving grace. Our doctor, Bill Crowe, made
us welcome at his stylish pool on Randall Mill Road, until he asked
Jack's advice about getting rid of a mammoth hornet's nest in a
tree in his back yard.
</P>
<P>
   Jack had a new chain saw and was super-confident about his
ability to use it. He insisted on cutting down the hornet-riddled
tree, which unfortunately fell smack in the swimming pool,
demolishing it.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, I remember Jack tried to discourage my dreams of
owning a swimming pool. Such a body of water, he remarked mildly,
was a lot of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy and her friends are young to be learning that lesson.
Maybe they'll stick with three-legged dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
