<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2801 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELAY-PROFILE-ART-895     06-20 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELAY-PROFILE-ART-895(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM DELAY SAYS HE'S CONFIDENT OF REACHING GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Tom DeLay swears it's only the force of his
personality that has everyone in Washington persuaded _ mistakenly,
of course _ that he's the guy running the House of Representatives
while Speaker Dennis Hastert sends out for sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just _ I'm aggressive, and I've been aggressive all my
life,'' says DeLay, the majority whip, not unhappily. And the
speaker, he says, is just understated. Hastert doesn't think it's
his job to talk to the press, DeLay notes, and will never suit
those who were expecting Newt Gingrich, the Sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denny has a completely different style _ thank God,'' says
DeLay, laughing, maybe a little giddy that he can say these things
now. ``Newt had to drive everything and control everything and
didn't believe in the committee system at all; Denny's just the
opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Which sounds awfully close to the point made by those who see
DeLay as the real power.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's big, brawling, guns-and-culture fight over what
combination of violent entertainment and the availability of
firearms is causing children to shoot children, it was DeLay who
dramatically took to the House floor to deliver a series of
elemental attacks on modern culture, indicting birth control, the
theory of evolution and day care. (His 27-year-old daughter and
campaign manager, he says, still talks about how awful it was
spending a summer in day care at age 5.)
</P>
<P>
   It was DeLay who got conservatives to go along with a strategy
hatched by a Democrat, Rep. John Dingell, a longtime ally of the
National Rifle Association, to water down a Senate measure
requiring background checks on customers at gun shows. After the
modest gun-control legislation promised by Hastert _ if only to rob
Democrats of a campaign issue _ was defeated on Friday, it was
DeLay who left the Capitol smiling.
</P>
<P>
   At least some of his reputation as a master manipulator seems to
stem from the fact that even when he loses, he projects a
confidence that says he knew what he was doing all along. At a news
conference following the final vote, he called the result ``pretty
sad.'' But he also put in, ``I've had a great time this week.''
</P>
<P>
   As he left the room, a reporter asked if things hadn't in fact
turned out pretty well for him. He had won on some of the culture
votes, passing, for example, a bill that gives schools federal
permission to post the Ten Commandments. And the Democrats had
killed gun control, which he didn't really want anyway, right? He
smiled and threw up his hands.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview afterward, he said that it wasn't quite so
simple. ``The Democrats think this is a great issue for them, and
I'll be living with this all summer.'' Still, he spoke of the week
as a whole as a ``great personal victory.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was Hastert who had come up with the idea of dividing
the legislation in two, one part focusing on culture and the other
on guns. And Hastert who had convinced him to vote for the
gun-control measure, only a few hours before the final vote, as the
only way of advancing the culture package.
</P>
<P>
   His own role? ``I was more driving it from a policy point of
view in advising Denny I thought it was important to make sure it
wasn't only guns'' being discussed. ``This was a culture problem
and we had to make that clear.'' In other words, he was in charge
of the bills that passed. In case anyone missed this point, he
spelled it out: ``Culture won, guns lost. I spent most of my time
trying to kill gun control.''
</P>
<P>
   (When asked about the part a fellow Texan, Dick Armey, the
majority leader, had played in the week's events, he had to think a
minute. ``He was more the manager, and made the trains run,'' he
said finally.)
</P>
<P>
   DeLay is nothing if not sure of himself and of what he believes.
For example, that gun control is scarier than guns, because ``the
government hopefully would never turn on the people, but it's human
nature for it to do that if you don't have the deterrent of
citizens bearing arms.''
</P>
<P>
   And when asked about the power of that certainty, he said it was
surely his greatest strength. ``I always wondered why Ronald Reagan
did so well. They say he was a great communicator, but all he did
was read, really. He hardly ever spoke without reading. But he
projected this certainty, and that translates into security, and
people want that in their leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   A conservative's conservative, he claims ``some weird
friendships'' with a few Democrats, like Dingell, with whom he
works out in the House gym every morning.
</P>
<P>
   He also professes to admire committed liberals and sees Rep.
Barney Frank of Massachusetts as a kindred spirit in the sense that
he ``knows from where he comes and fights for it.'' Doesn't he
provide Frank with some of his best material? DeLay laughed. ``And
vice versa. He plays in Texas just like I do in Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   Moderates, on the other hand, he doesn't understand. ``They have
a hard time with certainty.'' And Bill Clinton? How much time have
you got?
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, he was watching the president play golf in Bob
Hope's celebrity tournament, and became convinced that Clinton was
cheating. ``I play a lot of golf and I'm telling you, with his
swing he cannot play an 81 without cheating. You can tell a lot
about a person's character by the way they play golf. If they cheat
at golf, they'll cheat at anything.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   DeLay draws a straight line between Clinton's impeachment, which
might not have happened without DeLay's determination, and last
week's votes. ``Without that debate last year, I don't think some
of these culture amendments would have passed.''
</P>
<P>
   In a view that is not widely shared, he sees a lot of good
coming out of the Lewinsky scandal. ``Ever since the Monica story
broke there's been a lot of husbands telling the truth to their
wives and a lot of introspection and people re-evaluating who they
were.''
</P>
<P>
   But not Tom DeLay. Born in Laredo, Texas, in 1947, the second of
four children, he grew up mostly in Venezuela, where his father
worked in the oil business until he made enough money to move the
family back to Texas. ``It was wonderful for a kid _ jungles and
monkeys and burros and golf courses,'' he says, and with no TV,
``the only entertainment was to be a family.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about a recent New Yorker profile which said he is
estranged from much of his family, including his widowed mother and
a brother who has done jail time, he said, ``I'd rather not talk
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he did. ``My father was a wildcatter typecast straight
out of the movie `Giant,''' he said. ``He was a boisterous,
domineering alcoholic. We were not exactly an ideal family.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay sought considerably more order in his own life. He married
his high school sweetheart with whom he is today raising two foster
children, teen-agers who had been abused in previous homes. After
receiving a degree in biology from the University of Houston, he
went into the pest-control business and became, in his words, the
``best weasel killer in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling burdened by government bureaucracy, he ran for the state
Legislature, and served in Austin from 1978 until 1984. But it was
only after he arrived in Washington, in 1985, that he became the
man he is today, he says, motivated primarily by religious faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a real jerk when I got elected,'' he says. ``Me, me, me.
My job was my religion and I was mistreating my wife and
daughter.'' A video produced by James Dobson, called ``Where's
Daddy?'' he said, ``hit me like a 2-by-4'' and changed all that.
And it was then, he says, that he began ``the process that I now
see was preparing me for last year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990620.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2806 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SOAPS-DECLINE-2TAK     06-20 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SOAPS-DECLINE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES THE END OF `ANOTHER WORLD' SPELL DOOM FOR DAYTIME SOAPS? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They will gather Friday afternoon at Blondie's
Restaurant on Manhattan's West Side to reminisce about Cecile and
Peter's disastrous wedding, the time Lila gave birth in a stalled
elevator at the Lumina Ball, about Frankie's murder and when Vicky,
hovering between life and death, met Ryan in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Then at 2 p.m., they will tune to ``Another World'' for the last
time and say goodbye to Carl and Rachel, Joe and Paulina and Vicky
and Jake, and after 35 years and 8,891 episodes, one of
television's most venerable soap operas will be no more.
</P>
<P>
   If it seems like the end of an era for the fiercely loyal and
still-grieving fans of ``Another World,'' which will go out with a
final wedding and sundry surprises, it increasingly feels like
something close to that for America's soap operas.
</P>
<P>
   Buffeted by the entry of women into the workplace, the changing
routines for the ones at home and competition from real-life soap
operas ranging from Jerry Springer to l'Affaire Lewinsky, soap
opera audiences are plummeting. The changes, which have been
creeping up for more than a decade, are sending the industry into a
sense of gloom and providing an illustrative commentary on some of
the changes in American life and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The signs of distress are abundant. Estimates are that the shows
have lost a quarter of their audience over the last decade. Two of
the five weeklies that follow the soaps have closed down. No
successful new soap has been introduced over the last decade, and
shows increasingly are resorting to guest appearances by the likes
of Springer or increasingly outlandish gimmick plots to keep their
audiences. The so-called prime-time soaps that flourished in the
1980s are almost all gone, and rumors are rampant about which of
the remaining shows are most imperiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood ranges from concern to panic, depending where they
stand in the ratings,'' said Lynn Leahey, editor in chief of Soap
Opera Digest. ``The top shows are aware of the pattern, but they're
not losing sleep over it. The others are worrying about their shows
getting canceled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Another World,'' which was first broadcast on May 4, 1964, was
the top-rated soap opera during its heyday in the 1970s. It ranks
as NBC's longest-running daytime drama. During its first year, the
show, set in the fictional town of Bay City, Ill., set new
standards for its time by taking on topics like abortion and
illegitimate pregnancy. Fans, some of whom have united in a
last-ditch effort to save the show, have viewed it as a show based
on solid acting and socially attuned plots rather than mere
romantic plot gimmicks.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first soap to introduce celebrity guest stars like
Liberace, the first to expand to a one-hour format, and it was an
early nesting place for actors and actresses who later hit it big
elsewhere like Anne Heche, Morgan Freeman, Ray Liotta, Brad Pitt,
Faith Ford and Kelsey Grammer.
</P>
<P>
   But after it peaked in the 1970s, it had trouble regaining
momentum. Producers tried gimmicks, like flying the cast off at
great expense, to film at exotic locations. Producers and writers
came and went. Though the cast was constantly renewed, ``Another
World'' was less lucky than some of the other older soaps in having
some important actors in the cast die off, most notably Douglas
Watson, who played Mac Cory, the beloved publishing magnate who was
one of the show's dominant figures.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Lee, senior vice president for daytime programming at NBC,
said that ending the show was a painful decision but something had
to go to make room for a new show, ``Passions.'' The choice came
down to ``Another World'' or an even lower-rated show, ``Sunset
Beach,'' which, like ``Passions,'' is hoping to attract a younger,
more demographically desirable audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an emotional decision for everyone,'' she said. ``but
the show had not performed for the affiliates for the last decade.
It was like something that hung around and it wasn't growing,
wasn't moving and the affiliates kept saying, `Why are we still
carrying this program?' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Leahey of Soap Opera Digest said the show had improved
enormously over the last year since a new executive producer had
come on board, and it is a sign of desperation in the industry when
a franchise like ``Another World'' is simply dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations have been lowered, and justifiably so,'' said
Mary Alice Dwyer-Dobbin, head of production for Procter &AMP; Gamble
Productions, which once produced 13 soap operas and after Friday
will be down to two, ``As the World Turns,'' which has been on for
43 years, and ``Guiding Light,'' the oldest of them all which has
been on television for 47 years and began on radio 62 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The glory days are gone, because of choices in terms of
lifestyle and television viewing. We like to think there is room to
grow from where we are, but more than anything I think we need to
concentrate on maintaining the level we're at now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even for women not in the workplace, an hour of soap-opera
viewing is often not an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a working mom, but of people I know in my neighborhood,
many of the moms at home are never home,'' said Ms. Leahey.
``They're driving the kids to music lessons or soccer games. It's
very different from when I was young.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Not only does that reduce the potential audiences, but it breaks
the inter-generational chain that has renewed the audiences for
many soaps. For example, Elizabeth Walker is one of the organizers
of the luncheon Friday that is expected to draw about 50 fans of
``Another World.'' She said she began watching the show in 1975
when she was 13 with her mother, who had been watching from the
very first show.
</P>
<P>
   There are fewer mothers around to pass the baton in the same
way, she said, and she said that networks are making a mistake if
they think they can invent new soaps willy-nilly and jettison old
ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have slapped all their long-time fans in the face,'' she
said. ``I know I'm not going to watch `Passions,' and I know a lot
of people feel the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even some actors on soaps say the overheated melodramas of the
soaps are having trouble competing with the overheated melodramas
of the news _ that the travails of Vicky and Jake and Luke and
Laura have a hard time being more dramatic than the travails of
Bill and Monica or O.J. and Nicole. The steepest ratings decline in
the soap world came when the country was fixated on live coverage
of the O.J. Simpson trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society's changed,'' said Tom Eplin, one of the stars of
``Another World,'' who is one of four characters who will go over
to ``As the World Turns.'' (His character, Jake, and Vicky will
help Tom Hughes as he tries to prove Emily Stewart innocent of
murder and Lila and Cass will stop in Oakdale on the way to Hawaii
for their honeymoon and be drawn into Eddie Silva's search for
information abut his natural father.)
</P>
<P>
   ``During JFK's term, we didn't know as much about him as we do
now, or about most politicians,'' Eplin continued. ``It dulls the
sword of drama a little bit. We see so much now, that the
relationship of two people on television seems a lot less
tantalizing. What we see in real life exceeds the drama of our
shows.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
