<HEADER>
A2809 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILSON-MUSIC-REVIEW-N     06-20 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILSON-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RECLUSIVE ROCK LEGEND RETURNS, NOSTALGIC AND UNBOWED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JON PARELES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Oooh-whoo.'' ``Wah-do-day.'' ``Diddit-dit-dum-de-doo-wah.''
``Bow-bow-bow-b-b-b-bow.'' Those syllables meant a lot to Brian
Wilson when he was composing songs for the Beach Boys. They were
the sound of vocal harmonies, companionship turned into discipline
and beauty. Wilson used them to make complex chords metamorphose
behind simple love songs or confessions of unbearable loneliness.
With lapidary, compulsive craftsmanship, Wilson packed ideas into
his three-minute songs: harmonies, orchestral arrangements, song
forms that concealed improbable fantasias behind their hooks. His
songs were revived in all their elaborate restlessness when Wilson
appeared at the Beacon Theater on Friday night as part of his first
tour without the Beach Boys.
</P>
<P>
   Audience and musicians alike knew what a rare event they were
witnessing. Wilson became one of rock's most famously troubled
recluses in the 1960s, with drug and psychological problems that
persisted for decades. He stopped performing with the Beach Boys in
1964 while continuing to write and produce their songs. Although he
briefly rejoined the group on tour in 1976, his rare public
appearances since then showed a man with debilitating stage fright.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1998 Wilson released an album, ``Imagination'' (Giant),
that regained some of his old melodic grace. And though he looked
uneasy, rarely smiled and had lyrics on a teleprompter, at the
Beacon he made it through two 40-minute sets without faltering.
After ``I Get Around,'' he blurted, ``Yay for the audience!''
</P>
<P>
   Concerts by the current Beach Boys, led by Mike Love, are oldies
shows that run through the hits as exercises in nostalgia. But even
as his backup singers were doing the Swim, Wilson's performance was
a composer's showcase, mixing hits and collectors'-item
obscurities. Before Wilson came onstage, a 20-minute film was shown
that extolled his musicianship and only glimpsed his troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Rehearsal chatter from the 1960s led to the first few notes of
``The Little Girl I Once Knew,'' a single from 1965. (It was not a
hit, but a harbinger of experiments to come: a harmonically
intricate, tempo-shifting song that also included a couple of
four-second silences.) Then the band started the song onstage, as
if transporting the audience to Wilson's true home, the studio.
</P>
<P>
   It was rock as repertory, setting out to recreate Wilson's
studio creations down to their exact drum licks; the band, led by
Joe Thomas on keyboards, took liberties only in finishing songs
that had ended as fade-outs. The song selection favored Wilson's
extraordinary late-1960s work; ``Pet Sounds,'' Wilson's 1967
masterpiece, was represented with four songs and two instrumentals.
The band delighted in the inner workings of Wilson's music: the
way, for instance, that ``Wouldn't It Be Nice'' changes key right
after its introduction. To illuminate the pristine close harmonies
and hermetic purity of ``In My Room,'' Wilson and the many singers
onstage performed it with a lone guitar as accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In My Room'' was one of the first Beach Boys songs to reveal
the isolation and uncertainty that run through Wilson's most
cherished ballads. For all the cockiness in ``I Get Around'' and
``California Girls'' or the sheer elation of ``Good Vibrations,''
Wilson's songs repeatedly told the world how desperately he needed
love and reassurance: ``God Only Knows,'' ``Don't Worry Baby,''
``Caroline, No'' and even a 1998 song, ``Your Imagination,'' in
which the only happy moments are daydreams of the past. But from
his solitude came gorgeous melodies, rising above his steady,
imperturbable keyboard chords with tranquil desolation. The music
solved its technical challenges brilliantly; the sadness remained.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's original productions were so diverse that his band
sometimes needed to fill in with synthesizers. But with four
members of the Wondermints, a group of Wilson devotees, at its
core, the band also deployed the instruments of Wilson's studio
orchestras: French horn, vibraphone, timbales. While the concert's
emcee, Steve Dahl, faked playing a theremin on ``Good Vibrations,''
Probyn Gregory was playing a reproduction of a tannerin, a version
of the theremin with more reliable pitch that was used in the
original recording.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who turned 57 Sunday, is no longer the singer he was in
the 1960s. His high notes are gone. At the Beacon, his lower ones
scratched and sometimes went flat. His uptempo exuberance and the
yearning in his ballads have shifted toward an inscrutable tenacity
that was still touching in songs like ``God Only Knows.'' Around
him, while voices and instruments rebuilt his grand, fanciful,
intricate songs, the music sustained him and transcended his
frailties, just as he had surmounted so many private tribulations
to create it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
