<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NANOTECH-COMPUTERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NANOTECHNOLOGY _ GROWING COMPUTERS AN ATOM AT A TIME  &HT;     By DAVID EINSTEIN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Stan Williams knows good things come in small packages. In fact,
he's convinced that the future of the computer is just a few atoms
wide.
<P>
   Williams, a researcher at Hewlett-Packard, heads up a team that
is developing a new kind of computer memory using nanotechnology _
the art of manipulating material on a molecular scale.
</P>
<P>
   The memory, in the form of crisscrossing wires, will be just 100
nanometers across (a nanometer equals one-billionth of a meter, or
about the width of two atoms). It will hold 16 bits of data. That's
not much _ just enough to hold a couple of words. But if it works,
it could presage a quantum leap in the speed and power of all kinds
of computer chips, including microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nanotech should make it possible to build computers 1 billion
times as powerful as they are now,'' says Williams.
</P>
<P>
   That could translate into voice-activated supercomputers that
you wear on your wrist, unmanned space probes the size of a
grapefruit and home entertainment centers that make it hard to
distinguish reality from virtual reality.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' team _ as well as other research groups at places like
IBM, Cornell University and Rice University _ is probing the very
fabric of the universe. They're moving individual atoms around with
light beams called optical tweezers and laying the groundwork for a
new kind of computing based on molecular switches that take up much
less space than transistors and use far less power.
</P>
<P>
   Nanotech researchers are motivated to a large degree by the fact
that the technology used to make today's integrated circuits is
fated to hit a wall. If Moore's Law holds and chip companies
continue to double every 18 months the number of transistors they
can pack on a microchip, transistors will become so tiny in about
10 years that quantum forces _ which affect matter on the smallest
level _ will render them unstable.
</P>
<P>
   Also, manufacturing facilities will continue to become more
expensive, to the point that a full-on chip fabrication plant could
cost $50 billion by 2010. Not even Intel may have that kind of
money to spend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if engineering were available to go beyond 2010, there is
a real question of whether we could afford to build anything,''
says Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the beauty of nanotech is that instead of a fabrication
plant, chips could be made using chemicals as catalysts to coax
nanosize components to assemble themselves into circuits. In fact,
that technique, which sounds a lot like the way DNA works, is how
Williams' team intends to create its breakthrough memory component.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be real cheap,'' he says. ``It involves mixing up
chemicals in a beaker rather than building a huge fabrication
plant.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of defective parts that comes out of such a
manufacturing process is high, Williams admits. But so what?
They're so cheap to make that you can make more nanocircuits than
you need and simply route computing routines around the defective
ones.
</P>
<P>
   While people like Williams are working to create
nanoelectronics, a number of young companies have begun exploring
ways to use the technology in actual products, from personal
computers to ``smart'' fabrics that can replicate themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bringing nanoelectronics into computing is the whole reason
for our existence,'' said Robert Schmieder, founder and president
of NanoLogic, a small Walnut Creek company engaged in research into
mass production of devices such as molecular switches. ``We want to
bridge the gap between devices that are developed in laboratories
and the economics of producing them in the marketplace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of atomic-level computers isn't new. Nanotechnology
pioneer Richard Feynman, in a famous address 40 years ago at the
California Institute of Technology, laid out a theory for
manipulating atoms and suggested that the technology could be used
to build computers.
</P>
<P>
   Such computers _ far more powerful than conventional ones _
``could make judgments,'' said Feynman. ``They would have time to
calculate what is the best way to make the calculation they are
about to make. They could select the method of analysis which, from
their experience, is better than the one that we would give to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Feynman's vision, nanotech didn't really start to take
off until the late 1980s, when scientists at IBM invented the
Scanning Tunneling Microscope, which made it possible to capture
images of matter at the atomic level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that we'd taken a huge step forward in the ability to
control the structure of matter,'' said Donald Eigler, a physicist
at IBM's Almaden Research Laboratory in San Jose who helped perfect
the scanning microscope. ``And every time in history that we've
learned new ways to build things, something really unusual _ and
quite often something great _ has come out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eigler doesn't share Williams' unbounded vision of nanotech's
possibilities. ``I'm the last person to discourage someone from
dreaming what could be,'' he said, ``but if somebody tells you
about nanotech and really small widgets being computers, that's
fantasyland.''
</P>
<P>
   Eigler is confident, however, that ``the research being done now
will create knowledge that can be used in the future of the
computer industry. It will allow us to extend today's technologies
and create new ones.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
