<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GIVING A BIG PUSH TO `PUSH' TECHNOLOGY  &HT;     By JON SWARTZ 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Short takes on an alien sighting (sort of) and Net natterings
during a lazy summer week:
<P>
   PLEASE POLESE ME: Internet diva Kim Polese stopped by with a
progress report on Marimba Inc., the software company she
co-founded which went public last month despite sniping from the
press (guilty as charged).
</P>
<P>
   Given up for dead as another purveyor of ``push'' technology,
the Mountain View company now is worth $901.3 million, based on its
stock price of $39.63 per share. Sales tripled to $17.1 million
last year, from $5.6 million in 1997. Its Internet-management
software is used by more than 200 corporate customers, such as
Chrysler and Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. And it boasts the considerable
financial backing and guidance of John Doerr, the influential
venture capitalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remained focused, never got complacent and stuck with our
management team,'' Polese said. ``Plus, we didn't let the push
stigma hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   Push technology automatically delivered customized news and
information to consumers' desktop computers. But it didn't deliver
on its promise _ to the chagrin of investors and several doomed
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of force-feeding news and content to subscribers, as
high-tech flop PointCast did, Marimba opted to create a program to
manage Net services and deliver software updates within
corporations. Schwab, for instance, used Marimba's product to
develop a premium portal for heavy traders to ease transactions.
Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co., meanwhile, uses Marimba software to keep its
Web-based customer service operations running.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Net should be as easy as using a utility,'' Polese said.
``It should be as simple as turning on a faucet or flipping a
switch.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true CEO of a successful company.
</P>
<P>
   FIRMAGE SIGHTING: Joe Firmage's otherworldly views about
extraterrestrial intelligence earned him sensational headlines but
a pink slip from USWeb/CKS in January. Last week, he promoted a
more down-to-Earth venture _ with the financial backing of USWeb/
CKS.
</P>
<P>
   In a glitzy event at the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art,
Firmage introduced Intend Change, a consulting company for Internet
startups in need of expert advice on writing business plans and
schmoozing with venture capitalists. USWeb/ CKS, which Firmage
co-founded, is a major investor. The company also is expected to
announce a partnership with an executive recruiter this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our challenge is: How do you take a great idea and turbocharge
it into a sector leader?'' said USWeb/ CKS co-founder Toby Corey.
``We've coined a new category called venture construction.''
</P>
<P>
   Firmage and Corey are co-founders of Intend Change. The Santa
Clara company will handpick and tutor select Net hopefuls in
exchange for 10 percent of each company's equity. It already has
chosen InveSmart, a retirement-planning Web site in Pittsburgh;
e-commerce firm Electron Economy in Cupertino; and Infrastructure
Defense, a Washington, D.C., security consultant for cyberattacks.
</P>
<P>
   Some 700 dot com startups are created every quarter among the
10,000 business plans that are sent to venture capitalists
annually, according to industry experts.
</P>
<P>
   The otherwise pedestrian news drew a throng of journalists _ no
doubt intrigued by Firmage. The last time he made news was for
promoting his 600-page online treatise, ``The Truth''
(www.thewordistruth. org), which linked many of history's major
religious and technological events to ``visits'' from
extraterrestrials. He even recounted a close encounter of the third
kind in his Los Gatos home in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The quixotic Firmage still stands by his beliefs but has
softened the more off-the-wall comments.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ``Dateline,'' A&AMP;E Television Networks and Fox Family
Channel all plan special reports on Firmage this year.
</P>
<P>
   WEBLESS CEOs: The Net may be indispensable to the lives of geeks
and blue-collar types everywhere, but it drew a collective yawn
from 656 CEOs worldwide surveyed by market researcher The
Conference Board and Heidrick &AMP; Struggles, an executive headhunting
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Only 6 percent of grand poobahs at industrial manufacturers
consider the Web critical to their business; a paltry 15 percent of
all chief executives polled placed a high emphasis on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Just more than half of the high-tech CEOs questioned ranked the
Internet as a primary concern, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most CEOs are preoccupied with industry consolidation,
cost-cutting and retaining customers,'' said Melissa Berman, senior
vice president of research at The Conference Board in New York.
``If and when they can see the Internet as a clear path to answer
those problems, the survey numbers will gradually increase.''
</P>
<P>
   The report quotes CEOs from The Mutual Group, Merck &AMP; Co. and
Tellabs Operations Inc.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sth  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SCAM ALERT: AT&AMP;T WorldNet customers received disturbing e-mail
this month: A billing snafu apparently required them to resubmit
credit-card information within 48 hours or they risked losing
Internet access. Those who responded promptly with e-mail were
promised a rebate.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out the message was a ruse designed to wangle financial
data out of AT&AMP;T WorldNet's 1.6 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I thought `Oh, no,' '' said Cassandra
Mettling-Davis, an AT&AMP;T customer in San Francisco. ``Then, I became
suspicious. I called AT&AMP;T and the credit-card company, and they
said there was no problem. You can never be too cautious on the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The fake e-mail, titled ``Worldnet (sic) Billing Errors,'' is
the latest attempt by online hucksters to sucker personal
information out of cybersurfers. E-mail scams are among the most
common fraudulent acts online, according to the Federal Trade
Commission (www.ftc.gov).
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T WorldNet's fraud unit, which warned users of the faux
e-mail last week, is investigating the matter.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING RELIGION ONLINE: Take heart, exasperated eBay users.
Your prayers for reliable service may be answered.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican _ swear to God _ is considering the creation of a
patron saint of the Internet so that millions of cybersurfers can
pray for quicker service.
</P>
<P>
   St. Isidore, author of a 20-volume encyclopedia that is
considered the world's first database, is front-runner for the
mantle of digital divine intervention. Not bad for someone who died
1,400 years ago in Seville, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are patron saints of many things, so why not let the
Internet have one?'' Vatican spokesman Tom Hallwood said. ``It's a
good idea and might be able to help us all when we are about to
crash.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallwood, of course, is referring to the Catholic Church's
computer system _ not human foibles.
</P>
<P>
   The church's three computer servers _ which powered live
Webcasts of pope speeches and Vatican Radio _ are appropriately
named Raphael, Gabriel and Michael.
</P>
<P>
   SOMA DISPATCHES: A secretive Net startup nestled South of Market
is creating a buzz in high-tech circles.
</P>
<P>
   Desktop.com _ whose co-founder Larry Dreves started free e-mail
provider Four11/RocketMail _ has developed technology that lets
consumers create a personal computer-like desktop anywhere on the
Web. The mysterious project is scheduled to debut this summer.
</P>
<P>
   SITES OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Weekend warriors, take note. Limber up at www.sfsailing.com and
www.sportsmatchonline.com.
</P>
<P>
   After you've built up a sweat, feast your eyes on construction
of the city's newest playground, Pacific Bell Park, at
www.sfgiants.com /PACBELLPARK/LIVECAM /livecam.html.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Official Site of the International Society for the
Extermination of Jar Jar Binks means business at
www.jarjarmustdie.com. Jar Jar, beware.
</P>
</TEXT>
