<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2817 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHR     06-20 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DRUG FIRMS TRYING TO MAKE MEDICINE GO DOWN EASIER  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Drugmakers know that most patients shrink at the sight of needles
and shirk responsibility for taking pills on time.
<P>
   These two foibles have helped spawn the alternate drug delivery
industry. Top scientists in this field gathered last week in
Berkeley to talk about using inhalers instead of injections to
deliver insulin, and creating coated pills or skin patches for
timed release of drugs _ so we don't have to remember when it's
time for our medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron scientist Bret Shirley gave me a quick tutorial on the
differences between traditional drugs and biotech remedies _ and
why biotech firms have taken the lead in inventing new delivery
mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional drugs work just fine as pills (so long as we
remember to take them). That's because the active ingredient in
most drugs is a chemical compound so small that when the pill
dissolves in the stomach, the active ingredient slips through the
digestive machinery and enters the bloodstream _ which delivers the
drug to the site of the ailment.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech remedies are protein molecules hundreds of times larger
than the active ingredients in traditional drugs. ``They're
proteins just like we'd eat in a steak,'' Shirley said. So if
manufacturers tried to shove biotech pills down our throat, our
bodies would digest the remedy before it could travel to wherever
it was needed.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the only way to get remedial proteins past the stomach
and into the blood has been to deliver them through injection,
Shirley said. Because no one likes to get shots, this has limited
the use of biotech potions.
</P>
<P>
   Several Bay Area firms are trying to break the needle barrier by
using inhalers to deliver protein remedies through the lungs. These
companies include Inhale Therapeutic Systems in San Carlos, Aradigm
Corp. in Hayward and AeroGen Inc. in Sunnyvale.
</P>
<P>
   Insulin is their first target. It is a protein, which means
people can't take it as pills. Moreover, many of the 8 million
Americans who suffer from diabetes need to take several insulin
shots daily _ creating a huge market for an easier alternative to
the needle.
</P>
<P>
   Aradigm founder Reid Rubsamen explained his company's early
stage trials of an inhaler that dispenses an insulin vapor. The
vapor contains insulin particles, far smaller than specks of dust,
bound with water molecules. If sprayed into the air, this vapor
would resemble fog, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to pump this insulin-rich vapor into the labyrinth
of tissues inside the lungs. So vast are our lung linings, he said,
that if we could remove their tissue from our bodies and flatten it
out, it would cover a tennis court.
</P>
<P>
   Having this huge target is essential because the success of
inhaled delivery rests on ensuring that microscopic droplets of
insulin land on the tissue and are absorbed by the blood vessels on
the other side. Aradigm and its competitors are testing their
systems in hopes of convincing the Food and Drug Administration
that the lungs deliver as much insulin to the bloodstream as the
tried-and-true shot.
</P>
<P>
   Vapor delivery is one way of getting protein remedies past the
digestive trap. Shirley, the Chiron scientist, said other firms are
experimenting with wrapping biotech proteins in what we might call
smart, armored pills.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to coat the protein, which we would otherwise
digest, inside a layer of fat that would protect it from stomach
enzymes _ at least long enough to allow the armored pill to make it
to the bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   But why create protein pills when I started by saying people
often forget to take their medicines?
</P>
<P>
   That's where the smart part comes in, Shirley said. By varying
the thickness or chemical makeup of the wrapper, scientists hope to
fashion delivery systems that release remedies over time _ so we
can take a pill once a day instead of three times a day, or once a
week instead of daily.
</P>
<P>
   Time-release pills and capsules already are available for some
traditional drugs. The hope is to make the same one-a-day formulas
available for larger biotech proteins.
</P>
<P>
   Many people are familiar with other time-release technologies,
like the NicoDerm skin patch, which delivers tiny jolts of nicotine
to help people quit smoking. Many efforts are under way to expand
skin patches to deliver a wider range of remedies. But so far,
Shirley said, the patches are able to deliver only small chemical
packages, not big protein payloads.
</P>
<P>
   Patches aren't the only way companies are experimenting with
getting timed-release drugs under our skin. Lisa Nolan, with West
Pharmaceutical Services in Pennsylvania, said her firm is
developing a silicone sac that would be inserted under the eyelid.
</P>
<P>
   Sac sounds so ungainly for something an inch long and no wider
than a strand of angel hair pasta. Nolan said the sac is being
tested as a time-release alternative to the eye drops people must
take after getting cataract operations. Right now, people have to
cock their heads back and stare up into the eyedropper _ providing
they remember to take their medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech firms expect two benefits when, and if, some of these
alternative-delivery mechanisms win FDA approval.
</P>
<P>
   First, bypassing the needle would expand the realm of
biotech-treatable diseases. Today, we'll take a biotech shot only
for serious ailments. The companies would like to sell us remedies
for lesser ills.
</P>
<P>
   Second, if the various time-release strategies pan out, firms
expect to greatly increase the effectiveness of pharmaceutical
remedies, which many patients unwittingly sabotage by failing to
follow their drug regime.
</P>
<P>
   That should be good for patients, but it will be even better for
the profits of drugmakers. I could almost see the dollar signs
dance in Shirley's eyes when he explained, ``HMOs will pay more for
time-release (products) because it will insure compliance with the
treatment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
