<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-BOARD-GAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVENTORS MAKE A MOVE IN BOARD GAMES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:   Mass., Md., Utah, Colo.)   By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a world of cyber-this and video-that, can traditional board
games still gain attention?
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, dozens of patents have been issued to hopeful
inventors who dream that their new version of the old-fashioned
board game will one day become the next Monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   But in this age of Gameboy, is anyone still playing board games?
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has changed dramatically over the past 10 to 15
years,'' said Philip Orbanes, president of Winning Moves, a game
company based in Danvers, Mass. ``New games of that ilk have been
continual failures.''
</P>
<P>
   Orbanes ought to know. He left Hasbro Games Group several years
ago to form Winning Moves, a company that was supposed to
specialize in selling traditional board games.
</P>
<P>
   ``But consumers nowadays just don't have the patience,'' he
said. ``It was too formidable an environment.'' Orbanes' company is
branching out into other products.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Bradley and Parker Brothers, both divisions of Hasbro,
still produce best-selling board games, according to Orbanes, who
is the author of ``The Monopoly Companion'' (Adams Media). But they
stick to such classics as Monopoly or Pictionary _ games that
people already know how to play. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Orbanes offers a grim forecast for board game inventors. But the
example of Richard C. Levy, a successful toy and games inventor in
Bethesda, Md., suggests a silver lining.
</P>
<P>
   Levy recently received a patent, No. D406,614, to protect the
design of the board for his game based on the best-selling book
``Men Are From Mars, Women Are From Venus'' (HarperCollins). Levy
created the game for Cardinal Industries. It is based on the
best-selling book by John Gray, and the game _ which has the same
title as the book _ has begun to show up on toy store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Levy says, it's all about ``branding'' _ linking up
your game with a well-known book or product. He has created board
games based on ``Chicken Soup for the Soul'' (Health
Communications) as well as Uncle Milton's Ant Farm.
</P>
<P>
   Both games are now being introduced into stores.
</P>
<P>
   What other advice does Levy have? First, don't spend a lot of
money to patent something until you know you have a truly novel and
marketable product. Even then, unless the game has a singular
electronic or mechanical aspect, often trademark and copyright are
more important _ and cheaper to obtain.
</P>
<P>
   Second, try to license it. ``Self-publishing is absolute
suicide,'' Levy said. ``More than 99 percent of the people I know
who make the games themselves still have them in their basement.''
</P>
<P>
   Most big companies do not take submissions directly from
independent inventors. The Manhattan-based Toy Manufacturers of
America (www.toy-tma.org) has a list of toy and games agents who,
much like literary agents, take a cut of any future royalties as
their fee. (Toy agents are not to be confused with invention
submission companies, which are reviled by Levy as being ``carrion
birds circling the skies for unsuspecting inventors.'')
</P>
<P>
   Ronald O. Weingartner, a former executive at Hasbro Games Group
and the co-author with Levy of ``From Workshop to Toy Store''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster), adds that board games need to give children a
``wow'' experience. ``That usually means some kind of electronic
enhancement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even Levy's games, while successful, are unlikely to have an
enduring shelf life. According to Jonathan Becker, a toy agent in
New York, Hasbro introduced 24 games in 1996. Only two of those
were still around in 1997. None of them were on the market in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A WINNER IN SELF-PUBLISHING
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to Levy's advice, the self-publishing route has worked
for M. Ardell Olsen, an insurance salesman in Ogden, Utah, who
recently received patent No. 5,820,125 for a Bible game that he
originally assembled in his basement with the help of his wife and
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into a store looking for something to help our family
remember and understand the teachings of the Bible and we couldn't
find anything,'' Dana M. Olsen, the inventor's wife, recalled.
</P>
<P>
   So Olsen decided to invent a game that has the object of
entering the Kingdom of Heaven by demonstrating biblical knowledge.
He and his family read scriptures together to come up with
questions. ``Then we maxed out a couple of credit cards until we
could get a bank loan,'' Mrs. Olsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Now more than 250,000 copies of Biblequest _ which comes in Old
Testament and New Testament editions _ have been sold through
religious stores and Wal-Mart Stores outlets nationwide. Olsen
recently licensed the games to Specialties, a publisher of
religious products that is also based in Ogden.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE FICTION BOARD GAME
</P>
<P>
   Richard Recard, a retired management consultant in Louisville,
Colo., also plans to produce his recently patented science fiction
board game himself and begin selling it over the Internet this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Recard's game features hexagonal playing boards that represent
different solar systems and that can be tessellated, or attached,
together so that they represent a galaxy. Players, who draw
Catastrophe and Entropy cards, must navigate their spaceships
through hazardous conditions. They receive points both for
demonstrating their knowledge of astrophysics and for assisting
other spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   Recard, who also plans to develop a digital version of his game,
received patent No. 5,906,372 last month.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
