 EMI, LIQUID AUDIO PUTTING MUSICAL GIANTS ONLINE  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The Beatles, the Rolling Stones, Garth Brooks, the Spice Girls and
hundreds of other major artists are joining the online music
revolution.
<P>
   Music giant EMI Recorded Music, which has a stable of about
1,500 artists on record labels like Capitol, Blue Note and Virgin,
is preparing to offer its vast catalog for direct download from the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid Audio Inc. of Redwood City will convert EMI's music into
Liquid Audio's proprietary digital audio format, which allows songs
to be downloaded from the Internet and played on a computer while
preventing illegal copying.
</P>
<P>
   The next version of Liquid Audio's software, due out soon, also
will allow playback on handheld players made by electronics-makers
such as Diamond Multimedia's Rio, which now only plays songs
encoded in the popular MP3 format.
</P>
<P>
   The EMI deal, to be announced Monday, is a major coup for Liquid
Audio. EMI is the world's third-largest music company, after
Universal Music Group and Sony Music.
</P>
<P>
   EMI has not determined when or how the digitized music will be
sold, though EMI officials said it could be ready to go by the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Liquid Audio could thrust EMI ahead of its
competitors, which all are quickly lining up partners in the race
to bring Internet music into the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took the record industry some time to recognize the future
is here and the audience has spoken,'' said Jay Samit, EMI senior
vice president for new media.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid Audio officials declined to comment on the deal. The
company has registered with the Securities and Exchange Commission
to go public and is in the middle of a ``quiet period'' required by
the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   In SEC filings, Liquid Audio said it plans to offer 3.6 million
shares, representing 21 percent of the company, priced at $10 to
$12 per share. Web retailer Amazon.com has the option to take up to
a 10 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with EMI gives the music company a 1 percent stake in
Liquid Audio.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Mark Hardie of Forrester Research Inc. said the EMI deal
means Liquid Audio and CEO Gerry Kearby finally may have turned the
corner.
</P>
<P>
   For its first two years of existence, Liquid Audio tried
unsuccessfully to market its technology. It has signed about 1,300
musicians and 300 record labels, but they are mainly little-known
artists from independent labels.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past year, the grassroots popularity of the MP3 audio
compression format demonstrated the potential of Liquid Audio's
original premise that there is a market for selling music fans
digitized songs directly from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody was paying attention to him two years ago,'' Hardie
said of Kearby. Now after a string of minor hits, the EMI deal
gives Liquid ``a nice solid home run,'' Hardie said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the songs available in the MP3 format _ the second-most
sought-after topic on the Internet behind sex _ are legally
available songs from independent artists.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when MP3 first leaped into the mainstream, the
world's five biggest record companies, including EMI, complained of
lost revenues because their music was being pirated and distributed
in the MP3 format.
</P>
<P>
   But now all five have banded together with other music and
technology companies to develop piracy-proof standards for digital
music distribution and specifications for portable players such as
Diamond Multimedia's Rio.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the big five record companies have cut separate deals
with technology companies like Microsoft or IBM and have announced
plans to sell digital tracks within the year.
</P>
<P>
   The exception was EMI, which ``was pretty late,'' Hardie said.
</P>
<P>
   But EMI will be the first to start converting its library, which
includes artists like Janet Jackson and the Smashing Pumpkins, into
a existing digital download format. Liquid Audio also plans to
enable its software to play MP3-encoded songs in about one month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It positions Liquid now as, I would argue, the leader in
commercial delivery'' of digital music, Hardie said. ``MP3 is still
the de facto standard, but it's not commercial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
