<SLUG> BC-EXCITE-FREESERVICE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EXCITEATHOME TO OFFER FREE VOICE MAIL, FAX  &HT;     By JON SWARTZ 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
ExciteAtHome will lend a forceful voice to online communications
Monday, with a free voice mail and fax service on its Web site as
well as a new application that brings audio to chat rooms.
<P>
   The Redwood City Internet company is teaming up with General
Magic on Voicemail, which lets consumers receive voice-mail
messages and faxes from a special free phone number and e-mail
account. They then can listen to messages and view faxes from any
personal computer linked to the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We not only view the Web as a forum for content, but for
people to communicate,'' said Craig Donato, senior vice president
of network programming at ExciteAtHome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an aggressive effort for what we call the `access
anywhere' crowd _ especially traveling businesspeople who don't
want to constantly check their pager, fax machine and e-mail
account to stay in touch with the office,'' Donato said.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: Consumers register for an 800 phone number
with an extension listed on Excite's site. The number doesn't ring
at a real phone, but allows callers to leave a voice message or
fax.
</P>
<P>
   Those messages are then converted into computer files and
relayed to the e-mail accounts of Excite members, of which there
are at least 1 million. The members can either play audio files of
voice mail or view faxes.
</P>
<P>
   The service is based on General Magic's Portico technology, a
personal digital assistant that converts and delivers messages to
users via the Internet or phone. So-called unified messaging has
tantalized consumers but lagged in use because it can be slow and
clunky, industry observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome isn't the first company to offer free voice mail
and faxes online, but it is the largest. A slew of startups _
TeleBot Corp. in San Francisco, onebox.com of San Mateo and
uReach.com Inc. in Holmdel, N.J., _ all offer similar services.
</P>
<P>
   None, however, has the reach of ExciteAtHome. The Web's
second-largest portal site reaches 20 million people per month.
</P>
<P>
   A second service on Excite's Web site, Voice Chat, provides
audio for chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Co-developed with Lipstream Networks Inc. of Cupertino, the free
service lets anyone with an Internet connection, speaker and
microphone talk in real time over the Net with other chat room
participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everyone is a great typist, which can be a barrier to
participating in a chat room,'' Lipstream Networks CEO Bret Savage
said. ``It is the next logical step for communications.''
</P>
<P>
   Savage said the technology will eventually be extended to
instant-messaging systems and online customer-support operations
for companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
