<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PULSE-ANIMATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PULSE ENTERTAINMENT HITS BIG WITH 3-D JAY LENO  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
J ay Leno pops a foil-wrapped burrito into a microwave and surfs
the Internet on his computer.
<P>
   Zap. The cosmic-electrical forces summoned by nuking aluminum
foil traps the square-jawed comedian in a Web world of man-eating
pizzas, shameless Intel promos, scantily clad Victoria's Secret
models and an endless supply of Bill Clinton jokes.
</P>
<P>
   And now, ladies and gentlemen ... Virtual Jaaaaaaaay Leno!
</P>
<P>
   That was how Virtual Jay, a 3-D computer-animated version of
Leno created by Pulse Entertainment of San Francisco, made his
debut last week on Leno's ``Tonight Show.''
</P>
<P>
   He also became a regular evolving character on the ``Tonight
Show's'' Web site at www.nbc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Jay is a major break for Pulse Entertainment, which is
trying to sell its 3-D animation technology to Web designers as a
way of juicing up Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great validation of what we do,'' said Pulse chief
executive Fred Angelopoulos.
</P>
<P>
   Pulse's proprietary software, called the Pulse Creator, can
create moving, talking 3-D interactive characters for Internet
sites. Computer users can move the animated characters on the
screen with a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Virtual Leno character demonstrated how a virtual sales
representative could lead a consumer around an electronic commerce
site.
</P>
<P>
   The company also envisions the technology being used to make
pictures of products on Web sites more realistic, so they can be
inspected by consumers just as if they were on display on a store
shelf. A portable stereo, for example, can be depicted as a 3-D
object that plays music.
</P>
<P>
   The Pulse Player software is a free plug-in for Web browsers.
Angelopoulos said the software works even on lower-speed 28.8 Kbps
modems, and the animations can be embedded in banner ads.
</P>
<P>
   Pulse was founded in 1994 by former Macromedia Chairman Bill
Woodward as a producer of CD-ROM games like Iron Helix and Bad
Mojo.
</P>
<P>
   But the closely held company located on Brannan Street shifted
its focus last year from games to ``bringing life to the
Internet,'' President Mark Yahiro said.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the 25-employee company drew up a Virtual Bill
Clinton _ complete with a salacious ``MonicaCam'' view _ for MTV's
Web site. And it created an interactive disc jockey called DJ Dev
for an Internet company called RadioV.
</P>
<P>
   Those demonstrations brought Pulse some notoriety, but Yahiro
said the company needed greater exposure. So Pulse hatched the idea
of creating an animated Jay Leno and pitched the concept to the
``Tonight Show's'' producers in April.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PULSE21 (104332 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``The next thing you know, we're sitting in Jay's office pitching
ideas,'' Angelopoulos said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pitching Jay-jokes at the writers,'' Yahiro said.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, a little Hollywood-style karma also kicked in.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Crane, vice president and general manager of the network's
Internet arm, NBC.com, was at the same time looking for a 3-D
technology company to increase traffic on a Web site that promotes
another NBC show.
</P>
<P>
   Crane said she had a friend whose sister had just started doing
some consulting work for Pulse. The sister had a friend who worked
for the ``Tonight Show,'' and through that connection, Crane
learned that Angelopoulos and Yahiro were meeting with Leno's
producers.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, Crane met one of Pulse's investors at a cocktail
party and even heard more talk about Pulse while sitting in the
famous NBC commissary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things where I couldn't go anywhere without
hearing Pulse, Pulse,'' said Crane, who joined the meeting with
Pulse and ``Tonight Show'' execs.
</P>
<P>
   Angelopoulos and Yahiro had found their stage but still had to
convince the network that they could deliver. Crane said she had
not been impressed with other 3-D technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they first saw the technology, they didn't think it could
be done,'' Yahiro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay was really interested, but he wanted to make sure it was
funny,'' Angelopoulos said. ``When the audience went nuts, he just
loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Using computer modeling, Pulse refined Virtual Jay in about six
weeks. ``Tonight Show'' writers came up with his lines, and Leno
himself supplied the voice.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Jay debuted on Tuesday in a skit that had him trapped
inside his computer, bouncing to different Web sites, including one
for Intel, one of Pulse's major investors. The skit ended with the
real Leno being ``downloaded'' onto Bill Clinton's lap.
</P>
<P>
   The audience laughed and Leno directed them to the NBC Web site
for more Virtual Jay adventures, which will be created once a week.
The character will also appear from time to time on the show.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic on the ``Tonight Show'' site increased dramatically, but
Crane hedged on whether Virtual Jay will get his own virtual show.
She did say the network already plans to use a virtual character
for another show's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at a whole slate of cutting-edge programs,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Fenik, vice president of analysis for Zona Research Inc.
of Redwood City, said Pulse's technology has potential beyond
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   For example, aircraft mechanics learning how to service an
engine could first experiment with a graphic simulation in a
computer, Fenik said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has enormous potential in training and enormous potential
in documentation of physical things,'' Fenik said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Angelopoulos and Yahiro are concentrating on producing
new weekly installments of Virtual Jay. The company also has
developed a virtual trivia game show for NBC's ``Saturday Night
Live'' show and has another undisclosed project in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Pulse Entertainment is moving to new quarters on Mission Street
in San Francisco that Angelopoulos and Yahiro also hope will
provide more lucky karma: the building used to house an art gallery
for legendary cartoonist and Bugs Bunny animator Chuck Jones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
