 LET THE NET HELP EVALUATE MUTUAL FUNDS  &HT;     By HARRY DOMASH 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
_ First of two parts on mutual fund investing online.
<P>
   For many investors, mutual funds offer advantages compared with
buying individual stocks.
</P>
<P>
   If you're busy, you don't have time to analyze and follow five
or 10 companies. When you own a mutual fund, you have a team of
professionals working for you.
</P>
<P>
   Diversification is an important element of investing. Mutual
funds give you automatic diversification because most funds own
dozens of different companies.
</P>
<P>
   But picking the right fund can be daunting. Look up fund
performance data and you'll find mountains of statistics: one-year
returns, five-year returns, beta, alpha, standard deviation,
turnover, Sharpe ratio, etc. How do you know what's important?
</P>
<P>
   I've come up with a few simple rules for evaluating funds, and
here's the good news: All the information you need is available on
the Internet, and it's free.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite source for mutual fund information is Morningstar, a
Chicago company that is well known and respected in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   If a mutual fund earns a high grade from Morningstar, the fund
company features the rating prominently in its advertising. Even
more important, Morningstar gives away all the information you need
to analyze a fund.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find some Morningstar data on other sites such as Quicken
(www.quicken.com) or America Online, but the Quicktake report on
the Morningstar site is more complete and updated faster.
</P>
<P>
   LET'S GET STARTED
</P>
<P>
   Pick out a mutual fund you own, or are considering buying, and
I'll show you how I would analyze it.
</P>
<P>
   Log on to Morningstar (www.morningstar.net).
</P>
<P>
   Look up the fund's ticker symbol:
</P>
<P>
   _ Click on the Ticker Lookup selector directly above the data
entry box.
</P>
<P>
   _ Type the first few letters of the fund's name into the box.
</P>
<P>
   _ Push the enter key on your keyboard. (There's no ``go'' button
to click.)
</P>
<P>
   Return to the main page, and type the ticker symbol into the
data entry box. That brings up the Snapshot page of the Quicktake
report.
</P>
<P>
   START WITH STARS
</P>
<P>
   Notice the stars (upper left). That's Morningstar's overall
rating of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   The range is one to five stars, with five being the best.
Morningstar does not give a star rating to funds younger than 3
years old.
</P>
<P>
   I look for funds with four or five stars. A high rating doesn't
guarantee that the fund will perform well in the future, but I've
found I always end up rejecting lower-rated funds when I examine
their performance in detail. I figure there's no point wasting time
analyzing funds I'm not going to buy, so I eliminate them right off
the bat.
</P>
<P>
   LOAD VS. NO-LOAD FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Load is a sales charge usually paid to the stockbroker or
financial adviser who recommended the fund. If you invest $1,000 in
a fund with a 5 percent load, only $950 actually goes into the
fund. If you buy a no-load fund, the entire $1,000 amount goes to
work for you.
</P>
<P>
   Should you buy a load or no-load fund? It depends. If your
broker or adviser turned you on to a great fund, he or she deserves
to be paid. If you do all your own research, you may want to stick
with no-load funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Quicktake report consists of several sections listed near
the top of the page: Snapshot, Risk &AMP; Return, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Select Risk &AMP; Return, then click on Morningstar Rating from the
list on the left.
</P>
<P>
   You'll see the fund's Morningstar Return and Risk scores for
three-, five- and 10-year periods.
</P>
<P>
   RETURN RATING
</P>
<P>
   Return expresses the total appreciation of your investment
including dividends and distributions. Morningstar's return rating
compares a fund's return to all other funds in the same category.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, if you're looking at a U.S. stock fund, the fund's
return would be compared to all domestic equity funds. A return
rating of 1.0 means the fund's return is equal to the average of
all funds in the category. A rating of 2.0 means the fund's return
was twice the return of the average fund.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar's return rating takes the fund's load (if any) into
account. I've found the rating for the five-year period to be the
most reliable for predicting future performance.
</P>
<P>
   RISK RATING
</P>
<P>
   Consider two funds, both with a total return of 25 percent last
year. Fund A's share price moved in a steady upward path during the
entire year. On the other hand, Fund B's price gyrated wildly.
There even were times during the year when Fund B was losing money.
</P>
<P>
   Fund A has low volatility. Fund B is highly volatile and might
have kept you awake nights.
</P>
<P>
   Fund-rating services typically base risk ratings on volatility.
Morningstar's does, too, but gives most weight to periods when
shareholders were losing money.
</P>
<P>
   As with return, a score of 1.0 means a fund's risk is average.
In this case, a lower rating is better. A risk rating of 0.5 means
a fund's risk is only half that of the average fund. I've found the
three-year risk rating to be the most significant.
</P>
<P>
   PUTTING IT ALL TOGETHER
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to select funds with high returns and low risks. I
look for funds with a minimum five-year return rating of 1.5, and a
maximum three-year risk rating of 0.9. You may prefer different
criteria. However you do it, make sure the return rating is much
higher than the risk rating. For me, the return must be at least
twice the risk. For instance, if a fund has a risk rating of 0.8, I
require a minimum return rating of 1.6.
</P>
<P>
   MORE WORK TO DO
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar's return and risk ratings are based on past
performance. All things being equal, funds that historically have
outperformed the market tend to continue their winning ways. But
there are many other factors to consider. For instance, changes in
management, the makeup of the portfolio and the portfolio's
price/earnings ratio, turnover, expense ratios and more. We'll
continue the discussion in my next column.
</P>
<P>
   _ Next Monday: Part Two of a look at online mutual fund
investing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
