A2832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELECOM-MARKETPLACE-5     06-20 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-MARKETPLACE-595&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: THE BATTLE FOR U S WEST AND FRONTIER IS SYMBOLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's an investor to do when swept up in the turmoil of today's
communications industries?
</P>
<P>
   It's a quandary apparent in the most current donnybrook
concerning U S West, the smallest of the regional Bells, and
Frontier Corp., one of the United States' largest long-distance
telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Communications companies are all too aware that if they do not
transform themselves _ placing one foot in the new digital universe
of the Internet and the other in the more traditional world of
cable or copper wires _ they risk certain death.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the telecommunications upstart Global Crossing, a
Bermuda-based owner of undersea cables, recently agreed to merge
with both U S West and Frontier. And then, in a bold move last
week, another upstart, Qwest Communications International, raised
the stakes with a bid of its own for U S West and Frontier.
</P>
<P>
   But the combinations deemed necessary to propel
telecommunications companies into the Internet age are wreaking
havoc on Wall Street. Investors are struggling with these new
hybrids, surprised by what these companies aspire to become and
questioning how those ambitions fit their investing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Even executives with the best-laid plans to meld old and new
technologies are at odds with their shareholders these days.
``You've got different crosscurrents here,'' said William
Deatherage, an analyst at Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   And the steps that telecommunications, cable and networking
companies need to take now to prosper often do not mesh with the
short-term expectations of Wall Street. In May, when Global
Crossing first announced its intent to merge with U S West _ even
as Global had a pending deal to also acquire Frontier _ Wall Street
was not enthusiastic. Global Crossing's stock, which was trading at
more than $60 a share before that announcement, is now less than
$50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Investors swifter to punish Qwest. Its stock plummeted 24
percent last Monday, to $34.125 a share, although it began edging
back up, closing Friday at $37.9375.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen deals speak to this issue before,'' said
Deatherage. But the battle for U S West and Frontier ``is one of
the first times where the reaction from investors has been so
striking.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? For one thing, Wall Street loves pure plays. And these
proposed combinations are anything but. Qwest and Global Crossing
are high-growth companies staking their futures on the global
Internet boom. They trade like Internet stocks _ though that is not
what they are _ with billion-dollar market capitalizations based on
the promise of fast growth, despite no earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier and U S West are slower-growth enterprises in mature
corners of the telecommunications industry. But they have what both
Global and Qwest need _ cash and customers.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, investors are well versed in the trauma of fusing
hares and tortoises. When Worldcom said it wanted to acquire MCI
Communications in 1997, investors trashed Worldcom's stock. Now
that move _ forming MCI Worldcom _ is hailed as brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when AT&AMP;T Corp. said it would buy the cable TV
operator Tele-Communications Inc., AT&AMP;T's stock, too, took a dive.
Those share have since recovered, though it is anyone's guess if
AT&AMP;T's bet will pay off.
</P>
<P>
   What is new is the breadth of companies suddenly thrown into the
crucible of old and new communications technologies. ``We're in an
industry reforming itself,'' Joseph Nacchio, Qwest's chief
executive, said in explaining his move last week. ``Those of us in
the midst of it have to reshape our companies.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A bet on once-staid AT&AMP;T has become a gamble on the cable
industry. Lucent Technologies, AT&AMP;T's spin-off of its switches and
hardware division, is buying Ascend Communications and reinventing
itself as a networking company.
</P>
<P>
   Even Alcatel SA, the Paris-based maker of mobile phones and
undersea fiber-optic cables, is touting itself in ads as ``the hot
new Internet company that's 100 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet what might make corporate sense does not always dovetail
with what investors expect. ``If an investor buys Global Crossing
or Qwest with the idea of adding a turbo-charged growth company to
their portfolio and is confronted with a merger that will lower
that growth rate,'' said Deatherage, ``even if the deal makes
industrial logic, that person will be a seller.''
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing may have come up with a structure that _ at
least in the short term _ could satisfy Wall Street. Tom Casey, a
Global vice chairman and former investment banker, said the company
specifically set up a dual share offering to address potential
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two distinct groups of shareholders,'' he said. In the
proposed merger of Global, U S West and Frontier, shareholders
would have the option of either of two stocks _ one for Internet
assets, the other a dividend-paying traditional telephone offering.
</P>
<P>
   But few investors are fans of so-called tracking stocks. Those
can be confusing, and many businesses that Global would spin off,
sell or otherwise divest now overlap.
</P>
<P>
   Deatherage calls it ``an attempt to artificially split'' the two
companies. But until investors sort through how to value hybrids,
``it could be a model,'' said Robert Gensler, an analyst at T. Rowe
Price, a Baltimore-based mutual-fund company. ``Companies now are
stuck in an earnings box.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, though, any of these combinations are best judged on
their strategic merits, and few people outside the companies
themselves are defending the strategies. So far, Nacchio is drawing
the most ire. He spent much of last week on the road soothing angry
investors, and on Thursday Frontier rejected Qwest's current offer.
U S West is still evaluating Qwest's offer.
</P>
<P>
   While Global Crossing may look as if it has won the first round,
the skirmish is not over. Investors have not overwhelmingly
embraced its merger agreement with the two companies, either.
</P>
<P>
   But Gensler may have the most novel thesis of why Global
Crossing and Qwest are at war: Both want to bolster their fledgling
businesses with real assets while they still have a relatively
overvalued currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``These deals don't feel strategic,'' he said. ``They feel like
they are just trying to lock in the value of their high-priced
stock by merging with another company.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, a new type of investor is likely to emerge
for these hybrids _ one not courageous enough for the
roller-coaster ride of a pure technology play but demanding
better-than-average gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still,'' Deatherage warned, ``in the short term, this will
lead to a fair amount of shareholder churn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 1934EDT &QL; 
