</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VILLAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES FIND RUIN, LITTLE FOOD OR WATER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POSLIC, Yugoslavia _ The villagers here began arriving back home
Saturday night, part of a flood of refugees racing back over the
border from nearly three months in camps and makeshift housing.
</P>
<P>
   They found their houses in ruins _ both from Serbian pillaging
and NATO bombing _ no electricity or drinking water and, worst of
all, hardly any food across a wide stretch of southern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to come back,'' said Nijazi Kryeziv, who made
the short journey from Kukes, Albania, where six of the nine
refugees camps have already been closed and the refugees are
streaming out at the rate of about 15,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``On television, we have seen the pictures of people arriving
back home,'' he went on. ``We didn't have money to pay for
apartments in Albania. And our tractors were stolen there.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to even things out, a neighbor, Sherif Berisha, put in,
``My tractor was stolen by the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Inviting a group of strangers for the traditional hospitality of
coffee, dusting off plastic garden chairs and putting cushions on a
ledge, the villagers were suddenly embarrassed to realize they did
not have any.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have electricity, we don't have water _ only for
washing not for drinking, &UR; '' &LR;  Kryeziv said. ``We are going to a
spring up on the hill.''
</P>
<P>
   They are afraid to use their well because in many villages the
departing Serbs have poisoned the wells _ sometimes by killing
people and throwing in their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any food, we didn't bring anything with us,''
said Kryeziv, and Fidajie Berisha, an old woman with a scarf over
her head and a baby on her knee, broke in to add, ``We don't even
have a stove to make bread.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherif Berisha summed it up, sadly, ``Everything is broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 125,000 refugees have crossed back into Kosovo from
Albania and Macedonia in the past six days, Rupert Colville, a
spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, said Sunday
night _ and many are coming back to bleak situations similar to
this.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee agency and other relief agencies had hoped that the
refugees would stay put for at least three weeks, so that
preparations could be made for their arrival. Despite their
urgings, the refugees are packing up and coming here, catching the
relief agencies once again unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   This village and others have been appealing to the refugee
agency for food and other aid. Colville said he and other aid
workers feared the swift return of the refugees would overwhelm
their resources, diverting aid from the homeless refugees who have
been living inside Kosovo in the forests and mountains with little
food or shelter and are in much more desperate straits.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Poslic, a few miles south of the city of Prizren,
is typical of the early days of the Serbian campaign to drive out
the Kosovo Albanians. The army appeared in the village on March 27,
three days after the beginning of the NATO bombing, villagers said,
rolling six tanks into the surrounding fields. The people were
given half an hour to gather a few belongings and forced down the
main highway to the border.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs turned the houses into military barracks, apparently
part of their effort to disguise their troop deployments from the
NATO bombers. When the villagers returned they found their houses
wrecked and their televisions, VCRs and satellite dishes stolen.
</P>
<P>
   In one house, the Serbs chopped holes in doors and walls with a
big, rusty, primitive-looking axe. In another, they left the
Serbian sign of a cross and some Cyrillic letters, along with their
names: Ivica, Dudek and Franjo.
</P>
<P>
   In one part of the village four very large new houses had been
destroyed by NATO bombing, which blanketed the area late in the air
war. There were huge craters, the roofs were shattered and the tops
of a half dozen of the tall trees that lined the road leading into
the village were splintered, with dead branches lying all about.
The electricity lines dangled from poles and lay in tangles on the
ground. Dead cows lay in the fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter,'' Kryeziv said. ``They can blow up all my
house. I just wished when I returned not to find a single Serb
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
