<HEADLINE>
BILL RUSSELL'S DOWNS AND UPS AND DOWNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the year 2000 approaches, here's a look at some
of the interesting anniversaries that will occur this week in Los
Angeles sports history (followed by the ranking of the event from
the book ``Unforgettable: The 100 Greatest Moments in Los Angeles
Sports History'' in parenthesis, where applicable):
</P>
<P>
   June 21, 1998: The Dodgers fire manager Bill Russell and general
manager Fred Claire, replacing them with Glenn Hoffman and Tom
Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   June 21, 1997: The Sparks of the WNBA make their debut in a
67-57 loss at the Forum to the New York Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   June 22, 1988: Upholding coach Pat Riley's guarantee of a repeat
championship, the Lakers beat the Detroit Pistons 108-105 in Game 7
of the NBA Finals at the Forum. James Worthy is the series MVP;
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar scores 32 in the final game. (13)
</P>
<P>
   June 22, 1994: Before 93,134 at the Rose Bowl, the U.S. knocks
off Colombia 2-1 in the World Cup for their first tournament win in
44 years. (21)
</P>
<P>
   June 23, 1956: At Hollywood Park, Swaps runs a world-record 1:39
in the 1 1/16-mile race.
</P>
<P>
   June 23, 1996: Dodgers manager Lasorda suffers a mild heart
attack. He retires six days later.
</P>
<P>
   June 25, 1984: Russell becomes the Dodgers' all-time leader in
games played with his 1,953rd appearance.
</P>
<P>
   June 26, 1981: Magic Johnson signs a 25-year, $25 million
contract with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   June 26, 1964: The Angels pay a record $200,000 bonus to sign
University of Wisconsin outfielder Rick Reichardt.
</P>
<P>
   June 27, 1980: Dodgers left-hander Jerry Reuss throws a
no-hitter at San Francisco, 8-0. The only Giants baserunner comes
in the first inning on a throwing error by Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Birthdays: Today: Former Dodgers pitcher Rick Sutcliffe (43).
Wednesday: Former Kings star Bernie Nicholls (38). Sunday: Angels
outfielder Jim Edmonds (29).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
