<HEADER>
A2848 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANKS-DOCUMENTARY-ART     06-20 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANKS-DOCUMENTARY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATING A NEW IMAGE FOR VIETNAM'S WARRIORS 
</HEADLINE>
  ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Several months ago Tom Hanks received a video
documentary called ``Return With Honor'' from Richard Chew, a top
film editor. ``He sent me a note saying that he thought I might be
interested,'' Hanks recalled, ``but I just let it sit on my desk
for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally Hanks opened the package and began watching the video.
``I sat there amazed,'' he said. ``It didn't take much to be swept
away. It was one of the greatest stories I have ever heard.''
</P>
<P>
   The film depicts the heroism and endurance of American prisoners
of war in Vietnam, and Hanks has taken the unusual step of lending
his name as its ``presenter'' (``Tom Hanks Presents'') and is
actively promoting it.
</P>
<P>
   The 102-minute film opened in New York and Los Angeles to strong
reviews and is to be released in other large cities in the next few
weeks. An official opening is scheduled for Tuesday in Washington
at the Smithsonian's National Air and Space Museum, to be attended
by most of the former prisoners and their families as well as by
Hanks and government officials.
</P>
<P>
   The film was made by Freida Lee Mock and Terry Sanders,
documentary makers from Los Angeles who had won an Academy Award
for ``Maya Lin: A Strong, Clear Vision,'' about the architect who
designed the Vietnam War Memorial in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mock said she received a call in 1997 from three Air Force
Academy graduates, class of 1965, who had served in Vietnam and
were now successful entrepreneurs. They wondered if Ms. Mock and
Sanders had considered making a documentary about American pilots
shot down over North Vietnam who had survived as long as nine years
under harrowing and brutal conditions. The call came after the men
had seen the Maya Lin documentary.
</P>
<P>
   The three were Mark Johnson, a former commercial pilot; Bart
Holaday, a former Rhodes scholar and portfolio manager, and Warren
Langley, a former president of the Pacific Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, `Wow, what a great idea,' '' Ms. Mock recalled. ``We
began talking to the former POW's and what surprised us was how
open and candid and intimate these men were about their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``They were so forthcoming; they were not at all
stereotypical military men. Their experiences in prison camp
totally affected what they are today and, as they told us, as
difficult as that experience was, they were strengthened by it and
that's why they were so direct and open.''
</P>
<P>
   The film includes interviews and archival newsreels from Vietnam
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In his review of the film in The New York Times, Stephen Holden
said that the documentary signified a major shift in the screen
image of the Vietnam veteran from that of an alienated and damaged
person to a hero. ``The stories they tell are inspiring, sometimes
astounding, and most important, true,'' Holden wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The film cost about $1.3 million. Ms. Mock said the money came
from the Boeing-McDonnell Foundation and the MBNA Corp., a credit
card company.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks said he became involved in selling the documentary because
films like this one usually have trouble at the box office. He said
he had been unaware of the heroism of so many American prisoners,
as well as the brutalities they endured, and he assumed that that
was true of most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of their imprisonment has never been illuminated
like this,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
