<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TEN-DOLLAR TONGUE KNOWS A HIGH-DOLLAR RECIPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yr. Obdt. Correspondent is cursed, or blessed, with a $10
tongue. It was once valued at only $6, but everything has gone up
since then.
</P>
<P>
   I can enjoy and appreciate a $10 bottle of wine. I can't
truthfully say that my enjoyment is doubled or tripled when I am
served a $20 or $30 vintage.
</P>
<P>
   After a recent visit to chalk-lined cellars of the Marne River
winery that produces both Dom Perignon and Moet et Chandon
champagnes, we were served tulip glasses filled with the
world-famous brut.
</P>
<P>
   It tasted like champagne. I knew it wasn't Cook's. But it might
have been Korbel. You could have fooled me. See, I've got a $10
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   On that same trip to France, I had to confront yet another
truth. How much is my split nose worth?
</P>
<P>
   ``I divide the `nose' into two parts,'' explained Serge Dubs
during a two-hour wine tasting in the Alsace. What Dubs meant was
that he sniffs the wine just after it has been poured. Then he
sniffs it a second time, after revolving the glass in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, a group of judges from around the world
named Dubs ``Sommelier of the Year.'' This man is blessed with a
$300 tongue. Lord knows what his matched pair of noses are worth.
</P>
<P>
   Between sips of various French wines, we learned to look for
``tears'' on the sides of the glass. ``Is this wine limpid?'' he
asked. ``Look for the nuances of color from white or green to
red-orange. Is the aftertaste long or short. What dominates,
bitterness or sweetness? If the two are equal, you have a
remarkable wine.''
</P>
<P>
   I'll take his word for it. I might pop for a bottle of the
muscat or the pinot gris we sampled. If it didn't cost any more
than $10.
</P>
<P>
   I asked the former sommelier of the year whether he had any
Pacific Northwest wines in his personal cellar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some pinot noirs from Oregon,'' he admitted. ``And I
have some Washington wines from, what is the name? Ah yes, Ste.
Michelle.'' Dubs said he is impressed with some of the wines being
produced in Australia. But you will never get the French to rate
any wine above the local product, for sipping, slurping or cooking
in a dish like this:
</P>
<P>
   Cod Beaujolais
</P>
<P>
   6 6-ounce portions of true cod
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup light red wine, like Beaujolais
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon oregano
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon thyme
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon rosemary
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   18 black olives
</P>
<P>
   Parsley for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Wash fillets and pat dry with paper towels. Lay out in one layer
in a large oven platter or two small ones. Sprinkle with salt and
pepper and cover with wine. Cover the platter with aluminum foil
and bake in a 400-degree oven for 10 to 15 minutes, or until the
fish is just beginning to firm up.
</P>
<P>
   Remove fish to a platter. Pour the wine liquid into a small
saucepan and boil for 2 or 3 minutes. You need 1 cup of reduced
liquid, so add or pour off wine accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in a skillet. Over medium heat saute the onions for
about 2 minutes. Add garlic, reduced wine liquid, tomato sauce, 2
tablespoons parsley, the oregano, thyme and rosemary. Bring sauce
to a boil, stirring. Reduce heat to a simmer. Mix the cornstarch
with 1 tablespoon of cold water and stir this mess into the pan.
</P>
<P>
   When the sauce is thick, return fish fillets to oven dish and
cover with sauce. At this point you can refrigerate the fish,
covered, for a couple of hours if you wish.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before you want to serve, shove platter into a
350-degree oven and cook the fish, covered, until done to your
liking, maybe 15 or 18 minutes. Garnish with olives and more
parsley and this will serve six.
</P>
<P>
   Nah, you don't have to use French Beaujolais in this dish. You
can probably find a light red from Washington or Oregon. You might
even get one on sale for under $10.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure many French sommeliers would mix white wine with
red chili peppers, but it works in a dish like this.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic Steamed Mussels
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 large garlic cloves, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   4 dried chili peppers
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 and a half pounds mussels
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in your seafood pot and saute the onion, garlic and
chili peppers for about three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Dump in the mussels and wine, cover the pot and steam until all
the visible shells have opened. Remove pot from heat and let sit
covered for a minute. Dish the mussels up into two large bowls and
pour the contents of the pot _ through a strainer _ over the
mussels until the broth is evenly divided.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
