<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORTALS-STUDY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE WEB, AS ELSEWHERE, POPULARITY IS SELF-REINFORCING 
</HEADLINE>
  ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On the World Wide Web, the rich are getting
richer.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing new statistical support to an increasingly common
Internet wisdom, two Xerox Corp. researchers have found that the
most popular Web sites command by far the biggest share of Internet
traffic _ a signature of what economists refer to as ``winner take
all'' markets.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which is based on statistical measurements of
visitors to sites on the Internet's World Wide Web, looks at a
large data sample of Internet traffic to two types of sites:
universities and so-called adult entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, which are laid out in a report that is to be
presented at a technical conference this month by Lada Adamic and
Bernardo Huberman, would seem to undermine arguments by some
entrepreneurs and technologists that the World Wide Web would be a
democratizing force, allowing a large number of relatively equal
market contestants to compete on a level playing field. Instead,
the study finds, the most popular sites tend to gain an
accelerating advantage over their competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we found that you are rewarded not so much for
absolute performance as much as for relative performance,'' said
Huberman, a physicist who studies the ecology of computer networks
at Xerox's Palo Alto Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Xerox study is based on a sample of America Online users in
December 1997. The data look at 60,000 users and 120,000 Web sites.
Whether analyzing traffic to university sites or to the
sex-oriented adult entertainment sites, the research indicates that
the traffic distribution follows what is known as a universal power
law. This means that a small number of sites command the traffic of
a large portion of the entire Web population.
</P>
<P>
   Huberman said the pattern found in the America Online data was
reflected in the researchers' subsequent analysis of data from the
Web ``portal'' Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   The America Online user data indicated that among all sites
visited _ excluding America Online as a site itself _ 119 sites
received 32.36 percent of all visits, with Yahoo receiving the
most.
</P>
<P>
   The top 5 percent of all sites in the sample _ approximately
6,000 sites _ received 74.81 percent of all Web traffic. The top 5
percent of adult sites received 41.75 percent of total visitors to
such sites. And the top 5 percent of educational sites received
59.5 percent of all visitors to that category of sites.
</P>
<P>
   The finding that Web visitors are distributed among sites
according to the universal power law mirrors what social scientists
refer to as Pareto's Law _ named for a late 19th-century Italian
economist, Vilfredo Pareto, who studied different countries and
found the statistics of inequality in the distribution of wealth
showed a remarkable similarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most popular sites are generally not the ones that were
created first,'' Huberman said. Popularity instead tended to be
determined by a collective process he referred to as social search,
in which referrals from friends and acquaintances drove growth.
</P>
<P>
   The Xerox findings are closely correlated with the
yet-to-be-released results of similar research conducted by a group
of IBM researchers at the company's Almaden Research Center in San
Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a broader study undertaken in an effort to improve
the quality of a Web searching tool, a group of five scientists
graphed the hyperlinks, or pointers, between different Web sites.
Pointers that refer to other Web sites are another measure of
popularity on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their research is very similar to our research,'' said Sridhar
Rajagopalan, a member of the IBM research staff at the Almaden
center, referring to the Xerox team's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams of researchers said their findings could not be used
to predict winners and losers on the Web _ but did show that once a
Web site catches on, its popularity tends to increase rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't say it will be hopeless for a small mom-and-pop
Web site,'' Rajagopalan said. ``It's more like a lottery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990620.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2862 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-MAGS-ART-870&AMP;     06-20 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-MAGS-ART-870&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD FORMULA FOR FASHION MAGAZINES IS OUT OF STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the executives at Hearst Magazines wanted to place an ad in
the newspaper for the position of editor in chief of Harper's
Bazaar, it might read something like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Wanted: an editor with enough attitude to revitalize a
magazine that was once a solid No. 2 in the field and is now
wavering between Nos. 3 and 4; a woman (probably) who is willing to
make close to $1 million a year and has the ability to answer the
following question: Do American women _ and the advertisers that
cater to them _ care about fashion anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   This week, Cathleen Black, the president of Hearst Magazines, is
expected to announce which lucky contestant will win the coveted
opportunity to replace the late Elizabeth Tilberis as top editor of
Harper's Bazaar. While a half-dozen names are being mentioned,
executives of Hearst are mostly staying silent. (One who ventured
to speak off the record would do so only after asking if a reporter
was sure her phone lines were not bugged.)
</P>
<P>
   But whoever takes the helm will have to contend not only with
the problems at Harper's Bazaar _ dwindling advertising pages,
snazzy competition and sluggish growth in fashion advertising _ but
with the potential end of an era for the high-fashion glossy, as
magazines that combine style and lifestyle _ like In Style,
published by Time Inc. _ come to dominate the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   After a recession in Asian markets late last year, manufacturers
of high-end apparel and makers of luxury goods, like Gucci,
suffered some losses, and that translated into lower budgets for
fashion-magazine advertising. (These losses came on the heels of a
decline the previous year; in the category of ready-to-wear
clothing, manufacturers spent $539 million in magazine advertising
in 1997 but only $510 million in 1998, the first dip after a
precipitous rise during the previous five years.)
</P>
<P>
   Other categories remained strong. The four magazines in the
United States that focus on women's fashion _ Vogue, Elle, W and
Harper's Bazaar _ show relatively healthy advertising figures,
encompassing all categories, for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Harper's Bazaar was the least sprightly of the four, with just a
2 percent increase in overall advertising revenue for January
through May, compared with the period a year earlier. Vogue and W
are both up 13 percent, and Elle is up 3 percent, according to the
Publishers Information Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, In Style is up 60 percent. But much of this year's
rise can be credited to the fact that the fashion titles have
followed the lead of magazines like In Style and brought in new
categories of advertising, said Roberta Garfinkle, the director of
print media at McCann-Erickson, a unit of Interpublic Group of Cos.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to build your business, you're going to have
go beyond the traditional advertisers in fashion and bring in new
ones,'' Ms. Garfinkle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is fashion the staple it used to be? I don't know. They're
looking at automotive, at consumer electronics. If Harper's Bazaar
becomes more mainstream, does it make them a better candidate for
different kinds of advertising, more mass-market kinds of
advertising? Or does it stay where it is, stay focused on the creme
de la creme, the high-end couture, and limit themselves? That's a
business decision that Cathie Black has to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Elle, which is published by Hachette-Filipacchi Magazines, is
taking a particularly aggressive _ and increasingly common _
approach: It is starting a magazine to bring new and less frequent
advertisers into the fold.
</P>
<P>
   This November, Elle will arrive in subscribers' mailboxes
bundled with a new publication, Elle's Ultimate Road Trip, a
luxury-travel magazine that is being planned as a quarterly.
Intended to attract advertisers in categories like luxury goods,
culinary, hotels, automotive and high technology, Elle's Ultimate
Road Trip has already signed up Gucci, Cartier and Chopard, the
watch manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's mission, said Elaina Richardson, the editor in
chief of Elle, is to present women with what she called ``a
lifestyle approach'' to fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about lifestyle, and a sense of the good life, and this
is what fashion is about now,'' she said. ``I think we spend as
much time now thinking about the thread count of our sheets as the
ply of our cashmere. Fashion to women now is what's going on in
clothes, but also what company or designer is making furniture,
what designer is involved in a hotel. The world of fashion is
connected to travel and resorts and furnishings, and it's a much
bigger universe than it once was.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the categories that have grown most energetically in the
pages of magazines this year, according to figures released this
month by the Publishers Information Bureau, are technology, up 15
percent in advertising pages, home furnishings and supplies, up 14
percent, and travel, up 13 percent. Apparel has remained flat at
1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers, in the meantime, wait to see who will take the helm
at Harper's Bazaar and how that person will shape the magazine. For
much of its 132-year history, Harper's Bazaar has been strictly
devoted to fashion, but in the last two years it has had more
articles on other topics.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Vogue tends to be more celebrity-oriented: While Harper's Bazaar
recently featured an article about houses designed by the architect
Richard Neutra in Los Angeles, Vogue ran a spread on Oscar de la
Renta's vacation hacienda.
</P>
<P>
   W, too, covers the high-living celebrity life, as well as
highlighting its avant-garde photography (a recent spread showed a
macho-looking Brad Pitt holding a furry rabbit) and dozens of pages
of society news at the front of the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Elle maintains the most middlebrow approach, featuring
color-splashed fashion spreads and a particularly bawdy advice
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   But the success of lifestyle magazines points to a serious
issue: Do American women want to read fashion magazines? Nancy
Etcoff, a psychologist at the Harvard Medical School and the author
of ``Survival of the Prettiest: The Science of Beauty''
(Doubleday), said that American women may have grown
fashion-fatigued.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fashion magazines are about fulfilling fantasy, and they
are an art form _ they are theatrical,'' she said. ``We will always
have a longing for that kind of beauty and theatricality, but I
think right now, fashion magazines no longer present the most
popular images, and part of the problem was that there was such a
focus on the supermodel as an object and less a focus on
personality. Perhaps they need to rethink their approach to women
as more rounded personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Richardson of Elle said: ``A friend of mine used to tell me
that 10, 15 years ago, she used to sit at the beach at the end of
the summer and she and her friends would flip through the September
magazines and do their fall clothes shopping. Now what woman has
time to do that? She's faxing her office, or taking care of the
kids. I don't know if she has that time or inclination anymore. I
don't know if women even have time to sit on the beach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
