<HEADLINE>
THIS WEEK'S TV HIGHLIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
TODAY: If they put their minds to it, maybe the Spurs and Knicks
can break the record this time for lowest-scoring NBA Finals game.
It'd be a perfect footnote for the worst season in league history.
NBA Finals Game 3: San Antonio at New York, Channel 4, 6 p.m. (NBC
also has Game 4 Wednesday at 6 p.m. and, if absolutely necessary,
Game 5 Friday at 6 p.m. with Game 6 Sunday in San Antonio at 4:30
p.m.) 
TUESDAY: The WNBA-champion Houston Comets (4-0) are the last
unbeaten team in the league and should stay that way after a visit
by the road-weary Sparks. Just in case you were curious about that
sort of thing. WNBA: Sparks at Houston, ESPN, 5 p.m. 
WEDNESDAY: Don't worry, we haven't overlooked Wimbledon. It's Day
3, and by this time Andre Agassi's opening-round match against
Andrei Pavel should already have been put to bed. So now that
Agassi is the fourth seed and coming off the French Open stunner,
there'll be no surprise if the '92 Wimbledon champ charges through
this one. Except he's not 100 percent healthy and isn't the kind of
guy you can rely on, is he? ``Andre is the reverse Houdini _ he
appears when you don't expect it,'' said Martina Navratilova,
who'll be doing commentary for HBO. And what'll it be like this
time without Brooke getting overly emotional in the stands?
Martina's pick for the men's title is Patrick Rafter, who ``has the
perfect game for grass.'' On the women's side, HBO commentator Mary
Carillo says ``It's Steffi Graf's Wimbledon to win this year.''
Just as long as we don't have to see Martina Hingis in the crying
game again. Wimbledon, HBO, 6 a.m. to noon, live each weekday;
NBC's coverage Saturday (10 a.m. to 1 p.m.) and Sunday (11 a.m. to
3 p.m.) is tape delayed. 
THURSDAY: So on what channel do we get the female equivalent of
Andres Cantor? FIFA Women's World Cup: U.S. vs. Nigeria in Chicago,
ESPN, 5:30 p.m. (ESPN also has Sunday's U.S. game against Korea
from Foxboro, Mass., at 4 p.m.) 
FRIDAY: The Dodgers need to win this one to establish they're still
in the NL West race. Dodgers at San Francisco, Channel 5, 7:35
p.m. 
SATURDAY: The Dodgers need to win this one to strengthen their
national image. Dodgers at San Francisco, Channel 11, 1:05 p.m. 
SUNDAY: The Dodgers need to win this one 'cause it's against the
freakin' Giants, for cryin' out loud. Who needs another reason?
Dodgers at San Francisco, ESPN, 5:05 p.m. 

