<SLUG> BC-NY-BULL-SHOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER ESCAPING FROM RODEO, BULL IS SHOT DEAD IN QUEENS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A raging bull escaped from an illegal rodeo being
held in a Queens parking lot Sunday morning and charged through the
streets before four police officers shot it dead in the parking lot
of a housing project.
</P>
<P>
   Frightened tenants at the project, the Ravenswood Houses, awoke
to screams and looked out their windows as a scene right out of
Pamplona unfolded on the streets below.
</P>
<P>
   One tenant, Cassandra Daniel, 30, was walking her three children
to church. ``All of a sudden, I hear gunshots and I see a bull
running down 36th Avenue,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   After shepherding her children into the building for safety, she
said, she watched as the pursuing police officers surrounded the
bull and opened fire. ``They kept shooting at the bull and it
wouldn't die,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the bull fell next to a gray sedan in a pool of
blood.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said that the 1,700-pound bull had escaped from
a traveling Mexican rodeo that was to have been held in the parking
lot of a club in the Long Island City section of Queens, near the
entrance to the Queensboro Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Its organizers _ who advertised in bodegas to attract Mexican
immigrants and others _ were given three summonses for having wild
animals without the proper permits, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand people gathered in the club's parking lot last
month for a similar rodeo that featured bull riding, music and
food. But Police Capt. William D'Amora said that the club's
landlord, whom he did not name, grew upset when he learned that he
had rented his space to a traveling rodeo without the proper
permits.
</P>
<P>
   The landlord called the police Sunday and asked them to shut the
rodeo down, he said. As officers looked on and rodeo hands pulled
up stakes and loaded the bulls onto a trailer, he said, one
escaped.
</P>
<P>
   The bull, named Roughrider, bounded through the streets with
police cars in pursuit. Along the way he charged at several people,
but no one was hurt, said Officer Valerie St. Rose, a department
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   When the bull reached the parking lot at the Ravenswood Houses _
roughly three quarters of a mile from its starting point _ the
officers tried to corral it.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing pandemonium severely disrupted the Sunday morning
routine.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Davis, 50, heard the gunshots shortly after 10 a.m. ``I
went to the window and I thought I saw a horse running down the
street,'' she said. ``Then all of a sudden I noticed it had horns.
I said to my family, `Honey, that's a bull.' I told my son to run
out with his video camera.''
</P>
<P>
   He sold his tape to the local television news, she said proudly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
