A2885 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTE-TV-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-20 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTE-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPARDIEU REVELS IN REVENGE AND DERRING-DO AS THE COUNT OF MONTE
CRISTO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first of the many disguises adopted by the hero of ``The
Count of Monte Cristo,'' Edmond Dantes pretends to be a corpse.
Unjustly imprisoned for 20 years, Dantes sees a chance to escape by
changing places with a kindly old priest who has died. When one of
the guards hauling the body in a sack says, ``He's very heavy for
an old man who was just skin and bones,'' we know why. Dantes is
played by Gerard Depardieu, whose larger-than-life presence is just
right for this enjoyably fluffy extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the 1844 novel by Alexandre Dumas pere, this
French-Italian-American costume drama never takes itself too
seriously as it tells the story of the wronged Dantes who, after
his escape, discovers a fortune in a treasure chest and uses it to
get revenge on his betrayers. But the mini-series never winks at
the audience either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Count of Monte Cristo'' indulges its straightforward,
old-fashioned spirit. Loaded with action and as many coincidences
as can be crammed into its eight hours (including commercials),
this is the kind of film in which capes are always flying as men
dash off on horseback. There are poison potions and nick-of-time
antidotes, thwarted romances and duels, murders, a guillotining and
even a sultan's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Playing over four nights on Bravo, in French with English with
subtitles, ``The Count'' is a major investment of time, not to
mention eyesight. But it is a treat for anyone inclined to sink
into a world of sumptuous settings and tangled, overwrought plots
(though it may not be energetic enough to grab anyone who is not
predisposed to such over-the-top entertainments).
</P>
<P>
   Dantes devises ingenious strategies to destroy his enemies, but
he was not always so clever. While still in prison, at the start of
Episode I, he recalls in flashback how he came to be there. As a
young sailor he naively carried a letter from Elba that plotted
Napoleon's escape from the island.
</P>
<P>
   In prison he picks up valuable knowledge. Abbe Faria, the priest
whose death helps him escape, has directed Dantes to the island of
Monte Cristo and the treasure chest brimming with jewels. When
Dantes lets huge emeralds and diamonds flow through his hands like
sand, it is a stereotypical but satisfying image.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he is in Marseilles and Paris, and the series becomes more
than a costume drama; it is now a costume-upon-costume drama.
Adopting a fictional identity to suit his immense fortune, Dantes
calls himself the count of Monte Cristo and begins seeking his
revenge. This allows Depardieu to appear in a series of conspicuous
wigs and alarming noses, with the count masquerading as a priest,
Abbe Busconi and an English banker, Lord Wilmore.
</P>
<P>
   In all his escapades he is aided by his Italian servant and
right-hand man, Bertuccio, an indispensable Sancho Panza figure
played with flair by Sergio Rubini. (Look closely and you'll see
that the Italian actors' mouths do not always match the French they
are speaking.) The count is especially intent on destroying
Villefort, the judge who sent him to prison, and the Count de
Morcerf, a onetime friend who sent an anonymous letter betraying
him. Morcerf is now married to Dantes' former fiancee, the
beautiful Mercedes (Ornella Muti). When she meets the count,
Mercedes looks into his eyes and drops her tea cup on her valuable
carpet, without letting on whether she has actually recognized her
one true love or not.
</P>
<P>
   In a bit of stunt casting in Episode I, the younger versions of
these characters are played by Depardieu's son, Guillaume
Depardieu, and Ms. Muti's daughter, Naike Rivelli. In a more
substantial role, Depardieu's daughter, Julie Depardieu, gracefully
plays Villefort's sweet-natured daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard Depardieu has played many costumed heros in his career,
sometimes overdoing the swagger. Here he is at his restrained best.
The count glowers at his enemies and looks believably confused and
touched in his scenes with Mercedes and her grown son. But most of
the time he is simply racing around 19th-century France, followed
by Bertuccio and some turbaned servants he has picked up on a trip
to the Far East.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Count of Monte Cristo'' is not rich in psychological
insight, but it does suggest that bribery and deviousness will get
you everywhere. Though the count learns to forgive at the end, that
tacked-on lesson is less convincing than his gleefully vengeful
escapades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think I like being the Count of Monte Cristo?'' he asks
Bertuccio. ``He is terrifying, ruthless and cold. I didn't want to
become that man.''
</P>
<P>
   But a more truthful statement has come from Bertuccio after one
of their early adventures: ``You had fun, didn't you?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL; 
`THE COUNT OF MONTE CRISTO' &QL; 
Monday on Brave. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
