u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT &LR;      06-20 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS AND GRAF SEEK GRANDEUR AT WIMBLEDON 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ The wrought-iron gates are polished, the
bloom is on the roses twining through the courtside trellises and
the grass will never be greener. The last Wimbledon of the 20th
century is open for business, and the mood is a combination of
elegiac and electric.
</P>
<P>
   Some players are making an imprint here for the first time, and
some, like Boris Becker, for the last, but they are united in their
prayers for sustained sunshine and in their awe of the event that
treats them all like royalty and offers the best of them the chance
to rule their sport's most cherished castle, Center Court, in two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you took a census of all the players, I think Wimbledon is
the greatest tournament to win,'' said Andre Agassi, the
fourth-seeded player, whose recent French Open championship put his
name again in the history books, this time as the first man since
Rod Laver to win all four Grand Slam tournaments and the only man
to win his Grand Slams on three different surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   While grass is a surface that used to bemuse Agassi, the Las
Vegan became enamored of Wimbledon in 1992 when he won his first
major here. Since then, he has been a convert, and this year he is
eager to improve on recent poor play here: a first-round loss in
1996, an injury no-show in 1997 and a second-round exit last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes Wimbledon so enjoyable is not necessarily the
quality of the play,'' said the 29-year-old Agassi, who contends
that grass offers all the reliability of a banana peel underfoot,
``but what you're witnessing. You're part of a sporting event. It's
quite awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, there is history to be made here, and as usual, Pete
Sampras, Wimbledon's defending champion and its titleholder for
five of the past six years, is the man poised to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My form is there, my rhythm is there and my confidence is
back,'' said Sampras, whose game and attitude seem to respond to
Wimbledon the way a patch of parched turf responds to a dose of
fertilizer and water.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras expressed little apprehension about Scott Draper, his
opponent when he inaugurates Center Court on Monday. ``I raise the
bar whenever I come here. Knowing you've won before _ done it five
times _ gives you a good feeling about being able to go out and do
it again. For me at Wimbledon, it's all about expectation, not
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   The top-ranked Sampras, who won the Queen's grass title nine
days ago in London, is seeking his third consecutive Wimbledon
victory and sixth overall, a coup that would make him the first man
in 110 years to rule these lawns with such prolonged authority.
Should he succeed, Sampras, who is 39-1 over the last six seasons
here, will break his second-place tie with Bjorn Borg and Laver and
share Roy Emerson's record of 12 Grand Slam championships.
</P>
<P>
   Just as fond of this place, and as decorated by it, is Steffi
Graf. She tiptoes across the grounds of the All England Club like a
prima ballerina and is one of the few women players refusing to
berate this Grand Slam for paying the women $1.2 million less in
prize money than the men. Now she will try to insure that her
campaign for an eighth Wimbledon title is not anticlimactic to her
sixth French Open title, which she won two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still ``drunk with success'' after capturing her 22rd Grand Slam
championship at Roland Garros, a milestone she gilded by announcing
her retirement from that Grand Slam, the second-seeded Graf said
she isn't sure whether a title here would inspire a similar
declaration.
</P>
<P>
   At 30, Graf's body continues to be as fine-tuned as a Ferrari,
but beneath the sleek facade there is a chronically sore spine that
continues to test her pain threshold. Since Graf does not emulate
Sampras' reverence for records, the fact that she is just two Grand
Slam victories short of tying Margaret Court's record is not a
motivating force for continuing _ or quitting _ tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I win, I'm not ruling out anything,'' Graf said on Saturday
as she roamed the hallways beneath Center Court after her final
full-scale practice session for Monday's opener against Slovakia's
Ludmilla Cervanova, the 99th-ranked player. Graf used the French
Open as her practice session for Wimbledon and came away with a
title she thought she was far too tired to win. Here her
expectations, and her energy level, are higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because I won in Paris doesn't mean I'll win here, too,
but I feel more confident without a doubt,'' said Graf, who, just
in case this is her last Wimbledon, has coaxed John McEnroe back
onto a mixed doubles court for the first time in 20 years. ``I'm in
it now for the special moments, not planning that this or that may
be my last match, but just letting things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   One player with big plans for Wimbledon is top-ranked Martina
Hingis, who disgraced herself with her teen-age temper tantrum
during the French Open final against Graf.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly penitent, but aware that her behavior _ which Graf
characterized as unconscionable for any player, champion or not _
has burned some bridges between her and her public, Hingis
predicted a more businesslike approach to Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you will see a different Martina at Wimbledon, a
happier Martina,'' said Hingis, who won here in 1997. Hingis opens
against 16-year-old Elena Dokic, the Australian qualifier whose
father, Damir, was ejected nearly two weeks ago from an event at
Birmingham, England, for drunken and disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   In other notable opening-day encounters, sixth-seeded Venus
Williams, whose 10th-seeded sister, Serena, withdrew because of the
flu, takes on fifth-ranked Miriam Oremans, and 17th-ranked Anna
Kournikova tackles Barbara Schwartz, the Austrian qualifier who
upset Venus Williams at Roland Garros.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
