<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY BALLET THERAPIST MAKES MO BETTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mo Vaughn in a tutu?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. But the Anaheim Angels' burly designated hitter
could be back at first base Friday when the Angels open a six-game
homestand, thanks to the New York City Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, hobbled by a badly sprained left ankle since the first
game of the season, visited the ballet's physical therapist Friday
for a rigorous session that broke down scar tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been doing it three times a day since we've been here
and it has made all the difference,'' Vaughn said after Sunday's
4-2 victory over the Yankees. ``I mean it was serious. I was in
there sweating. Rotating the foot, really stretching it out. And it
worked. It feels great. I'm getting back as soon as I can. I've had
enough of this DH stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn played first base for three games in Dodger Stadium,
where there was no DH, and will work out in the field today before
the Angels' exhibition game against the club's Double-A team in
Erie, Penn. But he will remain the DH during the upcoming
three-game series in Seattle, which will be played on artificial
turf.
</P>
<P>
   Goin' deep: Matt Luke, the former Dodger called up six days ago,
hit a two-run homer in his first start (LF) with the Angels. It was
an added bonus that it came against the Yankees, the team that
drafted him in 1992. ``I feel great to have made a contribution in
a big win, but it feels especially good to happen here,'' he said.
``You see guys you played with and it is good to get their respect.
I plan on sticking around here and having a long career.''
</P>
<P>
   Luke spent five days with the Yankees in 1996, scoring as a
pinch runner but never batting in the big leagues until he joined
the Dodgers last year. He hit 12 home runs but was not re-signed,
joining the Angels as a non-roster invitee to spring training. Luke
started the season on the disabled list with an inflamed left rib
cage before hitting .421 (9 for 21) in six games with Triple-A
Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Goin' deeper: Third baseman Troy Glaus seemed to have put an
awful May behind him when he was named American League Player of
the Week on June 6 after batting .550 (11 for 20) with three homers
and six RBI.
</P>
<P>
   But since then Glaus has stumbled badly; no game has been worse
than Sunday's, when he struck out twice and hit into two double
plays. Since his streak ended, Glaus is 7 for 32 and 4 for 22 on
the trip. He went 1 for 12 against the Yankees and was hitless in
his last nine at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today all he was taking was home run swings,'' hitting
instructor Rod Carew said. ``There was no discipline. He has to get
back to just wanting to make contact on a consistent basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: When Tino Martinez shattered his bat popping out to
open the seventh, it struck on-deck hitter Paul O'Neill in the left
leg. O'Neill was on the ground for several minutes before coming to
the plate and singling to right. The next batter, Chili Davis, also
broke his bat and the barrel nearly struck O'Neill as he ran to
second.... To start the ninth inning the Angels went with Troy
Percival, who hadn't pitched in a week, and catcher Steve Decker,
who was making just his second start behind the plate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
