<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-POLL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW MANAGERS EXPECTING YEAR 2000 GLITCHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the latest sign of growing confidence about the millennium
computer challenge, a poll last week of American corporate managers
involved in year 2000 projects found that 83 percent expect
calendar-related glitches to have little or no impact on their
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 42 percent of the nearly 900 managers polled said they
had become more confident in the past three months. That figure
compared with only 4.2 percent who said they had become more
pessimistic about the rollover to Jan. 1, 2000, when many computers
could have problems because they might not recognize that the
two-digit figure ``00'' represents the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The poll was conducted by CIO Magazine, a publication for chief
information officers, the Information Systems Audit and Control
Association and a year 2000 clearinghouse run by Edward Yardeni,
the chief economist of Deutsche Bank Securities. Yardeni and CIO's
editor, Gary Beach, are known in year 2000 circles for arguing that
risks are being underestimated and that too many people are not
prepared for disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   But the vast majority of those polled disagreed with Yardeni's
oft-cited warning that year 2000 disruptions are likely to lead to
a worldwide recession. Only 7.3 percent expect a recession, and
less than 1 percent expect a major depression. In fact, 9 percent
say the economic impact could end up being positive.
</P>
<P>
   The poll seemed to confirm that fear of lawsuits is preventing
some companies from being honest about their year 2000 readiness,
but the impact is not as worrisome as many year 2000 alarmists
imagine. Just 1.5 percent said they were in much worse shape than
their companies had disclosed publicly. By contrast, 26.4 percent
said they were better off than they were admitting.
</P>
<P>
   Yardeni warned that the poll results might have been skewed
toward a rosy outlook because companies with more than 1,000
employees accounted for 61 percent of the responses, and 26 percent
were from the financial sector. Large companies in general and
financial-sector businesses in particular have shown up repeatedly
in research to be further along in dealing with year 2000 problems
than business as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more cautionary findings: Only 8.4 percent of the
companies surveyed have actually completed their year 2000 work;
one in three is running behind schedule; about half expect at least
one ``mission critical'' failure, and more than one out of every
three projects are currently waiting for software vendors to
deliver critical programs.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also asked about personal plans. Almost 12 percent of
the managers see year 2000 as a ``nonevent'' and nearly 60 percent
are following government recommendations to prepare for short-term
disruptions of less than a week. Others expect anything from
problems lasting for weeks to a ``catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   Most said they would be working or on call on Jan. 1, although
25 percent said they would be free to stay home. But 1 percent told
the surveyors that they planned to stay home even though they had
been told they would be required to work.
</P>
</TEXT>
