u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOPPERS-MYSTERY-SPI &LR;      06-20 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPERS-MYSTERY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY SHOPPERS - SLEUTHS FOR HIRE CHECK SERVICE OF RETAILERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Heather Larson doesn't look like a mysterious woman
with a double life.
</P>
<P>
   At first encounter, she's middle-aged, soft-spoken, with minimal
makeup _ unobtrusive, unlikely to stand out in a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in sensible shoes, flowered dress and a cardigan
sweater, Larson is an accounts payable specialist with a suburban
school district in the Seattle area.
</P>
<P>
   But in her other life _ wearing a baseball cap, jeans and
sneakers _ she's a mystery shopper for hire.
</P>
<P>
   She'll spend her off-hours hanging around movie theaters or
hardware stores. Or she might take her car in for an oil change, or
put on a special dress to visit a top-rated restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Larson is a sleuth who shops retail stores, apartment houses,
banks and other providers of goods and services. Her undercover
work helps retailers determine how they rank in service, quality,
cleanliness and other key issues with customers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a job she's been doing since the '70s, when she was home
with two preschoolers and looking for part-time work. She answered
an ad and was hired as a mystery shopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to eat in seven Jack in the Box restaurants every two
weeks. Sometimes we went to three in one night,'' Larson says.
After each meal she'd file a report. She did this for three years,
leaving her daughter with an addiction to Breakfast Jacks.
</P>
<P>
   When her children entered school, Larson branched out to car
washes, apartment rentals and banks. Now she works for about 20
different companies and checks Internet listings for other
interesting shopping jobs in this area.
</P>
<P>
   Larson says there's a great demand for mystery shoppers because
retail competition is fierce. With so many stores selling the same
merchandise at similar prices, only service and other side issues
differentiate them.
</P>
<P>
   Retail operators want to know how their customers are being
treated, and how their stores rate with consumers. Owners often
want to know what goes on when they're away. They rely on mystery
shoppers to tell them.
</P>
<P>
   It may sound interesting, even glamorous, but the life of a
mystery shopper can be boring and routine. ``It's good for extra
money, but I don't recommend it as a career change,'' Larson says.
</P>
<P>
   She describes an assignment in a megastore where she had to
interact with personnel in 17 different departments. She couldn't
find a salesperson in some of them, so she had to keep checking
back until she did.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the details that have to be remembered:
Background music, employee hygiene and appearance, number of loose
carts in a grocery store lot, etc. Each assignment and report has
different demands.
</P>
<P>
   Take a movie theater, for example, one of Larson's favorite
assignments.
</P>
<P>
   She has to arrive early and check the cleanliness of the parking
lot and the theater. She notes the ticket vendor's attitude and
makes certain she gets correct change when she buys her ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop is the concession stand to buy a snack and see if the
attendant is tending to business. Lobby and restroom are evaluated
for cleanliness. Larson then sits in the back of the theater so she
can count the house _ not always easy with patrons coming and
going. Finally, she evaluates quality of sound and picture.
</P>
<P>
   All this information has to be remembered for the written
report.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Larson decided mystery shoppers could use a
training class, because manuals and forms provided by employers
didn't prepare shoppers for the reality of the job.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote a proposal and sent it to community colleges in the
area. Renton Technical College and Highline Community College, both
south of Seattle, accepted. Now she teaches about 20 classes per
year.
</P>
<P>
   Students learn how to make detailed, factual reports and how to
interact with salespeople. ``I tell my classes to dress beige. They
don't want to be noticed,'' she says. That means no logos or
artwork on clothing that might make a mystery shopper memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Her classes are popular with retired people, business owners or
managers who want to know how mystery shopping works, and young
women in their 20s looking for part-time employment.
</P>
<P>
   She tells them how to avoid scams _ never pay to get a shopping
job _ and how to work the Internet to find them. Larson even gives
tips on keeping track of expenses for tax purposes.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who calls herself Ann Rogers _ not her real name, she
wants to stay anonymous _ took Larson's class last September. She
got her first assignment in October and ``I've just bloomed from
there,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She likes mystery shopping so much that she's now spending 30 to
40 hours a week at the job. Rogers has checked out fast-food
franchises and spent hours dining in a top Seattle restaurant.
She's also spent 40 minutes in a small store waiting for a
salesperson to approach her _ something specified in her
assignment. The three women on duty ignored her.
</P>
<P>
   She makes $10 to $30 per assignment. When visiting a restaurant,
mystery shoppers are usually given a set amount to spend on dinner
for two, and sometimes told what to order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking the course is a great way to find out what's expected
of you and how to go about it,'' Rogers says. ``You always have a
choice of assignments, and you're never forced to take a shop you
don't want. But it is work.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Worthley owns The Genesis Group, a Bellevue-based firm
specializing in customer service surveys. ``I hate the term
`mystery shopping.' It denotes spying on people,'' Worthley says.
</P>
<P>
   Worthley was managing a retail clothing store in the 1970s when
corporate headquarters told him his store would be checked out
anonymously sometime during a two-week period.
</P>
<P>
   Worthley and his staff were at their best during that time,
greeting customers and providing top-quality service. Sales went up
and Worthley took note.
</P>
<P>
   He began learning more about mystery shoppers and what they
could do for companies. Today he has clients in 42 states and a
database of 9,000 shoppers he can deploy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every store you go into hires shoppers _ wineries, hospitals,
clinics, restaurants,'' Worthley says. ``Companies who hire us
really want to change the culture of their organization.''
</P>
<P>
   He says there are just three issues in business: The product or
service, the price and the level of service. ``That's why service
today is so much more serious,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   When Worthley founded Genesis in 1991, there were only about 150
other customer survey companies in the country. Today there are
about 700, complete with a professional association (Mystery
Shoppers Providers Association) to set standards.
</P>
<P>
   Worthley likes to hire people with some retail exposure, people
who have seen the best and worst of service, actors, people with
flexible schedules.
</P>
<P>
   He likes to introduce his program to company employees and
explain to them how mystery shoppers work so they will feel
involved, not threatened by them. He also encourages companies to
reward good service.
</P>
<P>
   Worthley sees surveys as a coaching tool to help companies
refocus their energies and teach sales skills and hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to catch people doing something right,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
