<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990620.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2918 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FANFAIR-NASHVILLE-2TA     06-20 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANFAIR-NASHVILLE-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE COUNTRY STARS GO TO PRESS THE FLESH
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ In rap music, it's called keeping it real. In the
pop world, it's known as keeping your feet on the ground. In soul,
it's payback. And in rock-and-roll, it's remembering your roots.
</P>
<P>
   But nowhere is the practice of celebrity humility _ of stars
showing fans that they're simultaneously one of them but also
worthy of their veneration _ more widespread and wholeheartedly
embraced than in country music at the annual Fan Fair, which took
place at the Tennessee State Fairgrounds over the last week. Every
year since 1972, the biggest stars in country music have rented
booths at Fan Fair and sat there patiently, giving autographs,
posing for photos, chatting with fans and in some cases giving away
(or auctioning) their clothes and belongings. It's like a giant
swap meet with a star at the helm of almost every booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that you could do this in any other genre of
music,'' said the singer-songwriter Steve Wariner, pausing from a
special hourlong autograph session for his handicapped fans to
imagine the pandemonium that would ensue if Bruce Springsteen, John
Mellencamp, Pearl Jam and half a dozen other rockers gathered under
one roof for an open house.
</P>
<P>
   Wariner, one of Nashville's most enduring stars who began
signing autographs here in 1978, then recalled a legendary incident
from Fan Fair three years ago. Garth Brooks met with his admirers
for 24 hours straight, by Wariner's account, without a bathroom
break.
</P>
<P>
   But something was different at Fan Fair this year. There was no
Garth _ and no Shania Twain or Dixie Chicks or Reba McIntyre. Some
country stars, fans grumbled, are getting too swell-headed for
their cowboy hats.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year Shania Twain couldn't get anybody to get in her line
for an autograph,'' recalled Vince Smith, a 39-year-old restaurant
employee who drove in from Toronto and pitched his tent outside the
fair at 10 p.m. Wednesday to be among the first in line when the
gates opened at 9:30 on Thursday morning. ``The next year it was so
crowded you couldn't get into Shania's line. And now she doesn't
even bother.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoebe Cowart, an office manager from Indiana, said: ``We're
here for them. They should be here for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for the missing musicians said Brooks was
completing a rock concept album in Los Angeles, the Dixie Chicks
were touring Europe, Ms. McIntyre was making a movie in Canada and
Ms. Twain was completing a Northeast tour with a Madison Square
Garden performance.
</P>
<P>
   Other hot stars who performed in town the week of Fan Fair
either did not set up booths for autograph sessions or canceled
autograph appearances. The most in demand of them were Trisha
Yearwood and the country power couple of Tim McGraw and Faith Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Partly as a result, attendance at Fan Fair dropped. Though in
past years the event has sold out a month ahead of time, this year
2,000 of its 24,000 tickets (priced at $90 for the last three
years) went unsold despite the participation of nearly 200 country
singers, including LeAnn Rimes, Alan Jackson, Clint Black, Wynonna,
Neil McCoy, Vince Gill and Brooks and Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `Is this the death of Fan Fair?''' said Ed Benson,
the executive director of the Country Music Association, the music
support group that runs Fan Fair. ``I tell them it's the exhaustion
of the artists. We need to figure out how to manage the
expectations of fans against the reality of the artists.''
</P>
<P>
   In the world of country music, stars are not supposed to be
larger than life. They are supposed to be the embodiment of real
life, the perfect ideal of the everyday person. Explaining why they
liked performers like the new and improved David Ball and the
fantastic-voiced Sara Evans at Fan Fair, audience members made
comments like ``he looks like a guy you could sit down with and
tell your problems to'' and ``her mother was the kind of woman you
might see at Wal-Mart.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, musicians _ cognizant of the Dale Carnegie
dictum that the sweetest sound to people is the sound of their own
name _ make it a point to remember the names of admirers who show
up at Fan Fair year after year for autographs.
</P>
<P>
   Where rock stars often try to protect their family from prying
fans, country musicians make it a point to show off their spouses
and children. At a private show for fan club members last week,
Alan Jackson _ after introducing his wife, his children and his
housekeeper _ reinvented housecleaning when he and his wife invited
two fans to their house to cart off their clutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how I could have sold a hundred million records?''
Garth Brooks once asked rhetorically. ``Sign every autograph I
could have.''
</P>
<P>
   But over the last few years the stakes in country music have
gotten much larger. Just as in the larger world of pop, the
superstars keep getting bigger. Brooks has become the best-selling
male solo artist in the history of popular music and Ms. Twain is
among the top-selling female singers. And country, according to the
Recording Industry Association of America, is the best-selling
music genre next to rock, despite a slight dip since a huge country
boom in the mid-'90s.
</P>
<P>
   This makes the goal of Fan Fair, to have every fan feel like he
or she is the star's friend, impossible. After all, artists at Fan
Fair are not expected just to sign autographs and remember names;
they are also supposed to engage their fans in conversation as if
they were making small talk at a bar.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps some artists have stopped making appearances at Fan Fair
because the normally polite and orderly audience is beginning to
get too large and rambunctious to please. When there was confusion
in a line to meet Gill this year and it seemed as if some people
weren't going to get his autograph, one fan made a display of
ripping up Gill's photograph in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made this town is going to break this town,'' said John
Gilman as he stood in a stall for the Great Escape, a local record
store. ``Country music is growing too much. People can go anywhere
now to see it. They don't have to come to Nashville.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of a changing world of country was also provided in the
demographic shifts at Fan Fair. There was an increase in the number
of families (from young children to great-grandmothers) and more
tellingly, a large rise in teen-agers and preteens, Benson said.
Girls squealed as cute, boyish singers like Bryan White and South
Sixty-Five (country's inevitable answer to the Backstreet Boys)
walked into the building, evidence of the transformation of country
cowboys from the man next door to the boy on the pedestal.
</P>
<P>
   A new singer, Brad Hawkins, had no fans lined up at his booth
when he arrived at Fan Fair the first day. But word soon spread
among female fans that he was a hunk. And on day two Hawkins
arrived at his booth surprised to find that a line had formed for
him. It was rare evidence of a pop phenomena being created
literally overnight.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Country Music Association, women now account
for 65 percent of the audience in this genre, which was once
dominated by male fans. And in response the marketing of country
artists has begun to change. ``Look,'' hissed one manager as he
tried to explain the popularity of a booth featuring a young singer
without a recording contract, Greg Rowles. ``He kisses on the
lips.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowles was indeed giving very long, smoldering hugs to the women
who visited his small booth, some of whom dreamily compared his
looks to Ricky Martin. ``He's going to make it,'' said Sandra
Whitton, a 41-year-old nurse from Indiana, ``because of how he's
treating people.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his enthusiastic displays of affection for
strangers, Rowles, a former ``Star Search'' winner, explained:
``It's no technique. I do this with my family.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner from Rowles and directly across the aisle from
the young, hard-working Ms. Rimes sat a table full of old-time
musicians known as the Reunionairs. They weren't has-beens, they
were never-wases, and they sat there for the week virtually ignored
in the stampede of fans for Ms. Rimes and even for Rowles. It
wasn't a crime that they were being overlooked; it was evidence of
a pop music more interested in youth than tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't tell one artist from another,'' grumbled Raymond
(Cousin Ray) Woolsend, an 83-year-old disk jockey and the
Reunionairs' president, who sat proudly in his wheelchair. ``Now
they have no change in voices, no real songs and too much drums in
the leads. Musicians of yesteryear were just like uncles and
cousins, like family. They're not that way today.''
</P>
<P>
   The simple, thematically decorated booths at the fair were
packed side by side in several cavernous, brightly lighted and
distinctly unglamorous exhibition halls patrolled by a kindly
security staff that consisted mostly of local schoolteachers on
summer break. Lines of fans, many of them families on their annual
vacation and nourished by free meals ladled out of giant vats by
the Odessa Chuck Wagon Gang, were tightly coiled around each
building, lined up for hours to meet their heroes, who were either
dressed like Wariner in jeans and a T-shirt or like the faux
bad-boys Montgomery Gentry in exaggerated cowboy garb.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the booths, the event also offered fan-friendly
concerts by most of the popular acts. Instead of barricading the
area in front of the stage, a path was created so that fans could
walk by and take photographs, offer presents to and sometimes shake
hands with the artists as they performed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People outside of country music look at us and tell us we're
nuts,'' Clint Black told a cheering Fan Fair audience on Wednesday
night. ``They don't see this in other areas of entertainment, and
they're kind of surprised by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many participants and ticket-buyers wondered whether, with talk
of the convention moving downtown to the Nashville Arena next year,
the friendly, familial community of Fan Fair would give way to an
event that was simply a big, impersonal concert. It is a fear
reflected in one of the biggest and best recent country hits, Alan
Jackson's barrel-voiced eulogy for ``the little man that built this
town before the big money shut him down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless the little man,'' Jackson concludes the song,
offering a celebration of and lament for not just the independent
shopkeeper but also the denizens of the Fair, fan and artist alike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
