</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DRIVE-IN-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MOSCOW DRIVE-IN OFFERS CABBAGE AND PROMISES OF POPCORN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to add art note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It is true that the men behind the first and only
drive-in movie in Russia overlooked a few things, such as telling
the audience that films are best viewed with headlights off. Also,
popcorn. Somehow, a drive-in isn't quite the same munching on
cabbage pie.
</P>
<P>
   But those are nits. With a hastily built 56-by-30-foot screen
and a projection booth mounted on stilts, three Moscow
entrepreneurs staged a two-night dry run over the weekend of the
quintessentially American motion picture experience, and appeared
to have a hit on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, once the sun set _ that is, in this northern season of
bright summer solstice nights, at about 11:20 p.m. _ the Moscow
Kinodrome could well have been the Kenwood in Louisville or the
Moonlight in Pittsburgh instead of what it was: a deserted parking
lot, hard by an equally deserted velodrome built for the 1980
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing to have, just to relax,'' said 30-year-old
Igor Martinov as he stood by his red Nissan, downing beers and
smoking L&AMP;Ms. ``And if you have a good car with shaded windows,''
he grinned, ``it's a very good thing for young kids to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Drive-ins may be a dying breed in the United States, where their
number has shrunk to about 500 from 10 times that at the peak of
their popularity. But the story may well be different in Moscow, a
place desperately short of theaters and where the economics of
moviegoing is completely different.
</P>
<P>
   While most American drive-ins aim for the teen-age crowd or the
family seeking a cheap night out, the backers of the Kinodrome have
their sights on a slightly older, more upscale crowd. When it
reopens _ the theater is in hiatus after its two-night premiere _
it will cost 195 rubles per person, or $8, for a movie and a light
meal.
</P>
<P>
   While the Olympic complex has seen better days, the drive-in is
in one of the city's finer neighborhoods, a mile from President
Boris Yeltsin's city apartment and not far from clusters of luxury
high-rise apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Volkov, who came up with the idea after seeing
drive-ins in Hungary and Germany, said in an interview that the
backers decided to expand on one partner's successful experience
running 16 nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's based on the idea that in Moscow in the summertime, a
great number of people are living the night life,'' he said, ``and
secondly, that Moscovites love to watch films. We found that there
are a great number of people who haunt these clubs during the night
and prefer to sit not inside, but outside. They ask to move their
tables to the open.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the Kinodrome sports an outdoor cafe at the rear of the
parking lot, where filmgoers can buy apple, mushroom and cabbage
pies, fruit-stuffed pirozhki, or pastries, American soft drinks,
beer and _ soon _ vodka.
</P>
<P>
   The drive-in itself is a decidedly makeshift affair. The parking
lot, equipped with green gates to keep freeloaders out, holds only
150 cars and lacks a ticket booth. The screen is anything but
oversized, and the cramped projection room inexplicably flies a
skull-and-crossbones and is draped in camouflage netting.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the two water-cooled projectors were salvaged from the
defunct October Theater on Moscow's Novy Arbat, which is being
gutted and turned into a multiscreen cineplex. As there are no
water lines running to the lot, the projectionists' great fear _
unrealized, fortunately _ was that the evenings' feature films
would catch fire.
</P>
<P>
   Critics might have called that no great loss. Although the
Kinodrome promises the best in Russian and foreign film, the main
events Thursday and Friday were an American sci-fi potboiler,
``Virus,'' and one of the Mel Gibson vehicles, ``Lethal Weapon 4.''
</P>
<P>
   But the premiere audiences, lured by free tickets and the
novelty of it all, didn't seem to care. College girls and boys
strolled up and down the rows of obediently lined-up Audis,
Mustangs and other imported cars, looking for each other. In one
expensive-looking sport utility vehicle, Andrei Bezlepkin, his wife
and their two children said they were there strictly on a lark.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter Julia, 15, had seen three of the Lethal Weapon
films, but her dad was clueless. ``I think it's something like
Weapons Number Four,'' he said when asked about the night's
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   On the road by the theater, dozens more cars _ including one
police cruiser _ squeezed onto the gravel shoulder on Friday night
seeking their own free view. Still more people simply walked in and
squatted on the pavement, straining to catch the soundtrack
broadcast from the projection booth to car radios.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some glitches. At Thursday's first showing,
drivers in the front row had to be told to switch off their
headlights. Some who came on motorcycles or in cars without radios
were disappointed to find that they were watching a silent movie.
One walk-in, clearly there more for the beer than the movie, rose
in the middle of one presentation to demand that the sound be
turned up.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it a seamlessly American experience. For one thing, the
brief Russian summer nights mean that the first showing doesn't end
until close to 1 a.m., and the second finishes around first light.
The viewing season is also brief: the Kinodrome will close for the
winter in October, a projectionist said, because the oil in the
projectors freezes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at least one oversight is about to be remedied. When the
Kinodrome reopens later this month, Volkov said, it will serve
popcorn.
</P>
