<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TELECOMMUNICATIONS DEALS CONFUSING MANY INVESTORS
</P>
<P>
   Communications companies are all too aware that if they do not
transform themselves _ with one foot in the Internet and the other
in the more traditional world of copper wires _ they face certain
death. But the combinations deemed necessary to do that are
wreaking havoc on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent example is the takeover battle between Global
Crossing and Qwest Communications for Frontier and U S West.
Investors are surprised by what these and other companies aspire to
become and question how those ambitions fit their investing
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T PLEDGES CABLE FRATERNITY
</P>
<P>
   In his keynote address at the annual convention of the National
Cable Television Association, Michael Armstrong, the chairman of
AT&AMP;T, made his shrewd social debut as he tries to build AT&AMP;T into
the United States' biggest cable operator. At its highest levels,
cable is a fraternity, and AT&AMP;T is seen as a rich but untested
prodigy.
</P>
<P>
   `LIVE' PAY-PER-VIEW WEB BROADCAST
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock.com, an Internet music start-up, has announced what it
bills as the first pay-per-view Webcast of a live event _ even if
the concert in question did take place last year. On Friday, the
company will offer a Webcast of a Sarah McLachlan concert, to be
seen simultaneously on pay-per-view cable television in many
cities. The nearly two-hour performance was recorded in April 1998
in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA ONLINE WARY OF MICROSOFT
</P>
<P>
   Documents and testimony offered at Microsoft's antitrust trial,
during the appearance of an America Online senior vice president,
disclosed that the online service's leaders still feel seriously
constrained, even threatened, by Microsoft's power.
</P>
<P>
   AS PC PRICES FALL, SO DO PROFITS
</P>
<P>
   As PC Expo gets under way this week at the Javits Convention
Center in New York, the show's organizers are sounding a theme of
``smarter, faster, cheaper'' and highlighting the trend toward
powerful, portable devices. But among personal-computer makers, the
theme might as well be ``where have all the profits gone,'' as
cutthroat competition continues to erode earnings.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS MAGAZINES DOMINATE SUMMER
</P>
<P>
   Television programmers have bloated summer evenings with reruns
and news magazines, which always earn good ratings and advertising
revenue during the summer. But even the news magazine may be in
danger of being overdone. For the first time, the three major news
divisions have all scheduled hourlong news magazines five nights a
week.
</P>
<P>
   WEB POPULARITY PERPETUATES ITSELF
</P>
<P>
   Bringing statistical support to an increasingly common Internet
wisdom, two researchers have found that the most popular Web sites
command the biggest share of Internet traffic and tend to gain an
accelerating advantage over their competitors.
</P>
<P>
   NEW DESIGNER FOR NATIONAL ENQUIRER
</P>
<P>
   Roger Black, the designer who has applied his rigorous aesthetic
eye to the pages of The New Republic and Reader's Digest, is about
to embark on an entirely different design adventure: The National
Enquirer. David Pecker, the chairman of American Media Inc., which
publishes The National Enquirer and Star, has hired Black and two
ad agencies to reposition the tabloids.
</P>
</TEXT>
