<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-AD-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS DELIVER SMORGASBORD TO FILL ORDER FOR YOUNG VIEWERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Remember the episode of ``The Twilight Zone'' when a
horrified woman discovered that a book written by space visitors
called ``To Serve Man'' was actually a cookbook? Well, a book about
the 1999-2000 season for the broadcast television networks could be
titled ``To Serve Youth.''
</P>
<P>
   But now Madison Avenue is wondering whether that book will be a
best seller or a recipe for failure.
</P>
<P>
   For years, agencies and advertisers have exhorted broadcast TV
to appeal to younger viewers _ 12 to 24, 18 to 34, 18 to 49 _
because they are deemed more desirable consumers than their older
counterparts: more willing to spend, to try new products, to switch
brands. Besides, younger consumers, particularly teen-age and
20-something males, watch less television, making those who do
watch much more valuable to marketers.
</P>
<P>
   The ``dot com'' advertisers pitching computers, Web sites and
other high-technology products and services, whose dollars are
beginning to flood into TV, are licking their chops over the
millions of wired consumers in Generations X and Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's looking for young eyeballs,'' said Jamie Kellner,
president of the WB network in Burbank, Calif., which is owned by
Time Warner and the Tribune Co. and is enjoying strong gains in ad
revenue by delivering marketers audiences aged 12 to 24.
</P>
<P>
   So broadcasters are racing to add programs aimed at younger
viewers to their prime-time schedules for the coming season. By one
count, 18 of 37 new series on the six broadcast networks will look
at the world through youth-colored glasses, joining more than a
dozen returning series with similar skews.
</P>
<P>
   Among the newcomers: ``Freaks and Geeks'' on NBC, ``Manchester
Prep'' and ``Ryan Caulfield'' on the Fox Broadcasting Co. and
``Snoops'' and ``Then Came You'' on Walt Disney's ABC, as well as
more youthful fare for WB like ``Angel,'' ``Roswell'' and
``Popular.'' UPN, owned by Viacom, will appeal to young males with
a wrestling show called ``WWF Smackdown!'' and a Friday movie
called ``Blockbuster Video's Shockwave Cinema.''
</P>
<P>
   Even CBS, the network first in older viewers, is seeking to
climb down the demographic ladder a couple of rungs, pairing
younger and older cast members in new series like ``Judging Amy.''
</P>
<P>
   But after all those entreaties to broadcasters to think young,
some agency executives worry that the pendulum may be swinging too
far too fast in one direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too much of the same thing,'' said Paul Schulman,
president of Schulman/Advanswers NY, a media services agency in New
York owned by the Omnicom Group. ``People are copying the WB.''
</P>
<P>
   A primary concern is that the broadcast networks will be
diverted from an audience they ought to be pursuing: the aging baby
boomers, the 76 million consumers born from 1946 to 1964 whose
incomes for the most part dwarf those of younger viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being associated with youth is a positive because people like
to envision themselves as young, virile, active,'' said Stacey Lynn
Koerner, vice president for broadcast television research at TN
Media in New York, the media services arm of True North
Communications. ``That's our American culture. Advertisers like to
be in environments where there's a perception that positive things
are going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is no reason to believe older people are less
willing to try new things,'' she added. ``And there are different
levels to it. I might be 15 and want to do what my friends do. I
might be 45 and want the new Mercedes my neighbor has.''
</P>
<P>
   The executives also warn that the youth movement may conflict
with the traditional mission of broadcast TV: to reach the widest
audiences possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``A broadcaster is exactly that, a `broad-caster,''' Ms. Koerner
said, adding: ``Broadcasters can't narrow themselves to one
audience and remain viable. They have to in some sense be all
things to all people.''
</P>
<P>
   If broadcasters narrow their focus to fixate on youth, according
to this school of thought, they run the risk of becoming clones of
cable networks, which most commonly aim their programming at
smaller, specific targets. That would then weaken the strongest
argument for advertising on broadcast TV.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasting ``doesn't exclude,'' said Bob Igiel, president for
the broadcast division of the Media Edge in New York, the media
services arm of Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. ``When you turn on the TV, a
sign doesn't come on saying `You're 50 and you can't watch this.'''
</P>
<P>
   The rush to satisfy young viewers, the critics fret, may also
exacerbate the longstanding problem the broadcast networks
confront: declining ratings. Shows that seemingly exclude older
viewers may send them away to alternative fare, thereby further
eroding audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``If two networks of six focus on youth, that's fine,'' said
Peter Chrisanthopoulos, president for broadcast and programming in
the United States at the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide agency in New
York, a unit of WPP Group PLC, ``because if viewers have enough
choices, they don't always have to go to cable. ``If more than two
do it,'' he added, ``they start to cannibalize one another and lose
more viewers to cable.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the network that most ardently believes in the
puissance of older consumers is CBS, which has the most older
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no strong economic reason for Madison Avenue's
fascination with the young audience,'' said David F. Poltrack,
executive vice president for research and planning at CBS
Television in New York. ``I've always called this the programmer's
dilemma, pursuing the segment of the audience for which there is
greatest competition, which watches less TV over all, because of
Madison Avenue's obsession. ``As the baby boomers move into an
older age group,'' he added, ``Madison Avenue will become
increasingly aware that's where the money is.''
</P>
<P>
   The other networks say they are becoming more youth-centric
simply to deliver what advertisers and agencies request.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not different from any other business with a
market-share war going on,'' said Randy Falco, president of the
NBC-TV Network unit of NBC in New York, part of the General
Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   So while broadcast TV is ``still the only place you can reach
the mass audience,'' he added, if ``the advertising community cares
about 18 to 49,'' those are the viewers who will receive special
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good television is about taking chances, trying to capture
lightning in a bottle,'' Falco said. ``With `Freaks and Geeks,' we
will take a chance, do something different. Every once in a while,
you hit on something.'' That new series is about high school life
in the 1980's
</P>
<P>
   At Fox, a unit of the News Corp., the focus has been on viewers
18 to 34; the network finished first in that age group for the
1998-99 season and second behind NBC in viewers 18 to 49.
</P>
<P>
   ``We attract a higher percentage of light television viewers,
which makes our audience more valuable because it's more difficult
to reach,'' said Jon Nesvig, president for sales at Fox in New
York. ``And that correlates with youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ``reaching the largest possible audience is still
important,'' he added, and Fox is looking to viewers 12 to 34 as
well as 25 to 54 for potential audience gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ratings erosion is a major concern,'' Nesvig said, ``but in
general the biggest issue is better programs. You still see the
audiences respond on a given night if there are good programs and
we get them to the set. It's still, `The play's the thing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Come fall, Madison Avenue will be watching the broadcast ratings
as closely as teen-agers watch ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' or
``Dawson's Creek'' on WB.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of us representing advertisers,'' said
Chrisanthopoulos at Ogilvy &AMP; Mather, ``it's good if a network has a
focus, a mission, and tries to fulfill its goals by focusing on the
audiences it desires.
</P>
<P>
   ``The youth focus is good as long as they all don't do it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
