<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-TV-NEWS-NYT &LR;      06-20 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-TV-NEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTEAD OF SUMMER RERUNS, NETWORKS REPACKAGE PRIME-TIME NEWS
SERIES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As surely as summer brings visions of beaches and barbecue
grills, it brings reruns to broadcast television. And by making a
big promotional fuss about their shows' season finales in May, the
networks basically close up shop and tell viewers, ``See you in
September.''
</P>
<P>
   When they wave goodbye, they often send those viewers to cable
television camp. But since prime-time sitcoms and dramas are so
expensive to produce, programmers have bloated summer evenings with
reruns _ and with news magazines, which always earn good Nielsen
ratings (and advertising revenue) in summer.
</P>
<P>
   But even the news magazine may be in danger of being overdone
this summer. For the first time, the three major news divisions
have all scheduled hourlong news magazines five nights a week. And
several of these ``new'' hours are actually repackagings, with past
news stories updated to tell viewers what has happened since the
original story.
</P>
<P>
   The new summer-only series are six weeks of a program called
``Vanished'' on ABC (Thursdays at 10 p.m.), followed by four
Thursdays of ``Nightline in Prime Time: Brave New World'' (also 10
p.m.), and, on CBS, two new nights of ``48 Hours,'' each with a
special theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``48 Hours: Monday Mysteries'' earned such solid Nielsen ratings
last summer, its debut ``season,'' that CBS executives asked CBS
News if there was anything else that could be done with the genre.
The result is ``48 Hours: Tuesday Adventures,'' which will revisit
adventure stories from various past CBS News programs, not just
from ``48 Hours'' itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity to reintroduce your audience to a show,''
said Leslie Moonves, president of CBS Television. ``If you told
people, `We're doing another ``48 Hours,'' ' there's no sizzle to
it _ it's not saying anything new. But this way we're adding new
material, and we'll be able promote it in a whole new way.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, ``48 Hours: Tuesday Adventures,'' by its
title, ``will attract men, and there's a real void for men on
Tuesday at 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Having a promotable theme, Moonves said, is important in the
summer, because viewers tend to assume most nights are filled with
repeats, and that puts them off.
</P>
<P>
   ABC News addressed the problem with ``Vanished,'' a series of
hourlong stories about people who have disappeared, either
voluntarily or involuntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves praised the theme of ``Vanished,''saying ``It's a smart
move by ABC _ it can be promoted almost like a movie of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   But does this trend mean journalists are being asked to skirt
the line between news and entertainment?
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider these shows to be entertaining, but I don't
consider them to be entertainment,'' said Phyllis McGrady, vice
president and executive producer of special projects for ABC News
and the executive in charge of the ``Vanished'' series, which
includes a new look at the Lindbergh baby's kidnapping in 1932 and
a potentially news-breaking report on Madalyn Murray O'Hair, the
renowned atheist who led the 1960s movement to ban prayer in public
schools and disappeared in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   For Susan Zirinsky, executive producer of ``48 Hours'' and its
summer offspring, there is nothing wrong with making news
entertaining as long as it is valid. And, she said, with new
information, updated segments are fresh to viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not just putting on another show _ I'm evolving the
story,'' said Ms. Zirinsky, whose original ``48 Hours'' will
continue to appear Thursdays at 10 p.m. all summer. ``It's a
satisfying thing, as a journalist, to be able to put an additional
chapter on a story, perhaps even the closing chapter.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC will continue five nights of ``Dateline,'' a scheduling
concept successful during the regular season, and ABC will continue
its four nights a week of ``20/20.'' Both will mix some repeat
episodes with original stories, as will ``60 Minutes II,'' on
Tuesdays at 9.
</P>
<P>
   The venerable ``60 Minutes,'' on Sunday nights at 7, always
reverts to reruns in summer, selecting a ``best of'' collection of
episodes in the hope that viewers will want to see them again.
Judging by its high summer ratings, viewers do.
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Zirinsky sees a bonus in the new nights. ``We now have
three nights when, if news breaks, I can dump the show and do an
hour on the news,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
