<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN'S-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROWD, ON AND OFF THE FIELD, FORCED SCURRY TO SCRAMBLE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the largest crowd to ever see a women's sporting event in
the United States, larger than any crowd for a Giants game or a
Jets game, larger than any audience ever at Giants Stadium except
for the pope. That would be Pope John Paul II of the Vatican, not
Eddie Pope of D.C. United.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the American players got goose bumps in front of 78,972
fans on Saturday, some got tears. They all got nervous, which left
goalkeeper Briana Scurry to hold down the fort until Mia Hamm
gathered a rescuing cavalry charge for a 3-0 victory in the opening
match of the Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes into the match, Denmark's Gitte Krogh blasted a shot
across an empty goal mouth. Then, in the 15th minute, Scurry came
off her line and collided heavily with Danish forward Lene Jensen.
The shot to her ribs knocked the wind out of Scurry, who crumpled
to the ground. Wobbling, she climbed on all fours, then went down
again. Any harder, and the collision would have required an
insurance adjuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stunned; I saw the ball but I didn't see her,'' Scurry
said. ``I didn't want to get up, but I knew I had to.''
</P>
<P>
   Still woozy in the 17th minute, she somehow nicked a corner
kick, then smothered a header that was played into dangerous
territory. ``I'm just glad the ball landed near me,'' Scurry said.
``I was out of it for about five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   She fell on the ball like Lawrence Taylor pouncing on a fumble,
and Denmark seemed to deflate immediately. Its plan seemed to be to
get an early goal then to retreat into a bunker defense. To duck
and cover while the Americans blasted away.
</P>
<P>
   But Scurry fended off that first wave and, seconds later, Hamm
put the Americans up by 1-0 with a wonderfully balletic move,
trapping a long pass with her right foot and drilling it into the
net with her left. As Denmark wilted, Scurry pitched her 50th
shutout in 91 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really painful, but it was no time to be a baby,''
Scurry said of her collision. ``We were nervous. We knew their plan
was to throw the kitchen sink at us, and our job was to hold them
off for the first 20 minutes. We worked it out, and they ran out of
gas in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Scurry expects more of the same throughout the World Cup, teams
opening with a flurry of counterpunches, trying to back the
Americans up early. Next is a match against Nigeria Thursday night
at Soldier Field in Chicago, where more than 60,000 of the 65,000
available seats have been sold.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria is a fast, combative team, given to fierce tackling.
Forward Patience Avre scored three goals in a recent 4-3 victory
over China in a scrimmage. The Americans will get knocked down. The
question is how quickly they get back on their feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``My team is going to need me,'' Scurry said. ``We're on a grand
stage now. Teams don't want to have a bad showing. I realize they
are going to get through, and I am going to have to hold them off.
It's something I've become accustomed to. Sometimes we come out
nervous and the other team's excited and things happen here and
there.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory over Nigeria would almost certainly put the Americans
into the quarterfinals on July 1, thus letting the United States
qualify for a chance to defend its Olympic title at the 2000 Summer
Games in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The team was not in top form against Denmark, but it could take
encouragement on two fronts: Hamm appears ready to shoulder the
responsibility that comes with being considered the best female
player in the world. And the Americans are very fit, allowing them
to overcome early jitters with a relentlessness that eventually
wears down other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``For two months, we seem to be turning it on in the second
half,'' Scurry said. ``That's one thing that carries us through.''
</P>
<P>
   There were, however, a few vulnerable moments Saturday. The
defensive wall is not the fastest, and the Americans needed
desperate closing maneuvers by Carla Overbeck, Kate Sobrero and
Brandi Chastain to quiet several scares. Forward Tiffeny Milbrett,
the team's most reliable scorer this year, was knocked down twice
with pummeling hits and taken off her game. And forward Cindy
Parlow lacks a finishing gear that could have put her onto more
passes from Hamm.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tony DiCicco has not been hesitant to bring Kristine Lilly
from midfield to forward in the second half for increased mobility.
Lilly nailed a shot from 18 yards in the 89th minute Saturday, then
taunted a Danish defender who had fouled her moments earlier,
saying, ``That one was for you!''
</P>
<P>
   Scurry sees a need for minor adjustments, no major overhauls.
After Saturday's victory, she exhorted the record crowd to its feet
and clapped in appreciation for its support, leading the Americans
on a victory lap around Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was something we had been hoping for; it was unbelievable
seeing it,'' Scurry said. ``It shows that our team is out there in
the mainstream. We read that the only person to beat us was the
pope. We'll take a back seat to the pope any time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
