<HEADLINE>
THE AGONY OF A DISAPPOINTING BOOK DEAL 
NEW DESIGNS AND NEW ADS FOR OLD TABLOIDS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the summer of 1996, Joe McGinniss turned his back on a $1
million advance for a book on O.J. Simpson, parted with his
longtime literary agent and headed for a remote Italian village,
Castel di Sangro, to pursue his passion for soccer and an
eight-page proposal for a quirky book about a quixotic local team.
</P>
<P>
   The official dust jacket version of what ensued is that
McGinniss almost immediately ``was embroiled in a small-town drama
that had less to do with a game played by men kicking a ball than
with universal emotions like hope, fear, love, loss and almost
unbearable suspense.''
</P>
<P>
   Then McGinniss returned to the United States, where, with the
May publication of the resulting book _ ``The Miracle of Castel di
Sangro'' _ he was almost immediately embroiled in a small New York
drama with his publisher that had less to do with writing a book
than with universal emotions like hope, fear, loss, loathing and
almost unbearable tension.
</P>
<P>
   Since his book was published, McGinniss has rather publicly
suggested that he will never write a book again because of his
distress about how his publisher, Little, Brown &AMP; Co., handled
almost every element of the publication of the book.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail to Little, Brown's publisher, Sarah Crichton,
titled ``Arrivederci, Sarah,'' McGinness listed of what in his view
were missteps: a mediocre book cover, a canceled tour, legal
wrangling over a final chapter that chronicles how the team
purposely threw a game. The letter rapidly circulated among
literary agents, editors and publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Some who received the letter viewed McGinniss' situation as
unique because of his own outsized personality. Others were
sympathetic, saying his experiences echoed wider trends in
publishing. ``I think that the kind of problems Joe McGinniss had
are fairly widespread in the business in terms of how publishers
are pulling back very quickly,'' said Robert Gottlieb, a literary
agent and executive vice president of the William Morris Agency.
``These large publishing houses have different demands than they
had before. There's no real staying power. When expectations don't
get met, they pull back and cut expenses very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinniss said he considered his latest book his best ever. He
was so convinced that the subject would make a good book, he said,
that he split with his literary agent of 15 years, Mort Janklow,
because Janklow had doubts about its potential. And he said he
repaid his $1 million advance to his former publisher, Crown,
because he did not have the same interest in the Simpson murder
trial, which sometimes so bored him that he would divert himself by
doodling with crayons from a pack of 128 Crayolas.
</P>
<P>
   But thus far, McGinniss said, his publishers have been unable to
ignite enough interest in ``The Miracle of Castel di Sangro'' to
attract any national media attention. McGinniss never faced his
publishers directly to raise these complaints because he said he
had never met any of them in person. ``There's too much loneliness
and anxiety and fear and stress in the process of being out there
for three years,'' he said. ``And then, when you finally come in
from the cold, you're still in the cold.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Ms. Crichton who acquired ``The Miracle of Castel di
Sangro,'' for an advance of about $300,000, and she has remained
diplomatic so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, we're extremely proud of the job that we've been
doing, and we think it's a terrific book,'' she said, noting that
Little, Brown, part of Time Warner Inc., had paid for full-page
advertisements in The New York Times. ``The truth is that thus far
there hasn't been a tremendous amount of interest from national
shows for Joe McGinniss, but we can hope that there will be.''
</P>
<P>
   After the e-mail crossfire, McGinniss is now considering hiring
his own publicist to arrange a tour. But even this solution may be
raising tensions. McGinniss says he believes that Little, Brown may
be finished with his expenses, which means no money for air fare,
hotels or food _ or miracles.
</P>
<P>
   By DOREEN CARVAJAL.
</P>
<P>
   New Designs and New Ads for Old Tabloids
</P>
<P>
   Roger Black, the designer who has applied his rigorous aesthetic
eye to the pages of The New Republic, Foreign Affairs and Reader's
Digest, is about to embark on an entirely different design
adventure. Next week, Black will head to Lantana, Fla., to remake
The National Enquirer.
</P>
<P>
   David J. Pecker, the chairman of American Media Inc., the
company that publishes The National Enquirer and Star newspapers,
has hired Black and two advertising agencies _ each to spend $25
million annually on campaigns _ to reposition his two tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   To organize The Enquirer's advertising campaign, Pecker has
hired Della Femina/Jeary &AMP; Partners, an agency headed by Della
Femina and Michael Jeary. Pecker has hired Peter Arnell of Arnell
Group Brand Consulting to direct both advertising and redesign
efforts for Star, the Enquirer's sister publication.
</P>
<P>
   Pecker's mission? ``We are going to create history by turning
around these two properties,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The redesigned newspapers will be introduced in September, he
said. Arnell, who has worked on brand campaigns for Vanity Fair and
Elle magazines, among others, said that he would try to make Star
``a hip, relevant and cool media vehicle.'' (He would not say
whether that meant no more articles with titles like ``Chocolate
Diet to Lose 15 Pounds Fast!'')
</P>
<P>
   Jeary said that the Enquirer advertising campaign, a series of
print and television commercials, would focus on reclaiming
Enquirer readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the tabloidization of the news media, with `Dateline'
and `20/20' and Connie Chung and `Inside Edition,' '' he said.
``These shows have taken over the character of the tabloid
newspaper. We want people to get back into the habit of considering
The National Enquirer as the king of the tabloids, not the
television shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Della Femina, the man who brought Joe Isuzu to life, added that
he was excited by the proposition of remaking The Enquirer because
of its part-owners, the investment group Evercore Capital Partners
LLC, which is headed by former Deputy Treasury Secretary Roger
Altman. (Pecker also owns a stake in the company.)
</P>
<P>
   Della Femina said: ``The quality of the advertising has to be
such that people will feel comfortable buying the paper. It can't
be cheap or leering.''
</P>
<P>
   Della Femina said that remaking the National Enquirer into
something that consumers are not embarrassed to pick up will be far
from impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are basically doing what the networks do during sweeps,''
Della Femina said. ``They run out and try to get sensational
stories and news stories. I hate to say this, but this is going to
be relatively easy, because we all recognize the trend toward
gossip. People love gossip. Everyone loves gossip. My wife and
daughter and I fight over Page Six every morning,'' he said,
referring to the gossip column of The New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   By Alex Kuczynski
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
