<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New 'Twin Towers' gives Nicks fits
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After the NBA's first duo with the designation ``Twin
Towers'' failed to win a championship, the game eventually went
away from the concept of employing two 7-footers in tandem.
</P>
<P>
   But 13 years after Ralph Sampson and Hakeem Olajuwon missed
against the Celtics in 1986, their one chance together with
Houston, the latest set of ``Twin Towers'' is proving dominant.
</P>
<P>
   Two games into the Finals, Tim Duncan and David Robinson have
combined for 14 blocked shots and have so intimidated the Knicks
they have been unable to get things done in the paint.
</P>
<P>
   While Jeff Van Gundy insists his players must get to the line
more often, the fact remains they have been out-shot 66-31 from the
line and no one is seriously complaining about the officiating.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson says he and his partner have made life miserable for
the Knicks, who he says are trying to attack the basket. ``I think
it's pretty frustrating for them because they're doing a lot of
pump faking with their 6-6, 6-7 guys inside. It's going to be
tough. I mean they have to foul us really. And there's going to be
that disparity. They get a lot of their bucks in transition, off of
jump shots and you don't get a lot of fouls that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Knicks guard Chris Childs explains, ``You have to adjust your
shots because of their length. You still have to take the ball to
the basket. We have to make better decisions once we get in there
and that's not what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   They may be involved in a national championship, but on Father's
Day, but basketball players make time for their children.
</P>
<P>
   David Robinson's flew here Sunday to celebrate the day with
their dad. Avery Johnson's children already were here and he said
he was going to mark the day by taking them to the famous toy store
FAO Schwartz and then to a museum or a movie and then to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also may spend some time on my new personal computer they
got me for Father's Day,'' Johnson said. ``I'm the ninth guy on our
team to get a computer, so I'm way behind and I want to start
catching up.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan, eligible to sign a long-term contract for as much as
$85 million, has not committed to the Spurs beyond next season
because he wants to see if the city of San Antonio will insure the
team's future in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, does not mean Duncan has eyes for a city like New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a big city guy,'' he said Sunday. ``I come from a
small island (St. Croix). I went to Winston Salem for college (Wake
Forest), started in San Antonio for my professional career. I'm not
a big city guy. It's a great city, a lot of fun. I don't know if I
could live here for any extended period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is the math that works against the Knicks with an 0-2
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Only two teams have come back from 0-2, the 1969 Celtics against
the Los Angeles Lakers and the 1977 Portland Trail Blazers against
Philadelphia. Both lost their first two games on he road and got
back on track at home.
</P>
<P>
   No team has ever come back from 3-0 or 3-1 to win the Finals.
Six teams have come back from 3-2, most recently Houston in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
