<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Van Grundy's job not an easy one
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So, here are the San Antonio Spurs, two victories shy
of winning their NBA championship, two quick road victories away
from going 15-1 in the playoffs. Not even the Michael Jordan
Chicago Bulls ever did that.
</P>
<P>
   So, here is Jeff Van Gundy, who always appears frazzled, but
outwardly remained calm at an off-day practice in his home arena
Sunday, charged with finding a way to derail this San Antonio team
that is bigger, deeper, healthier and, not coincidentally more
talented, than his own depleted Knickerbockers.
</P>
<P>
   There are 18 million people, 13 newspapers, 11 radio outlets,
maybe 16 TV and cable outfits who insist that Van Gundy ought to be
able to do something to alter the outcome of this series _ not to
mention Dave Checketts, the guy who runs Madison Square Garden and
refuses to endorse his frumpy coach.
</P>
<P>
   So faced with the task of turning water into wine, gristle into
fillet mignon, Van Gundy is trying to balance fantasy and reality
as the NBA Finals advances into game 3 at 9 p.m. tonight in Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   What New York wants is for Charlie Ward, the former football
quarterback, to literally get lost. Ward and, to a lesser extent,
his alternate Chris Childs who is shooting 3-for-16, have become
the poster boys for everything that has happened to the Knicks in
this series.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, the starter, has not been able to run the offense _ the
Knicks are shooting .356, averaging 72 points. He has become the
target of extreme invective, particularly from NBC's Bill Walton.
In what may have been an unprecedented attack on a player by a
network analyst, Walton after game 2 Friday night called Ward's
play ``disgraceful'' He further called the player ``a disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday Ward was also reminded of harsh criticism levied
against him by the Nets' Stephon Marbury, who said the Knicks could
never win a title with him at the throttle. That led Ward to say in
his soft voice that he cares not what any man says about him, so
long as he is right with God.
</P>
<P>
   The critics in this city have little interest in Ward's peace of
mind. They simply don't want him on the floor. Van Gundy is being
urged to go with a backcourt of Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston,
a front line of Marcus Camby, Larry Johnson and Kurt Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of perspective, remember that Van Gundy took his
team from 21-21 with eight games left in the season to the
championship and he no longer has starting center Patrick Ewing,
who was lost in the Eastern finals with a torn Achilles. Van Gundy
sees opportunities, but he also sees problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go with less than eight players,'' Van Gundy
explains with some patience. ``Three healthy 'bigs' (Camby, Johnson
and Thomas) , one guy who is a little hobbled (Chris Dudley). So
you're gonna start three of the four and they're all getting in
foul trouble simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secondly, make all the changes everybody wants _ Marcus, Kurt,
Larry, Allan and Latrell _ then you're bench consists of two points
guards (Ward and Childs) and an unhealthy Chris Dudley. It's a
viable option that you can use in short spurts but I don't think
there's some panacea out there that says if we start a certain unit
that we're guaranteed of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   In its ardor to help the Knicks, the New York Times suggested
Sunday that deposed general manager Ernie Grunfeld should have
picked up another big man somewhere along the way, but the paper
did not have a player in mind. But that's one more knock to put on
the man who changed the Knicks by dealing Charles Oakley for Marcus
Camby and by pushing for the Sprewell deal that sent John Starks,
Terry Cummings and Chris Mills to Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it has become crystal clear to most that the Spurs
are much of what's wrong with the Knicks and Van Gundy's main
concern is that his team not suffer the same fate that befell the
Minnesota Timberwolves, Los Angeles Lakers and Portland Trail
Blazers in games 3 of their playoffs series with the Spurs. ``Teams
fell apart against them,'' Van Gundy said (average margin of loss,
12). We want to hang tough against them.''
</P>
<P>
   With so few players available _ Herb Williams and Rick Brunson
are out of the question _ the Knicks are much like the Atlanta
Hawks, whom they vanquished in the second round of the playoffs.
The question is whether they show a great capacity to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
