<SLUG> BC-PC-EXPO-ART-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLASHY CONFERENCE BELIES OUTLOOK FOR PC PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As PC Expo gets under way this week at the Javits
Convention Center in Manhattan, the show's organizers are sounding
a theme of ``smarter, faster, cheaper'' and highlighting the trend
toward powerful, portable devices that combine computing and
telephony.
</P>
<P>
   But among personal-computer manufacturers, the theme might as
well be ``where have all the profits gone,'' as cutthroat
competition continues to erode the industry's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Compaq Computer Corp., the world's largest PC
manufacturer, announced that it would lose 15 cents a share in the
current quarter, compared with analysts' estimates of earnings of
20 cents, even as it aims to reduce operating costs by $2 billion.
Compaq's difficulties led to a first-quarter shortfall in earnings
and the ouster of Eckhard Pfeiffer as president and chief executive
in April.
</P>
<P>
   IBM Corp. and Hewlett-Packard Co. have both found profitability
elusive in their PC divisions in recent quarters. And even Dell
Computer Corp., with the most efficient business model in the
industry, traded market-share gains for a small drop in profit
margins last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Among major players, the resurgent Apple Computer Inc. has
bucked the trend with growing sales, earnings and profit margins.
But Apple will not be at PC Expo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The present industry trend is going to make Expo-like shows
totally unfeasible, because nobody is going to have enough gross
profit to invest in them,'' said Seymour Merrin, a PC industry
consultant with Merrin Information Services.
</P>
<P>
   The industry ``has taken profitability and thrown it out the
window,'' he said. ``They think they've bought market share, but it
only lasts until someone else has a lower price. We have trained
the customer to expect the world for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   And prices continue to fall. Last week, Compaq announced the
5300 series, which will be available in retail stores starting at
$599 without a monitor. Gateway Inc., the second-largest direct
seller of personal computers, said it planned to introduce a PC for
less than $800 in an effort to increase unit shipments, and Dell,
which had long avoided low-end machines and first-time buyers,
introduced its first PC for less than $1,000, the $899 Dimension L.
</P>
<P>
   With the conventional desktop PC increasingly a commodity that
sells almost purely on the basis of lowest price, manufacturers
have to look to other parts of the product line for profits. Small
portable devices are one area of increased emphasis, as are
ever-slimmer, more powerful laptop computers, like Psion Enterprise
Computing Ltd.'s Netbook, a 2.5-pound, Java-based portable, and
IBM's Windows 98-based Thinkpad 240.
</P>
<P>
   ``One theme you're seeing is products that are wireless, rugged,
connected and powerful,'' Randy Zane, a spokesman for PC Expo,
said. ``We're seeing an explosive growth in remote access. We're an
information technology event for business, and all these products
are used by business professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   Another area of differentiation consists of large PC servers,
microprocessor-based machines that are used by numerous people
across an internal network or, increasingly, to support electronic
commerce over the Internet. These machines are called on to perform
tasks once relegated to minicomputers or mainframes and there is a
seemingly endless appetite for more power.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   IBM will be showing a new version of its Netfinity Server, with
eight Intel Pentium Xeon 550-megahertz processors _ the first of
its kind _ as well as a piece of software that allows eight of
these machines to be clustered to act as one powerful computer.
</P>
<P>
   IBM is also showing the Netfinity Switch, a dedicated piece of
hardware that allows customers to tie together from 12 to 1,000
servers, should anyone need to do that. ``Margins on the high-end
Netfinity products are well above 20 percent,'' Michael Corrado, an
IBM spokesman, said. ``What we're talking about is beyond the
commodity level.''
</P>
<P>
   Software is another way PC vendors hope to differentiate their
products. For example, Hewlett-Packard is showing a new version of
its software for server management, Web QoS, for the Windows NT and
Linux operating systems. Previously implemented on HP-UX,
Hewlett-Packard's own version of the Unix operating system, to
manage Web-site traffic, Web QoS will now be available on PC-based
servers for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
   And some vendors say that margins appear to be stabilizing.
``Demand is healthy,'' Joe Marengi, Dell's senior vice president
and group general manager, said. ``The component costs have taken
on a more normal decline, compared to last year, and pricing is
stable. As long as you can keep operating expense growing at a
slower pace than your revenues, then you will be fine in a
profit-and-loss sense. Some of our competitors have forgotten
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Dell long eschewed the sub-$1,000 space and the
first-time buyers that come with it, Marengi said declining
component costs have made such machines viable, and the Internet
has made the cost of servicing those customers less onerous. ``We
think this will be incremental business for us,'' he said. ``At the
end of the day, we wouldn't go into this market if we couldn't make
money at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
