<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URGENCY TO STREAMLINE GRIPS AIRBUS WITH BOEING'S REBOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Boeing Co., on the ropes the past two years as it
reeled from a series of production and financial difficulties, is
coming back as a leaner and a more formidable competitor than
before.
</P>
<P>
   And if rival Airbus Industrie hopes to be Boeing's competitive
equal in the new millennium, it must get its act together and
transform itself from a loose consortium of sometimes bickering
in-laws into a more streamlined and efficient centralized company.
</P>
<P>
   That was the warning sounded again and again last week by
European leaders as the world's aerospace industry came together
for the last time this century at the biennial Paris Air Show.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest and oldest air show on the planet ended Sunday, with
Airbus facing the most sweeping changes, and challenges, since it
was founded 30 years ago out of fear that European aerospace
technology could be snuffed out by the dominance of Boeing and
McDonnell Douglas Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Though much has been written of the progress Airbus has made _
at Boeing's expense _ in capturing nearly 50 percent of airplane
orders, the Airbus partners are at an historic crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   Noel Forgeard, the likable Frenchman who is Airbus managing
director, told the Financial Times of London on the eve of the air
show, ``One nice morning we will wake up and discover that Boeing
has recovered, that they've solved their production problems and
that they're better than we are.''
</P>
<P>
   He echoed that view a few days later at an air show news
conference when he told reporters that competition with Boeing ``is
going to be even fiercer'' in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our competition is the Boeing that will be in three years,''
he said in making the case that Airbus must, as soon as possible,
become a single corporate entity, or SCE as it is called in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That transformation to a single corporate entity was supposed to
have taken place earlier this year. Instead, it has been delayed
until at least next year. The sticking point has been trying to
determine the valuation of each partner's assets.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Boeing's apparent rebound, a new sense of urgency has
taken hold inside and out of Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   One day after Forgeard's news conference, aviation ministers
from Germany, France and the Britain met at the Paris show and gave
the four private companies now controlling Airbus _ DaimlerChrysler
Aerospace (Dasa), British Aerospace, Aerospatiale Matra and Spain's
Construcciones Aeronautics (Casa) _ until the end of summer to come
up with a concrete plan for turning Airbus into a single corporate
entity.
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize the point, Siegmar Mosdorf, Germany's industry
minister, said Dasa will provide no money for the planned Airbus
A3XX super jumbo until ``we have a complete integration plan
leading to a single corporate entity.''
</P>
<P>
   The A3XX is supposed to be launched next year, assuming Airbus
can line up enough customers to justify the $11 billion or more in
development costs. Airbus believes the A3XX, which will be able to
seat upwards of 500 passengers, is the final piece needed in its
plan to sustain a 50 percent share of the commercial market with
Boeing. The Seattle-based aerospace giant now enjoys a monopoly
with the 400-seat 747.
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard said Airbus can build the A3XX under its present
corporate structure, but most industry analysts don't agree.
</P>
<P>
   The problems and limitations of the archaic Airbus structure
have been more obvious than ever in recent weeks, and they all but
overshadowed the achievements made by the airplane maker as it
celebrated at the Paris Air Show the 30th anniversary of the launch
of its first airplane, the A300.
</P>
<P>
   Leading up to the air show, which is an important world stage
for Boeing and Airbus to showcase their products and achievements,
civil war had broken out between Aerospatiale Matra, the French
Airbus partner, and DaimlerChrysler Aerospace, the German partner,
over where to build the new A318. The A318 is a 100-seater that
Airbus is offering to airlines as an alternative to Boeing's new
717.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospatiale Matra wanted the A318 to be assembled in Toulouse,
where it builds the A320 and the widebody Airbus planes.
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace wanted the new plane assembled in
Hamburg. The A318 is a shortened version of the A319, which is
built there.
</P>
<P>
   As part of an agreement announced by Forgeard at the air show,
Hamburg will get to assemble the A318, but some A319 assembly work
will be shifted to Toulouse.
</P>
<P>
   But the dispute served to underscore that Airbus is a
politically conceived company with an encumbering bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airbus is crippled by politics and Boeing has been crippled by
money _ they lost investor confidence,'' said Richard Aboulafia,
chief aviation analyst with the Teal Group, a market research firm
in Fairfax, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus was formally created on Dec. 18, 1970, under French law
as a Groupment d'Interet Economique, the French term for a grouping
of economic interests.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, the Airbus partners are each
guaranteed a piece of the work. The planes are assembled in Hamburg
and Toulouse, but the British make the wings, the Germans and
French make parts of the fuselage and the Spanish make the
elevators and horizontal stabilizers.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus, at its headquarters in Toulouse, markets and sells the
airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   If Airbus makes a profit, it splits the net among its
shareholders, with Aerospatiale Matra and Dasa each holding 37.9
percent, British Aerospace holding 20 percent and Casa holding 4.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the Paris Air Show, The German partner, Dasa,
announced that it had reached agreement to acquire Casa, the
smallest of the Airbus partners. The combined company will be the
largest shareholder in the consortium.
</P>
<P>
   The current organization of Airbus is hardly a model of
efficiency. All that Forgeard and his management team control are
sales, marketing and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Changing the Airbus structure into a single corporate entity
would, the argument goes, force Airbus to reduce costs and improve
efficiencies by possibly closing factories and combining
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Airbus has been able to make dramatic market share
gains against Boeing in part by undercutting the airplane prices of
its U.S. competitor. As a single corporate entity, however, Airbus
would be more responsible to shareholders and would have to compete
by building cheaper airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Boeing executives welcome the coming
transformation.
</P>
<P>
   But not all of the Airbus gains against Boeing have come because
of this discount war. Airbus has simply done the better job on
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   This is what British Midland Airways Chairman Sir Michael Bishop
had to say at an April press conference when he announced the
carrier had broken with tradition and decided to buy 20 Airbus
A321s rather than Boeing's 757.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been a Boeing customer for a long, long time, since
1970, over 25 years. ... Boeing is a great, great company, but all
great companies have their peaks and troughs. This has been a
trough for Boeing ... I'm sure Boeing is going to be a supplier to
British Midland in the future, but I do think they felt they were
more invincible than they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airbus made a fantastic sales pitch to us in 1997. We had the
same salesman from Airbus for three years knocking, knocking,
knocking at our door. We must have seen six different sales teams
at Boeing, different people switching in and out. Airbus made a
consistent approach to us. They've actually backed that up with the
quality of the product.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Airbus last year had almost as many orders as Boeing, and
is even or slightly ahead this year, it is far behind in production
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Boeing delivered a record 560 planes and expects to
deliver 620 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus delivered 229 planes in 1998 and will deliver fewer than
300 this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of being able to deliver airplanes, Airbus is still
only half the equal of Boeing,'' said aerospace analyst Peter
Jacobs of Seattle's Ragan MacKenzie firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing still remains the dominate player. If the trend
continues over the next five years or so, then Airbus may grow to
the size of Boeing. But the jury is still out. They must become a
single corporate entity and expand production.''
</P>
<P>
   Aboulafia, the Teal Group analyst, said Airbus may well be able
to build as many airplanes as Boeing, but the question is whether
they can produce the higher value widebody planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airbus needs to generate capital to sell new airplanes,'' he
said. ``Given the current structure, that's problematic. Unless
they do something about that, they are going to have a very hard
time attracting capital. They are stuck in the old way, of going to
the government with cap in hand, versus the new way of going out
and saying, `We are a good company, invest in us.' They are stuck
between these two worlds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
