<HEADLINE>
STARS' WINNING GOAL LIKELY TO BE DEBATED FOR YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By delicious coincidence, the National Hockey
League's board of governors will meet Monday in New York to
discuss, among other things, the use of videotape replays to
determine if goals should be nullified when an attacking player
precedes the puck into the crease. The board could revoke a
three-year-old procedure that has provoked a discordant debate, one
that reached a boil over the weekend with a controversial
conclusion to the Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   A disputed goal by Brett Hull that was allowed to stand won the
championship for the Dallas Stars early Sunday morning, a 2-1
victory over the Buffalo Sabres in the third overtime at Buffalo's
Marine Midland Arena. The Sabres, who lost the game and the debate,
said a replay proved that Hull's goal was technically illegal and
should have been voided because his skate preceded the puck into
Dominik Hasek's crease. League officials ruled otherwise. Hull
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I interfering with Hasek?'' Hull said. ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull's goal, at 14 minutes 51 seconds of the third overtime,
gave the Stars their fourth victory in six games in the
championship round and their first cup since the franchise was
formed in Minnesota as the North Stars in 1967. In the six
close-checking and often passionate games, the Stars scored 13
goals and the Sabres nine. The last tense test of will and
endurance ended at 1:30 a.m. By then, the ice was worn out and so
were the players and spectators. Joe Nieuwendyk of the Stars, who
won the Conn Smythe trophy as the most valuable player in the
tournament, said: ``We had nothing left. They had nothing left.
Thank God it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing left except the arguments, and they could rage for
years. Lindy Ruff, the Sabres' coach, stood on the sidewalk outside
the arena at 3:30 Sunday morning, accepting thanks from passing
fans (``Great season, Lindy!'') while pleading his case again to
reporters. Inside, a half-dressed Hull sat atop a locker, high
above the loud music and the splashing champagne, stretching his
battered limbs and hooting that he did not care what anyone thought
_ after 14 seasons, he could no longer be labeled an underachiever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the world has left me, it's off my back, it's done,
we did it, and I don't have to answer to anybody,'' said the
34-year-old son of Bobby Hull, who put his name on the cup in 1961
with Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff contended that Hull, after capturing a loose puck, put his
left skate in the crease before he shot the puck. Apparent goals of
this nature are often waved off after video review. Ruff charged
that league officials were reluctant to review the goal because the
Stars' celebration was already in progress and to call it off and
resume the game would be ``the worst nightmare'' for the league.
Ruff said commissioner Gary Bettman turned his back on him when he
appealed for justice.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryan Lewis, the league's director of officiating, insisted
that he and other video judges reviewed the tapes at least half a
dozen times, even while the Stars celebrated. They ruled the goal
legal, Lewis said, because an attacking player is allowed to enter
the crease ahead of the puck as long as he is in control of the
puck. A memo dated March 25, sent by the league's senior vice
president, Colin Campbell, to general managers and other officials,
anticipated this and other situations and addressed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``An attacking player maintains control of the puck but skates
into the crease before the puck enters the crease and shoots the
puck into the net,'' the memo said, in Section 9. ``Result: Goal is
allowed.'' The rationale, according to the memo, is the same as
that governing offsides at the blue line, where part of a player's
body may precede the puck into the attack zone as long as he is in
control of the puck with other parts of his body. A close
slow-motion viewing of the Hull tape seems to show that the puck
and all parts of Hull's body were out of the crease at the instant
he began to take control of the loose puck by kicking it with his
skate to the blade of his stick, before his left foot entered the
painted area of the crease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a stupid rule,'' Hull said of video review for crease
violations. ``It's the No. 1 rule they have to address.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff scoffed at the league's justification of continuous puck
possession and predicted the governors would amend the rule. ``It
will be changed, obviously,'' Ruff said. ``They'll call it the
`Sabres rule.''' Ruff said the league was ``reaching for an
explanation'' by saying Hull was in control of the puck before
entering the crease. Joe Juneau of the Sabres said: ``Everybody
jumped on the ice and they were afraid to make the call. Everybody
will remember this as the Stanley Cup that was never won in '99. It
was not a legal goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the final round, Bettman discussed the rule's other
consequence: the disallowing of goals. ``The rule itself, as we now
apply it, works,'' Bettman said. ``The problem is whether or not it
is a good rule. I have a real question about relying on the replay
too much and taking some of the energy and excitement out of the
building when a goal is scored and people are worried about whether
or not they can cheer.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time the cup has been won on a disputed
goal by a road team in a Game 6 overtime. In 1966, the Montreal
Canadiens beat the Detroit Red Wings at Olympia Stadium on a goal
by Henri Richard, who, the Wings charged, swept the puck into the
net with his arm as he slid along the ice. Had this happened in
1999, the goal would have been reviewed on videotape and possibly
negated. Back then, there was no video review. The goal stood and
the Canadiens won.
</P>
<P>
   That game, theoretically, could still be in progress. Among
Detroiters of a certain age, this issue lives. And so it will be
with Buffalo fans. Such are the causes of hockey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
