<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MAKE CAMBY A STARTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once again, the Knicks find themselves behind the eight ball. A
pair of double-digit losses to San Antonio in the championship
series has put the Knicks down by two games to none.
</P>
<P>
   The last time his team was in this position, Jeff Van Gundy,
faced with the loss of Patrick Ewing and the surging Indiana
Pacers, relented and put Latrell Sprewell in the starting lineup.
Sprewell had been a spark off the bench, but Van Gundy conceded
that he needed a spark at the beginning of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Now against the taller, stronger Spurs, Van Gundy's Knicks need
all the sparks they can muster. The answer is clear: Van Gundy has
to start Marcus Camby. This is the final piece of the puzzle, the
final evolution to the new, flexible Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'm overestimating Camby; maybe all he can do is fly
around the basket and tip in missed shots, or maybe we have seen
just a hint of what he can do. He is talented enough and versatile
enough to keep the Spurs' post players occupied for an evening or
two _ or three. At this juncture, down by 2-0, playing Camby off
the bench is like having Secretariat pull a milk wagon.
</P>
<P>
   But the coach seems caught once again in the throes of loyalty;
he can't let go.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, someone asked Van Gundy whether he planned to remove
Larry Johnson from the starting lineup. The source of the Knicks'
woes has been the matchup between Tim Duncan and Johnson, the
smallish small forward who has been roasted by Duncan in both
games. Duncan has enjoyed two games of uncontested target practice
on offense, and on defense, he smothers Johnson, who has never been
a threat around defenders to explode to the basket for thundering
dunks. This is a series in which anything less than thundering
playground-like dunks, or attempted dunks, gets rejected.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-foot Duncan, towering over the 6-foot-5-inch Johnson, has
scored 58 points in two games, making 22 of 38 shots. When he has
missed, it has not been because of L.J. You have an excellent big
man, with youth, health and soaring confidence against a smaller,
injured veteran whose confidence has been punctured.
</P>
<P>
   But Van Gundy, perhaps trying to hide a secret strategy, said
absolutely not _ there would be no switch. ``As far as Larry not
starting, I don't think that's in our best interest,'' he said. ``I
think we need his. . . .'' Van Gundy paused and thought better of
using the word offense. ``He hasn't shot the ball well, but if
we're to win this series, he has to be efficient to help us do
that; that's why I'm keeping him in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny how two participants have opposite views of the same
event. When Mario Elie, San Antonio's rough and ready guard, was
asked about Johnson, he said: ``The man's not 100 percent. But he's
a warrior. He wants to help his team win. But I feel like now it's
hurting them. With him having to guard Tim and David, he's
6-foot-5, and they're 7-foot and they're a handful.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Van Gundy reminded us that it's not the start but the
finish that matters. That may be true in life, but in these rituals
of sport, where life is framed by quarters and innings, fast starts
are crucial. From the outset in each of the first two games, Duncan
has flown out of the block and built so much momentum that by the
time Camby comes in, there's simply too much inertia to contend
with. This was the same conundrum that forced Van Gundy to start
Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Camby has been the Knicks' good corporate soldier, through a
morass of double talk. Sunday he parroted Van Gundy. ``The lineup
that we have right now has been effective, has been working,'' he
said. ``We've started games real well, we just haven't finished
that in-between part.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby hinted that there might be a line change aimed at
attacking Avery Johnson, the Spurs' point guard. ``Maybe we can go
to a bigger lineup to go at Avery a little bit more, to post him
up,'' he said. ``We have options. When the time is right, Jeff is
going to use them.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Knicks' two-game deficit and San Antonio's confidence
surging, the time is now. And Avery Johnson is not the Knicks'
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Seems odd. Here we are on June 21, Game 3 of the National
Basketball Association finals, and we're still lobbying for one
final lineup change. But that's the unexpected beauty of this
Knicks team: flexibility, fluidity. Players go down, and the lineup
is rearranged and suddenly corresponds to the opponent's weakness.
Now the Knicks, with a desperate need to attack, can insert Camby
in a starting lineup to join Sprewell and Houston and have them
joined intermittently off the bench by Johnson, Childs and Kurt
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   But Van Gundy says no, and you have to assume he knows best. He
gets paid millions _ now several millions _ to work these things
out. What he sees up close is what we see at a distance. Except
that in this odd Knicks season, in which allegiances and alliances
have clouded judgment and tempted rational people to abandon
objectivity and clarity, closer has not necessarily meant better.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that is the lesson of this season, this series, Monday
night's game and even this slogan _ Free Marcus: Save the Knicks. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
