<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERT BROADCAST IS A FIRST FOR WEB  
 THE COST OF INTELLIGENCE  
 A DAY FOR TECHIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The music industry notion of a ``live album'' has always been
something of an oxymoron, considering that albums are, by
definition, recordings. Now Woodstock.com, an Internet music
start-up, is about to raise the semantic stakes. The company has
announced what it bills as the first pay-per-view Webcast of a live
event _ even if the concert in question did take place last year.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, at 9 p.m. ET, the company will offer a pay-per-view
Webcast of a Sarah McLachlan concert, offered simultaneously via
pay-per-view cable television in many cities through Spring
Communications. The performance was recorded in April 1998 in
Portland, Ore., at the end of Ms. McLachlan's ``Surfacing'' tour.
</P>
<P>
   The Webcast is apparently aimed at people who are such zealous
McLachlan fans that they would be willing to watch her performance
in a small portion of a PC screen in the choppy video still
characteristic of Webcasts. Or maybe it will attract viewers who do
not subscribe to cable or do not live in the right cable markets.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the Web viewers will be drawn by the discount: $7.95
for the nearly two-hour concert, compared with $14.95 for the
television version.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans are not going to be having a broadcast-quality
experience, so we didn't want to charge them for one,'' Rand
Bleimeister, chief executive of Woodstock.com, said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the show does not draw a large Web turnout, Bleimeister
predicts that pay-per-view Web concerts will eventually be a big
business, as the technology improves.
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock.com says that the Webcast will be the first to use new
video-streaming technology from Microsoft that allows a user's
password to work only at a single location. This feature is a
breakthrough for Internet vendors because it prevents multiple
users from dodging the pay-per-view fee by sharing the same stream.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodstock.com name comes from Woodstock 99, the rock
festival to be held in Rome, N.Y., July 23 through 25;
Woodstock.com is the official site of that show, which will mark
the 30th anniversary of the original concert. The company plans to
Webcast the festival live _ in this case, as it is actually taking
place.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   For a Price, Intelligence on Viruses and Worms
</P>
<P>
   As the malicious computer worm known as Explore.exe ripped
through computer networks across the globe over the last two weeks,
it took a heavy toll on corporate systems. But could the attacks
have been predicted?
</P>
<P>
   That is a question prompted by a new information service begun
this month by Infrastructure Defense Inc., a year-old company based
in Alexandria, Va., that conducts research into what its founder,
James Adams, author of a dozen books on covert warfare and
intelligence, terms information warfare. On Monday, June 7, the
company began sending daily news briefings to corporate clients,
intended to serve as advance warnings on the latest computer
viruses, worms and hacker plots.
</P>
<P>
   The service's first big test came the next day _ Tuesday, June 8
_ when the company learned of the worm and began warning its
charter clients, which include Microsoft and Citigroup. That was
two days before widespread invasions of Explore.exe began to be
reported. On the other hand, it was two days after the first signs
of the worm were noted on Sunday, June 6, by some people involved
in computer security.
</P>
<P>
   As Jerry Irvine, a company spokesman, said, ``It's very
difficult to give a heads up to something that's happening in real
time.''
</P>
<P>
   To gather its information, the 35-person company devotes as many
as 20 staff members to eavesdropping on Internet chat groups and
monitoring Web sites where hackers and computer virus writers are
known to congregate. It also employs automated searching tools,
called spiders, to search the Internet for key words that might
lead to new sources of vulnerabilities.
</P>
<P>
   It is still not known who created the Explore.exe worm and
turned it loose, though it is believed to have originated in
Israel. Generally, though, the company, also known as Idefense,
says its form of intelligence gathering should help companies stay
apprised of the more organized efforts within the underground of
computer hackers.
</P>
<P>
   Such intelligence does not come cheap. For $20,000 a year, an
Idefense customer will receive general daily reports. For $100,000,
a client company gets a more specialized report devoted to that
company's particular network needs and vulnerabilities.
</P>
<P>
   _ MATT RICHTEL
</P>
<P>
   `Techies Day' Is Aiming to Clear Up a Misconception
</P>
<P>
   With the demand for technology workers expected to double in the
next four years, and with the supply of such workers chronically
low, the Education Department and several commercial partners are
planning this week to declare Oct. 5 as National Techies Day. A Web
site is already in place (www.techiesday.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a perception problem around this area,'' said Doug
Berg, chief executive of Techies.com, a job recruitment site that
is supporting the observance. ``People think everyone in it is all
geeks and nerds, and kids don't think it's a fun career. But it's
the funnest, most riveting career out there.''
</P>
<P>
   And all this time people had thought stock options were the big
draw.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA NAPOLI
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990620.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT &LR;      06-20 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORDONEZ AND HIS OFFENSE DESERVE CREDIT FOR VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ If ever a position player deserved a ``W'' beside
his name in the box score, it was Rey Ordonez. And it was for his
offense on Sunday, not his defense.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez had three hits, scored three runs, including the tie
breaker on a heads-up play, and drove in two key runs to lead the
New York Mets to a come-from-behind 9-6 victory over the St. Louis
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Busch Stadium scoreboard said there had been no errors. But
there were mental errors aplenty. And Ordonez capitalized on two of
them on the base paths to lead the comeback, as the Mets finished
off this road trip, 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez raced home from second base on infield grounders twice _
including for the go-ahead run _ to help the Mets (38-31) to their
11th victory in their last 14 games. Mike Piazza, meanwhile,
singled twice to extend his career-best hitting streak to 23 games,
one shy of Hubie Brooks' club-record 24, set in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   So the Mets are back where they were before they went on an
eight-game losing streak: seven games over .500 and in the thick of
the postseason chase. They are off Monday before playing Florida
three games at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Mets rallied from a 6-2 deficit with a five-run
sixth inning, Rick Reed (5-3) was credited with the victory, even
though he allowed six runs and eight hits in five innings. The last
of the Cardinals' runs came on a three-run bomb from Mark McGwire,
his 21st home run of the season and second in two days.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, it could be argued, earned the decision only because there
was no way to give it to someone else _ like Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing like an All-Star,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said
of Ordonez, mindful that his shortstop trails Cincinnati's Barry
Larkin by only a few thousand votes in the balloting for the
midsummer game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my decision,'' Ordonez said, when asked if he would
be interested in being in Boston on July 13 to make his first
All-Star appearance. ``But yes, I want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, he deserves to, too.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Ordonez was benched one game by Valentine for
throwing a tantrum the day before, when Ordonez saw he was not in
the lineup. Since being reinserted in the lineup on April 24,
Ordonez is hitting .333 (50 for 150) to raise his average from .170
to .294.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a decent average for just about anybody. But in
Ordonez's case, it is more like a transformation. The 26-year-old
shortstop has won two Gold Gloves in a row, but he was a career
.242 hitter in the majors before this season and had never hit
higher than .257 in any one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more relaxed right now,'' said Ordonez, who admitted he
had stubbornly refused to listen to others' advice for most of the
last three-plus years. ``And I'm playing every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Added third-base coach Cookie Rojas, who was interpreting for
Ordonez, ``And he's using the whole field now.''
</P>
<P>
   And the base paths.
</P>
<P>
   The first time Ordonez created a run on Sunday was in the top of
the third inning, when he was on second base and caught McGwire
napping at first. While Roger Cedeno was legging out an infield
hit, Ordonez never stopped running, as Rojas waved him home.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire paused as if to question the call of the first-base
umpire, Greg Bonin, on Cedeno, and by the time McGwire realized
Ordonez was flying home, it was too late. Ordonez scored without a
throw to start a two-run rally and erase the 2-0 lead Ray Lankford
had given St. Louis with his first-inning home run.
</P>
<P>
   The second run that Ordonez created was all his own, Rojas said.
</P>
<P>
   With the Mets trailing by 6-2 entering the sixth inning, John
Olerud, Piazza and Robin Ventura delivered consecutive singles off
Jose Jimenez for a run. One out later, Benny Agbayani _ who was 3
for his previous 25 _ grounded a run-scoring double over third
base. Now it was 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Up stepped Ordonez against the reliever Rick Croushore. Ordonez
lined a two-run single past a diving second baseman Joe McEwing to
tie the score at 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez took second on pinch-hitter Matt Franco's groundout.
Then it was Croushore's turn to freeze. Cedeno pulled a grounder
between first and second, enough to lure McGwire into the hole.
McEwing fielded the ball and tossed to Croushore, who was racing
Cedeno to first. The throw was a little awkward, and Cedeno got
there first.
</P>
<P>
   Croushore, meanwhile, went tumbling. He glanced at third to
check Ordonez, who had stopped after rounding third. Croushore,
seeing that Ordonez was taking a step back toward third, looked
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was stupid,'' Croushore said. ``I sat there for a second.''
He said he was going to give the ball to McEwing. ``I could have
sworn I heard something behind me,'' Croushore said. ``I don't know
if I thought it was the ump calling timeout. But I looked behind
me.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ordonez shot off for home, easily beating Croushore's throw
from his knees, and the Mets led, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored twice more in the top of the ninth, and then
John Franco closed out his 17th save in 18 tries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
