<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-YANKEES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BEAT YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For a week the Anaheim Angels look tired, scared and
not too hungry, perched on a South Bronx street corner with nowhere
to go.
</P>
<P>
   They waited for a break that never came, a base hit that meant
something, a manager with a smile on his face. They waited for a
game like Sunday's, when all that happened and then some.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just one break that made the difference in a 4-2
victory in front of 55,626 fans at Yankee Stadium. There were at
least six breaks, including a phantom catch by Reggie Williams at
the right-field wall that should have tied the game in the eighth,
but wound up being an inning-ending double play that helped break a
six-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly trailing Texas by nine games in the American League
West didn't look so bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it isn't September, but we were facing an absolute
must-win situation today,'' said first baseman Darin Erstad, who
had three hits and drove in the Angels' final two runs. ``If we
continued to play this way, it could be a season that is over at
the All-Star break.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead they head to Erie, Penn. today for a game against the
Angels' Double-A affiliate before moving on to Seattle for three
games against the second-place Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   In one day they will leave New York for the seven-inning
exhibition, fly to Fargo, N.D., to refuel and reach Seattle
sometime Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   It's a veteran's nightmare. But imagine if they had lost Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a great win going into Erie,'' Angels starter Tim
Belcher (5-6) said, laughing after pitching eight solid inning.
``It gives us a lot of confidence. They don't stand a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   He can laugh now, but he spent the ninth in the trainers room
``biting my nails.''
</P>
<P>
   Closer Troy Percival, who hadn't pitched in a week, took over
and quickly allowed a walk, a base hit and an RBI single by Tino
Martinez. With Derek Jeter at third and Martinez (the tying run) at
first, Tony Tarasco fouled off six pitches, including a blooper
down the left-field line that was foul by no more than an inch. He
popped out.
</P>
<P>
   Chili Davis was next and he hit a blooper to the same spot that
landed just a foot foul. He walked to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was agonizing,'' manager Terry Collins said. ``But how many
times during the past few weeks had those been just an inch fair?''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius, almost a .400 hitter last year with runners in
scoring position, grounded into a double play to end the game, and
the Angels rejoiced. Percival, who threw a fist in the air, later
said mechanical problems created poor velocity and location.
Collins hugged him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all we've been through, that ninth inning was like
climbing Mt. Everest,'' Belcher said.
</P>
<P>
   The other eight were pretty amazing, too.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the second inning, Garret Anderson hit a slow
roller to third. Replays showed that Brosius' throw beat Anderson,
but first-base umpire Mark Johnson ruled him safe. After struggling
Troy Glaus struck out, former Dodger Matt Luke hit a two-run homer
in his first start as an Angel. If Johnson makes the right call,
Luke never comes to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been struggling and maybe this was just their day,''
said losing pitcher David Cone (7-3). ``I threw him a 2-0 fastball
down and away and tried to finesse him. He hit it into the upper
deck.''
</P>
<P>
   An inning earlier, Belcher, who needed just 88 pitches, had
runners at first and second with two outs. The defending World
Series champions had already won the first two games of the series
and looked ready for the sweep.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill hit a sharp one-hopper over the first-base bag that
could have scored both. Instead, Erstad made a diving stop and
raced to the bag to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game had Darin all over it,'' hitting instructor Rod
Carew said. ``He had three hits, but he also stole a base and
showed the kind of aggressiveness that we really need.''
</P>
</TEXT>
