<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-NOTES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daly blows cool, takes an 11 at 8th
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Big John Daly and big numbers seem to go
together as smoothly as his favorite snack, Oreos and milk, even in
a major championship.
</P>
<P>
   Daly took 11 shots on the par-4 8th hole in Sunday's final round
of the U.S. Open at Pinehurst No. 2, risking a fine by the PGA Tour
when he swatted a ball in motion across the green before it could
roll back to his feet a second time.
</P>
<P>
   Joining other Daly blow-ups, most recently a 6-putt from eight
feet at the Memorial, the hole pushed him to an 83 and a finish of
29-over 309. He received a two-stroke penalty for hitting the ball
as it was rolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself and I told (caddie) Brian (Alexander) that if
that ball dares to come back down the hill, I'm going to do what
Kirk Triplett did last year _ take my two shots so I just don't go
stupid,'' Daly said. ``It's frustrating. I lost my patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly's worst hole was an 18 last year at Bay Hill's sixth hole
in the fourth round. He took a 12 at Atlanta Country Club's eighth
hole in the 1996 BellSouth Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Daly vows he will not play next year's U.S. Open at Pebble
Beach, saying, ``The U.S. Open is not John Daly's style of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to go to Pebble and watch the USGA ruin that
golf course, either,'' said Daly, who apologized on the 10th hole
to playing partner Tom Kite for the tirade.
</P>
<P>
   The 11, blow-by-blow:
</P>
<P>
   1 _ Drive.
</P>
<P>
   2 _ Approach over the green.
</P>
<P>
   3 _ Putt back up slope to green rolls back.
</P>
<P>
   4 _ Another putt back up slope rolls back.
</P>
<P>
   5 _ Hits putt while still rolling and sends ball across and off
front of the green.
</P>
<P>
   6 _ Chip back to front of green.
</P>
<P>
   7 _ Putt 10 feet past hole.
</P>
<P>
   8 _ Putt to just left of hole.
</P>
<P>
   9 _ Taps in.
</P>
<P>
   11 _ After two-stroke penalty for hitting ball in motion.
</P>
<P>
   Love never threatened
</P>
<P>
   One of the pre-tournament favorites, Davis Love III opened with
a 70 and never made a contending move. He shot 72 Sunday and
finished at 9-over 289. ``I just didn't hit my irons good enough,''
Love said. ``I didn't get close enough to the pin. I knew this
course would stand the test. If we had four sunny days with no
rain, 15-over would have won.'' . . . After a solid opening 69,
Columbus' Larry Mize found the opposite Saturday with a nightmarish
84, when the course turned windy and wild. The 1987 Masters
champion shot a 76 Sunday for 24-over 304. ``I just picked a bad
time to have a poor iron game and not make any putts,'' Mize said.
While he heard Jack Nicklaus say during a practice round that No.
2's greens were the toughest he ever had putted, Mize cited the
real problem as ``the slopes that run you off the greens and down
in the little valleys and swales. I've never putted so much from
off the green in my life.'' . . . Paul Goydos' wife, Wendy, pulled
a brain cramp Friday. Temporarily misplacing her wedding ring when
she removed it to wash her hands, she decided to tell Paul about it
while he was waiting on the fifth tee. He parred the hole. She
found the ring and told Paul, who eventually would go from 67 to
74, on the next hole. . . . The head of Ted Tryba's sand iron flew
off the shaft as he played a bunker shot at the 18th hole. . . .
U.S. Amateur champion Hank Kuehne, who will turn pro this week,
finished with a 78 for 26-over. ``I had a good week,'' he said. ``I
didn't finish last. I probably beat about 100 guys.'' . . . Tim
Herron, who played with Tiger Woods Sunday, defeated a 15-year-old
Woods in the second round of the 1992 U.S. Amateur. . . . European
fans had little to cheer about this week, beginning with the hand
injury to Jose Maria Olazabal. Darren Clarke of Ireland was the low
European, tying for 10th at 8-over.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
