<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES LOSING THEIR MARGIN FOR ERROR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mo.)   By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees have lost their compass, the magnetism
that steered them safely through the crossroads that appear in
every game. They have been a team that gets the big outs, but
Sunday, there was David Cone making a costly pitch. They have been
a team that gets big hits, like they were blessed with a special
power, but a botched umpire's call left them feeling fated.
</P>
<P>
   They have been a team that starts and finishes rallies, but
after jabbing away at the Anaheim closer Troy Percival in the
bottom of the ninth and thrilling those who remained in a sellout
crowd of 55,626, the Yankees were knocked out, 4-2. They have been
a team that buries mediocre opponents, and yet for the third
consecutive series, they failed to sweep after winning the first
two games.
</P>
<P>
   They lead the American League East with a 39-28 record, but it
is hard to say whether the Yankees are going north or south; since
May 7, they are 20-19, and for every sign of progress there have
been setbacks. Their starting rotation is doing well now, but they
aren't hitting consistently. Their bullpen has been terrific, but
their defense often lousy. They had great reason to be frustrated
with the first-base umpire Mark Johnson Sunday, but the Yankees
have rarely created margin for error this season.
</P>
<P>
   After a respite Monday, the Yankees may have to resume their
schedule without right fielder Paul O'Neill, who could be sidelined
for a few days after a frightening incident in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez, the Yankees' first baseman, broke his bat hitting
a pop-up, the wood snapping just above Martinez's hands. The barrel
of the bat somersaulted wildly in the air toward the on-deck circle
and caromed off O'Neill's thigh, just above his knee. O'Neill _ who
never saw the broken bat flying in his direction _ fell to the
ground, and though he took his at-bat and singled, he was replaced
before the next inning.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, O'Neill said his leg was bruised and sore, and
the Yankees are unsure whether he will be out of the lineup against
Tampa Bay this week. ``It's just a weird thing,'' O'Neill said.
``That will probably never happen to me again.''
</P>
<P>
   Mistakes by Johnson, the umpire, weren't quite so rare Sunday.
Replays showed he probably missed a call in the second inning,
after Garret Anderson rolled a ground ball to third base that Scott
Brosius barehanded and threw to first.
</P>
<P>
   Safe, Johnson called, and with two out, Matt Luke slugged a
two-run homer into the upper deck off Cone. But the Yankees really
weren't upset with Johnson for that: It was a close call, several
said, and Cone felt he made a terrible pitch to Luke, after falling
behind by two balls and no strikes. ``I don't want to blame the
game on breaks or bad luck,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson missed another call at first base in the sixth _ the
umpire said Martinez's foot was not on the bag, and replays showed
that it was _ but Johnson infuriated the Yankees in the bottom of
the eighth inning. Jorge Posada was on first with one out, and
Chuck Knoblauch smacked a high drive to right field off Tim
Belcher.
</P>
<P>
   Angels right fielder Reggie Williams, who had just entered as a
defensive replacement, misjudged the placement of the wall, backing
and bumping into it, and reaching up with his glove for Knoblauch's
drive. Posada, at second base, saw the ball ricochet off the wall
and bolted for third (As Posada acknowledged with a smile later,
his eyesight was deemed perfect when tested last week).
</P>
<P>
   The ball caromed down, off Williams' neck or head, and he
juggled it in front of him briefly before gathering it. Johnson
called Knoblauch out, ruling that Williams caught the ball on the
fly, and Williams fired to first to double off Posada and end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees Manager Joe Torre didn't argue, having a poor vantage
point from the dugout, but the Yankees' relievers, stationed in the
bullpen in left-center field, were screaming and hollering that
Knoblauch's drive had thumped against the wall. ``You could hear
it,'' one pitcher said, ``and you could see it easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, replays showed Johnson was wrong _ the ball went
over Williams' glove and hit the wall _ and that Johnson had hardly
moved from first base. ``It's not necessarily impossible'' for
umpires to see that kind of play, Torre said dryly, ``if they move
toward it, like they're supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels scored in the ninth to move ahead, 4-1, and Percival
entered in the bottom of the inning to close out the Yankees,
having shut them out for 211/3 consecutive innings. But he allowed
a walk and a hit, and another hit and a run, and soon the Yankees
had runners at first and third and nobody out, with the potential
winning run at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Tarasco smashed a liner over third, down the line, and
thought he saw the ball land and raise chalk _ a foul ball, by an
inch or so. On the 10th pitch of his at-bat, Tarasco popped up.
Chili Davis also ripped a ball down the left-field line _ foul, by
a foot, the crowd groaning again. If either liner had been fair,
the Yankees would have at least tied the game.
</P>
<P>
   Davis walked on Percival's 26th pitch of the inning, loading the
bases for Brosius, and Brosius went to a full count. But he bounced
to third baseman Troy Glaus, who stepped on the bag and threw to
first _ double play _ and the Angels' six-game losing streak was
over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
