u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      06-20 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO REBELS SIGN DISARMAMENT PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The Kosovo Liberation Army's status as a
military force officially ended early Monday morning as NATO and
the rebels signed an accord providing for the demilitarization of
the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   The accord states that the KLA must follow a strict timetable
for placing its weapons in storage depots, taking down roadblocks
and checkpoints and stopping its fighters from appearing in public
in military uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is a turning point in our mission to establish an
enduring climate of peace and security for all the people of
Kosovo,'' British Lieutenant General Michael Jackson, NATO's Kosovo
commander, said at the signing ceremony a few minutes after
midnight in the provincial capital of Pristina. Hashim Thaci,
political head of the KLA also signed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   And as the last of Yugoslavia's troop's left Kosovo a half-day
ahead of schedule, the United Nations hoisted its blue flag over
the former Yugoslav Army headquarters here and NATO formally
declared an end to its bombing campaign Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But the hard work of making peace, rebuilding a devastated
province, returning hundreds of thousands of refugees, and actually
disarming the KLA is still months, perhaps even years, away.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying and dismantling the land mines and booby-traps that
litter the countryside, UN officials say, will almost certainly
take years.
</P>
<P>
   Some doubt whether the ravages of this war can ever be healed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the greatest challenge the UN has faced since
the launching in the late 1940s of the concept of peacekeeping,''
said Sergio Vieira de Mello, head of the UN mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As the last column of the 40,000 Yugoslav troops rolled out of
northern Kosovo hours ahead of Sunday's UN-imposed deadline, they
towed broken-down tanks and military vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said they believe only stragglers in the Yugoslav
Army are left behind, but expressed concern that members of the
brutal and murderous Serb paramilitary forces have switched to
civilian clothing and are staying on in Serb villages.
</P>
<P>
   The province's infrastructure is severely damaged. In an early
assessment, UN officials said 50 percent of the housing in the
province is damaged or destroyed. Government institutions such as
police and courts are nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations plans the monumental task of trying to
rebuild Kosovo and attempting to keep the peace amid the chaos and
the seething atmosphere of vengeance on the part of returning
ethnic Albanians refugees and fear on the part of the Serb
population left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful that the departure of the Serbian troops would leave
them vulnerable to attacks, thousands of Kosovar Serbs are fleeing
in an exodus that mirrors the flight of ethnic Albanians two months
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has tried to conceal the
Serb exodus, which he reportedly sees as a sign of defeat his
enemies could use to unseat him. The government has prevented the
refugees from getting near Belgrade, blocked their attempts to set
up tent cities, and urged them to go home to the province many
Serbs consider the cradle of their culture.
</P>
<P>
   Some reports indicated that thousands of Kosovar Serb refugees
were being loaded onto buses and forced back to the province they
had fled.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the ceremonial UN flag raising here on his first day
heading the mission in Pristina, de Mello seemed to recognize the
difficult task ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please bear with us if we do not respond instantaneously to
the many challenges that are emerging day after day. . . . We will
try to cope,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The UN mission will begin by trying to help the province put
into place a 3,000-member police force and to establish a newly
fashioned judicial system and an interim government.
</P>
<P>
   The future of Kosovo will depend in large part on what the KLA
rebels do. Since the peace deal, the rebels have been asserting
themselves across the province, even appointing an administration
and police force in the city of Prizren.
</P>
<P>
   A top KLA official, Mehmet Hajrizi, said the group intends to
``transform itself into a security force for Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The intention runs up against NATO's insistence that it will be
the sole security force for the time being. And Sunday NATO forces
continued the thorny task of demilitarizing the rebels. At
checkpoints around the province Sunday, NATO troops were stripping
KLA soldiers of hand grenades and machine guns even before the
demilitarization agreement was reached.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the KLA agreed to stop carrying weapons in
many parts of Kosovo and to place anything bigger than a sidearm or
hunting rifle in storage within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also calls for the rebels to maintain a
cease-fire, expel all foreign members, and respect the
peacekeepers' authority on security matters.
</P>
<P>
   Buja Bukoshi, who is the former prime minister of the so-called
shadow government established by Albanian Kosovars, said Kosovo
must rebuild a government ``that belongs to the people who live
here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of his return to Kosovo since the fighting
began, Bukoshi said, ``The first phase of euphoria and enthusiasm
will end. And in the next phase we will have to face reality.''
</P>
<P>
   A glimpse of just how complex, and explosive, that next phase
will be was evident on the streets of the northern city of
Mitrovica Sunday. Deep divisions between the minority Serbs and the
ethnic Albanians seemed only to be widening since the Serb forces
withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian Kosovars, who for nearly three months hid in fear
in their apartments, camped in the surrounding mountains, or fled
to refugee camps, were on the streets looting and burning Serb
homes and stores.
</P>
<P>
   At a shoe store, a dozen ethnic Albanian Kosovars smashed the
window and lugged out bags full of leather dress shoes and Nike
sneakers. NATO forces in the area did little to stop them. At
approximately 2 p.m., gunfire erupted on Ducica Street.
</P>
<P>
   A Serb man in the building was taken into custody by French
paratroopers assigned to police the town. From the back of the
armored personnel carrier he said he was shooting because Albanians
had broken into his home.
</P>
<P>
   Two Albanian men were also detained and a machine gun was taken
from one of the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``That man was in the police forces. He knows what he did,''
said an ethnic Albanian woman, referring to the Serb man in
custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves everything he gets,'' she added bitterly.
</P>
<P>
   As the NATO forces moved in and tried to restore order, an
elderly Serb couple emerged from the building with bags and boxes
full of their belongings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it, we can't stay here if we want to live,'' said
Ratome Istanisovic, 60, who struggled with his wife to carry the
few belongings they could gather.
</P>
<P>
   The couple said they were going to a predominantly Serbian
neighborhood across town where they felt they would be safer.
</P>
<P>
   They walked to a bridge that has become a new dividing line,
separating the southern and predominantly Albanian part of town
from the Serbian north.
</P>
<P>
   NATO tanks flanked both ends of the bridge as an angry crowd of
Serbs gathered on the northern side and a jeering crowd of
Albanians gathered on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb crowd was stopping anyone they suspected of being
ethnic Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a de facto dividing of the city going on,'' said S.
Jesseume, a French paratrooper in one of the tanks. ``We do not
have the forces to keep these people from hurting each other. Can
you imagine if we had to go to protect each person? We can't do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   An ethnic Albanian, Agim Hassani, shook his head as he watched
the looting going on and the yelling and taunting back and forth
across the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the future,'' he said. ``Look at what is happening. I
am afraid that there are only worse things to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
