</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-DUDLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUDLEY'S CRUSADE IS BATTLING DIABETES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Ore., Pa.)  (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sometimes in the middle of a game _ and always during
intermission _ Chris Dudley opens a small black box about the size
of a sewing kit. He pulls out a small needle, pricks his finger and
transfers the blood to a test strip, which is used to read his
blood-sugar level.
</P>
<P>
   If the reading is normal, he can go back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Among all the halftime rituals during NBA games, Dudley's is
easily the most vital. It is the difference between the Knicks'
veteran center coping with diabetes and controlling the disease
completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to know your own body; you have to be your own
doctor,'' Dudley said Sunday after practice as he sat in the
Knicks' locker room. ``The biggest difference from other diseases
is that it's 24-7. You can't take a break. You always have it. It's
not like you can work out hard for a week and then take a week off.
You have to deal with diabetes constantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Game 3 of the NBA finals is Monday night at Madison Square
Garden, where the brawny, 6-foot-11-inch Dudley will pull a black
rubber sleeve over his injured right elbow so he can bang bodies
with San Antonio's 7-foot bookends, Tim Duncan and David Robinson.
His elbow is in enough pain that he is considering shooting free
throws left-handed, his battered body a symbol for how beat up the
Knicks have been the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the icing, electrode stimulation and various physical
therapies are merely a small part of Dudley's preparation. Beyond
testing his blood sugar, he administers four insulin injections a
day into his right or left thigh _ one before each meal and another
before he goes to sleep. He has been doing it since he learned he
had diabetes at the age of 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of scary to be told you're diabetic,'' he said.
``The thing that helped me was that my uncle has it. So I knew
something of it and knew it could be dealt with. The first question
I asked was, would I still be able to play basketball?
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Yes, but you have to take care of yourself.'''
</P>
<P>
   For the past 18 years, that has been his mantra. It has not only
enabled him to thrive as a defender and rebounder the past 13 years
in the NBA, but also inspired him to help children living with
diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   For the last four years, 64 children have traveled to Veronia,
Ore., a hamlet 30 miles west of Portland, where Dudley used to
play. At the camp, called Chris Dudley's Basketball Camp for
Children With Diabetes, they not only learn to dribble, shoot and
rebound better, but they also learn to live with diabetes _ just as
Dudley learned to live with the disease as a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these kids come from areas where they may be the only
kid in school who has diabetes and they've never met another kid
who has it,'' Dudley said. ``And at that age, a lot of kids feel
self-conscious. I think it's real helpful to not make them feel
self-conscious. They learn they're not alone. The other message
they take is, you can do anything you want as long as you take care
of yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of the more than 400 NBA players put on off-season
camps that bear their name or likeness. Few attend the camps full
time, instead letting assistants or friends run the drills. Some
athletes show up as a courtesy on the first and last days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris is there morning until night every day,'' said
Christine, Dudley's wife. ``He goes on the slip-and-slide with
them, runs through the drills, talks to them about anything they
want. He never leaves the kids. You literally have to drag him out
of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Children ages 10 through 16 from as far away as Denmark have
attended the camp, whose national profile has helped raise
consciousness about the disease. While in Indianapolis for the
Knicks-Pacers series, the Colts center Jay Leeuwenburg, who is
diabetic, waited for Dudley and visited him after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Dudley had his own diabetic role model growing up. Part of his
childhood was spent in Philadelphia, where the Flyers Hall of Famer
Bobby Clarke dealt with the disease while becoming a hockey legend.
</P>
<P>
   The fraternity of athletes living with diabetes is small, Dudley
being the only known player in the NBA, where high-energy demands
hit the body all game, with the disease. Dudley has Type 1
diabetes, which is usually hereditary and characterized by its
juvenile onset. It is more severe than Type 2 diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, it starts when the pancreas no longer produces
insulin, the hormone that regulates the metabolism of glucose and
other carbohydrates. Once the disease is diagnosed, a constant
balancing act of blood-sugar levels takes place between insulin and
the food a person takes in. If the balance is seriously off, a
diabetic coma is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Dudley's discipline has helped him avoid any episodes. He
remembers feeling dazed his rookie year in Cleveland, and the
trainer's having to run and find him some juice to raise his
blood-sugar level. But that was an isolated incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just times when you know you have it,'' he said. ``You
just have a reaction. You might start having a cold sweat. You're
kind of out of it. Dazed. I don't know how else to describe it.
You're not all there.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has been religious about his routine. Monday will
be just another day Dudley deals with the disease during the
season. He will rise at about 8:30 a.m., test his blood-sugar
level, inject himself in his right thigh, eat breakfast, attend a
morning practice and repeat the process two more times before Game
3. He will test his blood-sugar level as many as 12 times a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shots don't hurt at all,'' said Dudley, pulling out a
syringe about the size of a felt marker from his right pants
pocket. ``See, it's not that long. It's easier than carrying a
needle and a vial. I have the regular set-up at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Christine said: ``If there is a blessing to it, it's made Chris
incredibly tolerant to adversity. He plays through pain. There are
no excuses. He plays through everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he ever wondered why he had to live with this disease
and its daily demands, Dudley said, ``There are times I thought
about that, but I always quickly remind myself that I've been
blessed in a lot of other areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one, I can help other kids. When I found out, I told only
my close friends. I didn't tell everybody. And that's one thing we
try to tell kids at the camp, to be open about it. People don't
treat you different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
