<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-RUSSIA-BOS </SLUG>
  
 CLINTON, YELTSIN PUT DIFFERENCES BEHIND THEM
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ His face was puffy, his balance unsteady, and
his remarks sometimes left his listeners puzzled. But by the time
President Boris N. Yeltsin of Russia left here Sunday, the biggest
chill in US-Russia relations since the Cold War, ignited by Kosovo,
was beginning to thaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two countries are back in business,'' declared Samuel R.
Berger, the White House national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   In an hourlong meeting with President Clinton, their first
face-to-face since last September, the two leaders acknowledged
that disagreement over Kosovo had strained their relations. Russia
opposed NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But now, they said, it was time to put their differences behind
them. With presidential elections next year in the United States
and Russia, the two lame ducks agreed it was in their best interest
to use the rest of their terms to get things done for their
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Also in that spirit of good will, Clinton told Yeltsin he would
raise with his counterparts whether debt forgiveness for Russia was
possible, though he thought it unlikely. But Clinton said Russia
should at least be allowed to reschedule the $69 billion in debt,
run up by communist governments, through the Paris Club of
government creditors. First, however, Moscow would have to reach
agreement with the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, they pledged to reduce the level of
nuclear warheads, among other arms control measures. They also
agreed to hold talks on changes in the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty to allow the possible development of a US defense system
against missiles, something Russia has long resisted _ and to begin
discussions of a START III nuclear reduction treaty this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Berger quoted Yeltsin as saying he wanted to maintain ``personal
control'' over the arms reduction efforts. Yeltsin, in a display of
humor, added: ``If we left things only to the experts, nothing
would get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin also gave Clinton a thick file of Russian civilian,
military, and private documents that he ordered declassified
several years ago relating to the assassination of President John
F. Kennedy. US officials said the documents were in Russian and
they did not yet know what they contained. Lee Harvey Oswald,
Kennedy's accused killer, had lived in the former Soviet Union and
married a Russian woman.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's stay, which was only eight hours, occurred on the last
day of a three-day summit of the leaders of the United States,
Japan, Germany, France, Britain, Italy, and Canada. During the
meeting's first two days, he was represented by his prime minister,
Sergei Stepashin.
</P>
<P>
   Before he arrived, Yeltsin said he was ``in a fighting mood.''
But shortly before meeting with Clinton, he said, ``We need to make
up after our fight. That is the main thing.''
</P>
<P>
   US officials portrayed Yeltsin as robust and forceful, not the
figure whose wobbly descent from his plane raised questions not
only about the status of his health but also whether he was still
in control of his country.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, who sat across the table from Yeltsin during his meeting
with Clinton, said Yeltsin was animated, pounded the table for
emphasis, and displayed a sense of humor, though he walked ``a bit
stiffly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When some of his colleagues, his ministers, and others, made
points and he didn't agree with them, he said, `No, that's not what
_ I don't believe that,' '' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a CNN interview, said Yeltsin's ``behavior was
neither erratic nor shaky today. He was strong, clear, forceful,
and looking to the future. We actually had quite a good meeting. We
got a lot done.''
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, which Berger described as one of the best of
17 between the two leaders, Yeltsin invited Clinton to Moscow. No
date has been set, but Stepashin is expected to meet with Vice
President Al Gore in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let them get together as fast as they can and get down to
business _ and help Secretary Albright,'' Yeltsin said, leaving
unclear what he meant by the last statement that referred to
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright.
</P>
<P>
   During their meeting, Clinton did not ask Yeltsin why Russian
forces had moved into Kosovo ahead of NATO and seized control of
the airport near Pristina. Yeltsin did not challenge Clinton on the
opposition by the United States and its allies on reconstruction
aid to Serbia as part of a costly rebuilding package for Kosovo and
its neighbors in southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``This entire difficulty in Kosovo has been a great test for the
relationship between the United States and Russia,'' Clinton said
in a taped interview with Russian television. ``But it is a test, I
believe, that both countries have passed.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, however, Clinton, had some firm words about
Russia's economic situation. In an interview with Russian
television Sunday, he said no amount of outside help could bolster
Russia's economy unless the nation made some fundamental changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how much the'' International Monetary Fund ``tries
to help Russia, until your country makes the basic changes every
country must make to function in the global economy'' Russia will
not prosper, Clinton said on the program Itogi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
