<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clutch putts bring Stewart 2nd Open
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ One classic met another late Sunday afternoon
in the Sandhills. Pinehurst No. 2 and Payne Stewart's U.S. Open win
No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   We might be in for a quite a wait to match the drama that played
out on Donald Ross' famous old track Sunday beneath a cool mist
that would have suited the architect's Scottish blood. With a
pressure-packed stretch run worthy of a thoroughbred, 42-year-old
Payne Stewart snatched his second U.S. Open title, defeating Phil
Mickelson by one stroke on the 72nd hole with a par putt of 15 feet
that dropped into the middle of the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who closed with a 70 for a 1-under 279, the only
under-par score on the leaderboard, stuck his right fist into the
sky and screamed, unloading the emotions that had tumbled in his
gut all afternoon. He put a bear hug on caddie Mike Hicks that
lifted him completely off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything bubbles inside of you and then all of a sudden it's
over and you did it _ you did it again,'' Stewart said, savoring
the ultimate Father's Day. ``I'm tired. I'm worn out and I'm
whipped, but I don't think I'll be sleeping much tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   On the green, as the gallery in the bleachers around the 18th
erupted, tears already filled Stewart's eyes. He cradled Phil
Mickelson's face in his hands and said, ``You're going to love
being a father.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson would have loved being a U.S. Open champion just as
much, but will have to wait until next year, when the tournament
moves to Pebble Beach and familiar California soil. He and his
expecting wife, Amy, who thankfully never dialed the beeper in his
golf bag, will have substitute the loss with their own private
major championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disappointing day right now,'' said Mickelson, who
3-putted the 16th hole to lose his advantage down the stretch, then
pulled a 7-foot birdie try at the 17th, ``but in the next few days,
we're expecting our first child, so that should even things out.''
</P>
<P>
   To speak of any evening out process was particularly meaningful.
Stewart had rebounded from last year's deflating U.S. Open, when
after leading for 54 holes he failed at the end, with a closing 74,
thwarted by a sand divot and winner Lee Janzen's good fortune to
have bounced out of a tree to the middle of a fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, who tied for third with a 70, joining Vijay Singh
(69), grabbed a piece of the closing script. He finished two
strokes back, at 1-over 281, lipping out a 5-foot par putt at the
17th after pulling to within one on a 12-foot birdie at 16. He
curled a 35-foot try for birdie just by the hole at 18. Happy that
Stewart exorcised the demons of Opens past, Woods added, ``From a
selfish standpoint, I'm glad he made it. It would have been tough
sleeping for the next few nights. To lose the U.S. Open by one
would be hard to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrilled with the chase, despite the outcome, Woods said, ``This
is what it's all about, to be able to step back on 18 and handle
it, like Payne did.''
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, the world's No, 1-ranked player, spent another
major championship to forget, slipping to a 75 and tying for
seventh, eight shots back.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to measure his disappointment, Duval said it was
``probably more than you can imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart won his first U.S. Open in 1991 in a Monday playoff over
Scott Simpson. He avoided one this time by grabbing hold of the
moment and refusing to let go.
</P>
<P>
   At the 16th, after chipping poorly, Stewart rolled in a
25-footer for par. At the 17th, he sent a 6-iron three feet from
the hole and nailed it for birdie to retake the lead while
Mickelson missed.
</P>
<P>
   At the 18th, after driving in the rough and hacking out to 77
yards away, he settled his nerves and knocked a wedge 15 feet below
the hole. After Mickelson missed his putt, Stewart, taking a tip
from his wife Tracey to keep his head still during the stroke,
struck the putt he read as inside-left and watched its sweet path.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked up, it was about two feet from the hole and
breaking right in,'' Stewart said. ``I couldn't believe I had just
accomplished another dream. I told you before I'd enjoy it more if
I won again, and I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Clutching the U.S. Open trophy, Stewart felt the additional
satisfaction of officially having clinched a spot on the Ryder Cup
team. ``It's time for us to hold that cup again,'' he said, ``just
like I'm doing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
