<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-620(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET THE SLOW BURN, JOHNSON GOES NUCLEAR
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe it was the cresting frustration caused by a
sprained knee that had limited him, a miracle touch that had
deserted him and a talented Tim Duncan who had dominated him.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Larry Johnson was simply reacting to the weight of an
unsettling situation: If he cannot muster a better performance for
Game 3 at Madison Square Garden Monday night _ and offset the heavy
burden on Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell _ the Knicks could be
setting themselves up to be swept in the NBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Johnson's mercurial mood ring turned as
dark as coal Sunday. He went on a profane tirade after two league
officials requested that he stop shooting for a moment and
participate in a mandatory interview session before the Knicks'
practice at the Garden. Johnson was fined $25,000 for his obscene
remarks and the Knicks were also fined $25,000 for his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   His behavior opened a window into his disappointment concerning
his play in the finals. After granting interviews for about the
last five minutes of the 30-minute session and going on his
unsolicited and obscene outburst against the league officials,
Johnson finished by saying between expletives, ``I've got a job to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that job is the thankless one of guarding Duncan even
though Johnson is banged up and undersized, and part of it is the
challenge of scoring points around Duncan in the paint and beyond
him on the perimeter. So far, Johnson has shot an abysmal 20
percent in the finals and was 1 for 7 from 3-point range in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to get some balanced scoring on the floor,''
Johnson said Sunday after cooling down. ``For me, I've got to make
shots. My knee wasn't affecting my mechanics, just the fact I
hadn't been able to practice. My knee is better. But now, I can't
get shots up'' with the league officials ``bothering me.''
</P>
<P>
   He had all the time in the world for extra shooting after
practice. But this was not a day for such considerations. This was
the team's co-captain _ a player who had been at the center of
glory during the Eastern Conference finals _ knowing that he has to
find a way to produce for a team shooting 35.6 percent in Games 1
and 2. A team desperate for points.
</P>
<P>
   But apparently not desperate enough to make a change in the
starting lineup. Although coach Jeff Van Gundy said that a plan to
play a big backcourt of Houston and Sprewell was a viable strategy
for some stretches, he said there was no reason to tinker with his
starters.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs' David Robinson agreed, saying: ``To be honest, I
think it's beyond that. I think it's very hard to come up with some
magic in the end. I think you have got to go with what got you
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have got away from that formula. Faced with the
intense defense of the Spurs, they have failed to move the ball, to
get to the free-throw line or to create better shots for their
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   To Van Gundy, improving the offense is a matter of ``how we've
finished games'' and not who has been starting them. And it is a
matter of his team getting into its offense quicker, making the
shots that are open and keeping positive about overcoming the
ominous pairing of Duncan and Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main question is: Are we trying to avoid getting swept or
do we believe we can win the series?'' Van Gundy said. ``To me,
that's critical. If we're trying to just avoid getting swept, when
our resolve is tested in a tight situation, we're not going to have
the determination to get through it. If we really still believe in
our heart that we can do this, then I believe in our heart that we
can do this. I believe that mind-set will go a long way toward
helping us get a win. That's what we need to get back in the
series. We need one win.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   One victory would give the Knicks hope. So far, they have been
unable to decode the Spurs' defense by having Sprewell and Houston
go one-on-one, with each banging his head against a 7-foot wall on
every drive to the basket. Even if the Knicks go with a big
backcourt and try to post up Spurs point guard Avery Johnson with
Sprewell or Houston, the Spurs can double-team them and force the
two clumsy ballhandlers to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel our team is versatile,'' Avery Johnson said. ``When we
played Orlando, I had to guard Penny Hardaway. We were still
successful because we have guys who can trap. I mean, we have a
little fear in our attitude because if I guard Houston, he's a
terrific scorer. But we feel we can do some things to counteract
that. The thing is, with Patrick Ewing not being there, we know the
offense is going to end up in one of those guys' hands down the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   It is too predictable. Sprewell and Houston need someone else,
to throw off the pattern. That player could be Marcus Camby or Kurt
Thomas. But neither of those players is capable of affecting the
game as Larry Johnson is when his 3-point shot goes down.
</P>
<P>
   Against Indiana in the conference finals, he shot 39 percent
from 3-point range and averaged 16.5 points a game. He also became
a part of Garden lore when his miracle four-point play won Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   That seems long ago for Johnson. He has been a study in futility
during the finals with a mismatch against Duncan and a knee that
will not allow him full mobility.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.J.'s out there giving his heart,'' Spurs guard Mario Elie
said. ``But I feel like he may have been better off if he had taken
Game 1 and 2 off. But he's a warrior. He wants to help his team
win. But I feel like now it's hurting them. With him having to
guard Tim and David, he's 6-foot-5 and they're 7-foot and they're a
handful. Then he tries to guard me and Sean Elliott and we make him
move to see how his knee reacts.''
</P>
<P>
   But that knee is better. Now, Johnson may go from a hindrance to
a help. By being able to practice his jump shot Sunday, he may
start feeling more comfortable on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Once he calmed down Sunday, he seemed more upbeat. Minutes
before, he was out of control. The incident occurred after Johnson
ignored the two league officials' request to make himself available
for the interview session. All players must abide by the league
rule or risk a fine.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Washington, the NBA's director for sports media services,
allowed Johnson to shoot for about 15 minutes before she approached
him. He nodded yes to her, but mumbled an expletive and kept
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Terry Lyons, the vice president for
international public relations, spoke with Johnson. Johnson cursed
him, too, and continued to shoot until there were about 5 or 10
minutes left in the interview session. As reporters circled him to
ask about the health of his knee, he unleashed an unsolicited
stream of obscenities.
</P>
<P>
   The league _ which by its existence allows players like Johnson
to make millions _ also took away Sunday. Of Johnson's $84 million
contract, $25,000 is gone through a fine after a tirade that seemed
born out of Johnson's frustration. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
