<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART RIDES HIS PUTTER TO U.S. OPEN VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ With one last courageous putt, Payne Stewart
won the U.S. Open, climaxed a day of high drama and authored the
signature moment of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Capturing his second U.S. Open title and winning his third major
championship at age 42, Stewart edged Phil Mickelson by one stroke
by making a 15-foot putt on the tournament's final hole, a putt
that instantly became part of golf lore. It ended a day of
roller-coaster emotional swings, with four players dueling for
victory on the back nine of a course that ranks among the world's
toughest.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Stewart conquered everything _ the difficulty of
Pinehurst Resort &AMP; Country Club's No. 2 course, the challenges of
Mickelson, Tiger Woods and Vijay Singh, the intense pressure that
would have cracked a lesser player, and the disappointment of
losing last year's Open by one stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart shot an even-par 70 on Sunday to finish at 1 under par
for the tournament (279), one stroke ahead of Mickelson, who
finished at even par after Sunday's 70, and two strokes ahead of
Singh (69) and Woods (70), who tied for third place.
</P>
<P>
   You can call Stewart many things _ resilient, experienced,
confident, talented. But after this day, it was most fitting to
call Stewart a champion. Because only a champion would have found
the resolve to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never gave up, I got the job done, and that means a lot to
me,'' said Stewart, who won $625,000 with his victory. ``I knew it
was going to come down to having to make putts. I've heard on
television before that one of the detriments of Payne Stewart's
golf game is that he's not a good putter. Well, maybe I squelched
those rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   The final moments were about as good as it gets, with thousands
of people surrounding the 18th green, some sitting on the clubhouse
roof, a few in the trees, and everyone holding their breath
watching the national championship unfold. It came down to this,
Stewart leading by one stroke, Mickelson on the green with a
20-foot putt for birdie, while Stewart faced a 15-foot putt for
par.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson's putt was difficult, and he missed it right, and then
tapped in for par. That left Stewart with a chance to win on a
15-footer, uphill, that broke right to left. Stewart read the putt,
while thousands around the green remained quieter than a Sunday
afternoon prayer meeting.
</P>
<P>
   As Stewart struck the putt, Mickelson watched with a slight
smile, knowing that his fate was out of his hands. Either Mickelson
and Stewart were headed for an 18-hole Monday playoff, or Stewart's
putt would win it.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart held the path to victory on the blade of his steady
putter. And even before the ball dived into the hole, Stewart knew
that his putt was true.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked up, it was about 2 feet from the hole, and it
was breaking right in the center,'' he said. ``I couldn't believe
it. I couldn't believe that I'd accomplished another dream of
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   After the putt went in, the crowd roared, Stewart hugged his
caddy, Mike Hicks, and then Stewart and Mickelson congratulated
each other, with Stewart holding both sides of Mickelson's face.
Moments later, Stewart's wife, Tracey, rushed onto the green to hug
her husband, and Stewart trembled with emotion as they embraced.
</P>
<P>
   Despite winning the 1991 U.S. Open and the 1989 PGA
Championship, Stewart has been on a mission the past year. He
entered the final round of last year's U.S. Open with a four-stroke
lead, only to lose by one stroke to Lee Janzen. Stewart wanted
another chance to win the Open; he played well enough to get it,
and this time, instead of faltering down the stretch, he
flourished.
</P>
<P>
   There were many key final-round moments. Stewart took the lead
for good with a birdie at the par-3, 191-yard No. 17, when he hit a
terrific 6-iron tee shot to 3 feet and then made the putt.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson followed Stewart's tee shot at No. 17 with a terrific
tee shot of his own, but Mickelson missed an 8-foot birdie putt
that would have kept him tied for the lead. Mickelson also made a
crucial bogey at No. 16, his only bogey, when he failed to get up
and down for par, missing an 8-foot putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Payne's tee shot at No. 17 where he knocked it close
where the realization that he could beat me entered my mind,'' said
Mickelson, who made the strongest bid to win his first major
championship at age 29. ``Until then, I felt like I was in control.
I just didn't have that little extra that Payne showed. Payne came
through on a couple of putts, and I ended up missing mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Woods also missed a crucial putt at No. 17, an
8-footer that gave him a bogey and dropped him to 1 over par for
the tournament. Woods also missed a 2{-foot putt at No. 11, and if
he had made those two putts, he would have finished at 1 over
instead of 1 under. But Woods left believing that at age 23, a U.S.
Open victory was in his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 11 was a putt I should have made, but if you look at my
entire week, I made a lot of putts,'' he said. ``I know I have the
game to win a U.S. Open; I know I have the mind. I'm glad Payne
made that putt at No. 18, so I could sleep a little better
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh got within one stroke of the lead on the back nine, but he
bogeyed No. 16 to fall two strokes behind and he never recovered.
In the end, Stewart was too determined, too steady and too focused.
And when it was over, he vowed to enjoy the U.S. Open title more
than he did in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where it puts me in the golf world is that I'm a pretty
accomplished player,'' he said. ``It felt so good to accomplish
what I did today. And nobody can ever take that away from me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 2220EDT &QL; 
