<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-ACCIDENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITER STEPHEN KING STABLE AFTER SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH LOVELL, Maine _ Stephen King, chronicler of the sinister
potential in everyday landscapes, met with his own nightmare
Saturday afternoon on a ferny stretch of road near his summer home.
</P>
<P>
   King, 51, whose writing lends a permanent dark tone to such
previously benign phenomena as the high school prom and the
unoccupied summer resort, had gone for his regular walk when he was
hit from behind by a motorist who had swiveled toward the back seat
of his Dodge Caravan to subdue an unruly Rottweiler.
</P>
<P>
   The best-selling author was thrown 14 feet into a depression by
the side of Route 5 and lay ``covered with blood'' and in obvious
pain, according to Oxford County Sheriff's patrol deputy Matt
Baker.
</P>
<P>
   King was flown by helicopter to Central Maine Medical Center in
Lewiston, where he was treated for a collapsed lung and multiple
fractures of the right leg and hip early Sunday morning. He was in
stable but serious condition Sunday night, and will be operated on
again Monday to repair his right leg, according to hospital
spokesman Chuck Gill.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the driver who hit King, identified as Bryan
Smith, 41, of Fryeburg, has not been charged. In fact, despite
disorienting pain, King was characteristically unassuming, Baker
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He actually apologized to the driver,'' said Baker. ``There
certainly was no animosity there.''
</P>
<P>
   As word of King's accident spread, his readers all over the
world were straining for information about the acknowledged master
of horror who burst onto the scene with ``Carrie,'' in 1974, going
on to dominate the genre for 25 years. Camera crews clustered along
the empty roadside where King had been hit, looking for anything at
all to film. Swamped dispatchers from the sheriff's office were
fielding calls from London and Seattle and CNN.
</P>
<P>
   But here in this town of 1,000, people were just worried about a
local luminary who ``made the earth and started it twirling,'' as
one neighbor put it.
</P>
<P>
   Friends say King's life has never been like his novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, because he's who he is, people are going to read
something spooky into what happened, but the reason I like him is
because he's the most normal, sane, down-to-earth person in the
world,'' said humor columnist Dave Barry, in a phone interview from
his home in Florida. Barry plays with King in the Rock Bottom
Remainders, a group made up of writers, which he described as ``not
a good band.''
</P>
<P>
   It's precisely King's ability to tap into the submerged fears of
ordinary people that has brought him such success, Barry said.
``Stephen is very good at staying sane and being totally insane at
the same time. He can communicate between two worlds _ the
unconscious and the conscious. He has this amazing ability to say
or write what you are thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   King was a high school English teacher when he published
``Carrie,'' the gruesome tale of an unpopular girl's prom-night
revenge. That was a year after ``The Exorcist'' raised the stakes
for the horror genre. Though Doubleday paid only $2,500 for the
hard-cover rights to ``Carrie,'' the book soon got a purchase offer
from Brian de Palma, who went on to make the movie starring Sissy
Spacek. Months later, the paperback rights sold for $400,000, said
Gary Goshgarian of Arlington, Mass., who teaches a course on horror
fiction at Northeastern University.
</P>
<P>
   King quit his day job and started the run of bestsellers _ among
them ``The Shining,'' ``Pet Sematary,'' and ``The Stand'' _ that
would secure his status as the hottest commodity in publishing.
King's influence was so strong that for years in the late 1980s,
publishing houses were so inundated by his imitators that they
wouldn't even look at horror manuscripts, Goshgarian said.
</P>
<P>
   The King phenomenon was not confined to America. ``I was in New
Guinea about 10 years ago and Stephen King's books were there in a
bookstore beside the jungle,'' said Goshgarian.
</P>
<P>
   King, who was born in Portland and lives in Bangor, has spent
summers in North Lovell for over 20 years. That makes him the
biggest Kezar Lake celebrity since Rudy Vallee, who could be heard
singing from the opposite shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maine is a poor state, and we don't have a lot of superhero
kinds of people,'' said George Westerberg, 66, who lives in Lovell.
``He's one of the people Maine can take some pride in. Every time
someone sees him there's a Stephen King report.''
</P>
<P>
   As for King's reported status as the world's wealthiest writer _
Forbes said he earned $84 million in 1996 and 1997 alone _ it
doesn't really make much difference in North Lovell, locals said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't know he makes that kind of money if you ran into
him in the market,'' said James Randall, 73, who said King recently
let him cut in line at the market because he had fewer items.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
