<HEADER>
A2994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLORADO-POLITICS-ART     06-20 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLORADO-POLITICS-ART-735&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMAN FROM LITTLETON EXPLAINS VOTE FOR GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Rep. Tom Tancredo, a Republican with a libertarian
streak, was elected to Congress last fall with donations that
included $9,900 from the National Rifle Association, the group's
largest contribution to one of Colorado's six representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on Friday, Tancredo stood out as the only representative
from Colorado to vote for the final gun-control bill, which allowed
just 24 hours for background checks at gun shows but also placed
some restrictions on semiautomatic rifles and high-capacity
ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made the difference?'' Tancredo asked, repeating the
question Saturday during a visit to his home. ``Twelve dead
children, one dead adult, 24 injured kids, and a community that has
had its heart broken _ that made the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Tancredo lives in Littleton, six blocks from Columbine High
School. Before entering politics, he taught in Jefferson County
schools. His wife, Jackie, just retired from a lifetime career of
teaching in the district, now known around the world for the
shootings on April 20. The Tancredos knew Dave Sanders, the teacher
who was fatally shot at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``My neighbor's son held Sanders' head in his arms when he
died,'' Tancredo said, numbly remembering the horror stories told
by neighbors and friends. ``I can't go home to them and say we
didn't do anything, because guns aren't an issue. Guns are an
issue, they did take children's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The House gun-control bill died in a lopsided vote, a victim of
Democrats who thought it too weak as well as Republicans who
thought it too strong.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to his conservative, suburban district this weekend,
Tancredo met with support.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, at a Denver summit on youth violence sponsored by
Colorado Gov. Bill Owens, Steven Vieregg, a Littleton resident,
sought out Tancredo, his congressman, in a crowded hall. He shook
Tancredo's hand and said, ``It took some guts to vote that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Rising from a folding chair nearby, Carol Williams-Craigie, a
Littleton resident who does not often agree with Tancredo, said,
``I'm glad to see someone voted for gun control.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the rest of the Colorado delegation _ three
Republicans and two Democrats who all voted against the final bill
_ she said, ``I was disgusted that they don't seem to be paying
attention to what the public is saying.''
</P>
<P>
   A trace of uneasiness came from Jon Caldara, Tancredo's
successor as president of the Independence Institute, a libertarian
research group based in the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom is learning the art of politics,'' he said, choosing his
words carefully. ``I hope he is not changing his views on the
Second Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing alone with his thoughts was Tom Mauser, whose only son,
Daniel, was killed at Columbine. Aware of Tancredo's strongly held
conservative beliefs, Mauser had traveled to Washington a week
before the vote, urging him to vote for gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked beyond ideology,'' Mauser said, adding that Tancredo
had called him on Friday, the day of the vote. Mauser said he had
asked some of Colorado's other Republicans in Congress, who all
oppose expanding gun control, ``How many shootings does it take to
move away from ideology?''
</P>
<P>
   Over a box lunch during a break in the panels and speeches,
Tancredo, who boycotted President Clinton's State of the Union
speech last January, freely admitted that geography had influenced
his vote. The Columbine shootings, he said, did not hit as close to
home for his colleagues in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life in El Paso County, life on the Western Slope, life in
eastern Colorado, is a lot different than life in Littleton,
Colo.,'' he said. ``My community is in shock, and I am speaking
literally. Movie houses are half empty, the same for restaurants,
the shopping mall. Family groups are staying closer together, not
going out in the evenings.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Saturday, Tancredo called the shooting incident
``a seminal event.'' In an indirect reference to his gun-control
vote, he added: ``April 20, 1999, marked that date for us. It will
always be in our hearts as something that changed our lives. It
made us do things we would not have done before.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience of 600 gave him tepid applause, which Tancredo
later attributed to the fact that he had minimized gun control and
warned that ``the scariest thing of all is we only get focused on
the guns and not on the sickness in our society.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tancredo said later in an interview that ``gun control is a
bandage,'' a superficial covering for societal sores, adding that
the legislation he voted for would not have kept Eric Harris and
Dylan Klebold from obtaining the guns they used in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   He urged restoring prayer and moral education in public schools,
slashing income taxes so more mothers could afford to be home when
their children returned from school, and shielding children from
violence and sexuality in videos, videogames and on the Internet.
Tancredo said that Harris and Klebold had soaked up negative
influences like sponges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that any amount of counseling would have
helped Klebold and Harris _ they needed an exorcist,'' said
Tancredo, a conservative Christian. ``It was pure evil in their
hearts _ and it got there because there was no goodness coming
in.''
</P>
<P>
   The week before he spoke here, Tancredo used the Republican
Party's weekly radio address to expound on the same themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our material wealth has increased, but our cultural wealth has
been squandered,'' he said, voicing support for laws to curb
children's access to violent movies and videogames. ``We have come
to tolerate ever more outrageous behavior, choosing to look the
other way rather than to appear to be judgmental.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Tancredo said he was frustrated by America's
unwillingness to debate its social decay and angered by
exploitation of the human tragedy of Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet you it was used 1,000 times, for every possible
amendment, they would invoke Columbine High School,'' he said of
last week's congressional debate. Referring to his colleagues in
the House of Representatives, he said: ``I wanted to throttle them.
I finally had to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   When the final gun-control vote came, he says, ``I'm the only
guy in the Colorado delegation that ends up voting for the bill.''
Recalling his years of ideological opposition to expanding controls
on guns, he said, ``Sometimes, I stop and think, `Boy, have I
changed since Columbine.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
