<SLUG> BC-SOC-W-GERMANY-ITALY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY TIES ON PENALTY KICK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KEN GURNICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Germany, the top-seeded team in Group B and
the 1995 Women's World Cup runner-up, scored its only goal on a
penalty kick in the second half and settled for a 1-1 tie with
Italy on Sunday in an opening first-round game at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Bettina Wiegmann blasted the goal past Italy goalkeeper Biorgia
Brenzan (11 saves) in the 62nd minute after defender Roberta
Stefanelli tackled Birgit Pirnz in the penalty box. That countered
the Italian goal by striker Patrizia Panico, who headed in a pass
to beat goalkeeper Silke Rottenberg in the 36th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's offense, determined to penetrate Germany's defense with
short passes and solo dribbling, succeeded after defender Doris
Fitschen, the German captain, took down midfielder Manuela Tesse
near the corner for a foul.
</P>
<P>
   Antonella Carta, Italy's captain, received the ensuing short
free kick and sent a cross to the far side of the goal, where
Panico had slipped free from Fitschen. Panico headed the pass into
the bottom right corner of the net to beat Rottenberg, who was late
reacting.
</P>
<P>
   To that point, the game was an even struggle between contrasting
offensive styles, Germany countering Italy's short game with
repeated long passes and shots that kept Brenzan busy. Germany
increased the pressure in the second half and it paid off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
