<HEADER>
A2999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-OBSERVER-NY     06-20 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AL GORE TURNS THE VOLUME WAY, WAY UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore has been trying to be more exciting on the stump _
trying so hard that if he keeps it up, he'll rupture his vocal
cords before the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   The new Al Gore yells quite a lot. Caught between Bill Clinton
and George W. Bush, two natural campaigners, the vice president is
trying to make up in decibels what he lacks in spontaneity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not satisfied! INDEED I AM RESTLESS!'' he cried in New
York, announcing his candidacy for president with a list of
promises about what he would do to move the country TOWARD
AMERICA'S NEW HORIZONS, a goal that will involve eliminating EVERY
LAST DIME OF WASTE, fighting GLOBAL WARMING and making our public
schools THE FINEST AND BEST IN THE ENTIRE WORLD.
</P>
<P>
   This is our fault. We have been carping about how boring Al Gore
is, and the poor man is all but howling at the moon in an effort to
sound more compelling. We are being forced to watch him go through
an enormous effort to look effortless, and it is as discomfiting as
looking at the underside of a swan swimming on the lake.
</P>
<P>
   The public is not going to elect a president who makes them feel
like nervous parents at the second-grade class play. Gore has to
give up this futile attempt to become Kennedyesque and embrace the
boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Let Gore be Gore! Where is it written that the American people
want a fun guy for president? True, but most of our chief
executives weren't people you would necessarily want to pal around
with. No one ever accused George Washington of being the life of
the party. ``Today I dined with the president, and as usual the
company was as grave as if at a funeral,'' reported one of his
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it is a disadvantage to have to campaign in the age of
mass media when the only TV star you resemble is Howdy Doody. But
history shows that when America is in a period of economic boom,
the public is comfortable having someone in the White House who is
more stolid than the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   During the Roaring Twenties, the electorate fell in love with
Calvin Coolidge, a monosyllabic politician who barely had the
energy to get out of bed in the morning. (Coolidge was also, as far
as we know, the first vice president to serve while his boss was
having sex with a woman not his wife in a room just off the Oval
Office. He never felt compelled to point out that this was
outrageous.)
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Coolidge, Al Gore is an energetic politician, and you
only have to listen to his speeches to know that there will
probably be A LOT OF INITIATIVES in a Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   Even though George Bush has been gloriously unspecific about his
own agenda, it is already easy to see that the two front-runners
for the presidential nominations have very different outlooks.
Gore, for all his worries about BUREAUCRATIC EXCESS, is a
government activist, and Bush, for all his talk about being a
compassionate conservative, does not seem to really have many new
initiatives in mind.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to describe the difference between them so far is
that Gore promises to make ``high quality preschool available to
EVERY CHILD IN EVERY FAMILY'' and Bush promises to get the Head
Start classes to teach phonics.
</P>
<P>
   The first time I saw Al Gore, he was running in the New York
Democratic primary in 1988, a contest the Gore people thought they
had wrapped up when they won the endorsement of New York City Mayor
Ed Koch.
</P>
<P>
   But Koch was in full-throttle third-term hysteria, having
insulted or alienated almost every conceivable section of the city
population. The mayor led Gore around like a spaniel, and at almost
every stop the Tennessee senator was asked to apologize for
something Koch had said or done to somebody. During that campaign
Gore did not look so much stiff as numb, as if he had been knocked
over the head with a bat.
</P>
<P>
   The second time I saw Gore was when he returned to New York City
for an environmental conference. He was happy as a clam, discussing
dire predictions of receding shores and expanding populations.
Reading the text of his remarks would probably have been pretty
boring then, too. But in person, Gore was utterly at ease with
himself and his audience. Even his hair looked less stiff.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Olivari, who worked for Gore in that fatal 1988 primary,
claims his candidate was at his best in Staten Island, the home of
the nation's largest landfill, where people were actually
interested in hearing him talk about solid waste. ``He had a very
good first day and then it went downhill,'' recalled Olivari last
week, at a fund-raising cocktail party for Gore in Manhattan.
``Maybe he should just try being who he is and things will work
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Seize the moment, Gore. Dare to be dull.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
