<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE LONGEST FINAL PUTT TO WIN THE OPEN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ On the 18th green that was as hard as Payne
Stewart's determination, the putt was 15 feet long, slightly
uphill, with a slight break to the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself, `This is an inside-left putt. Just believe
that,''' he would say later. ``I remembered what my wife Tracey had
told me Saturday night, to keep my head still when I putted, that I
had been moving my head. And two feet from the hole, it was
breaking right in the center. I couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   When that putt plunked into the cup, the 40,000 who had been
holding their breath around the 18th green at Pinehurst No. 2,
exploded in a roar that reverberated through more than a century of
U.S. Open Championship history.
</P>
<P>
   In the most theatrical situation in golf, Stewart had won the
Open with the last putt of the tournament for a par 4, a final
round of par 70 and a 72-hole score of 279. If he had missed, he
would have been in an 18-hole playoff Monday with Phil Mickelson,
who was standing nearby after having already putted out for a 70
and 280, even par.
</P>
<P>
   In this 99th Open, the 42-year-old Stewart, the only pro who
wears the plus fours that were popular a century ago, had put an
exclamation point on one of the most dramatic Opens in golf
history.
</P>
<P>
   According to the archivists of the U.S. Golf Association, which
governs the Open, this was the first time that the championship was
won with the last putt of any substantial length.
</P>
<P>
   The important word there is substantial. In the 1996 Open at
Oakland Hills, for example, Steve Jones holed a last putt of about
3 feet to win. In other years, other golfers have tapped in to win.
But until now, no golfer had ever made a lengthy last putt to
snatch the huge silver trophy that Jack Nicklaus, Ben Hogan and
Bobby Jones each won four times.
</P>
<P>
   What Stewart did belongs up there on the same pedestal with what
Arnold Palmer did with a final-round 65 at Cherry Hills in 1960;
what Ben Hogan did at Merion in 1950 only 16 months after the
head-on collision with a bus that nearly killed him; what Jones did
at Winged Foot in 1929 with a curling putt to force a 36-hole
playoff with Al Espinosa that he won.
</P>
<P>
   But none of those Opens came down to the last putt as Sunday's
shootout here in the Sandhills of North Carolina did.
</P>
<P>
   Every Open has its moments, but none of the golf historians
could remember an Open quite like this one. Throughout the cloudy,
misty afternoon, Stewart and Mickelson, in the last pairing,
swapped the lead as Tiger Woods, the precocious 23-year-old who won
the 1997 Masters, and Vijay Singh, the reigning PGA champion,
lurked a stroke or two behind.
</P>
<P>
   On the green of the 489-yard 16th hole, the longest par 4 in
Open history, Stewart holed a 25-footer to save par and Mickelson
missed an 8-footer for par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I needed to chip that ball in there,'' Stewart said,
alluding to his shot from left rough, ``but I hit a very poor chip.
I shouldn't have thought that way. On the putt, I got my line, went
through my routine, looked up and it's going into the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they were tied. With the honor on the 17th, Stewart lofted a
6-iron that spun to a stop about three feet away. ``When I won the
1991 Open at Hazeltine,'' he recalled, ``on the 17th hole there,
all my shots were right at the pin. And all four of my shots here
at the 17th were right at the pin.''
</P>
<P>
   So was Mickelson's shot, a 7-iron that floated in there about
eight feet, but he missed the putt, the stroke that would make the
ultimate difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``That putt broke left early and right at the end,'' Mickelson
said later. ``But it didn't take the break and I left it too far
out on the right.''
</P>
<P>
   With the opportunity to take the lead with what Stewart called
an ``inside left putt,'' he knocked it in for the lead at 1-under
par for the tournament and strode to the 18th tee with a one-stroke
lead. By then Singh was already in with a 69 for 281, 1-over par,
and Woods would miss a 35-footer for a par 70 and 281.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I could make it, and I almost made it,'' Woods said
later.
</P>
<P>
   On the 18th hole, a slightly uphill par-4 of 446 yards that had
yielded only one birdie (by Colin Montgomerie) Sunday, Mickelson
was in the fairway, but Stewart put his drive in the right rough,
then hit a wedge short of the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I collected myself,'' Stewart said. ``I had no chance to think
about getting to the green. I took my medicine. I didn't compound
my situation by making two mistakes in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart made history instead. He wedged his third shot to 15
feet, watched Mickelson miss a 20-footer, then made the putt that
will be remembered as long as the Open is played. As long as golf
is played, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Open, you usually play for pars and wait for somebody
to falter,'' Mickelson said, ``but Payne made something happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne Stewart had one-putted the last three holes. And the putt
that he made on the 18th green now enters the next century as the
longest last putt to win the Open. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
