<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NEW YORK FOR BOTH OF US, CLINTON SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Sunday that he and first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton intend to ``get a place'' in New York _
soon enough to allow Mrs. Clinton to use it as a residence if she
decides to run for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Answering the question about a possible move more clearly than
he has in the past, Clinton, in an interview on CNN's ``Late
Edition,'' left the impression that the first couple might be
house-hunting soon. He did not say where in New York they wanted to
live.
</P>
<P>
   Under New York law, a U.S. Senate candidate does not have to
establish residency in the state until the election.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said earlier this month that she would form an
exploratory committee for a possible campaign in 2000 for the
Senate seat being vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., who
is retiring after four terms.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton dismissed a report in U.S. News and World Report that
said Mrs. Clinton's move to New York was already ``in the works,''
apparently without her husband.
</P>
<P>
   That report, in the issue that goes on sale Monday, said that
Mrs. Clinton would move out of the White House by the fall and
suggested that she would return sporadically for official events.
</P>
<P>
   In the CNN interview, Clinton said, ``Well, it's not true that
she's going to move out of the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Months ago, we said that we intended to get a place
in New York. We talked, we started talking not long after we moved
to the White House about where we would live when we got out. She's
always wanted to live in New York, so we said we'd do that. And I
would divide my time between New York and going home to Arkansas
and finishing my library and doing my work there.''
</P>
<P>
   In his comments, the president said that if Mrs. Clinton ran for
the Senate, she would spend part of her time away from the White
House, but not all of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now if she runs for the Senate, she'll obviously have to spend
a lot more time there,'' Clinton said. ``But it will be more like
an incumbent member of Congress running for re-election; that is,
she's not going to stop being first lady and doing her other
responsibilities, but she'll have to spend a lot more time in New
York, and we'll have to get a place there for her to be while she's
spending the time there.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said he might change his own residency from
Arkansas to New York before he left office so that he could vote
for his wife in the Senate race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
