</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-RUSSIA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE BUOYED BY CLINTON-YELTSIN MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert three new grafs of Clinton remarks near end of 2nd
take, beginning: In an interview ...)  (mk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ The reasonable face of Russia, President
Boris Yeltsin, walked stiffly, but his presence here Sunday was
enough to reassure President Clinton and other leaders that
dialogue with Moscow was possible in the aftermath of the Kosovo
war.
</P>
<P>
   After months of tensions since the start of the war, culminating
in an unnerving standoff between Russian and NATO troops at the
main airport in Kosovo, the Russian and American leaders met Sunday
and decided to let bygones be bygones, according to Clinton's
aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're actually in a position to have a stronger
relationship with Russia in the future than before the conflict
started,'' Clinton said after their hourlong session.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to give a fresh start to the frayed relationship, the
aides said, the two leaders instead focused in their meeting on the
Russian economy, Moscow's sharing of nuclear technology with Iran,
and arms control.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, in a joint statement, agreed for the first time to begin
discussions on changes to the linchpin accord on nuclear weapons
between the two countries, something desired by successive American
presidents, including Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The encounter between Clinton and Yeltsin, their first since the
president was in Moscow last September, was set in the context of
the summit meeting of the Group of Eight _ the world's seven
leading industrial nations and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Russia was included in the prestigious club several years ago as
a way of showing that Moscow counted as a major power, and
Yeltsin's appearance, truncated to about seven hours and uncertain
until the last moment because of the precariousness of his health
and tensions over Kosovo, was as important for him as it was for
the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make up after our fight,'' Yeltsin said of the
heated differences over Kosovo between the NATO allies and Russia.
As a traditional ally of Yugoslavia, Russia vehemently opposed
NATO's bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The other leaders, who had watched the roller-coaster behavior
of Russia over Kosovo _ helpful, then obstinate over the role of
its troops, then helpful again in arriving at a solution two days
ago _ were relieved and grateful.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing buoyed by Sunday's encounter with the Russian
president, Clinton's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, said
the meeting was ``one of the best'' the two leaders had held.
Despite the concerns about the health of Yeltsin, who appeared
uncertain on his feet at times, Berger described the Russian leader
as ``pounding the table'' and being very ``forceful'' in overruling
his aides arrayed on either side of him.
</P>
<P>
   The French president, Jacques Chirac, spoke warmly of
``reconciliation'' between Russia and the West.
</P>
<P>
   But the summit leaders, in a reflection of their underlying
uncertainty about Russia's political and economic future, offered
only modest economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
   In the summit's final communique Sunday, Russia was urged to
step up its economic reforms so it could meet requirements set by
the International Monetary Fund for an agreement on a $4.5 billion
loan.
</P>
<P>
   Only after the agreement with the fund was in place should the
Paris Club of sovereign creditors ``act expeditiously'' to
negotiate a debt rescheduling agreement, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan for the Paris Club debt relief was a ``little thank you
by the West'' for Russia's final role in resolving the Kosovo
crisis, Karl Kaiser, a German foreign ministry official, said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half of Russia's total debt of about $150 billion is owed
to Germany, and further debt relief would require a ``green light''
from the German government, Kaiser said. So far, such a go-ahead
was not in sight, he added.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several weeks, as the negotiations over Kosovo went
up and down, the White House had prepared several scenarios for the
meeting between Clinton and Yeltsin. In a worst-case scenario, some
officials were ready for a total blowup.
</P>
<P>
   Until almost the last moment, it looked as though the two men
would talk almost exclusively about Kosovo and finalize an
agreement on how Russian soldiers would operate with NATO in the
province.
</P>
<P>
   But with Yeltsin apparently giving the order to settle the talks
in Helsinki, Finland, before the summit meeting, the way was
cleared, according to Berger, for the two countries to be ``back in
business.''
</P>
<P>
   In their face-to-face meeting, held in an bland conference room
in a local hotel where the Russian delegation was staying _ a
locale chosen so Yeltsin would not have to move around too much _
Clinton reiterated the position of the other summit leaders on
economic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Russia must meet the revenue-raising requirements set by the IMF
in order to start the disbursement of the $4.5 billion loan, the
president said. Berger quoted Yeltsin as saying: ``I am personally
committed'' to finalizing the IMF agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In agreeing in the joint Russian-American statement to discuss
the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty between the the two countries,
Yeltsin acceded to a process the Russians had previously refused to
consider, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration wants to start these discussions because
modifications to the treaty are needed if a decision is made to
deploy the national missile defense system proposed by Clinton in
his State of the Union address in January.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, the statement also said, pledged to work toward the
ratification of the START II treaty _ stalled by Russia's
Communist-dominated Parliament _ but that is a pledge the Yeltsin
government has made many times before. The two sides also agreed to
continue discussions on the START III treaty, which aims to reduce
both sides' nuclear arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   According to Berger's account, the Russian foreign minister,
Igor Ivanov, said that it was unlikely that the Russian Parliament
would deal with the START II ratification before its summer recess.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Yeltsin raised the issue of
Congress' lifting the Jackson-Vanik Act, a 1974 law that forbids
Russia to be automatically granted normal trading relations with
the United States because of Moscow's Soviet-era refusal to permit
freedom of emigration.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been declared eligible for normal trading relations
status, even though the law remains on the books, so the law has
little practical effect. Recent expressions of anti-Semitism by
Communist Party politicians in Russia have made Congress reluctant
to repeal the law, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When told that those Russian politicians were blocking
congressional action, Yeltsin, according to a White House official,
replied: ``Give me the names. I will grind them down and come at
them like a ton of bricks.''
</P>
<P>
   On the question of Russia's helping Iran with nuclear
technology, Yeltsin said he wanted to be co-operative in working
out disagreements, administration officials said. He said he wanted
to revive what had been the Gore-Chernomyrdin Commission _ named
after Vice President Al Gore and the former Russian prime minister,
Victor Chernomyrdin _ by including the new prime minister, Sergei
Stepashin. The proliferation issues could be dealt with under the
aegis of the new commission, Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
   As a special gesture to Clinton, Yeltsin presented the president
with documents on President Kennedy and his assassination which had
been declassified by Russian military and civilian archives at
Yeltsin's request, Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview afterward with CNN's Late Edition, Clinton
expanded on his thinking at the start of NATO's air campaign and on
his foreign policy generally. Asked if he thought the bombing of
Yugoslavia would last 78 days before Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic agreed to NATO's terms, he said: ``I thought that there
was maybe a 50 percent chance it would be over in a week.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``I knew if he decided to take the punishment of
the air campaign, it could go a long _ quite a long _ while.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there was a doctrine that best characterized his
foreign policy, Clinton said it was that ``whether within or
beyond'' a country's borders, ``if the world community has the
power to stop it, we ought to stop genocide and ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   After Yeltsin flew back to Moscow, Clinton spoke Sunday night at
a short ceremony marking the move of the American Embassy in
Germany from Bonn to Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the summit meeting, Clinton said, coincided with a
potential turning point in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find ourselves at that pivotal moment between winning a
conflict and winning the peace,'' he said. ``Today the last Serb
forces are leaving Kosovo, in accordance with the deadline that has
been set.'' What happened now, the president said, ``will determine
the character of this Continent, the shape of our alliance and the
nature of our partnership with Russia for years and years to
come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
