<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-CLASSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAK EASES THE PRESSURE WITH LPGA VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABSECON, N.J. _ With a horde of media from her native Korea
descending upon the Seaview Marriott Resort here, Se Ri Pak was
under enormous pressure Sunday. The 21-year-old felt the burden of
having to please an entire country, and she responded by winning
her first tournament of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Pak captured the $1 million Shoprite Ladies Professional Golf
Association Classic with a round of 5-under-par 66 for a total of
198 on the 6,051-yard Bay Course, an original design of Donald
Ross. She was spurred on by shooting a course and tournament record
of 63 on opening day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy I finally got one in 1999,'' said Pak, who won
four tournaments in her rookie season last year. ``No more
questions about winning one. I think my fans in my country will
start to trust me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak, who presented the trophy to her father, Joon Chul, as a
Father's Day present, earned $150,000 by finishing two shots ahead
of Trish Johnson, who shot 65, tied for the best round of the day.
It was the best finish of the year for Johnson, who in 12 years on
the tour has three victories, the last in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who earned $93,092, narrowed the gap to one stroke with
birdies on 16 and 17, but that was the closest she could come to
Pak.
</P>
<P>
   Juli Inkster, the winner of three events this season, including
the U. S. Open two weeks ago, finished third at 10 under after
shooting 69.
</P>
<P>
   Pak started Sunday's round with a birdie on the second hole, the
most difficult on the course, chipping in with her sand wedge from
about 25 yards. She also made another birdie on the next hole, a
475-yard par-5, which played the easiest all three days of the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``That chip was great,'' she said. ``I felt confident that
everything would be OK the rest of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak said the victory came at the perfect time. She said it gave
her confidence to defend next week's McDonald's LPGA Championship,
the major she captured last year before winning the U.S. Open to
become the first rookie to capture two major titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a perfect week,'' Pak said. ``Everything is good going
into next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosie Jones matched Johnson's best round of the day in the
persistent drizzle coming off the bay. Jones shot 65 to finish in
fourth at 204 for her fourth top-10 finish in her last five events.
Jones has nine career victories, but none this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fairway woods were awful, but my short game took over,''
Jones said. ``I haven't been playing well on Sundays, so this is
nice to have going into next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Tammie Green got her fifth hole-in-one when she aced the
179-yard 14th with a 9-wood and won a Mercury Cougar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
