<HEADLINE>
LOUIS GLICKMAN, 94, REAL-ESTATE INVESTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Fla.)  (lb) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Louis J. Glickman, a widely known real-estate
investor and philanthropist, died on Friday at New York Hospital.
He was 94 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman formed a Manhattan-based real-estate investment company
in 1942 and was widely active in real-estate investments in the
United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   One of his best-known deals was not completed. In 1956, he made
it known that he had arranged to buy Carnegie Hall and planned to
tear it down and replace it with a 40-story office building.
Demolition was to begin when the Philharmonic-Symphony Society's
lease expired in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   But Glickman later dropped his option to buy the building, and
it was unclear whether a Save Carnegie Hall campaign or an
inability to finance the project on profitable terms led to his
backing out. The building was eventually preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman's son Adam said that his father ``never had any
intention of demolishing Carnegie Hall; he basically got involved
with that to get some publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, Glickman offered $4.6 million for the Dakota apartment
building on West 72nd Street and for an adjoining lot. Soon after
acquiring the properties, he sold the Dakota to its tenants and the
lot to other developers, who built an apartment house, the Mayfair
Tower, there.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman was born and raised in Brooklyn, attended Brown
University and the University of Virginia, and entered the New
York-based real-estate and construction firm of his father, Pincus
Glickman, in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Glickman founded his real-estate investment company in
1942 and was its chairman after it became a corporation, his son
said. But in 1962 he was forced out of the corporation. His son
said he ``was overextended in some personal investments at that
time,'' and the corporation was acquired by a group of investors.
</P>
<P>
   In later years, Adam Glickman said, Louis Glickman was an
independent real-estate investor. He was dictating letters to his
secretary an hour before his death.
</P>
<P>
   The objects of his philanthropy included the United Jewish
Appeal, nonprofit organizations concerned with cerebral palsy and
epilepsy, the Albert Einstein College of Medicine, and Yeshiva and
Brandeis universities.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his son Adam, of Millburn, N.J., he is survived by his
wife of 67 years, the former Helene Hauptmann; another son, Warren,
who lives in Israel; four grandsons, and a sister, Ruth Gleen, who
lives near Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
