r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELSIDE-LADN     06-20 0253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEADY PLAY: UMP WALLEYED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Sidebar to Angels-Yankees game story) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Of all the wacky moments in Sunday's 4-2 Anaheim
Angels victory at Yankee Stadium, the greatest was the catch, or
noncatch, by Reggie Williams against the right-field wall with one
on and one out in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who took over as a pinch-runner and defensive
replacement for Todd Greene in the top of the inning with the score
3-1, raced back to the wall on Chuck Knoblauch. At first, it
appeared to hit his glove, then his head before he grabbed it off
his chest. First-base umpire Mark Johnson signaled out and Williams
threw to first to complete a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Only problem: Replays showed that the ball hit the fence above
Williams' glove. It would have meant extra bases for Knoblauch and
an RBI. Surprisingly, Yankees manager Joe Torre never argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't see it from where we were,'' Torre said. ``We
couldn't tell if it hit his glove or hit behind, but obviously it
hit behind and the umpire didn't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   That play was one of at least a half-dozen breaks the Angels got
Sunday. But after ending a losing streak at six games, they could
only smile and tease Williams in the postgame clubhouse .
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I thought I caught it and if the man says so, that's good
enough for me,'' Williams said. ``No, I don't think I'll be
watching that replay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-20-99 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
