<DOCNO> NYT19990620.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3016 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBAFINALS-HNS &LR;      06-20 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFINALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ The morning spent watching tape promised to be rough. It
was worse. The spacing was terrible, the shooting even poorer. Big
men were fooled by double teams. Reserves were completely out of
sync.
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was but one saving grace: The Spurs did lead the NBA
Finals 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   As the series moves to Madison Square Garden tonight, a New York
turnaround is looking much less likely than the Knicks'
inexplicable run to the Finals. But even though they are halfway to
a championship, the Spurs have struggled enough themselves on
offense to maintain the humility they seek when on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of funny,'' San Antonio forward Sean Elliott said.
``We feel like we're 2-0, but it's not as gratifying a 2-0 as we
wanted. We can't be picky about it, but we don't feel like we've
played well at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the big-picture pursuit of their first championship,
aesthetics do not matter. The Spurs have won 13 of 14 playoff
games, including an NBA-record 12 straight. They have won 44 of
their past 50 games overall, losing just once in 53 days.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the chances of a Knicks comeback, Spurs guard Mario
Elie said, ``I just can't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Elie's vision is fine. New York's chances might be too small to
be detected by the human eye.
</P>
<P>
   But backed into a corner, the Knicks are expected to lift their
level of play at home. And even though the Spurs would still be
awarded the title with two more ``ugly'' wins, they cannot help but
want to play well on offense for its own sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us want to show the country how good we are,''
Elliott said. ``We sit out there in San Antonio, which is the 37th
(largest) media market in the country. A lot of people don't see
what we're all about. This is a great stage to show everybody we're
a great team. I know we have a lot better games in us.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a pair of convincing wins so far, the Spurs shot only
27-of-63 from the field in taking Game 2 80-67 on Friday night,
contributing to the lowest-scoring Finals contest since 1955.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offense was a little sluggish,'' Elie said. ``I expect it
to be a better game. They weren't really double-teaming. They were
sort of faking. But our big guys got a little confused. They need
to dribble a little bit and extend the double team a little longer.
Dave (Robinson) and Tim (Duncan) need to hold the ball a little
longer, give our outside guys time to shoot or set up the drives.
We have a couple things we know we can do better. I know we can
shoot better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we play better on the road. Our confidence level gets
higher on the road. It's sometimes tough playing in that (Alamo)
dome, getting a good look at the basket. You come in the Garden _
man, the rims look good. I saw all the guys smiling today. Shots
were going good. It's going to be good for us. When we went to LA,
Minnesota, Portland _ that Game 3, we played great.''
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 has been the Spurs' worst throughout the playoffs. They
defeated the Trail Blazers by one, beat the Lakers by three and
lost to the Timberwolves by nine. In Game 3 on the road, they beat
the Trail Blazers by 22, the Lakers by 11 and the Timberwolves by
14.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went to LA after we had those two games that were
low-scoring, we got it up to 115,'' Spurs guard Avery Johnson
noted. ``As long as we've got more points, I don't care if it's
69-60 or 115-110. But it (the Spurs' offense) is not good. We saw
it on the film. That's one of the reasons when we come on the road
we play better. We come on the road with so many problems. And we
seem to correct those problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is because the Spurs are so unimpressed with
themselves that they don't allow the home adulation to go to their
heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our attitude has been the constant,'' Elliott said. ``It's
almost us against the world. We like people cheering against us. We
like when the fans get up and cheer for their team. It helps us get
sharp and get focused. Whenever teams make runs at us, we just
respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crowds don't bother us, and Tim is unfazed by anything. Who
knows what's going to happen in this building (the Garden)? But
it's not going to bother us.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Knicks refuse to consider the return home a panacea,
something needs to be. If San Antonio's offense has been
``sluggish,'' New York's has been downright atrocious.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs' defense deserves much of the credit for that, but the
Knicks are not about to concede that the combination of Duncan and
Robinson inside and the Spurs' sticky man-to-man defense outside
will paralyze their ability to get good shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, we usually learn from the first loss, and we
didn't,'' Knicks guard Allan Houston said. ``We played very
similarly. We have to rely and depend on each other instead of
doing it on our own. They are a very good defensive team, but we're
giving them too much credit by not playing together.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the Spurs can be motivated by seeing their sloppy play on
tape, the Knicks can see the same thing and find hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we can win,'' Houston said. ``I would be worried if I
looked at the tape and said, `This team is that much superior to
us.' We don't believe that. They are a very good team. They have
done what they've done for a reason. We're here for a reason also.
We've got ourselves in a hole, but we can win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
