<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- June 20, 1999 -- ISRAEL-MIX-2, 6-20 -- Yuli
Edelstein, 40, the immigration minister of Israel, left, as a young
man in the Soviet Union. Edelstein represents a new breed of
Israeli politicians, less likely to be veterans of the great
Israeli wars, lifelong Zionists or even Jewish. Their stories form
the new narrative strands of a country that is redefining itself. A
former Soviet refusenik, Edelstein is No. 2 to Natan Sharansky at
the helm of Yisrael B'Aliya, the small but powerful Russian
immigrant party. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ALON SHVUT, West Bank -- June 20, 1999 -- ISRAEL-MIX-1,
6-20 -- Yuli Edelstein, 40, the immigration minister of Israel, in
the West Bank settlement which he now calls home. Edelstein
represents a new breed of Israeli politicians, less likely to be
veterans of the great Israeli wars, lifelong Zionists or even
Jewish. Their stories form the new narrative strands of a country
that is redefining itself. A former Soviet refusenik, Edelstein is
No. 2 to Natan Sharansky at the helm of Yisrael B'Aliya, the small
but powerful Russian immigrant party. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SAN FRANCISCO -- June 20, 1999 -- ONLINE-OUTAGES, 6-20
-- Jan Hier-King, senior vice president of electronic trading
technology for Charles Schwab, watches the company's Web page in
her San Francisco office during an early-morning conference call to
Web administrators at the company's Web control center in Arizona.
Ms. Hier-King knows full well, hardly a week goes by without an
outage at a major E-commerce site, whether online brokerage
servicess like Schwab, merchants like the bookseller Amazon.com
(www.amazon.com), or the auctioneer Ebay (www.ebay.com). (Peter
DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SAN FRANCISCO -- June 20, 1999 -- PORTAL-STUDY, 6-20 --
Researchers Bernardo Huberman, right, and Lada Adamic found
evidence that a relative handful of sites command a large
proportion of traffic on the Web. The study, which is based on
statistical measurements of visitors to sites on the Internet's
World Wide Web, looks at a large data sample of Internet traffic to
two types of sites: universities and so-called adult entertainment.
(Darcy Padilla/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- June 20, 1999 -- WILSON-MUSIC-REVIEW, 6-20
-- Brian Wilson 57, at the Beacon Theater, on his first tour
without the Beach Boys. Concerts by the current Beach Boys, led by
Mike Love, are now oldies shows that run through the hits as
exercises in nostalgia. But even as his backup singers were doing
the Swim, Wilson's solo performance was a composer's showcase,
mixing hits and collectors'-item obscurities. (Nancy Siesel/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- June 20, 1999 -- FATHERS-DAY-FLOATER, 6-20
-- Brian Williamson of Tampa, Fla., and his sons, Dustin, 2, left,
and Levi, 3, ride a carousel together on Sunday at the National
Mall in Washington. The family stopped in the capital on their way
to Maine to visit relatives for Father's Day. (Justin Lane/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) DENVER -- June 20, 1999 -- COLORADO-POLITICS, 6-20 --
Rep. Tom Tancredo, R-Colo., right, embracing Craig Bowman, a
teacher, on Saturday at a Denver meeting on youth violence.
Tancredo, who was elected to Congress last fall with donations that
included $9,900 from the National Rifle Association, is the only
representative from Colorado to vote for the final gun-control
bill, which allowed just 24 hours for background checks at gun
shows but also placed some restrictions on semiautomatic rifles and
high-capacity ammunition clips. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LOS ANGELES -- June 20, 1999 -- HANKS-DOCUMENTARY, 6-20
-- Actor Tom Hanks is promoting a documentary ``Return With
Honor,'' on American prisoners of war in North Vietnam. The
102-minute film opened in New York and Los Angeles to strong
reviews and is to be released in other large cities in the next few
weeks. ``The history of their imprisonment has never been
illuminated like this,'' says Hanks. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 20, 1999 -- PC-EXPO, 6-20 -- As the
opening of this week's PC Expo approaches, Steve Tang of Viewsonic
connects a computer monitor as part of the display at the company's
booth at the Javits Convention Center in Manhattan. The show's
organizers are sounding a theme of ``smarter, faster, cheaper'' and
highlighting the trend toward powerful, portable devices that
combine computing and telephony. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) MOSCOW -- June 20, 1999 -- RUSSIA-DRIVE-IN, 6-20 --
Moscow's first drive-in movie, the Kinodrome, a hastily built
56-by-30-foot screen and projection booth mounted on stilts. The
quintessential American motion picture experience was staged by
three Moscow entrepreneurs over the weekend and appeared to be a
hit. Promising the best in foreign films and showing ``Lethal
Weapon 4'' and ``Virus,'' even at $8 a person for the movie and a
light meal of pirozhki or cabbage pie, no one complained.
(Jacqueline Mia Foster/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- June 20, 1999 -- REPUBS-ABORTION, 6-20 --
In a notable triumph of practical politics over ideology, House
Republicans this year picked an advocate of abortion rights, Rep.
Thomas M. Davis of Virginia, center, to head the National
Republican Congressional Committee, which is responsible for the
party's drive to retain its House majority next year. The
Republican Party has undergone a fundamental repositioning, and
softening, of its stand on abortion, recognizing that a more
tolerant position on probably the most divisive issue in American
politics is crucial to its hopes of reclaiming the White House.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SENOVCE, Yugoslavia -- June 20, 1999 -- KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL,
6-20 -- Villagers from Senovce rebury a victim, Shaban Krasniqi, on
Sunday. The victim was disinterred as evidence of massacres by
Serbs. There are perhaps hundreds of places across Kosovo where
Albanians were apparently massacred by Serbs over the last two
months, and new mass grave sites and bodies are being discovered
virtually every day. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- June 20, 1999 -- DELAY-PROFILE, 6-20 --
Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the majority whip. In last week's big,
brawling, guns-and-culture fight over what combination of violent
entertainment and the availability of firearms is causing children
to shoot children, DeLay dramatically took to the House floor to
deliver a series of elemental attacks on modern culture, indicting
birth control, the theory of evolution and day care. ``I'm
aggressive, and I've been aggressive all my life,'' says DeLay.
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) KRUSH E MADHE, Yugoslavia -- June 20, 1999 --
KOSOVO-RDP-3, 6-20 -- A forensic team from Scotland Yard gears up
in front of a German NATO military vehicle in Krush e Madhe. The
forensic experts are investigating a house where the bodies of some
30 to 40 ethnic Albanians were found recently. British government
officials have estimated that at least 10,000 ethnic Albanians were
killed in Serb massacres throughout the region. Some 90 mass grave
sites have been reported. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- June 20, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RDP-2,
6-20 -- A Kosovar woman returning to her looted apartment in
Mitrovia on Sunday. For many Kosovars throughout the region, the
withdrawal of the much-feared Serbian soldiers and police officers
has brought a palpable sense of relief. In city after city, village
after village, there are renewed signs of life and commerce. (Alan
Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- June 20, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RDP-1,
6-20 -- A British soldier in Pristina helps a baby suffering from
heat exhaustion. The baby was riding on board a bus of Serb
refugees fleeing from Pristina on Sunday. On the road to Serbia
proper from Pristina to Leposavic, dozens of Serb families headed
north in bedraggled convoy, their trucks and tractors crammed with
whatever they could carry. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
