<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLOCK-FUNERAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS BID FAREWELL TO BULLOCK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Even in death, Bob Bullock was bigger than life
Sunday, as several hundred friends and admirers _ including a
``Who's Who'' from two generations of Texas politics _ gathered to
pay their last respects.
</P>
<P>
   Central Christian Church, located two blocks from the state
Capitol, was filled with legislators, former legislators, members
of Congress, lobbyists and scores of what one former Bullock
staffer called the ``little people'' who at one time or another had
worked for one of state government's most influential _ and
demanding _ bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Mourners included every living former Texas governor and Lady
Bird Johnson, the widow of a president. The current governor and,
perhaps, future president eulogized Bullock as a mentor and the
``essence of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What a man! What a man!'' Gov. George W. Bush declared. ``Can
you imagine Bob Bullock and St. Peter? Bob's got him locked in a
conference room, and he won't let him out until he is happy with
his plan for eternity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Dr. Fabaus Landry, who officiated, said the former
lieutenant governor, comptroller, secretary of state and state
legislator was ``one of the giant oaks of Texas,'' who had worked
tirelessly to make life in his state better for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Rangers, the state's elite, legendary law-enforcement
force, were pallbearers, laying Bullock to rest on a rainy day in
the historic State Cemetery, not far from Texas founder Stephen F.
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, whose strong relationship to the veteran Democratic
officeholder crossed generational and partisan lines, said the
church wasn't big enough to hold all of Bullock's admirers.
</P>
<P>
   And, referring to the political tempests that periodically
rocked Bullock's four decades in state government, Bush joked, ``I
bet a few would come just to make sure he was really dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was one of the last people to visit with Bullock, 69,
before he died Friday, five months after leaving office. He had
been undergoing chemotherapy for lung cancer and recently developed
pneumonia and congestive heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``His (Bullock's) temper could break like a summer storm. His
tongue should have been registered as a concealed weapon. His
passions came out undiluted,'' the governor continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Bob, there were steel and acid. But there were also loyalty
and friendship and love. And there was something more _ the essence
of Texas: a frontier toughness, a sentimental heart, a rough-hewn
grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Bullock ``embodied the Texas of our myths and our
hearts.'' He compared his passing to Texans losing ``our tie to an
age of giants.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he learned from Bullock and ``will miss him as a
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock angered some Democrats last year when he not only
endorsed the Republican governor for re-election over Democratic
nominee Garry Mauro, a former Bullock aide, but also said Bush
would make a good president. The statement came months before Bush
launched his campaign for the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But Mauro, ironically, was one of the first mourners to arrive
at the church for Bullock's services.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who visited Bullock last week after returning from a
campaign trip to Iowa and New Hampshire, said Bullock already had
lived, at that point, longer than his doctors had predicted and
bragged to Bush, ``Governor, I showed them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that Bullock, when asked about his health a couple of
years ago, was quoted as saying, ``I'm so busy, I ain't got time to
die.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the governor added: ``We all make time for death. And I
know, after a life of fighting, he has found a peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Former longtime aide Claudia Stravato said Bullock hired the
``best and the brightest'' but also hired people no one else wanted
and taught them to be the best and to be proud to work for the
state of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Bullock friend Byron Tunnell, a former speaker of the
Texas House and former member of the Texas Railroad Commission,
said he watched the transformation of Bullock from a law student
more than 40 years ago to the ``giant of a man he ultimately
became.''
</P>
<P>
   Tunnell said he will miss Bullock the most as a friend. But he
added, ``Though he would scoff at me for saying it, this man, this
friend of ours, has achieved true greatness ... by hard work, long
hours ... and sheer determination to do the job right.''
</P>
<P>
   Tunnell said Bullock _ who was a major budgetary player during
16 years as comptroller and had an active hand in virtually every
piece of major legislation enacted during eight years as lieutenant
governor _ didn't subscribe to the old government axiom, ``If it
ain't broke, don't fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he took it on, he fully intended to fix it whether it was
broken or not,'' Tunnell said.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Pete Laney noted that Bullock, in retirement,
continued to follow the Legislature's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, at the end of another legislative session, as if he was
finally satisfied that we could carry on without him, he left us,''
Laney said.
</P>
<P>
   Five former governors _ Democrats Ann Richards, Mark White,
Dolph Briscoe and Preston Smith and Republican Bill Clements _
attended Bullock's services. They all were in office during the
Bullock era, which began in 1956 with his election to the Texas
House from his hometown of Hillsboro.
</P>
<P>
   Smith hired Bullock as an aide and later appointed him secretary
of state.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred people, many huddled under umbrellas, stood in
the rain for the graveside ceremony that followed the church
services.
</P>
<P>
   A Texas Department of Public Safety honor guard presented
Bullock's widow, Jan, with the Texas flag that had draped the
former lieutenant governor's coffin.
</P>
<P>
   DPS troopers also fired three rifle volleys, and a bagpiper
played ``Amazing Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   The church service included audio and video highlights of
Bullock's recent public years, which closed with Bullock delivering
his trademark line, ``God Bless Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
