<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG DAY FOR DALY ENDS IN LAST PLACE 
DUVAL'S DISAPPOINTMENT 
PERRY SURRENDERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Add another bizarre day to the wild life of
John Daly. Daly shot a 13-over-par 83 Sunday, including an 11 on
the par-4, 446-yard No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting his approach shot over the green, Daly twice tried
to putt up the slope onto the green, but the ball rolled back down
the hill.
</P>
<P>
   On his third putt, the ball started to roll back again, and Daly
lost patience.
</P>
<P>
   While the ball was still rolling backward, Daly gave it a whack
and sent the ball across the green and off the front edge.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Daly chipped and three-putted, then was assessed a
two-stroke penalty for hitting a ball in motion.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Daly, who shot a first-round 68 but ended up at
29-over and in last place, said he might skip the U.S. Open next
year at Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think it's worth my time,'' Daly said of the 2000
Open. ``I just feel the courses are set up too unfair. I'm not
going to go to Pebble and watch the USGA ruin that golf course
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval's Disappointment
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, the world's No. 1-ranked player, started the day
just three strokes off the lead, but he shot a 5-over-par 75 to
finish tied for seventh. A bogey at No. 7 and a double bogey at No.
9 took Duval out of contention for his first major championship.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he were disappointed, Duval said: ``Probably more than
you can imagine. Coming in, I felt good about my chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry Surrenders
</P>
<P>
   Showing his respect for Pinehurst, and a sense of humor, Chris
Perry dropped to his hands and knees, then crawled the final 10
feet to the 18th green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be kind of funny,'' said Perry, who
finished at 17-over par for the tournament. ``I knew the crowd
would like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year at the Open at the Olympic Club in San Francisco,
three golfers finished at 20 over or worse. At Pinehurst, 16
golfers who made the cut were 20 over or worse, including Tom
Watson, Tom Kite and last week's winner on the PGA Tour, Ted Tryba.
</P>
<P>
   Tryba was 19 under in winning the FedEx St. Jude Classic. He
finished at 28 over this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
