<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO'S GUN VOTES: CONSISTENCY OR CALCULATION? 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The hodgepodge gun-control bill that died on the
floor of the House of Representatives on Friday was as much
political Rorschach test as legislation. Turn it one way, and a
congressman might look like a gun-control zealot. Turn it another,
and he might look like a die-hard defender of the Second Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Take Rep. Rick Lazio, a Republican from Suffolk County on Long
Island who is a virtual candidate for the Republican nomination for
U.S. Senate. (Although he has not declared his candidacy, Lazio
said on Friday that an official announcement would be ``pro forma''
at this point.)
</P>
<P>
   To win the nomination, Lazio, who is generally viewed as a
moderate, must broaden his appeal among the conservatives who
dominate Republican primaries. But he must also differentiate
himself from his apparent chief rival, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of
New York City, who is arguably more liberal than Lazio on several
fronts.
</P>
<P>
   So, many analysts wondered last week, would Lazio follow other
moderate Republicans and buck his party's conservative leaders by
voting for a Democratic measure requiring criminal background
checks for gun buyers at gun shows? Or would he heed the call of
the right and support a much weaker gun-show amendment endorsed by
the National Rifle Association?
</P>
<P>
   The answer was: both.
</P>
<P>
   In a crucial vote late Thursday, Lazio sided with gun-control
advocates, voting against the weaker gun-show measure and for the
stronger one, which was sponsored by Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y.,
whose husband was killed and son seriously injured by a gunman on
the Long Island Rail Road in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But the weaker measure, sponsored by Rep. John D. Dingell,
D-Mich., prevailed and was incorporated into a broader gun-control
bill that the House voted on Friday. At the urging of his
leadership, Lazio voted for the final bill, breaking with
gun-control advocates in both parties who argued that no bill was
better than one with Dingell's amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The final bill was defeated, 280 to 147, as some conservative
Republicans, who thought the gun-control measure too strong, joined
with almost all the Democrats, who thought it too weak.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Lazio's fellow moderate Republicans joined with the
Democrats in voting no, but Lazio was one of only about a dozen
Republicans who voted for both the McCarthy amendment and the final
bill. Among that group was another potential New York Senate
candidate, Rep. Peter King of Nassau County.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said Lazio's votes were a classic bit of fence
straddling. On the one hand, he could tell gun-control advocates
that he had voted for the McCarthy amendment; on the other, he
could also assure gun-control opponents that he had voted for the
Dingell amendment that was part of the final bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``As usual, he tries to split the baby,'' said David Bishop, a
Suffolk County legislator who is considering seeking the Democratic
nomination next year for Lazio's seat.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio said in an interview that there was no inconsistency
in his votes. He said he supported the McCarthy measure because it
closed a loophole in the Brady law, which he also supported. But he
said he voted for the final bill because he thought it included
other important gun restrictions. (The bill's provisions included
mandatory trigger locks, new restrictions on the possession of
semiautomatic rifles by children under 18 and a ban on the
importing of high-capacity ammunition clips.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be folks who grumble no matter what I do,'' he
said. ``It's important for me to be true to what I believe and stay
consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this vote typifies Lazio's struggles to bridge the
gap between the centrist and conservative camps in his party.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he supports abortion rights but has voted for
prohibiting late-term abortions and against Medicaid financing of
abortions. And while he has often supported President Clinton's
policies, he voted for impeachment. And while he calls himself a
fiscal conservative, he regularly opposes Republican efforts to cut
spending on federal programs, including health care and the
National Endowment for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   He is a leading member of several moderate Republican groups in
Congress, but he has also worked to get closer to the conservative
House majority leader, Dick Armey of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats see in Lazio's record a calculating politician who can
be portrayed on the stump as an opportunist with no clear
philosophical core. ``What we need are solutions, not political
votes,'' said Bishop, the county legislator.
</P>
<P>
   To which Lazio replies, ``It is my goal to see if I can
transcend a label.'' But he does not deny that he has tried to cut
a more conservative image in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   He is also very openly courting leaders of the Conservative
Party in New York state. For the last 20 years, Republicans have
needed help from third parties to win statewide elections.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Long, the party's state chairman, described Lazio as a
``moderate conservative'' with a mixed record on issues of concern
to conservatives. He said, for example, that some conservatives
would be disappointed that Lazio had voted for Mrs. McCarthy's
gun-show amendment, which he described as extreme.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said that Lazio might have helped himself by voting
for the final gun-show bill, which he called ``decent
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, the final one is the one that counts,'' Long
said.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
