<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROAD, SWEET ROAD: SPURS ARE UNFAZED BY GARDEN'S AURA
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ First, the good news for the Knicks entering Game 3:
they're at home.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news? The Spurs aren't.
</P>
<P>
   As the Knicks return to the presumably friendly confines of
Madison Square Garden Monday night down by 2-0 in the best-of-7
championship series, they face an obstacle even more ominous than
Tim Duncan: the San Antonio Spurs play better on the road than in
the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs haven't lost on the road in almost two months, since a
104-100 defeat to Sacramento on April 27. They finished the regular
season 16-9 on the road, and have won all six of their road playoff
games by an average margin of 13.4 points. That is six points more
than their margin of victory in their seven home playoff victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concentration level seems to get higher,'' said the Spurs'
Mario Elie, a New Yorker. ``When you're on the road and in a
hostile environment, all you've got is your team and your coaches.
Your focus has to be high.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumpy mattresses, crummy room service, bad choices on
pay-per-view television. Nothing seems to unsettle a team that,
according to David Robinson, even manages to thrive on the energy
of the unfamiliar pre-game pyrotechnics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just a little more fearful of the road,'' Steve Kerr
said. ``We have a little more edge. When you play that way, you're
a little more dangerous. We tend to get a little too confident at
home.
</P>
<P>
   During the playoffs, playing at home is tougher. You've got all
the distractions, the tickets, family staying with you. When you go
on the road, you stay in a hotel, you're isolated, it's easier to
lock in.''
</P>
<P>
   That is terrifying news for the Knicks. The Spurs, although
nobody in New York may have noticed, have not played their best
game in the finals. Their perimeter shooting, for one thing, has
been subpar.
</P>
<P>
   The antidote for that seems to be to get away from the
notoriously difficult dome setting. The Spurs shoot better from the
field, from the 3-point arc and from the free-throw line on the
road than at home. They also rebound, assist and steal better.
</P>
<P>
   And their defense, already the best in the league, even seems to
rise a level on the road. A final indignity for opponents: the
Spurs make them shoot worse from the field and from 3-point range
in their own building than they do in the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been able to ignore external circumstances because we're
a grind-it-out team,'' Robinson said. ``We have that good
mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, the Spurs figure, is the result of years of churning
through big games. Although most of the Spurs _ with Kerr, Will
Perdue and Mario Elie the notable exceptions _ have never won a
championship before, this is a veteran group, with years of
experience in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Spurs paid homage to Madison Square Garden, to the
New York fans, even to the celebrities who will be courtside. And
then they coolly dismissed the notion that any crowd, any setting,
could rattle them. They won two in Minnesota, two in Los Angeles
and two in Portland. The Garden, for all its glamour, should be no
different, they feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out attitude has been a constant,'' Sean Elliott said. ``It's
like us against the world. It helps us get sharp. I've been in the
league for 10 years, David for 10 years, Avery for 11, Mario for 9
or so. Crowds don't bother us. Tim is unfazed by anything. Who
knows what could happen in this building, and it's not going to
bother him.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery Johnson said: ``When teams go on a 10-2 run and the crowd
gets into a game in the middle of the fourth quarter, we don't
expect to crack up. You always see guys pointing to their heads on
this team, reminding ourselves to stay mentally tough. I guess age
and maturity have something to do with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
