<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3141 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAYNTER-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      06-20 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAYNTER-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE'S `TOBACCO SLAYING' ATTORNEY GENERAL HONORED BY MAGAZINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PAYNTER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ With the character issue now a top campaign priority,
Good Housekeeping magazine's golden seal of approval is something
any officeholder would love to take to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   But while Washington state Attorney General Christine Gregoire
will get the magazine's highest award for women in government on
Wednesday in Washington, D.C., she will not be allowed to accept
the $25,000 check that comes with it.
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   Because the rules of the Washington State Ethics Commission,
which works for the Attorney General's Office, say that no one in
state government can receive any additional compensation for simply
doing his or her job. No matter how far beyond the call of duty
they may go and no matter where the money comes from.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crazy as it may sound, the Ethics Board is very strict about
this,'' Marty Brown, Gov. Gary Locke's deputy chief of staff and
legislative director, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Gregoire was chosen first among 10 ``women who made a
difference'' in 1999. ``The Tobacco Slayer,'' as the article calls
her, is being honored for tenaciously waging the tireless
negotiations that ultimately forced the nation's top cigarette
makers to pay taxpayers a $206 billion settlement. And for ridding
the landscape of Joe Camel and other cigarette ads aimed at kids.
And for helping to secure millions of dollars from big tobacco for
a campaign to discourage teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if you were in the private sector, you would get a
bonus or a contingency fee for something like this,'' Brown said.
``But that's not the way the Ethics Board works. Unfortunately,
it's just seen as doing your job _ really, really well.''
</P>
<P>
   No one argues the months Gregoire spent separated from her
family to hammer out the settlement in New York City amounted to a
huge sacrifice, Brown said. ``But the problem is where do you draw
the line?''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, nobody in the Department of Labor and Industries
got a reward for the $4.4 million settlement _ including a record
$1.1 million fine _ that was paid to the state by Equilon Puget
Sound Refining after the Anacortes, Wash., explosion in November
that killed six.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gregoire is reportedly the only winner of the Good
Housekeeping prize who ever had to turn down the money. She admits
she was surprised and she says the people from Good Housekeeping
were ``shocked'' when she told them she couldn't take the money.
</P>
<P>
   The award was established with the thinking that people who go
into public service are less handsomely paid than those in the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Last month a citizens panel raised Gregoire's salary from
$93,000 a year to $123,000. Commission members noted that some
state officials hadn't seen any raises, including cost-of-living
adjustments, since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Gregoire has no intention of fighting the ethics rule and
emphasizes that, check or no check, she is thrilled with the award.
</P>
<P>
   Gregoire didn't even know she had been nominated for the award
by Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals Judge Margaret McKeown until an
editor from the magazine called for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went home and told my family and they couldn't believe it,''
Gregoire said on Friday while en route to meet Vice President Al
Gore on his presidential campaign stop in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Gregoire had told her two teenage daughters,
Courtney and Michelle, the $25,000 would be equally spent on their
educations.
</P>
<P>
   The other nine winners will receive $2,500 each.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend the Gregoire family got together via conference
call to decide which charities will get the money.
</P>
<P>
   Gregoire, her husband, Mike, and their daughters will donate
$5,000 each to the charity of their choice. Then, as a family, they
will give the remaining $5,000 to one charity they all like.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney, 19, is working in Washington, D.C. this summer and
will join her mother there for the awards ceremony while Mike stays
home to take Michelle, who just finished the eighth grade, to her
soccer game.
</P>
<P>
   Gregoire took a red-eye flight home from the tobacco
negotiations last year to be in the bleachers for one of Michelle's
games. But she missed too many others, she admits.
</P>
<P>
   Mike takes in stride the good-natured kidding he sometimes gets
as the husband of one of only seven female attorneys general in the
country. When he goes to events for spouses, the outings are
usually shopping trips and museum tours.
</P>
<P>
   He'll change that when he takes charge of spouse events when the
National Association of Attorneys General has its annual meeting in
Seattle next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Next week Gregoire will travel to Nashville, Tenn., for this
year's annual convention. The group recently elected Gregoire
president by a unanimous vote.
</P>
<P>
   And what's next for the ``tobacco slaying'' medal winner, the
woman Mississippi Attorney General Michael Moore nicknamed the
``Tiger Lady'' for her never-back-down style?
</P>
<P>
   Since the settlement victory, and since deciding not to run
against Sen. Slade Gorton for a seat in the U.S. Senate, Gregoire
pondered her options.
</P>
<P>
   Some say she will surely be offered a presidential Cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
   She says she'll believe that when she sees it. And she won't
talk about it until then.
</P>
<P>
   She has also been urged to run for governor and Gregoire says
she is not ruling that out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say that the state may very well be the key,''
Gregoire said. ``At this point, I haven't seen the federal
government capable of reaching into the lives of everyday people to
help them solve their problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
