<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-DIAMONDBACKS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves pound big lumps on `Big Unit,' 10-4
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The biggest shame for Braves fans back in Atlanta is
that they couldn't see this one.
</P>
<P>
   In the Braves' first game not televised back East, they pulled
off the remarkable and dwarfed the other accomplishments of this
road trip _ the back-to-back wins by Tom Glavine and Greg Maddux,
winning three of four from the NL Central-leading Astros.
</P>
<P>
   They raked Randy Johnson and hit five home runs in a 10-4 romp
over the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the 6-foot-10, 100-mph pitcher known as ``Big Unit,'' who
had humbled the Braves with 15 strikeouts on April 10, was chased
after five innings, having allowed four homers for the first time
in his 11-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez hit for two of them, both two-run shots, and Gerald
Williams hit one of his two for the night off Johnson to lead off
the game. Lopez, who started this road trip with six home runs, now
has 11.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves completed their two-city swing with a 5-2 record,
having beaten the top teams in the NL Central and NL West, and
return to Atlanta with the league's best record at 42-27.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who had won five starts in a row, surrendered seven
runs on nine hits, the most runs he has allowed since coming over
to the National League from Seattle last July. The Braves had four
consecutive hits off him in the fifth inning, including
back-to-back home runs by Lopez and Andruw Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the first inning, it was going to be Glavine who
would have the long night. He needed 41 pitches to get through the
inning after he loaded the bases twice, walked three batters and
gave up a hit. But he allowed only one run, on a Steve Finley
sacrifice fly, and gave himself a chance to win in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks manufactured three runs off Glavine, one each
in the first three innings, but once he got the 7-3 lead in the top
of the fifth he buckled down.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves wanted to get to Johnson early, and Williams, the
leadoff hitter, took it to heart, sending the first pitch of the
game to the right field seats.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
