<DOCNO> NYT19990620.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3147 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-20 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PINEHURST, N.C. _ He has walked among golf's legends but always a
couple of paces back, never really being one of them.
</P>
<P>
   He was like a nervous hanger-on among a generation of names
you'll never forget: Fred Couples, Greg Norman, Ben Crenshaw, Nick
Price, Nick Faldo and Seve Ballesteros.
</P>
<P>
   They all had something Payne Stewart didn't have. They had green
jackets or big, powerful swings. They had passionate looks in their
eyes, like those of Ballesteros and Crenshaw. They had machine-like
precision, like Faldo and Norman.
</P>
<P>
   And they had moments _ something Stewart never had, at least not
until a damp, unforgettable Sunday evening at a place called
Pinehurst No. 2, where Stewart finally earned what money and
knickers couldn't buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid, I used to imagine I was Jack Nicklaus,
putting on the green for a win,'' Stewart said. ``I used to think,
`I'm going to be Jack today. I'm going to make this putt and win
the U.S. Open.'''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he was. What happened on No. 18 at Pinehurst was a
moment that might surpass anything anyone in his generation has
produced.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart sank a 15-foot putt on the 72nd hole of the U.S. Open.
It was as dramatic as anything you'll see. And it was something you
can only feel. It made Stewart a legend.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is he only the guy in the funny knickers. No longer is
he merely a great pro but nothing special to the masses. No longer
just a golfer who has won more than $10 million on tour and even a
couple of major championships but somehow never chased away the
reputation that hounded him.
</P>
<P>
   He had no nerve. He lost leads. He played only for the money. He
was great but not special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I considered myself a pretty good and pretty accomplished
player,'' Stewart said. ``I thought nobody could ever take that
away from me no matter what was written and said about me.''
</P>
<P>
   But things definitely were written and said.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't putt under pressure. His irons faded on Sunday
afternoons. Tiger Woods and Phil Mickelson would take him.
</P>
<P>
   For so long he was the guy who used props, not a clutch game, to
bring attention to himself, dressing in those wild outfits. For
some reason, not even a couple of major championships _ the PGA in
1989 and the U.S. Open in 1991 _ could earn Stewart a spot among
his generation's greats.
</P>
<P>
   Those others, those Faldos and Normans, all seemed to have
something something that made crowds gather 10-deep against the
ropes and watch in awe. They all seemed to have something that made
imaginations dance.
</P>
<P>
   They were a generation of super-talents that arrived after Jack
Nicklaus, Lee Trevino and Gary Player, then dominated the tour and
bridged the game into the era of David Duval, Justin Leonard,
Mickelson and Woods.
</P>
<P>
   And somewhere there was Stewart, always walking a couple of
paces back. But then there was Sunday afternoon, when Stewart
walked across Pinehurst No. 2 with a game and an outfit that
turn-of-the-century Pinehurst designer Donald Ross would have
loved.
</P>
<P>
   He did things he never had done before and earned something he
never had before.
</P>
<P>
   His irons were true and his putting spectacular. Through much of
the day it was Mickelson's putter that looked unshakable. But every
time Mickelson made a big putt down the stretch, Stewart's face
showed no emotion as he walked calmly to the next hole.
</P>
<P>
   Then, it was Mickelson who began to waver, yanking a couple of
big putts on the final three holes. Later, Mickelson admitted that
he began to feel things slipping away going into those final three
holes.
</P>
<P>
   And it was there where Stewart finally gripped his place in the
game. The 25-foot putt on No. 16 to save par was one of the most
clutch shots the tour has seen in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought,'' Mickelson said, ``he could beat me.''
</P>
<P>
   The tee shot to within five feet and a birdie on the 191-yard
17th, which gave Stewart the lead, was dead-on. And then there was
18.
</P>
<P>
   There was a wayward tee shot and no choice but to lay up 77
yards from the hole with the Open championship on the line. There
was the chip that landed well short, rolling back slightly to 15
feet. There was the stunning silence and Stewart leaning over the
putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was telling myself, `You've given yourself a chance. Do
it,''' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   And he did. The putt never wavered, like he never wavered.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart jumped into the air, hugged his caddie, kissed his wife,
cried, yelled and shook his head over how unbelievable the moment
was. It was a moment like few before, a moment the nation had to
embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where this puts me in the golf world,'' he said later, ``I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is all so clear now. Maybe today, some kid somewhere will
hitch up the hems of his pants, stand over a putt and imagine that
he is Payne Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``To question his toughness is not right,'' Mickelson said. ``I
have to admit, he had something that I didn't have in the last few
holes.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because Stewart is something that Mickelson and the
entire next generation of greats can only aspire to be. A golfing
legend, finally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
