<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, June 21. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
WARHERO (Phoenix) _ Edward Sherlock doesn't have much time left.
</P>
<P>
   A stomach problem, which has plagued him since being released as
a prisoner of war during World War II, has slowly deteriorated his
body. For now, most of what he sees is in room 526, bed B, at a
hospital in Sun City West. And some days, his family feared, there
wasn't much more for the 75-year-old. But as Sherlock's wife, Anna,
and son, J.W., searched through his old Army records, trying to
find something that might increase his veteran's benefits and help
pay his bills, they discovered a secret of his past. Sherlock is a
war hero. They already knew he had spent 27 months as a prisoner of
war. But what they didn't know was that his efforts fighting in
three battles in North Africa during World War II had earned him a
Bronze Star, a Purple Heart and several other ribbons for his
service. By LAURA TRUJILLO. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   ALS (Phoenix) _ The hard part about having a fatal disease in
1999 is that the promises of miracle cures, genetic antidotes and
biococktails twinkle all around like lights of distant rescue ships
_ too far off to be of assistance. ``It's very maddening,'' said
Kevin Spicer, afflicted with Lou Gehrig's disease. ``I wish those
breakthroughs would be available right now, before the disease
takes over more of my body.'' Lacking the muscle control to speak,
the Tucson man communicates these thoughts through his computer
e-mail system. Spicer's disease, named for the baseball legend who
died of it in 1941, is scientifically known as amyotrophic lateral
sclerosis, or ALS. Though the disease has no cure, many of its
victims do not sit and wait. An estimated 20 percent of Arizonans
with ALS, including Spicer, are enrolled in research projects. ALS
gradually destroys the motor nerves, causing muscles to atrophy,
leading to paralysis. Arizona's 250 to 300 victims of Lou Gehrig's
disease know that three to five more years of life is the most they
can expect after diagnosis. In Arizona, at least four major studies
are under way at Mayo Clinic Scottsdale and at the University of
Arizona. Barrow Neurological Institute in Phoenix also is
nationally known for its research on ALS, though it doesn't have a
study under way presently. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
